        <div id="theories">

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="kuhn-paradigms-and-scientific-revolutions">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy of Science</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Kuhn, 1962</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Kuhn: Paradigms and Scientific Revolutions</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Scientific progress through paradigm shifts and revolutionary change</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Science advances not through steady accumulation but through
                        revolutionary paradigm shifts when anomalies accumulate and a new worldview replaces the old.
                    </p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🔬 <strong>Normal Science:</strong> Puzzle-solving within established
                            paradigms</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚡ <strong>Paradigm Shift:</strong> Revolutionary change when anomalies
                            mount</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🌍 <strong>Incommensurability:</strong> Different paradigms see different
                            worlds</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>Relevance for IS:</strong> Understanding how IS research evolves through paradigmatic shifts
                    (e.g., from technical systems to sociotechnical practice)
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="popper-falsification-and-what-counts-as-science">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy of Science</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Popper, 1934</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Popper: Falsification and What Counts as Science</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Science distinguished by falsifiability, not verification</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Scientific theories must be falsifiable. Science advances through
                        bold conjectures and rigorous attempts at refutation, not through verification.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Falsifiability:</strong> Theories must make testable
                            predictions</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔍 <strong>Critical Testing:</strong> Seek evidence that could disprove
                            theories</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📊 <strong>Demarcation:</strong> Separates science from pseudoscience
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>Relevance for IS:</strong> Designing research that makes testable predictions and can be
                    empirically refuted
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="lakatos-research-programmes-as-the-middle-ground">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy of Science</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Lakatos, 1970</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Lakatos: Research Programmes as the Middle Ground</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Science as evolving research programmes with hard cores and protective
                        belts</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Scientific theories have a hard core (central assumptions)
                        protected by auxiliary hypotheses. Programs are progressive or degenerating based on novel
                        predictions.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🛡️ <strong>Hard Core:</strong> Central assumptions protected from
                            falsification</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔄 <strong>Protective Belt:</strong> Auxiliary hypotheses that can be
                            modified</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📈 <strong>Progressive vs Degenerating:</strong> Quality of research
                            program evolution</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>Relevance for IS:</strong> Evaluating IS research programs (e.g., TAM extensions) as
                    progressive or degenerating
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="kuhn-vs-popper-vs-lakatos-comparison-table">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Comparison Framework</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Multiple Authors</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Kuhn vs Popper vs Lakatos: Comparative Analysis</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Understanding different philosophies of scientific progress</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Compare and contrast three major philosophies of science to understand
                        how scientific knowledge develops and what counts as good research.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">📊 <strong>Comparison Table:</strong> Side-by-side analysis of key
                            dimensions</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🎓 <strong>Exam Critical:</strong> Essential for comprehensive exam
                            discussions</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔗 <strong>Integration:</strong> How each applies to IS research
                            evaluation</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>Relevance for IS:</strong> Framing your research approach and defending methodological
                    choices in comprehensive exams
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="positivism">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy of Science</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Comte, 1830s</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Positivism</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Scientific knowledge through empirical observation and objective
                        measurement</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> True knowledge comes from empirical observation and scientific
                        method. Reality exists objectively and can be measured through systematic observation, leading
                        to laws and predictions.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🔬 <strong>Empiricism:</strong> Knowledge through observation and
                            measurement</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📊 <strong>Objectivity:</strong> Reality exists independent of observer
                        </div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚖️ <strong>Causality:</strong> Identifying cause-effect relationships
                            through testing</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📈 <strong>Prediction:</strong> Scientific laws enable forecasting</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>Relevance for IS:</strong> Foundation for quantitative IS research using surveys,
                    experiments, and statistical analysis to test causal relationships and build predictive models
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Positivism is a philosophy-of-science tradition rather than one paper. In IS, it is
                                    usually discussed as a paradigm that supports hypothesis testing and causal
                                    explanation. A common IS framing is the paradigms discussion in Goles and Hirschheim
                                    (2000).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Philosophy of science.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta (not a theory type). Positivism is a stance about knowledge, not a theory of a
                                    phenomenon.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Objectivity, empiricism, measurement, causal explanation, replication.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>You treat reality as external and measurable, then you test claims about
                                    relationships using data and formal logic.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Most useful when constructs can be operationalized with reasonable validity and when
                                    causal claims are supported by design (experiments, quasi-experiments, strong
                                    controls). Less useful for meaning-making questions where "what the thing is"
                                    depends on interpretation.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Positivist logic remains the default in many IS empirical papers (especially in
                                    security, analytics, and economics-style work), but it is rarely cited as
                                    "positivism" directly. It shows up in research design choices and review criteria.
                                    (Not typically listed as a theory lens in citations.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Positivism grew out of the idea that science should be grounded in observable facts and that good
                        explanations should connect causes to effects in a way that can be tested. In practice, what
                        matters for comps is how positivism shapes the "rules of the game": clear constructs, testable
                        hypotheses, measurement validity, and attention to alternative explanations.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The core claim is not about any single social phenomenon. It is about what kind of knowledge
                        counts as credible. A positivist paper usually aims to explain and predict: it models
                        relationships among constructs, tests them with data, and tries to separate signal from noise.
                        The causal mechanism in positivist work is often expressed as a nomological network. The exam
                        move is to connect it to design. If your causal story is strong but your design is weak
                        (endogeneity, common method bias, selection), positivist reviewers will push back hard. Boundary
                        conditions matter because positivism can look "clean" but be wrong if the constructs do not
                        travel well across contexts. For example, a measure that works in one country or platform might
                        not mean the same thing elsewhere.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS has long debated paradigms, especially when interpretive and critical traditions challenged a
                        single dominant view of "rigor." Goles and Hirschheim (2000) is a useful anchor for comps
                        because it shows how paradigms shape assumptions, methods, and what reviewers reward. More
                        recently, IS also debates whether purely variable-based models are enough for digital phenomena
                        that change fast (platforms, AI, ecosystems). This does not mean positivism disappears. It means
                        positivist work increasingly borrows designs and data sources (field experiments, trace data,
                        audits) to strengthen causal claims.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Positivism gives clear standards. It pushes you to define constructs, design tests,
                        and take alternative explanations seriously. This is why it remains dominant in many top-journal
                        review processes. Weaknesses: It can underplay meaning, context, and power. It can also create
                        "measurement confidence" where we trust a scale too much even when the underlying phenomenon is
                        shifting (example: new AI work practices that older scales do not capture well). Common
                        misapplications in IS: Treating statistical significance as substantive truth, using weak
                        proxies for complex constructs, and claiming causality from cross-sectional survey correlations.
                        Alternatives and competitors: Interpretivist research (often grounded in phenomenology) focuses
                        more on meaning and lived experience. Critical research (radical humanism/structuralism)
                        foregrounds power and ideology. Process theories emphasize sequences and mechanisms over static
                        variable relationships.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use a positivism discussion when the question is about "what counts as evidence"
                        or when you need to defend a causal claim and your identification strategy. Example research
                        question: "Do mandatory breach notification laws reduce breach incidents, and through what
                        mechanisms?" Example hypothesis: "Stronger regulatory pressure is associated with a lower rate
                        of breaches in the affected firms." What I would measure (simple): I would define a clear
                        outcome (breach incidents), measure regulatory change as a policy shock, and use a
                        quasi-experimental design (difference-in-differences) with robustness checks for pre-trends and
                        selection. Seminal APA citation: Goles, T., & Hirschheim, R. (2000). The paradigm is dead, the
                        paradigm is dead... long live the paradigm. <em>Omega, 28</em>(3), 249-268.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="phenomenology">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Husserl (1931)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Phenomenology</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Understanding how people experience and make meaning from phenomena in their lived worlds</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Phenomenology privileges subjective lived experience and intentionality as the foundation for understanding human phenomena. Rather than reducing experience to variables too early, it asks: "How is this phenomenon experienced and made meaningful by people?"</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🧠 <strong>Lived Experience:</strong> The focus on how people actually encounter the world in their daily lives, not abstract concepts</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔍 <strong>Intentionality:</strong> Consciousness is always directed toward something; meaning emerges through this directedness</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📍 <strong>Context & Interpretation:</strong> Meaning is contextual and interpretive, not universal or predetermined</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Sensemaking:</strong> Understanding requires describing how people make sense of phenomena, especially when constructs are unstable or new</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Phenomenology is foundational for interpretive IS research that examines digital experience, meaning-making, and identity in new work contexts. It guards against forcing emerging phenomena into pre-existing theoretical boxes.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Husserl's early work in phenomenology (often associated with <em>Ideas</em> and
                                    related writings) established the focus on lived experience and consciousness. In
                                    IS, phenomenology is usually a foundation for interpretive research rather than a
                                    cited causal theory.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Philosophy.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta (not a theory type). Phenomenology shapes how we study phenomena, not a
                                    predictive model.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Lived experience, meaning, intentionality, context, interpretation.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>You try to understand a phenomenon by describing how it is experienced and made
                                    meaningful by people, rather than reducing it to variables too early.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for questions about sensemaking, identity, experience, and meaning, especially
                                    when constructs are not stable or not well-defined. Less useful when the goal is
                                    prediction or estimating causal effects.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Phenomenology shows up indirectly in interpretive IS traditions (experience-centric
                                    studies of work, digital practice, and transformation), but it is rarely named as
                                    the explicit "theory" in top-journal empirical papers. (More a philosophical
                                    grounding than a citation lens.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Phenomenology begins with the idea that we should take subjective experience seriously. Instead
                        of assuming we already know what a concept means (like "trust" or "control"), phenomenology asks
                        how people actually experience these ideas in their daily lives. That matters in IS because many
                        digital phenomena are experienced differently across roles, contexts, and histories.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>Phenomenology is not built around propositions like a variable model. Its "core" is a commitment:
                        meaning comes from how people encounter the world. For IS, the exam move is to connect this to
                        research questions that are about interpretation, not just behavior. Boundary conditions are
                        important. If the exam question is asking for prediction ("what increases adoption?"),
                        phenomenology is not the best primary answer. But if the question is "how do users experience
                        algorithmic control?" or "what does dignity mean in AI use?", phenomenology is a strong
                        grounding.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS researchers often use phenomenology as background for interpretive methods (interviews,
                        ethnography) and for analysis that stays close to experience. In a comps answer, you can
                        position phenomenology as a counterweight to purely instrumental models: it helps you keep the
                        phenomenon human.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: It helps you avoid forcing new digital phenomena into old boxes. It encourages deep
                        description and careful interpretation, which is valuable when technologies change fast.
                        Weaknesses: It can be criticized for limited generalizability and for being hard to evaluate
                        with the same criteria as positivist work. It also requires strong methodological discipline to
                        avoid turning into storytelling. Common misapplications in IS: Using "phenomenology" as a label
                        without doing the hard work of experience-based analysis, or making causal claims without a
                        design that supports them. Alternatives and competitors: Positivist approaches for causal
                        estimation, critical approaches for power and ideology, and process theorizing when you want
                        sequences of events plus mechanism.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use phenomenology when the exam question is about meaning, experience, or
                        identity, especially in new digital work settings. Example research question: "How do
                        experienced professionals experience the introduction of substitutive AI tools in their daily
                        work?" Example hypothesis: Phenomenology usually does not produce classic hypotheses. A better
                        exam move is to state an expected pattern: "Professionals will describe AI as threatening when
                        it challenges what they see as the core of their expertise." What I would measure (simple): I
                        would not start with a survey scale. I would collect interview or diary data about work
                        episodes, then code for recurring meanings (threat, loss of autonomy, pride, relief) and link
                        them to specific AI features and organizational practices. Seminal APA citation: Husserl, E.
                        (1931). <em>Ideas: General introduction to pure phenomenology</em>. George Allen & Unwin.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="radical-humanism-burrell-and-morgan">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Burrell & Morgan (1979)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Radical Humanism (Burrell and Morgan)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How ideology, consciousness, and domination shape digital life and opportunities for emancipatory change</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> People are often trapped not just by material structures but by ideology and distorted consciousness about what is normal. Digital systems reinforce these ideological traps by shaping what users see, believe is possible, and accept as inevitable.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🧠 <strong>Ideology & Consciousness:</strong> Digital systems encode beliefs about what is "normal" or "necessary," limiting what people perceive as possible</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚖️ <strong>Domination via Meaning:</strong> Power operates through shared but contested interpretations, not just objective constraints</div>
                        <div class="key-point">✊ <strong>Emancipation through Critique:</strong> Understanding ideological structures is the first step toward collective action for change</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔍 <strong>Radical Change Imperative:</strong> The goal is not adaptation or fit but transformation of oppressive arrangements</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Critical and emancipatory IS research uses this lens to study surveillance, algorithmic management, digital labor, and workplace control. It reveals how digital systems can reinforce domination through ideology.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Burrell and Morgan (1979), <em>Sociological paradigms and organisational
                                        analysis</em>. Key contribution: a map of paradigms based on subjective vs
                                    objective assumptions and regulation vs radical change.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Sociology / organization studies (paradigm theory).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta (not a theory type). This is a paradigm lens.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Subjective reality, ideology, emancipation, consciousness, critique.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>You explain social outcomes by looking at how beliefs and ideologies shape what
                                    people see as normal, and how that limits freedom.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for research questions about domination, ideology, and emancipation in digital
                                    life (surveillance, algorithmic control, workplace resistance). Less useful for
                                    narrow prediction questions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Critical and emancipatory IS work continues (especially around digital
                                    responsibility, ethics, and AI harms), but it is not always labeled as "radical
                                    humanism." It often appears as critical theory or emancipatory critique.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Burrell and Morgan's framework is about paradigms, not about one phenomenon. Radical humanism
                        sits on the "subjective" side and the "radical change" side. The key idea is that people can be
                        dominated not only by material structures but also by ideology and taken-for-granted meanings.
                        That is why radical humanism cares about consciousness and emancipation.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that social arrangements can trap people through ideology and distorted
                        consciousness. Digital systems can participate in that trap by shaping what users see, what they
                        believe is possible, and what they accept as normal. The mechanism is critique. You look for how
                        digital practices reproduce domination (for example, workers internalizing metric pressure) and
                        how alternative interpretations and collective action can create emancipation. Boundary
                        conditions are practical. This lens is powerful when there is a clear power issue, but it can be
                        rejected as "too normative" if you do not connect the critique to concrete practices and
                        evidence.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, this paradigm shows up through critical approaches that study surveillance, digital labor,
                        algorithmic management, and harm. It connects naturally to dignity and digital responsibility
                        conversations.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: It helps you see power in places where mainstream models treat technology as neutral.
                        It gives you language for harms, dignity, and emancipation. Weaknesses: It can drift into moral
                        statements without clear empirical grounding. Reviewers may push back if the paper does not show
                        "so what" beyond critique. Common misapplications in IS: Using critical language without
                        connecting it to real organizational practices, or presenting a critique but offering no
                        plausible path to change. Alternatives and competitors: Radical structuralism focuses more on
                        objective structures (institutions, class, material constraints). Interpretive research focuses
                        on meaning without necessarily taking an emancipatory stance.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use radical humanism when the exam question involves ideology, meaning, and
                        emancipation in digital systems (surveillance, AI control, platform labor). Example research
                        question: "How do algorithmic performance systems shape how workers define 'good work' and
                        'self-worth' over time?" Example hypothesis: This lens often avoids classic hypotheses. A good
                        exam move is a claim: "Algorithmic metrics can become internalized as moral judgments, which can
                        reduce workers' sense of autonomy and dignity." What I would measure (simple): Interviews and
                        ethnographic observation of work practices, plus artifacts (dashboards, ranking screens, policy
                        documents). Then analyze how meanings and justifications change. Seminal APA citation: Burrell,
                        G., & Morgan, G. (1979). <em>Sociological paradigms and organisational analysis</em>. Heinemann.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="radical-structuralism-burrell-and-morgan">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge sociology">Sociology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Burrell & Morgan (1979)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Radical Structuralism (Burrell and Morgan)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How structural power relations and material constraints drive conflict and radical transformation</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Social outcomes are shaped primarily by objective structural power relations, not individual beliefs. Real change comes through conflict when structural pressures and contradictions force transformation, not through adaptation or consensus.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🏗️ <strong>Objective Structures:</strong> Material and institutional constraints are real and operate independently of individual awareness</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚔️ <strong>Conflict as Change Driver:</strong> Transformation happens through structural pressures and conflicts, not voluntary adoption</div>
                        <div class="key-point">💰 <strong>Power & Inequality:</strong> Structural arrangements benefit some groups and disadvantage others; ask "who wins and who loses?"</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔄 <strong>Structural Contradictions:</strong> Systems contain internal contradictions that force change when pressures become unbearable</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Useful for understanding platform power dynamics, labor control, regulatory capture, and why digital reforms often fail despite good intentions. Structural incentives override individual motivation.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Burrell and Morgan (1979), <em>Sociological paradigms and organisational
                                        analysis</em>. Radical structuralism is the objective + radical change quadrant.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Sociology / organization studies (paradigm theory).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta (not a theory type).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Objective structures, power, conflict, material constraints, transformation.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>You explain outcomes by focusing on structural power relations (not only individual
                                    beliefs), and you ask how conflicts drive change.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for research questions where structures clearly matter (labor markets,
                                    regulation, platform power, inequality). Less useful for micro-level experience
                                    questions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Shows up indirectly in work on platform power, data governance, and digital
                                    responsibility, but the label "radical structuralism" is not common in IS papers.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Radical structuralism shares the "radical change" goal, but it is more objective than radical
                        humanism. It treats structures as real constraints that shape behavior, conflict, and
                        inequality. Digital systems can reinforce or shift these structures (think of platform
                        monopolies, labor control, and regulatory capture).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that social outcomes are shaped by structural power relations, and real
                        change often comes through conflict. The mechanism is not "people change their minds." It is
                        "structures create pressures and conflicts, and these conflicts force transformation." In IS,
                        this can be used to explain why some digital reforms fail: because structural incentives and
                        power relations block them, even if individuals have good intentions.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS research uses related structural lenses (institutional theory, political economy, critical
                        realism) more often than explicitly calling it radical structuralism. But the exam value is the
                        contrast: if institutional theory explains legitimacy pressures, radical structuralism pushes
                        you to ask: who benefits from the institutional arrangement, and who loses?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: It keeps you honest about power and constraints. It is a good antidote to "managerial
                        optimism" stories about digital transformation. Weaknesses: It can become deterministic if you
                        ignore agency and local practice. It can also be hard to operationalize if you stay at a very
                        abstract level. Common misapplications in IS: Treating every outcome as oppression without
                        careful evidence, or ignoring the micro-level processes through which structures are enacted.
                        Alternatives and competitors: Institutional theory for legitimacy and isomorphism,
                        sociomateriality for practice-level entanglement, and radical humanism for ideology and meaning.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use radical structuralism when the question is about power structures, inequality,
                        and conflict in digital systems (platform dominance, surveillance capitalism, labor control).
                        Example research question: "How do platform governance rules shift bargaining power between
                        platforms and complementors over time?" Example hypothesis: "When a platform tightens control
                        over APIs and data access, complementors' dependence increases and their strategic options
                        narrow." What I would measure (simple): Platform policy changes, API access restrictions,
                        complementor entry/exit, revenue dependence, and qualitative evidence of conflict (public
                        statements, lawsuits, policy debates). Seminal APA citation: Burrell, G., & Morgan, G. (1979).
                        <em>Sociological paradigms and organisational analysis</em>. Heinemann.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="emancipatory-pedagogy">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Freire (1970)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Emancipatory Pedagogy</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How dialogue, critical reflection, and collective action enable people to resist domination and control their lives</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Liberation requires praxis—critical reflection on one's situation combined with collective action to change it. The "banking" model of passive knowledge transfer reproduces domination, while dialogue and co-creation support conscientization (critical consciousness) and emancipation.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">💬 <strong>Dialogue & Co-creation:</strong> Knowledge is created through dialogue between equals, not deposited from expert to passive learner</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🧠 <strong>Conscientization:</strong> Critical reflection on one's world that reveals domination and opens possibilities for change</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚙️ <strong>Praxis:</strong> Reflection plus action—not just thinking about problems, but taking steps to solve them</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔓 <strong>Literacy & Agency:</strong> Understanding how systems work (algorithmic literacy, digital literacy) is necessary for resistance and meaningful participation</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Used in ICT4D, digital inclusion, algorithmic literacy initiatives, and participatory design research. Guides interventions that build critical understanding rather than passive adoption of technology.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Freire (1970), <em>Pedagogy of the Oppressed</em>. Key contribution: education
                                    should be dialogical and liberating, not a "banking" model of depositing knowledge.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Education / critical theory.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type V (design and action) when used as a guide for intervention, and Type II when
                                    used as a critique of domination.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Oppression, dialogue, conscientization, praxis (reflection + action), liberation.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People become able to change their situation when they critically reflect on it and
                                    act together, instead of passively accepting imposed meanings.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for contexts where learning, empowerment, and inequality are central (digital
                                    inclusion, ICT4D, worker training, algorithmic literacy). Less useful for narrow
                                    predictive questions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Most often appears indirectly in ICT4D and critical digital inclusion research. In
                                    top IS outlets, it is more common as an underlying stance than a named theory. (Use
                                    as a critical lens, and be explicit about the intervention.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Freire wrote for contexts of oppression and unequal power, where education can either reproduce
                        domination or support liberation. The "banking" model treats learners as empty containers.
                        Freire argues for dialogue where learners and teachers co-create knowledge and build critical
                        consciousness.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The core proposition is that liberation requires praxis: reflection plus action. In digital
                        contexts, this translates to questions about who controls technology, who understands it, and
                        who has the ability to contest it. A simple example is algorithmic literacy: if people cannot
                        understand how a system shapes them, it is hard to resist harm. Boundary conditions matter. This
                        lens is not a plug-in variable model. It is a critical and action-oriented stance. If you use
                        it, you should be ready to talk about participation, dialogue, and change, not only description.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, emancipatory ideas show up in digital inclusion work, participatory design, and critical
                        perspectives on technology. It also connects to dignity: emancipation is partly about protecting
                        and restoring human dignity in systems that can dehumanize.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: It gives a strong ethical and action orientation. It helps you link research to real
                        change, not only explanation. Weaknesses: It can be criticized for being normative and hard to
                        evaluate with standard positivist criteria. It also requires careful attention to whose voice is
                        included and whose is missing. Common misapplications in IS: Using emancipatory language while
                        still designing top-down interventions, or treating "participation" as a checkbox without real
                        power sharing. Alternatives and competitors: Critical theory traditions, participatory design,
                        and dignity-focused approaches like CARE when the focus is on affronts and responses.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use emancipatory pedagogy when the exam question involves empowerment, digital
                        inclusion, or designing interventions that reduce harm and inequality. Example research
                        question: "How can organizations design AI training so employees can question and reshape AI
                        work practices instead of only learning compliance?" Example hypothesis: "Training programs that
                        include dialogue and reflection will increase employees' perceived agency and reduce blind
                        reliance on AI outputs." What I would measure (simple): Pre/post measures of perceived agency
                        and critical awareness, qualitative evidence from workshops, and behavioral indicators (raising
                        concerns, proposing changes, contesting AI decisions). Seminal APA citation: Freire, P. (1970).
                        <em>Pedagogy of the oppressed</em>. Herder and Herder. # Part 0C. Meta-Theory and Research Craft
                        (From BCIS 6670) This section covers frameworks about how to build, evaluate, and write theory.
                        These are not theories of phenomena, but theories about theorizing itself. They are
                        exam-critical because they help you think like a reviewer and construct strong theoretical
                        arguments.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Part 0C Divider -->
            <div class="part-divider" id="part-0c">
                <div>
                    <h2>🧠 Part 0C: Meta-Theory & Research Craft</h2>
                    <p style="margin: 0; opacity: 0.9; font-size: 0.95rem;">Frameworks about how to build, evaluate, and
                        write theory</p>
                </div>
                <div class="part-count">7 Frameworks</div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="what-constitutes-a-theory-whetten-1989">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge meta">Meta-Framework</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Whetten (1989)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>What Constitutes a Theory (Whetten, 1989)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">A diagnostic framework for evaluating whether theoretical contributions are complete and well-specified</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Complete theories answer four interconnected questions: What (constructs), How (relationships), Why (causal logic), and Who/Where/When (boundary conditions). Missing or weak elements indicate incomplete theorizing.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🔍 <strong>WHAT:</strong> Which constructs and variables belong in the theory? Are any missing or redundant?</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔗 <strong>HOW:</strong> What are the relationships among constructs? How do they connect?</div>
                        <div class="key-point">❓ <strong>WHY:</strong> What is the underlying causal logic? Why should these relationships exist?</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📍 <strong>BOUNDARIES:</strong> When does the theory apply, and when does it break down? For whom, where, and when?</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Essential for exam preparation and evaluating theory contributions in IS research. Provides a fast diagnostic checklist for completeness, helping you think like a reviewer.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Whetten (1989), "What Constitutes a Theoretical Contribution?" <em>Academy of
                                        Management Review</em>. Key contribution: defines what makes a theoretical
                                    contribution complete (what, how, why, who/where/when).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Management/organizational theory (meta-theory).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed, but universally used in IS for evaluating theory contributions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta-framework (Type I analysis). Not a theory of a phenomenon, but guidance for
                                    theory building.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>What (constructs/variables), How (relationships), Why (causal logic), Who/Where/When
                                    (boundary conditions), comprehensiveness vs parsimony.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>A complete theory needs: what factors, how they relate, why those relationships
                                    exist, and under what conditions. Missing any element weakens contribution.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>This is a framework for evaluating contributions, not a model to test empirically.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Whetten wrote this as an AMR guide for reviewers and authors. The problem he addressed is simple:
                        many papers claim <span class="key-term">theoretical contribution</span> but do not clearly
                        articulate what makes the
                        contribution theoretical. His solution is to break theory into building blocks (what, how, why,
                        boundaries) and show what "adding value" looks like at each level.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        Whetten's framework provides four essential questions every theory must answer
                    </div>

                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>1️⃣ WHAT</h4>
                            <p>Which <span class="construct-badge">constructs</span> and <span
                                    class="construct-badge">variables</span> should be included? Are any missing or
                                redundant?</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>2️⃣ HOW</h4>
                            <p>What are the <span class="key-term">relationships</span> among constructs? Arrows,
                                correlations, processes?</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>3️⃣ WHY</h4>
                            <p>What is the underlying <span class="key-term">causal logic</span>? Why should we expect
                                these relationships?</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>4️⃣ WHO/WHERE/WHEN</h4>
                            <p>What are the <span class="key-term">boundary conditions</span>? When does the theory
                                apply, and when does it break down?</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        If a comps question asks "evaluate this theory," run through these four elements systematically.
                        If any are weak or missing, you have a structured critique.
                    </div>

                    <h4 style="margin-top: 1.5rem; color: var(--primary-color);">Extended from BCIS 6670 StudyGuide:
                    </h4>

                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Whetten's 7 Reviewer Questions</strong> are exam-gold:
                        <ul class="theory-list">
                            <li><strong>"What's new?"</strong> - Novelty of contribution</li>
                            <li><strong>"So what?"</strong> - Significance and impact</li>
                            <li><strong>"Why so?"</strong> - Theoretical justification</li>
                            <li><strong>"Well done?"</strong> - Design quality</li>
                            <li><strong>"Done well?"</strong> - Execution quality</li>
                            <li><strong>"Why now?"</strong> - Timeliness and relevance</li>
                            <li><strong>"Who cares?"</strong> - Target audience</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Incremental vs Radical Contributions:</strong> Whetten distinguishes
                        <span class="construct-badge">incremental</span> (improving existing theory) from
                        <span class="construct-badge">radical</span> (challenging foundational assumptions).
                        This helps frame novelty precisely, especially alongside Sun et al. (2025).
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>Whetten is widely cited in IS for the same reason it is cited in management: it gives a fast
                        checklist for completeness. In BCIS 6670, Whetten pairs with <strong>Gregor (2006)</strong> for
                        type of theory,
                        <strong>Markus & Robey (1988)</strong> for causal structure, and <strong>Burton-Jones et al.
                            (2021)</strong> for digital-specific
                        theorizing moves.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <h4 style="color: #059669;">✅ Strengths:</h4>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li>Simple, memorable, fast diagnostic tool</li>
                        <li>Works across paradigms</li>
                        <li>Helps avoid incomplete theorizing</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h4 style="color: #dc2626;">❌ Weaknesses:</h4>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li>Can feel like a checklist rather than real theorizing if applied mechanically</li>
                        <li>Boundary conditions ("who/where/when") often weakest in published work</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h4 style="color: #f59e0b;">🔄 Common Misapplications:</h4>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li>Treating it as a template to fill in rather than critical thinking tool</li>
                        <li>Weak "why" sections that only restate relationships without causal mechanisms</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h4 style="color: #4f46e5;">🔗 Alternatives/Competitors:</h4>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Gregor (2006)</strong> for theory types</li>
                        <li><strong>Sutton & Staw</strong> for "what theory is not"</li>
                        <li><strong>Burton-Jones et al.</strong> for digital theorizing shifts</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">🎯 Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        When a question asks "critique this theory" or "what is missing," apply Whetten's four elements
                        systematically.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example Research Question:</strong> "What theoretical elements are needed to explain AI
                        delegation as a sociotechnical governance mechanism?"</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure in comps:</strong>
                        <ol class="framework-steps">
                            <li><strong>WHAT constructs:</strong> delegation willingness, AI capability, accountability
                                structure</li>
                            <li><strong>HOW they relate:</strong> feedback loops, appraisal-driven updates</li>
                            <li><strong>WHY:</strong> delegation requires authority + trust + capability assessment</li>
                            <li><strong>BOUNDARIES:</strong> works for agentic AI in enterprise settings, less clear for
                                fully autonomous systems</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Whetten, D. A. (1989). What constitutes a theoretical
                        contribution?
                        <em>Academy of Management Review, 14</em>(4), 490-495.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="theory-types-gregor-2006">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Gregor (2006)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Theory Types (Gregor, 2006)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">A taxonomy organizing theories by primary goal and components, helping authors communicate their theoretical contribution</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Different research purposes require different theory types, each with distinct primary goals and components. Matching your theory type to your research goal improves clarity and helps reviewers apply appropriate evaluation criteria.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">📋 <strong>Type I (Analysis):</strong> Describes and classifies what exists; no causal claims or predictions</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔍 <strong>Type II (Explanation):</strong> Explains why and how things work; offers causal logic but no formal predictions</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Type IV (Explanation + Prediction):</strong> The most common in positivist IS; combines causal story with testable hypotheses</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🛠️ <strong>Type V (Design & Action):</strong> Prescriptive; offers design principles and interventions to accomplish specific goals</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Essential for exam preparation and positioning theory contributions in IS. Helps you communicate what kind of theory you are building and why your criteria for success differ from other types.
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Gregor (2006), "The Nature of Theory in Information Systems," <em>MIS Quarterly
                                        Research Perspectives</em>. Key contribution: taxonomy of five theory types in
                                    IS (Analysis, Explanation, Prediction, EP, Design/Action).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (meta-theory about IS theory).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type I (analysis/classification) by her own framework.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Five theory types (I-V), primary goals, components (constructs, relationships,
                                    scope, causal explanations, testable propositions, prescriptive statements).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Different research goals require different theory types. Matching type to goal
                                    improves clarity and evaluation.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>This is a classification framework, not a phenomenon theory. Use it to position and
                                    evaluate theory, not to test hypotheses.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Gregor argues that IS borrows theories from many reference disciplines, which creates confusion
                        about what counts as "theory." Her solution is a taxonomy that organizes theories by primary
                        goal and components. This helps authors communicate what kind of contribution they are making
                        and helps reviewers apply appropriate criteria.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        Gregor's Five Theory Types — each serves a different research purpose
                    </div>

                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Type I: Analysis</h4>
                            <p>Describes <em>what is</em>, classifies phenomena. <strong>No causal claims.</strong>
                                Example: taxonomies, frameworks.</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Type II: Explanation</h4>
                            <p>Explains <em>what, why, how</em>. Causal explanations but <strong>no
                                    predictions</strong>. Example: process theories.</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Type III: Prediction</h4>
                            <p>Predicts <em>what will happen</em>, not why. Testable propositions <strong>without causal
                                    explanation</strong>. Rare.</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Type IV: EP</h4>
                            <p>Both explains and predicts. <mark>Most common</mark> in positivist IS research. Causal
                                story + testable hypotheses.</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Type V: Design & Action</h4>
                            <p><strong>Prescriptive.</strong> Says how to do something. Design principles and
                                guidelines. Common in DSR.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="info-box">
                        <h4>📋 Gregor Table 3: Seven Theory Components</h4>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Means of representation</li>
                            <li>Primary constructs</li>
                            <li>Statements of relationship</li>
                            <li>Scope</li>
                            <li>Causal explanations</li>
                            <li>Testable propositions</li>
                            <li>Prescriptive statements</li>
                        </ol>
                        <p style="margin-bottom:0;"><strong>Not every type includes every component:</strong> Type I =
                            1-4; Type II adds 5; Type III adds 6; Type IV = 1-6; Type V = all 7.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Variance vs Process:</strong> Variance theories ask "how much variance in Y is explained
                        by X?" — often cross-sectional. Process theories focus on sequences and need longitudinal
                        evidence. A comps trap is papers that claim process but only test variance.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>Gregor's taxonomy is widely used in IS for positioning contributions. In BCIS 6670, it pairs with
                        Whetten for completeness checking and Markus & Robey for causal structure. Together they give a
                        comprehensive lens for evaluating theory quality.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Strengths<strong>: Clear taxonomy; helps authors position contributions; reduces confusion
                                about what "theory" means; widely accepted in IS. - </strong>Weaknesses<strong>: Some
                                theories blend types (e.g., Type II + Type V); strict classification can oversimplify
                                complex contributions. - </strong>Common misapplications<strong>: Claiming Type IV (EP)
                                but only providing correlation evidence; mixing levels without cross-level mechanisms;
                                ignoring boundary conditions. - </strong>Alternatives/competitors**: Whetten for theory
                            completeness; Sutton & Staw for "what theory is not"; Burton-Jones for digital-specific
                            theorizing.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p><strong>Exam use note:</strong> When asked "what type of theory is this," use Gregor's five
                        types. When asked "what's missing," check which components (Table 3) are present vs absent.
                        <strong>Example research question:</strong> "What type of theory is needed to guide the design
                        of human-AI delegation interfaces?" <strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> Not applicable—this is
                        a classification framework. <strong>What I would measure:</strong> In comps, I would classify
                        the theory type (likely Type V: Design/Action for interface design) and then show which
                        components are present: constructs (delegation affordances, feedback mechanisms), relationships
                        (how affordances enable delegation), scope (enterprise AI contexts), and prescriptive statements
                        (design principles for delegation interfaces). <strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Gregor, S.
                        (2006). The nature of theory in information systems. <em>MIS Quarterly, 30</em>(3), 611-642.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="3-dimensions-of-causal-structure-markus-robey-1988">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Markus & Robey (1988)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>3 Dimensions of Causal Structure (Markus & Robey, 1988)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">A framework for making causal assumptions explicit in IT and organizational change research</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Much confusion in IT research comes from making different causal assumptions without stating them. This framework makes three causal dimensions explicit: who/what drives change, how causality works (variance vs process), and at what level.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🔧 <strong>Causal Agency:</strong> Is change driven by technology, organization, or emergent interaction between them?</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📊 <strong>Logical Structure:</strong> Variance theorizing (explaining outcome variation) or process theorizing (explaining sequences of events)?</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📍 <strong>Level of Analysis:</strong> Individual, group, organization, or societal level—and do mechanisms connect across levels?</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚙️ <strong>Research Design Implications:</strong> Choices about agency, logic, and level determine what evidence counts and what methods are needed</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Essential meta-framework for exam answers about IT and organizational change. Helps you articulate whether your theory is technological imperative, organizational imperative, or emergent; and whether you are building a variance or process explanation.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Markus & Robey (1988)</mark>, "Information Technology and Organizational Change: Causal
                                    Structure in Theory and Research," <em>Management Science</em>. Key contribution:
                                    framework for analyzing causal structure across <span class="construct-badge">causal agency</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">logical structure</span> (variance vs process), and
                                    <span class="construct-badge">level of analysis</span>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS/organizational change (<mark>Management Science</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed into IS, but IS-adjacent because it is directly about IT and organizational
                                    change.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta-framework (closest to Type I: analysis/classification). It is about making
                                    causal assumptions explicit, not predicting a specific outcome.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Causal agency</span> (<span class="construct-badge">technological imperative</span> / <span class="construct-badge">organizational imperative</span> / <span class="construct-badge">emergent</span>),
                                    <span class="construct-badge">variance vs process</span>, <span class="construct-badge">level of analysis</span> (individual/group/org/society).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Many disagreements come from being unclear about "what causes what" and "how
                                    causality works." If we make these dimensions explicit, theorizing and research
                                    design become cleaner.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for critiquing and designing theorizing, not as a substitute for a phenomenon
                                    theory.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Markus and Robey</mark> start from a practical problem: IT and organizational change research often
                        makes contradictory claims, which makes generalization difficult. A big part of the problem is
                        that papers assume different kinds of <mark>causality</mark>. Their move is to critique the causal structure
                        underneath theories rather than only debating theory content.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The framework asks three questions that are very usable in comps answers, making causal assumptions explicit
                    </div>

                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>1️⃣ Causal Agency</h4>
                            <p>What drives change—technology, organization, or emergent interaction?</p>
                            <ul class="theory-list">
                                <li><span class="construct-badge">Technological imperative</span>: Technology determines outcomes</li>
                                <li><span class="construct-badge">Organizational imperative</span>: Organization/context determines outcomes</li>
                                <li><span class="construct-badge">Emergent perspective</span>: Outcomes emerge from interaction</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>

                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>2️⃣ Logical Structure</h4>
                            <p>Variance theorizing or process theorizing?</p>
                            <ul class="theory-list">
                                <li><span class="construct-badge">Variance</span>: Focus on explaining variation in outcomes (correlation, regression)</li>
                                <li><span class="construct-badge">Process</span>: Focus on sequences of events and mechanisms over time</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>

                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>3️⃣ Level of Analysis</h4>
                            <p>Individual, group, organization, or society?</p>
                            <div class="critical-point">
                                Mismatch between theory level and data level creates mis-specification
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        These choices change your method needs. Variance theorizing can often tolerate cross-sectional evidence, while process theorizing usually needs longitudinal evidence. If level of analysis is mixed without cross-level mechanisms, the model is mis-specified from the start.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In BCIS 6670, this connects naturally to <mark>Sarker et al. (2019)</mark> because the six types in the
                        sociotechnical axis also imply different causal stories about the social and the technical. That
                        cross-mapping is a good comps move because it shows you can compare theories structurally.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Fast tool for reviewer-like thinking; makes variance vs process explicit;
                                helps explain contradictions as "structural" not personal.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Not a phenomenon theory; some phenomena are truly multi-level
                                and the framework warns more than it solves.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Using process language but only cross-sectional tests; mixing levels without cross-level
                                mechanisms; claiming "emergent" while modeling technology deterministically.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Whetten</mark> for completeness and <mark>Gregor</mark> for theory types.
                            This framework is a complement.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        When asked "is my theorizing framed correctly," apply Markus & Robey's three dimensions.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "Is my theorizing about AI
                        delegation framed as <span class="construct-badge">technological imperative</span>, <span class="construct-badge">organizational imperative</span>, or <span class="construct-badge">emergent</span>, and do my
                        methods match that causal structure?" <strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "In contexts with
                        high task uncertainty, emergent human-AI interaction processes explain delegation outcomes
                        better than a pure technological imperative model."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong>
                        <ul class="theory-list">
                            <li><strong>For variance:</strong> IV/DV in a cross-sectional model with controls</li>
                            <li><strong>For process:</strong> sequences of events (adoption, failures, overrides, redesign) and longitudinal trace data</li>
                            <li>In both cases, make the <span class="construct-badge">level of analysis</span> explicit</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Markus, M. L., & Robey, D.
                        (1988)</mark>. Information technology and organizational change: Causal structure in theory and
                        research. <em>Management Science, 34</em>(5), 583-598. <em>Grounding in BCIS 6670
                            materials:</em> <code>BCIS 6670/Week 3 & 4/Papers/Information_Technology_and_Org.pdf</code>
                        (scan/OCR) and <code>BCIS 6670/StudyGuide/session3.html</code>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="next-generation-is-theorizing-burton-jones-et-al-2021">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Burton-Jones et al. (2021)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Next-Generation IS Theorizing (Burton-Jones et al., 2021)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">A call to move beyond theoretical templates toward theorizing that fits digital phenomena</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> IS theorizing often relies on narrow templates borrowed from reference disciplines. Next-generation theorizing requires moving beyond templates, developing better mechanisms, and specifying tighter boundary conditions that actually fit digital phenomena.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Theorizing Shifts:</strong> Named moves in how you theorize (e.g., from technology-centric to sociotechnical, from adoption to practice change)</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔧 <strong>Mechanism Building:</strong> Going beyond listing variables to explaining how and why things work in specific contexts</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📍 <strong>Boundary Conditions:</strong> Specifying when theory applies, not assuming universal applicability across all contexts</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📝 <strong>Digital-Native Theorizing:</strong> Building theory that fits the phenomenon rather than forcing phenomena into pre-existing templates</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Essential for evaluating and constructing theory contributions in exam answers. Helps you name the theorizing shift you are making and justify why it fits the digital phenomenon you are studying.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Burton-Jones et al. (2021)</mark>, "Next-Generation Information Systems Theorizing: A Call
                                    to Action," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: argues IS needs
                                    <mark>"next-generation theorizing"</mark> and proposes shifts/strategies for how we theorize
                                    digital phenomena.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (meta-theorizing about theorizing).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">IS-native</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta-framework. It is not a phenomenon theory, it is a framework about how
                                    theorizing should change.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">"Next-generation" theorizing shifts</span> and <span class="construct-badge">strategies</span>; <span class="construct-badge">Motivate/Create/Mobilize</span> logic
                                    in the paper.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>The paper argues that how we theorize shapes what we can see and explain. New
                                    digital phenomena require moving beyond narrow theory templates and improving how we
                                    build mechanisms and boundaries.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>It is guidance for theorizing, not a causal model for an outcome. It helps you
                                    evaluate and craft theory sections, not estimate coefficients.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>The paper is written as a <mark>call to action</mark>. Its starting point is that IS faces fast-moving <mark>digital
                        phenomena</mark>, but our theorizing practices can lag behind. The "origin" problem is not one
                        empirical puzzle, but how we build explanations and what we treat as theoretical contribution.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        A meta-framework that helps diagnose whether theory sections are stuck in templates versus doing real digital theorizing
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        A practical way to use it is to show that you can name the shift you are making (what changes in theorizing) and then justify why that shift fits the digital phenomenon.
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        Template thinking: "copy a reference discipline model and add moderators" versus real digital theorizing that fits the phenomenon
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In BCIS 6670, the paper is used alongside <mark>Whetten</mark>, <mark>Gregor</mark>, and <mark>Markus & Robey</mark>. The combined exam
                        move is: <mark>Whetten</mark> checks completeness, <mark>Gregor</mark> positions the type of theory, <mark>Markus & Robey</mark> checks
                        causal structure (variance vs process, level), and <mark>Burton-Jones</mark> pushes you to update the
                        theorizing itself for digital contexts.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Useful to break "template thinking"; good language for explaining why new
                                digital phenomena need new theorizing moves.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Because it
                                is meta, it can stay abstract if you do not translate it into concrete theoretical
                                propositions and boundaries.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Treating it as
                                motivational text but not changing actual theorizing choices (<span class="construct-badge">constructs</span>, <span class="construct-badge">mechanisms</span>,
                                <span class="construct-badge">boundaries</span>).</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Whetten</mark> and <mark>Gregor</mark> are the closest
                            complements; this paper does not replace them, it pushes the field toward stronger digital
                            theorizing.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "What shift in IS theorizing is needed to explain
                        delegation and accountability in human-AI systems?"</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        This is a meta-framework, so an exam-appropriate move is to state propositions about how a theorizing
                        shift changes what can be seen (lens) rather than a statistical hypothesis.
                    </div>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> In comps, I would show which strategy the paper follows, what it
                        <span class="construct-badge">Motivates</span>, what it <span class="construct-badge">Creates</span>, and how it <span class="construct-badge">Mobilizes</span>. This is conceptual evidence rather than
                        statistical measurement.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Burton-Jones, A., Butler, B. S.,
                        Scott, S. V., & Xu, S. X. (2021)</mark>. Next-generation information systems theorizing: A call to
                        action. <em>MIS Quarterly, 45</em>(1), 301-314. <em>Grounding in BCIS 6670 materials:</em>
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 3 & 4/Papers/burton_jones_full.txt</code> and
                        <code>BCIS 6670/StudyGuide/session3.html</code>.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="writing-is-papers-framework-baird-2021">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Baird (2021)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Writing IS Papers Framework (Baird, 2021)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Five elements for writing strong IS papers that clearly communicate tension and present credible resolution</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> A publishable IS paper is not just "a topic plus a method." It must have a clear tension or puzzle that the paper resolves for a specific audience. Writing matters, and the process of "middle-out" writing—starting with theory, then evidence—is more effective than linear writing.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Focus:</strong> A clear area of focus—what the paper addresses and why it matters</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📚 <strong>Background:</strong> Existing knowledge and context that sets up the puzzle</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚡ <strong>Theoretical Tension:</strong> The conflict or assumption that breaks down in a new digital context</div>
                        <div class="key-point">✅ <strong>Resolution:</strong> How the paper credibly resolves the tension with evidence and argumentation</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Practical guidance for writing exam answers and research papers. Helps you frame contributions using "assumption challenging" rather than "gap spotting"—a stronger rhetorical move.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Baird (2021)</mark>, "On Writing Research Articles Well: A Guide for Writing IS Papers,"
                                    Journal of the Association for Information Systems. Key contribution: five elements
                                    for writing strong IS papers (<span class="construct-badge">focus</span>, <span class="construct-badge">background</span>, <span class="construct-badge">theoretical tension</span>, <span class="construct-badge">resolution</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">guidelines</span>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (research writing craft).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">IS-native</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Practical framework (closest to Type V design/action for writing).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Area of focus</span>, <span class="construct-badge">background</span>, <span class="construct-badge">theoretical tension</span>, <span class="construct-badge">resolution</span>, <span class="construct-badge">guidelines for future
                                    application</span>; <span class="construct-badge">assumption challenging</span> vs <span class="construct-badge">gap spotting</span>; <span class="construct-badge">"middle-out" writing</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>A paper becomes publishable when it clearly communicates tension and resolves it for
                                    a specific audience. The writing process matters (outline first, write middle-out,
                                    intro last).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Guidance for writing, not a phenomenon theory. Works best when paired with a real
                                    theoretical idea and evidence.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Baird</mark> wrote this as practical guidance for IS researchers (especially theory papers). In Week 1
                        notes, the key message is that a strong paper is not just "a topic plus a method." It is an
                        argument with a clear <span class="construct-badge">tension</span> and a credible <span class="construct-badge">resolution</span> that matters for a specific <mark>audience</mark>.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The five elements are the backbone for writing strong IS papers
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>1️⃣ Focus</h4>
                            <p><span class="construct-badge">Area of focus</span> - what the paper addresses</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>2️⃣ Background</h4>
                            <p>Context and existing knowledge</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>3️⃣ Theoretical Tension</h4>
                            <p>The conflict or puzzle that needs resolution</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>4️⃣ Resolution</h4>
                            <p>How the paper resolves the tension</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>5️⃣ Guidelines</h4>
                            <p><span class="construct-badge">Guidelines for future application</span></p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        For comps, the useful move is <span class="construct-badge">"assumption challenging"</span> instead of <span class="construct-badge">"gap spotting"</span>. Gap spotting is "nobody studied X." Assumption challenging is "the field assumes X, but that assumption fails in this new digital context." That frames contribution better.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>As a meta tool, this pairs naturally with <mark>Whetten</mark> and <mark>Gregor</mark>. <mark>Whetten</mark> helps check completeness
                        (what/how/why/boundaries), <mark>Gregor</mark> helps position the type of theory, and <mark>Baird</mark> helps you present
                        the tension and audience clearly so a reviewer can see the value.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Very practical; centers tension and audience; helps a PhD student write a
                                coherent paper.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> If used as a rigid template, it can make
                                writing feel robotic.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Re-labeling gap
                                spotting as assumption challenging; using the five elements but still having a weak
                                resolution; forgetting to include real guidelines for application.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Whetten</mark> for theory completeness; <mark>Sun et al.</mark> for
                            novelty/rigor/relevance lens in editorial context.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "What theoretical tension am I resolving, and which
                        taken-for-granted assumption should I challenge to resolve it?"</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        In comps, show the tension clearly and tie the resolution directly to it.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "<span class="construct-badge">Assumption-challenging</span> introductions lead reviewers to perceive higher
                        novelty than pure <span class="construct-badge">gap-spotting</span> introductions, holding execution constant."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> Coding of introductions (<span class="construct-badge">assumption challenging</span> vs <span class="construct-badge">gap spotting</span>) and
                        reviewer assessments if data exists.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Baird, A. (2021)</mark>. On writing research
                        articles well: A guide for writing IS papers. <em>Journal of the Association for Information
                            Systems, 22</em>(5), 1197-1211. <em>Grounding in BCIS 6670 materials:</em>
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 1/Notes/Handout_2_Required_Readings.md</code> and
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 1/Papers/Baird_WritingResearchPaper_JAIS2021.pdf</code>.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="reviewing-framework-q-r-sarker-et-al-2023">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Sarker et al. (2023)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Reviewing Framework (q-r) (Sarker et al., 2023)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">A framework for developmental and paradigm-aware reviewing that separates idea quality from execution quality</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> The q-r framework separates quality of idea (q) from quality of execution (r). A weak idea is rarely saved by good methods (weak q, strong r is still weak). Conversely, a great idea with weak execution can often be improved. Developmental reviewing coupled with paradigm awareness reduces unfair cross-tradition criticism.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">💡 <strong>q = Quality of Idea:</strong> Is the idea important, interesting, and novel for the target audience?</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚙️ <strong>r = Quality of Execution:</strong> Is the design, evidence, and writing strong enough to support the idea?</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Developmental Stance:</strong> Help authors improve even if rejecting; distinguish fatal flaws from fixable issues</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🌐 <strong>Paradigm Awareness:</strong> Different research traditions have different standards; evaluate within paradigm, not across</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Helps exam writers position their answers and theory contributions with reviewer awareness. Teaches how to distinguish idea-level contributions from execution improvements.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Sarker et al. (2023)</mark>, "Editorial: Some Thoughts on Reviewing for Information Systems
                                    Research and Other Leading Information Systems Journals," <em>Information Systems
                                        Research</em>. Key contribution: <span class="construct-badge">q-r framework</span> (<span class="construct-badge">q</span> = quality of
                                    idea, <span class="construct-badge">r</span> = quality of execution) and practical guidance for <span class="construct-badge">developmental</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">paradigm-aware</span>, <span class="construct-badge">civil reviewing</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS reviewing/editorial practice.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">IS-native</span> (ISR editorial).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Practical guidance (closest to Type V design/action for reviewing).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">q-r framework</span>, <span class="construct-badge">developmental reviewing</span>, <span class="construct-badge">paradigm awareness</span>, <span class="construct-badge">reviewer role metaphors</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">fatal flaws</span> vs <span class="construct-badge">fixable issues</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Separating <span class="construct-badge">q</span> and <span class="construct-badge">r</span> improves feedback: <span class="construct-badge">r</span> is often improvable, <span class="construct-badge">q</span> is harder to fix.
                                    <span class="construct-badge">Paradigm awareness</span> reduces unfair reviews across research traditions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Framework for reviewing and positioning, not a phenomenon theory. In comps, it helps
                                    me write reviewer-aware answers.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>This editorial comes from the <mark>ISR</mark> reviewing process and tries to make evaluation standards
                        explicit. The BCIS 6670 Week 1 notes emphasize the <span class="construct-badge">developmental</span> goal: reviews should help
                        authors improve even when the paper is rejected.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The q-r framework separates idea quality from execution quality, improving feedback and evaluation
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>q = Quality of Idea</h4>
                            <p>"Is the idea important and interesting?"</p>
                            <div class="critical-point">
                                Weak q is rarely saved by fancy methods
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>r = Quality of Execution</h4>
                            <p>"Is the execution solid?"</p>
                            <div class="exam-tip">
                                r can often be improved through revision
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        For comps, the direct implication is: fix "So what?" first, then defend design and execution.
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        The editorial emphasizes <span class="construct-badge">paradigm-aware reviewing</span>. Criteria differ across
                        positivist, interpretive, design science, and other traditions, and reviewers should not apply
                        one paradigm's criteria to another.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In practice, this sits naturally next to <mark>Whetten</mark> and <mark>Sun et al.</mark>. <mark>Whetten</mark> checks theory
                        completeness. <mark>Sun</mark> helps frame novelty with rigor and relevance. <mark>Sarker</mark> makes "quality of idea"
                        vs "quality of execution" explicit. In comps answers, using these together sounds
                        reviewer-aware.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Fast evaluation tool; normalizes developmental and civil reviewing; makes
                                paradigm awareness explicit.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> If <span class="construct-badge">q</span> is treated as only
                                novelty, it can undervalue replication and consolidation; if <span class="construct-badge">r</span> becomes method
                                fetishization, it can reward complexity over clarity.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Mixing <span class="construct-badge">q</span> and <span class="construct-badge">r</span> (criticizing method when the real issue is weak
                                question); ignoring paradigm; unprofessional tone.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Sun et al.</mark> for more nuance on novelty; <mark>Whetten</mark> for
                            theory completeness; <mark>Gregor</mark> for theory types.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        When a question asks "evaluate this study," separate <span class="construct-badge">q</span> from <span class="construct-badge">r</span> explicitly.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "Does this study have high <span class="construct-badge">q</span> (important
                        idea) and high <span class="construct-badge">r</span> (rigorous execution), and which dimension is the bottleneck?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Reviewer recommendations are more positive when <span class="construct-badge">q</span> is high, even if <span class="construct-badge">r</span>
                        is initially low, because <span class="construct-badge">r</span> is perceived as improvable."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> Coding of reviewer comments into <span class="construct-badge">q</span> vs <span class="construct-badge">r</span> themes, decision outcomes, and revision trajectories. In
                        comps, I write the answer to show <span class="construct-badge">q</span> clearly and then defend <span class="construct-badge">r</span>.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Sarker, S., Whitley, E. A., Goh, K.-Y., Hong, Y., Mahring, M., Sanyal,
                        P., Su, N., Xu, H., Xu, J. D., Zhang, J., & Zhao, H. (2023)</mark>. Editorial: Some thoughts on
                        reviewing for information systems research and other leading information systems journals.
                        <em>Information Systems Research, 34</em>(4), 1321-1338. <em>Grounding in BCIS 6670
                            materials:</em> <code>BCIS 6670/Week 1/Notes/Handout_2_Required_Readings.md</code> and the
                        ISR editorial PDF in <code>BCIS 6670/Week 1/Papers/</code>.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="novelty-rigor-relevance-triad-sun-et-al-2025">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Sun et al. (2025)</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Novelty-Rigor-Relevance Triad (Sun et al., 2025)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">A balanced evaluation framework that redefines novelty in relation to rigor and relevance for IS research</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Evaluating novelty alone creates inconsistency and leads to "interesting but unrigorous" work or "rigorous but who cares" contributions. The triad requires balancing novelty with rigorous logic and clear relevance for the intended audience. Novelty can take multiple forms: new mechanisms, new boundary conditions, new theory integration, or improved conceptual clarity.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">✨ <strong>Novelty (Redefined):</strong> New mechanisms, boundary conditions, theory integration, or conceptual clarity—not just new variables</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Rigor:</strong> Why the logic and evidence are credible and convincing, regardless of paradigm</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📢 <strong>Relevance:</strong> Who cares and why now? What audience does this matter for?</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚖️ <strong>Balanced Contribution:</strong> All three elements must be present and defended; tradeoffs must be explicit</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> The latest (2025) editorial guidance for contribution evaluation. Helps exam writers frame contributions that are simultaneously novel, rigorous, and relevant. Clarifies that novelty looks different across paradigms.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Sun et al. (2025)</mark>, "Rebalancing Novelty with Rigor and Relevance in Information
                                    Systems Research," <em>MIS Quarterly</em> (Editor's Comments). Key contribution:
                                    argues <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span> must be evaluated together with <span class="construct-badge">rigor</span> and <span class="construct-badge">relevance</span>; novelty looks
                                    different across paradigms.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS editorial/reviewing philosophy (<mark>MISQ</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">IS-native</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta-framework (Type I + Type V flavor): classification + prescriptive guidance for
                                    authors/reviewers.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Novelty</span>, <span class="construct-badge">rigor</span>, <span class="construct-badge">relevance</span>; tradeoffs and tensions; novelty across paradigms;
                                    pitfalls (<span class="construct-badge">post-hoc theorizing</span>, <span class="construct-badge">construct proliferation</span>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Evaluating <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span> alone creates inconsistency and "interesting but weak" work. The
                                    triad pushes the field to define novelty as substantively necessary and balanced
                                    with <span class="construct-badge">rigor</span> and <span class="construct-badge">relevance</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Framework for evaluating contribution, not a phenomenon theory. In comps, it helps
                                    me defend why my contribution matters now.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Sun et al.</mark> argue that <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span> has become a dominant criterion in IS, but it is often used
                        inconsistently. That ambiguity confuses authors and leads to unbalanced work (either <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span>
                        without <span class="construct-badge">rigor</span>, or <span class="construct-badge">rigor</span> without a real "why care"). The triad is meant to rebalance evaluation
                        and clarify what <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span> means across paradigms.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The triad is a contribution-evaluation lens: novelty must be balanced with rigor and relevance
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>1️⃣ Novelty</h4>
                            <p>Not just "new variables" - can be new <span class="construct-badge">mechanisms</span>, new <span class="construct-badge">boundary conditions</span>, new <span class="construct-badge">theory integration</span>, or new <span class="construct-badge">conceptual clarity</span></p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>2️⃣ Rigor</h4>
                            <p>Why the logic and evidence are credible</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>3️⃣ Relevance</h4>
                            <p>Must matter for an audience - who cares and why now</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        In comps answers, use it to frame contribution: novelty must be supported by rigor and must matter for an audience (relevance).
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>This pairs naturally with <mark>Sarker's</mark> <span class="construct-badge">q-r framework</span>. <span class="construct-badge">q</span> is not only <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span>, but <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span> is one major
                        ingredient of <span class="construct-badge">q</span>. <mark>Whetten</mark> helps check completeness of the theoretical argument. Together, they
                        give a reviewer-like way to position a paper's contribution.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Helps avoid novelty obsession; makes contribution debates more
                                consistent; fits multiple paradigms.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Still requires
                                judgment, and authors can game it by claiming <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span> post-hoc without actually changing
                                the theory.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Equating <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span> with <span class="construct-badge">construct
                                proliferation</span>; using <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span> language to hide weak mechanisms; ignoring <span class="construct-badge">relevance</span> (who
                                cares).</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">q-r</span> (<mark>Sarker</mark>) for simpler evaluation;
                            <mark>Whetten</mark> for completeness; <mark>Gregor</mark> for theory types.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        When positioning contribution, explicitly state <span class="construct-badge">novelty</span>, <span class="construct-badge">rigor</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">relevance</span>.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How do I justify that my
                        contribution is novel, rigorous, and relevant, without overstating novelty?"</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> In comps, I would explicitly state:
                        <ul class="theory-list">
                            <li><span class="construct-badge">Novelty</span> (what is new)</li>
                            <li><span class="construct-badge">Rigor</span> (why the logic and evidence are credible)</li>
                            <li><span class="construct-badge">Relevance</span> (who cares and why now)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Sun, H. (2025)</mark>. Rebalancing novelty with rigor and
                        relevance in information systems research. <em>MIS Quarterly.</em> <em>Grounding in BCIS 6670
                            materials:</em> <code>BCIS 6670/Week 1/Notes/Handout_2_Required_Readings.md</code> and the
                        MISQ editorial PDF in <code>BCIS 6670/Week 1/Papers/</code>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Davis (1989), "Perceived usefulness, perceived ease of use, and user acceptance of
                                    information technology," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: a parsimonious
                                    belief based model of IT acceptance with validated PU and PEOU measures.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (built on social psychology logic from TRA/TPB).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native, but strongly borrowed in its causal logic (beliefs -> intention ->
                                    behavior).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type IV (explanation and prediction): TAM explains why adoption happens and predicts
                                    intention/use.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Perceived usefulness (PU), perceived ease of use (PEOU), attitude (in early
                                    versions), behavioral intention, and use.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People adopt a system when they believe it helps them perform better (PU) and does
                                    not feel hard to use (PEOU). Ease of use also increases usefulness because "easy"
                                    systems are easier to see as helpful.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Strongest in voluntary contexts, early adoption stages, and work productivity tools.
                                    Weaker in mandatory use settings, habit-driven use, and settings where social
                                    influence, identity, or risk dominates.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Direct "pure TAM" tests in MISQ/ISR/JAIS/JMIS are less common, but TAM still shows
                                    up as a baseline in adoption work (including analytics adoption) and in newer
                                    conversations about why AI is not "just another IT" (trust, explainability,
                                    algorithm aversion).</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>TAM started with a practical IS problem: organizations were investing in new systems, but many
                        systems were underused or used in a shallow way. Davis's move was to translate social psychology
                        into a small set of beliefs that fit workplace IT. Instead of modeling many attitudes and norms,
                        he focused on two beliefs that are easy to recognize in real projects: "Will this help me do my
                        job better?" (perceived usefulness) and "Will this be hard?" (perceived ease of use). The
                        intellectual roots matter in comps answers. In the Theory of Reasoned Action, Fishbein and Ajzen
                        argue that behavior is driven by intention, and intention is shaped by beliefs and attitudes
                        (and, in later work, norms). Ajzen's Theory of Planned Behavior extends this logic by adding
                        perceived behavioral control. TAM keeps the belief -> intention -> behavior logic, but it
                        narrows the belief set to IT-relevant beliefs. That is why TAM became a cumulative research
                        programme quickly: it was simple, it was measurable, and it traveled across systems and
                        settings. Affiliation note: I did not have the original MISQ PDF in my local workspace when
                        writing this section, so I am not listing Davis's institutional affiliation here (logged in QA).
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The core claim is that PU and PEOU explain a large part of why people form intentions to use a
                        system, and why they later use it. PEOU also influences PU because when a system feels
                        difficult, people are less likely to see it as helpful. In the earliest formulation, attitude
                        toward using the system plays a role, but many later TAM studies drop the attitude construct and
                        connect beliefs directly to intention. The exam move is to be explicit about which version you
                        are using, because reviewers often expect that clarity. The mechanism is belief-based and mostly
                        cognitive. People do not adopt because a system is "good" in some abstract sense. They adopt
                        when they expect personal performance gains and low effort costs. That expectation then drives
                        intention and, when conditions allow, actual use. In other words, TAM is an efficiency story
                        about why rational-looking adoption happens, not a deep theory of identity or power. Boundary
                        conditions are where TAM gets tested. TAM fits best when individuals have discretion (voluntary
                        use) and when the core value of the system is productivity. It struggles more in mandatory
                        settings (where "use" is required), in long-term use where habit dominates, and in settings
                        where risk and uncertainty are central (privacy, cybersecurity, AI decisions). In those
                        settings, usefulness can still matter, but trust, accountability, and perceived risk often
                        become primary mechanisms.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>A major extension is TAM2. Venkatesh and Davis (2000) add social influence and more detailed
                        drivers of usefulness. This is important because it answers a question that basic TAM leaves
                        vague: where does usefulness come from? In TAM2, PU can be shaped by things like job relevance,
                        output quality, result demonstrability, and social influence (subjective norm, image). This also
                        makes TAM more dynamic, because these drivers can change as people gain experience. Another big
                        step is UTAUT, which integrates several acceptance models. It keeps the core acceptance logic,
                        but reframes the constructs as performance expectancy and effort expectancy, and it adds social
                        influence and facilitating conditions. In comps, UTAUT is useful for showing you know the
                        evolution, but it also sets up a critique: adding more predictors is not always better theory if
                        the mechanism becomes a long list of antecedents without a clear "why" story. The critique phase
                        is also part of TAM's evolution. Benbasat and Barki (2007) argue that TAM became a default
                        template in IS and sometimes replaced more interesting theorizing about systems, tasks, and
                        contexts. Bagozzi (2007) pushes further and argues for richer models of decision making and
                        self-regulation, not only belief-intention links. These debate papers are very exam-friendly
                        because they let you answer "when is TAM appropriate" and "when is TAM lazy" without sounding
                        dismissive. In 2020-2025, TAM often appears as a baseline that newer work builds beyond.
                        Black-box AI systems, for example, raise adoption questions that PU and PEOU do not fully cover
                        because the key issue is uncertainty about how the system behaves and how to be accountable for
                        it. Asatiani et al. (2020) highlight the challenge of explaining black-box AI behavior. Jussupow
                        et al. (2024) connect adoption to algorithm aversion and appreciation, which links naturally to
                        trust and perceived control. Min and Lea (2023) show that even in analytics adoption, motivators
                        and inhibitors go beyond simple usefulness, especially across cultures.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: TAM is popular because it is simple and cumulative. PU and PEOU are intuitive, they
                        are easy to measure, and they often explain a meaningful share of variance in intention. This
                        makes TAM a useful baseline when you need a clean adoption story and your goal is explanation
                        and prediction. Weaknesses: TAM can become shallow if it is treated as the whole theory of
                        adoption. It under-theorizes social influence, identity, power, and organizational constraints
                        unless you extend it. It can also encourage incremental papers where the contribution is just
                        adding another antecedent to PU or PEOU. The biggest conceptual weakness is that it can turn
                        into a checklist rather than a mechanism-driven explanation. Common misapplications in IS: A
                        common misuse is applying TAM in mandatory settings and treating reported "use" as success.
                        Another misuse is measuring only intention and treating it as behavior. A third is treating PEOU
                        and PU as generic survey items without grounding them in a specific task and system, which
                        weakens construct validity. Alternatives and competitors: If your setting is about risk and
                        vulnerability, trust theory is often a better core mechanism. If your setting is about human-AI
                        authority allocation, delegation provides a more direct dependent variable than "intention to
                        use". If your setting is about ongoing work practices, sociomateriality or affordance theory
                        often give richer mechanisms than belief-intention models. UTAUT and TPB are closer cousins when
                        you still want an acceptance-style model but need a broader belief set.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use TAM when the question is about user adoption of a specific system and you want
                        a simple baseline mechanism (usefulness and ease of use). Example research question: "When
                        employees are offered a generative AI assistant for report writing, what beliefs drive their
                        intention to use it, and when does trust matter more than usefulness?" Example hypothesis:
                        "Perceived usefulness of the AI assistant is positively associated with behavioral intention to
                        use the assistant." What I would measure (simple): I would measure PU and PEOU using Davis-style
                        Likert items adapted to the specific system ("Using the assistant improves my performance",
                        "Using the assistant is easy to learn"), then measure intention and, if possible, actual use
                        from logs rather than only self-reports. If the setting involves privacy or high-stakes
                        decisions, I would add trust and perceived risk measures to avoid forcing everything into
                        PU/PEOU. Seminal APA citation: Davis, F. D. (1989). Perceived usefulness, perceived ease of use,
                        and user acceptance of information technology. <em>MIS Quarterly, 13</em>(3), 319-340.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="unified-theory-of-acceptance-and-use-of-technology-utaututaut2">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Venkatesh et al., 2003</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Unified Theory of Acceptance and Use of Technology (<mark>UTAUT/UTAUT2</mark>)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Why people adopt and keep using IT — unified through beliefs, conditions, and moderators</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> People form intentions to use technology when they expect performance gains, low effort, social support, and real enabling conditions. Over time, habit and facilitating conditions matter more than initial beliefs.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">⚡ <strong>Performance Expectancy:</strong> "Will this help me do my job better?"</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Effort Expectancy:</strong> "Is it easy enough to use?"</div>
                        <div class="key-point">👥 <strong>Social Influence:</strong> "Do important others think I should use it?"</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔧 <strong>Facilitating Conditions:</strong> "Is the support infrastructure there?"</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>Relevance for IS:</strong> The dominant integrative model for technology acceptance research — synthesizes TAM, TPB, and DOI into one framework with explicit moderators (age, gender, experience, voluntariness)
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Venkatesh, Morris, Davis, and Davis (2003)</mark>, "User acceptance of information
                                    technology: Toward a unified view," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: a
                                    synthesis of major acceptance models into a small set of core determinants plus key
                                    <span class="construct-badge">moderators</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Key extension</td>
                                <td><mark>Venkatesh, Thong, and Xu (2012)</mark>, "Consumer acceptance and use of information
                                    technology," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Adds <span class="construct-badge">hedonic motivation</span>, <span class="construct-badge">price value</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">habit</span>
                                    (UTAUT2) and targets consumer settings more directly.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (synthesis of social psychology and prior IS acceptance models).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">IS-native</span> (a unifying model built for IS).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type IV (explanation and prediction): UTAUT explains and predicts intention and use
                                    with a stronger "why this set of beliefs" logic than many one-off acceptance models.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Performance expectancy</span>, <span class="construct-badge">effort expectancy</span>, <span class="construct-badge">social influence</span>, <span class="construct-badge">facilitating
                                    conditions</span>, <span class="construct-badge">behavioral intention</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">use</span>; with <span class="construct-badge">moderators</span> like age, gender,
                                    experience, and voluntariness (UTAUT), plus <span class="construct-badge">habit</span>, <span class="construct-badge">hedonic motivation</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">price
                                    value</span> (UTAUT2).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People form intentions when they expect <mark>performance gains</mark>, <mark>low effort</mark>, <mark>social
                                    support</mark>, and real support resources (training, infrastructure). Over time, <span class="construct-badge">habit</span> and
                                    enabling conditions matter more for actual use.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Strong for explaining "will people adopt and keep using this IT?" but weaker for
                                    explaining deep work practice change, power, or ethics. It can also become a
                                    checklist if used without a clear theoretical focus.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>In top IS outlets, pure "test UTAUT" papers are less common today, but UTAUT remains
                                    a living research programme through synthesis and critique. One good recent anchor is the
                                    JAIS meta-analysis by <mark>Blut et al. (2022)</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>UTAUT</mark> was created because the acceptance literature became crowded. By the early 2000s, IS had
                        many overlapping models (<mark>TAM</mark>, <mark>TPB</mark>, innovation diffusion variants, social cognitive ideas), and
                        papers often looked like small incremental tweaks. <mark>Venkatesh and colleagues</mark> tried to bring order
                        by asking: across models, what keeps showing up, and when do effects change across groups and
                        contexts? Their answer was a unified view with four core determinants and a set of <span class="construct-badge">moderators</span>
                        that explain why results differ. <mark>UTAUT2</mark> comes from a similar motivation, but with a different
                        context. Many acceptance models were workplace-focused. <mark>UTAUT2</mark> shifts toward consumer and
                        everyday technologies where <span class="construct-badge">enjoyment</span>, <span class="construct-badge">habit</span>, and "value for money" can matter as much as
                        usefulness.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        Intention and use can be explained by a small set of beliefs and conditions, with effects varying by context
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>1️⃣ Performance Expectancy</h4>
                            <p>The main "value" belief (close to <mark>usefulness</mark>)</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>2️⃣ Effort Expectancy</h4>
                            <p>The ease belief (close to <mark>ease of use</mark>)</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>3️⃣ Social Influence</h4>
                            <p>Captures <span class="construct-badge">normative pressure</span></p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>4️⃣ Facilitating Conditions</h4>
                            <p>Whether the environment makes use feasible (resources, compatibility, training)</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        UTAUT also insists that these effects are not constant: they vary by age, gender, experience, and whether use is voluntary. The mechanism is still belief based, but it is more explicit about context.
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        In UTAUT2, <span class="construct-badge">habit</span> becomes a key mechanism because repeated use can shift the driver from "I intend to use"
                        to "I just do it." Boundary conditions are where comps answers get stronger. UTAUT is not the
                        right tool when the dependent variable is not "use" but something like delegation,
                        accountability, or dignity outcomes.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, <mark>UTAUT</mark> often serves as a baseline or a "starting model" that researchers adapt to a domain
                        (health IT, mobile services, AI assistants). That pattern is both a strength and a weakness. It
                        makes studies comparable, but it can also encourage papers that only add context-specific
                        antecedents without sharpening the mechanism. Recent work also revisits UTAUT critically. <mark>Blut
                        et al. (2022)</mark> provide a large meta-analytic view and highlight where effects are stable vs
                        fragile, which helps you answer "when does UTAUT work?" more honestly. Integration is common
                        with <mark>trust</mark> and <mark>risk</mark>, especially in privacy and AI settings.</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        The exam move is to justify the integration: UTAUT explains intention via performance/effort/social/support, while trust
                        explains intention via perceived vulnerability and reliance. They overlap but are not the same
                        mechanism.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <mark>UTAUT</mark> is useful because it is integrative and comparative. It gives you a common
                        language across adoption studies and it explains why results vary (<span class="construct-badge">moderators</span>). It is a good way
                        to write an exam answer that feels cumulative rather than ad hoc.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can become a
                        kitchen-sink model. If you throw in every construct without a story, you get statistical fit but
                        weak explanation. Another weakness is that <span class="construct-badge">moderators</span> are often ignored or poorly theorized,
                        which defeats the purpose of UTAUT.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Treating <mark>UTAUT</mark> as universal
                        across contexts without checking meaning (measurement invariance), dropping <span class="construct-badge">moderators</span> because
                        they are inconvenient, and using UTAUT for outcomes that are not really "acceptance" outcomes.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>TAM</mark> (simpler baseline), <mark>TPB</mark> (more explicit about control and
                        norms), <mark>diffusion of innovations</mark> (population spread over time), and delegation/sociomateriality
                        when the phenomenon is about changing work arrangements rather than "will people use it."</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use <mark>UTAUT</mark> when the exam question is clearly about adoption or continued use, and
                        you need a richer baseline than TAM (especially if <span class="construct-badge">social influence</span> and <span class="construct-badge">facilitating conditions</span>
                        matter).
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "In a hybrid workplace, what drives sustained use of an AI
                        meeting assistant, and how does prior experience shape those drivers?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "<span class="construct-badge">Performance expectancy</span> is positively associated with <span class="construct-badge">behavioral intention</span> to use the AI meeting
                        assistant."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would measure <span class="construct-badge">performance expectancy</span>, <span class="construct-badge">effort
                        expectancy</span>, <span class="construct-badge">social influence</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">facilitating conditions</span> using UTAUT-style Likert items adapted
                        to the specific tool. I would measure use with logs if possible and model experience (time since
                        first use) as a <span class="construct-badge">moderator</span>. If the setting is high risk (privacy), I would add <mark>trust</mark> and
                        perceived <mark>risk</mark> as parallel mechanisms.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Venkatesh, V., Morris, M. G.,
                        Davis, G. B., & Davis, F. D. (2003)</mark>. User acceptance of information technology: Toward a unified
                        view. <em>MIS Quarterly, 27</em>(3), 425-478.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="diffusion-of-innovations-doi">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge sociology">Sociology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Rogers, 1962</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Diffusion of Innovations (DOI)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How innovations spread through populations via social communication and perceived attributes</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Innovations spread unevenly through populations based on perceived attributes (relative advantage, compatibility, complexity, trialability, observability) combined with social communication, network effects, and adopter categories over time.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">📊 <strong>Perceived Attributes:</strong> Relative advantage, compatibility, complexity, trialability, and observability drive adoption decisions</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🌐 <strong>Social Diffusion:</strong> Adoption follows an S-curve with innovators, early adopters, early majority, late majority, and laggards</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔄 <strong>Communication Channels:</strong> Networks and interpersonal channels amplify innovation awareness and legitimacy</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⏱️ <strong>Time Dimension:</strong> Diffusion is fundamentally a temporal process with distinct phases and decision points</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> DOI explains technology adoption patterns at the population level, especially valuable for understanding how IT innovations spread across organizations, professional networks, and user communities when social learning and network effects matter.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Rogers (1962; later editions)</mark>, <em>Diffusion of innovations</em>. Key contribution:
                                    explains how innovations spread through communication over time in a <span class="construct-badge">social system</span>,
                                    and why adoption is uneven across groups.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Sociology / communication.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II/IV (depends on use): DOI can explain diffusion mechanisms (Type II) and can
                                    support prediction of adoption patterns when operationalized (Type IV).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Innovation attributes</span> (<span class="construct-badge">relative advantage</span>, <span class="construct-badge">compatibility</span>, <span class="construct-badge">complexity</span>, <span class="construct-badge">trialability</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">observability</span>), <span class="construct-badge">adopter categories</span>, <span class="construct-badge">communication channels</span>, <span class="construct-badge">time</span>, <span class="construct-badge">social system</span>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People adopt when an innovation looks better than what they have, fits their
                                    context, is not too complex, and can be tried and observed. <span class="construct-badge">Social communication</span> and
                                    <span class="construct-badge">network position</span> shape who adopts first and who follows.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for explaining spread over time and across populations. Less precise for
                                    explaining deep post-adoption use, local work practices, or power and politics.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td><mark>DOI</mark> logic still appears in IS adoption work (especially where timing, categories,
                                    and social diffusion matter), but it is often used indirectly or combined with
                                    acceptance models. In top IS outlets, DOI is more visible as a foundation for
                                    constructs like perceived innovation attributes than as a full diffusion model.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Rogers</mark> built DOI to explain a recurring pattern: new ideas and technologies rarely spread evenly.
                        Instead, a small group adopts early, then adoption accelerates, then it slows. <mark>DOI</mark> explains this
                        by combining <span class="construct-badge">innovation attributes</span> with <span class="construct-badge">social communication</span>. People do not adopt in isolation.
                        They learn about innovations through <span class="construct-badge">networks</span> and they watch what happens to <mark>early adopters</mark>. In
                        IS, <mark>DOI</mark> matters because many technologies are networked. The value of adoption can depend on
                        others adopting (platforms, standards, security practices). <mark>DOI</mark> gives you language for the
                        social spread process, not only individual intention.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        Diffusion is a communication process over time within a social system - adoption depends on perceived innovation attributes and social learning
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Relative Advantage</h4>
                            <p>Innovation looks better than what they have - pushes adoption</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Compatibility</h4>
                            <p>Fits their context - pushes adoption</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Complexity</h4>
                            <p>Not too complex - slows adoption if too high</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Trialability & Observability</h4>
                            <p>Can be tried and observed - supports learning and reduces uncertainty</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>Mechanism:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Uncertainty reduction</span> plus <span class="construct-badge">social proof</span>. <mark>Early adopters</mark> take risks. Later adopters follow when uncertainty drops and
                        the innovation becomes socially legitimate.
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Boundary conditions are key. <mark>DOI</mark> is strong for
                        questions like "Why did this technology spread slowly in this industry?" It is weaker for
                        questions like "How does using this AI tool change work identity?" where practice and meaning
                        become central.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS researchers often use <mark>DOI</mark> to measure perceived innovation characteristics. <mark>Moore and Benbasat
                        (1991)</mark> is a classic IS adaptation that operationalizes DOI-style perceptions for IT innovations,
                        which made <mark>DOI</mark> easier to test in IS settings. <mark>DOI</mark> also gets combined with <mark>TAM/UTAUT</mark>.</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        The combo can be clean if you are explicit: <mark>DOI</mark> explains innovation perceptions and spread, while
                        <mark>TAM/UTAUT</mark> explain intention and use. The combo becomes messy if you include everything without a
                        story.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <mark>DOI</mark> helps you explain adoption at the population level and it gives you clear levers
                        (<span class="construct-badge">compatibility</span>, <span class="construct-badge">trialability</span>, <span class="construct-badge">observability</span>). It is also exam-friendly because it gives you a
                        process story over time.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can treat adoption as too smooth and rational. It often
                        underplays power, institutional pressure, and strategic manipulation (especially in platforms).
                        It also does not give a deep account of ongoing use and reinvention.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Treating <mark>DOI</mark> as a list of attributes without studying diffusion over time, and claiming
                        "diffusion" from a single cross-sectional survey.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>Institutional
                        theory</mark> for legitimacy pressures, <mark>TAM/UTAUT</mark> for individual intention, and
                        sociomateriality/structuration for deeper practice change.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use <mark>DOI</mark> when the exam question is about how an innovation spreads across a
                        population (firms, users, hospitals), not only why one person adopts.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "Why did some hospitals adopt patient-facing AI triage faster than others, and how did adoption
                        spread through professional networks?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Perceived <span class="construct-badge">compatibility</span> of the AI
                        triage system with existing clinical workflows is positively associated with adoption."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would measure perceived <span class="construct-badge">innovation attributes</span> (<span class="construct-badge">compatibility</span>,
                        <span class="construct-badge">complexity</span>, <span class="construct-badge">relative advantage</span>), <span class="construct-badge">network exposure</span> (who talks to whom), and <span class="construct-badge">time of adoption</span>. A
                        good design is a longitudinal diffusion model or event history analysis rather than a one-time
                        survey.</p>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Rogers, E. M. (1962)</mark>. <em>Diffusion of innovations</em>. Free
                        Press.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="task-technology-fit-ttf">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Goodhue & Thompson, 1995</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Task-Technology Fit (TTF)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Performance improves when technology capabilities align with task requirements and characteristics</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> The alignment (fit) between technology features and task demands directly explains performance outcomes. Utilization alone is insufficient; the critical mechanism is whether the tool actually supports what the task requires.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Task Characteristics:</strong> Task complexity, information requirements, and interdependence define what capabilities are needed</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚙️ <strong>Technology Characteristics:</strong> Functionality, data quality, ease of use, and support capabilities determine what a tool can deliver</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔗 <strong>Fit as Mechanism:</strong> Alignment between task needs and technology capabilities drives performance, not just adoption or usage</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📈 <strong>Performance Outcomes:</strong> Better fit leads to improved task performance through enabling users to meet task demands more effectively</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> TTF bridges acceptance models and performance outcomes, explaining when and why technology investments deliver actual performance improvements. Essential for evaluating IS effectiveness beyond intention-to-use.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Goodhue and Thompson (1995)</mark>, "Task-technology fit and individual performance,"
                                    <em><mark>MIS Quarterly</mark></em>. Key contribution: links <mark>technology characteristics</mark> and <mark>task
                                    characteristics</mark> to <mark>performance</mark> through <span class="construct-badge">fit</span>, not just <mark>intention</mark>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td><mark>IS</mark> (influenced by <mark>contingency logic</mark> in <mark>organization theory</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Mostly IS-native (fit logic is broader, but the model is built for IT).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td><mark>Type IV</mark> (explanation and prediction): explains why <span class="construct-badge">performance</span> improves when
                                    technology matches task needs and supports prediction of <mark>performance impacts</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Task characteristics</span>, <span class="construct-badge">technology characteristics</span>, <span class="construct-badge">task-technology fit</span>, <span class="construct-badge">utilization</span>,
                                    and <span class="construct-badge">performance impacts</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>If the tool supports the actual <mark>task requirements</mark>, people can do the task better.
                                    <span class="construct-badge">Fit</span> is the key channel between <mark>features</mark> and <span class="construct-badge">performance</span>, and <mark>use alone is not
                                    enough</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best when tasks are <mark>clear enough to specify requirements</mark> and when technology
                                    features are <mark>stable</mark>. Harder when tasks are <mark>emergent</mark>, <mark>exploratory</mark>, or when value
                                    comes from <mark>experimentation</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>TTF remains common in applied IS work, but in <mark>top IS outlets</mark> it is often used as a
                                    <mark>secondary lens</mark> (for <span class="construct-badge">performance impacts</span>) rather than the central framing. It is
                                    especially useful when the exam question is "<mark>does the tool improve performance, and
                                    for which tasks?</mark>" (If you want, I can add 2020-2025 top-outlet examples with a
                                    targeted search.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        TTF was proposed because <mark>acceptance models</mark> were not enough for <span class="construct-badge">performance</span> questions—people can use a system and still perform poorly if it doesn't match task demands.
                    </div>

                    <p>TTF was proposed because <mark>acceptance models</mark> were not enough for <span class="construct-badge">performance</span> questions. People can
                        use a system and still perform poorly if the system does not match what the task demands.
                        <mark>Goodhue and Thompson</mark> argued that the key is <span class="construct-badge">fit</span>: the alignment between <span class="construct-badge">task needs</span> (<mark>information
                        requirements</mark>, <mark>interdependence</mark>, <mark>complexity</mark>) and <span class="construct-badge">technology capabilities</span> (<mark>data quality</mark>,
                        <mark>functionality</mark>, <mark>ease</mark>, <mark>support</mark>).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Fit</span> drives <span class="construct-badge">performance</span>. <span class="construct-badge">Utilization</span> matters, but <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> is the mechanism
                        that explains why use translates into performance impacts.
                    </div>

                    <p>The main proposition is: <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> drives <span class="construct-badge">performance</span>. <span class="construct-badge">Utilization</span> matters, but <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> is the mechanism
                        that explains why use translates into <span class="construct-badge">performance impacts</span>. This is why TTF is powerful in <mark>comps
                        answers</mark> when you want to move beyond "<mark>intention</mark>" to "<mark>outcomes</mark>."</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use TTF when you want to move beyond "intention" to "outcomes" in exam answers.
                    </div>

                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> If tasks are changing fast, it can be hard to specify what "<span class="construct-badge">fit</span>" means. Also, <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> can
                        be <mark>subjective</mark>: two people can see different fits depending on <mark>skill</mark> and <mark>experience</mark>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS research, TTF is often used in combination with <mark>TAM/UTAUT</mark>. The combination can be coherent:
                        <span class="construct-badge">acceptance beliefs</span> explain <span class="construct-badge">use</span>, while TTF explains whether <span class="construct-badge">use</span> leads to <span class="construct-badge">performance</span>. The risk is
                        redundancy if you treat "<span class="construct-badge">usefulness</span>" as the same thing as "<span class="construct-badge">fit</span>." They are related, but
                        <span class="construct-badge">usefulness</span> is an <mark>expectation</mark>, while <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> is an <mark>alignment claim</mark> that can be evaluated against <span class="construct-badge">task
                        requirements</span>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> TTF gives a clear mechanism for <span class="construct-badge">performance impacts</span>. It is also very practical: it
                            connects <mark>design choices</mark> to <mark>outcomes</mark> through <span class="construct-badge">task needs</span>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Fit</span> can be hard to <mark>measure</mark>
                            well. Many studies measure it as a <mark>perception scale</mark>, which can collapse <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> back into
                            "<span class="construct-badge">usefulness</span>." Another weakness is that <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> can be <mark>dynamic</mark>: the task and the technology
                            <mark>co-evolve</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Treating <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> as a <mark>vague positive feeling</mark>, or using
                            <mark>cross-sectional self-reports</mark> for both <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> and <span class="construct-badge">performance</span> (<mark>common method bias</mark>). Another misuse
                            is ignoring the <mark>task analysis</mark> and only measuring <span class="construct-badge">technology features</span>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Affordance theory</mark> and <mark>sociomateriality</mark> can explain use and outcomes as <mark>emergent
                            from practice</mark>, not only from a pre-specified task-feature alignment. <mark>RBV</mark> and <mark>human capital</mark> can
                            explain performance outcomes at the <mark>firm level</mark> rather than <mark>task level</mark>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use TTF when the exam question is about <span class="construct-badge">performance impacts</span> and "<mark>which tool for
                        which task</mark>", not just <mark>intention to use</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "When does a generative AI
                        writing assistant improve analyst performance, and which tasks see the biggest gains?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "<span class="construct-badge">Task-technology fit</span> is positively associated with individual <span class="construct-badge">performance impacts</span> of
                        the AI writing assistant."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would classify <span class="construct-badge">tasks</span> (<mark>summarization</mark>,
                        <mark>drafting</mark>, <mark>brainstorming</mark>, <mark>compliance writing</mark>), measure <span class="construct-badge">perceived fit</span> for each task, and measure
                        <span class="construct-badge">performance</span> with <mark>objective outcomes</mark> when possible (<mark>time</mark>, <mark>quality ratings</mark>, <mark>error rates</mark>). I would
                        also measure <mark>experience</mark> to see whether <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> changes with learning.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Goodhue,
                        D. L., & Thompson, R. L. (1995)</mark>. Task-technology fit and individual performance. <em><mark>MIS
                            Quarterly, 19</mark></em>(2), 213-236.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="delone-and-mclean-is-success-model">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">DeLone & McLean, 1992</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>DeLone and McLean IS Success Model</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">A multidimensional framework organizing IS success across quality, usage, satisfaction, and organizational benefits</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> IS success is multidimensional and evolves over time. Quality dimensions (system, information, and service) drive usage and user satisfaction, which together produce organizational net benefits. Success is context-dependent and must be evaluated at the appropriate stakeholder and organizational level.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">⚙️ <strong>Quality Dimensions:</strong> System quality, information quality, and service quality determine whether the IS can deliver value</div>
                        <div class="key-point">👥 <strong>User Response:</strong> Quality drives both usage intensity and user satisfaction as intermediate outcomes</div>
                        <div class="key-point">💰 <strong>Net Benefits:</strong> Usage and satisfaction translate into organizational benefits (improved decisions, faster processes, better outcomes)</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Context-Dependent:</strong> Success indicators and stakeholder perspectives vary by system type, industry, and organizational level</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Provides a foundational framework for IS evaluation, ensuring researchers move beyond individual measures to understand how technical quality translates into organizational value. A diagnostic tool for understanding what "success" means in context.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>DeLone and McLean (1992)</mark>, "Information systems success: The quest for the dependent
                                    variable," <em><mark>Information Systems Research</mark></em>. Key contribution: a unifying model
                                    that organizes what IS researchers mean by "<mark>success</mark>".</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Key update</td>
                                <td><mark>DeLone and McLean (2003)</mark>, "The DeLone and McLean model of information systems
                                    success: A ten-year update," <em><mark>Journal of Management Information Systems</mark></em>.
                                    Adds <span class="construct-badge">service quality</span> and clarifies "<span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span>".</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (built as a synthesis of prior IS measures and outcomes).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td><mark>Type IV</mark> (explanation and prediction): it explains pathways from <span class="construct-badge">IS quality</span> to
                                    <span class="construct-badge">outcomes</span> and supports prediction of <mark>success indicators</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">System quality</span>, <span class="construct-badge">information quality</span>, <span class="construct-badge">service quality</span> (update), <span class="construct-badge">use / intention to
                                    use</span>, <span class="construct-badge">user satisfaction</span>, <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Better <span class="construct-badge">quality</span> systems and outputs lead to more <span class="construct-badge">use</span> and higher <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span>. <span class="construct-badge">Use</span> and
                                    <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span> are the channels through which the IS produces <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Works best as an <mark>evaluation framework</mark> for a specific IS in a defined context. Causal
                                    direction between <span class="construct-badge">use</span> and <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span> can be <mark>reciprocal</mark>, and "<span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span>" depends
                                    on <mark>stakeholder</mark> and <mark>level of analysis</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>In <mark>2020-2025</mark>, <mark>top IS journals</mark> often study <span class="construct-badge">value</span> and <span class="construct-badge">impacts</span> using more specific
                                    lenses (<mark>digital resources</mark>, <mark>resilience</mark>, <mark>privacy</mark>, <mark>trust</mark>) rather than the full DeLone
                                    and McLean chain. The model remains common in <mark>applied evaluation work</mark>, but direct
                                    use in <mark>MISQ/ISR/JAIS/JMIS</mark> is less visible compared to the 1990s-2000s. (Logged as an
                                    exception in QA.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        DeLone and McLean built their model because IS research had a basic problem: everyone cared about
                        "<mark>IS success</mark>", but the field did not agree on <mark>what to measure</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p>DeLone and McLean built their model because IS research had a basic problem: everyone cared about
                        "<mark>IS success</mark>", but the field did not agree on what to measure. Some papers treated <span class="construct-badge">usage</span> as
                        success, others used <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span>, and others used <span class="construct-badge">impacts</span>. Their <mark>1992 paper</mark> is a <mark>synthesis
                        move</mark>. It organizes prior dependent variables into a coherent structure and argues that success
                        is <mark>multidimensional</mark> and unfolds <mark>over time</mark>. The <mark>2003 update</mark> matters because it shows how the
                        model evolved under critique. By then, researchers had debated whether "<span class="construct-badge">use</span>" is a cause or an
                        effect, whether quality should include <span class="construct-badge">service quality</span>, and how to define impacts. The update
                        reframes impacts as "<span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span>" to emphasize that benefits are <mark>context-specific</mark> and can
                        differ by <mark>stakeholder</mark>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Quality</span> (<span class="construct-badge">system</span>, <span class="construct-badge">information</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">service</span>) drives <span class="construct-badge">use</span>
                        and <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span>, and these drive <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p>The core proposition is a <mark>pathway model</mark>: <span class="construct-badge">quality</span> (<span class="construct-badge">system</span>, <span class="construct-badge">information</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">service</span>) drives <span class="construct-badge">use</span>
                        and <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span>, and these drive <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span>. Many empirical studies test a subset of the
                        chain, but the theoretical claim is that the pieces belong together. The causal mechanism is
                        mostly about <mark>capability</mark> and <mark>perception</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">System quality</span> and <span class="construct-badge">information quality</span> capture whether
                        the system works well and provides good outputs. <span class="construct-badge">Service quality</span> captures the support context.
                        If these are strong, people are more willing and able to use the system, and they are more
                        satisfied. <span class="construct-badge">Use</span> and <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span> then translate into tangible benefits like <mark>better decisions</mark>,
                        <mark>faster processes</mark>, or <mark>improved outcomes</mark>.</p>

                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions are central:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Use</span> can be
                        <mark>mandatory</mark>, so use may not equal success. <span class="construct-badge">Satisfaction</span> can be high even when <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span> are low
                        (for example, if the system is pleasant but not productive). <span class="construct-badge">Net benefits</span> can also conflict
                        across <mark>stakeholders</mark>. A system can benefit management while creating extra work for frontline
                        employees. This is why the model often works best as a <mark>diagnostic framework</mark> rather than as a
                        deep causal theory of organizational value.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, the model became a common backbone for evaluation studies, especially for <mark>enterprise
                        systems</mark>, <mark>e-government services</mark>, and <mark>online platforms</mark>. Over time, researchers refined what "<span class="construct-badge">use</span>"
                        means (<mark>frequency vs depth vs feature use</mark>), and they clarified the level of benefits they are
                        claiming (<mark>individual vs organizational</mark>). A major debate paper is <mark>Seddon (1997)</mark>, which challenged
                        parts of the original causal structure and argued for clearer separation between <span class="construct-badge">use</span> and
                        <span class="construct-badge">usefulness</span> and for more careful thinking about the dependent variable.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        For comps, the key point is that the model is <mark>influential but contested</mark>, and you should be able to explain what the
                        debate is really about (<mark>measurement and causal direction</mark>, not "do we like success models").
                    </div>

                    <p>For <mark>2020-2025</mark>, one pattern is that the "<mark>IS success</mark>" conversation in top outlets often appears
                        through adjacent concepts like <mark>digital resource value</mark>, <mark>resilience</mark>, and <mark>performance impacts</mark>,
                        rather than by directly using the DeLone and McLean chain. That does not make the model
                        obsolete. It means you usually need a more specific <mark>kernel theory</mark> to explain why quality
                        translates into benefits in your context.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> The model is popular because it gives a <mark>shared vocabulary</mark> for talking about <span class="construct-badge">success</span>.
                            It forces researchers to be explicit about what kind of "<mark>success</mark>" they mean, and it helps
                            connect <mark>technical qualities</mark> to <span class="construct-badge">user outcomes</span> and <span class="construct-badge">organizational value</span>. It is also easy to
                            communicate to practitioners who want <mark>evaluation metrics</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> The biggest weakness is
                            that it can be used <mark>without real theorizing</mark>. If you treat it as "<mark>include these variables and run
                            SEM</mark>", you may produce a diagram but not a mechanism. Another weakness is <mark>causal ambiguity</mark>: <span class="construct-badge">use</span>
                            and <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span> can influence each other, and <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span> can reshape future <span class="construct-badge">use</span> (<mark>feedback
                            loops</mark>). The model is more of a <mark>map</mark> than a deep explanation of value creation.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> A common mistake is to claim <mark>organizational</mark> <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span> based on
                            <mark>individual survey responses</mark> without appropriate data and <mark>level alignment</mark>. Another is to treat
                            "<span class="construct-badge">use</span>" as success even when use is <mark>mandatory</mark>. A third is to <mark>ignore time</mark>: success is often a
                            <mark>trajectory</mark>, not a <mark>snapshot</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> For focused questions, researchers
                            often use more specific theories of value, capability, or behavior (for example, <mark>RBV</mark> for
                            strategic value of resources, or <mark>trust/privacy theories</mark> for platform outcomes). These can
                            complement DeLone and McLean by supplying a stronger "<mark>why</mark>" behind the success pathway.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use DeLone and McLean when the question is about evaluating "<mark>IS success</mark>" and you
                        need a clear chain from <span class="construct-badge">quality</span> to <span class="construct-badge">use</span> and <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span> to <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "What explains the net benefits of an enterprise collaboration platform in a hybrid
                        work organization, and which quality dimensions matter most for sustained use?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Higher <span class="construct-badge">system quality</span> is positively associated with <span class="construct-badge">user satisfaction</span>, which is
                        positively associated with <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span> of the platform."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">System
                        quality</span> and <span class="construct-badge">information quality</span> can be measured via <mark>validated survey items</mark> (<mark>reliability</mark>, <mark>ease</mark>,
                        <mark>timeliness</mark>, <mark>relevance</mark>). <span class="construct-badge">Use</span> should be measured with <mark>logs if possible</mark> (<mark>active days</mark>, <mark>feature
                        breadth</mark>), and <span class="construct-badge">net benefits</span> should be defined at the right <mark>level</mark> (<mark>individual productivity</mark>, <mark>team
                        coordination</mark>, or <mark>organizational performance</mark>), ideally with <mark>outcome data</mark> rather than only
                        <mark>perceptions</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>DeLone, W. H., & McLean, E. R. (1992)</mark>. Information systems
                        success: The quest for the dependent variable. <em><mark>Information Systems Research, 3</mark></em>(1),
                        60-95.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="technology-affordance-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Gibson, 1979</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Technology Affordance Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Technology offers action possibilities that emerge from the relationship between artifact, user goals, and context</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Affordances are action possibilities that exist in the relationship between a goal-oriented actor and their environment. Technology doesn't determine outcomes; rather, it offers potentials that users perceive and actualize based on their goals, capabilities, and context.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Relational Property:</strong> Affordances exist between artifact and actor, not in the artifact alone or the person alone</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔧 <strong>Functional Affordances:</strong> What actions the technology makes possible (e.g., anonymity, persistence, traceability)</div>
                        <div class="key-point">💭 <strong>Symbolic Expressions:</strong> Values, meanings, and suggested ways of use communicated by the technology</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚡ <strong>Actualization:</strong> Outcomes emerge through user perception and appropriation of affordances over time, not automatically</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains IT effects as mediated by affordances, avoiding technological determinism while accounting for how design shapes possibilities. Particularly valuable for understanding platform features, digital transformation, and heterogeneous user adaptations.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Gibson (1979)</mark>, <em>The Ecological Approach to Visual Perception</em>. Key
                                    contribution: <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> as action possibilities that exist in the relationship
                                    between an actor and an environment, not just "features" of an object.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Key IS adaptation</td>
                                <td><mark>Markus and Silver (2008)</mark> reframe IT effects using <span class="construct-badge">"technical objects"</span>, <span class="construct-badge">"functional
                                    affordances"</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">"symbolic expressions"</span> to get beyond feature lists and designer
                                    intent.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Psychology (ecological psychology).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (imported into IS).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Mostly Type II (explanation): it explains how IT enables and constrains action
                                    through relational possibilities, without always aiming for precise prediction.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Technical object</span>; <span class="construct-badge">functional affordances</span>; <span class="construct-badge">symbolic expressions</span>; <span class="construct-badge">affordance
                                    actualization</span>; <span class="construct-badge">outcomes of use</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>A technology does not cause outcomes by itself. It offers possibilities for
                                    goal-oriented action to specific users in a context. Outcomes happen when users
                                    perceive and actualize those <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> over time.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Affordances</span> depend on actor goals/capabilities and on context. Same feature can
                                    enable one group and constrain another. <span class="construct-badge">Affordances</span> can exist but never be
                                    actualized.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Affordances</span> remain central in top IS work on societal change and platform features,
                                    for example, an affordance-based institutional logics perspective (MISQ) and
                                    research on ephemerality features in social media (MISQ).</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Affordance theory</span> starts in ecological psychology. <mark>Gibson (1979)</mark> argued that perception is deeply
                        tied to action. We do not just see objects, we see what we can do with them. A chair affords
                        sitting, but not for everyone (a toddler may not be able to sit on a tall chair). The key is
                        relational: <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> are not "inside the object" alone, and they are not "inside the person"
                        alone. They sit in the relationship between a goal-oriented actor and the environment. IS picked
                        up <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> because it solves a classic problem: how to talk about the IT artifact without
                        turning the theory into either <mark>technological determinism</mark> ("tech causes outcomes") or <mark>social
                        determinism</mark> ("everything is social"). In IS, <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> became a way to speak about what
                        technology makes possible, while still leaving room for human agency and context.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        IT effects flow through affordances - they are potentials, not automatic outcomes
                    </div>
                    
                    <p>The core proposition is that IT effects flow through <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span>. A <span class="construct-badge">"technical object"</span> (the IT
                        artifact and its components) offers <span class="construct-badge">functional affordances</span> to a specified user group, and it
                        also communicates <span class="construct-badge">symbolic expressions</span> (values, meanings, and suggested ways of use). These
                        together shape what people can do and what they believe the technology is for.</p>
                    
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        Outcomes are not automatic. They emerge through appropriation and through the <span class="construct-badge">actualization of affordances</span> over
                        time. <span class="construct-badge">Affordances</span> are potentials, not outcomes. A system may afford
                        transparency, but if no one uses the dashboard, transparency is not actualized.
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        This is why affordance research often uses process thinking and longitudinal
                        designs. Boundary conditions are built into the definition: <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> depend on goals and
                        capabilities, so heterogeneity is expected. The same feature can be an enabler for one group and
                        a constraint for another.
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        It is important to distinguish between <span class="construct-badge">"perceived affordances"</span> (what users think they can do) and <span class="construct-badge">"existing affordances"</span> (what is actually
                        possible given the artifact and context). Misalignment between the two is a common source of
                        failure in implementations.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, affordance theorizing evolved in a few connected moves. One move was conceptual clarity
                        about what an <span class="construct-badge">affordance</span> is (and is not). <mark>Markus and Silver (2008)</mark> are important because they
                        pushed the field away from treating <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> as a fancy word for features. They also added
                        the <span class="construct-badge">symbolic side</span>, which fits well with IS settings where values and norms are part of
                        technology use. Another move was a stronger process view. <mark>Volkoff and Strong (2013)</mark> link
                        <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> to critical realism and argue that <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> work like generative mechanisms: they
                        exist in the real domain, they are actualized through action, and they lead to observable
                        effects. <mark>Strong et al. (2014)</mark> then build an explicit theory of organization-level <span class="construct-badge">affordance
                        actualization</span> in the EHR context. These papers are useful because they give you an exam-ready
                        vocabulary for how <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> become outcomes. The third move is application in contemporary
                        digital contexts. <mark>Faik et al. (2020)</mark> show how IT <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> can shift institutional logics in
                        societal change (<span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> become a route to explain "how IT matters"). <mark>Lehrer et al. (2023)</mark>
                        use a feature-specific approach (ephemerality) that is consistent with affordance thinking
                        because it links design properties to patterns of engagement. Together, these illustrate how
                        <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> connect design and social outcomes in IS.</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Integration with other theories is common. <span class="construct-badge">Affordances</span> often pair well with institutional logics (to explain how <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> shift power
                        and legitimacy) and with sociomateriality (to explain entanglement of technology and practice).
                        The exam trap is to combine them without clarifying ontology. If you treat <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> as
                        properties that exist independent of practice, you need to be clear how that fits with
                        sociomateriality's stance on inseparability.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Affordance theory</span> is popular because it gives a balanced way to theorize the IT
                        artifact. It supports richer explanations than feature lists, but it avoids deterministic
                        claims. It also travels well across contexts because the unit is not "the system", but "what
                        actions the system makes possible for which users".</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Affordance</span> language can be vague
                        if researchers do not specify actor, goal, and context. Another weakness is that <span class="construct-badge">affordance</span>
                        claims can become unfalsifiable if everything is labeled an <span class="construct-badge">affordance</span> after the fact. The
                        solution is to define <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> clearly and trace <span class="construct-badge">actualization</span> empirically over time.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> The most common misuse is to treat <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> as synonyms for features
                        ("the affordance of a like button"). Another is to skip <span class="construct-badge">actualization</span> and jump straight from
                        <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> to outcomes without showing how action produced the outcome. A third is to ignore
                        constraints and unintended effects. <span class="construct-badge">Affordances</span> are not only enabling; they also highlight what
                        is not possible.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>Adaptive Structuration Theory (AST)</mark> is a close
                        cousin in spirit (technology and social structure in use). Sociomateriality is another
                        competitor, but it rests on different ontological assumptions. Actor-network theory and
                        structuration theory are also common alternatives for explaining sociotechnical effects.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use <span class="construct-badge">affordance theory</span> when the question is about what actions a technology enables
                        or constrains for a user group in a specific context, not only whether people adopt it.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How do ephemerality features on social media change user engagement
                        behaviors, and what <span class="construct-badge">affordances</span> do users actualize when content disappears?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Greater perceived ephemerality affords more self-disclosure by reducing perceived long-term
                        social risk, which increases posting frequency."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would define
                        the focal <span class="construct-badge">affordance</span> explicitly (for example, "low persistence self-disclosure"), measure user
                        perceptions and goals (risk, impression management), and then use behavioral logs to capture
                        <span class="construct-badge">actualization</span> (posting frequency, content type, deletion behavior). The key exam point is to
                        separate potential (<span class="construct-badge">affordance</span>) from realized outcomes (<span class="construct-badge">actualization</span> and engagement).
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal
                        APA citation:</strong> <mark>Gibson, J. J. (1979)</mark>. <em>The ecological approach to visual perception</em>.
                        Boston, MA: Houghton Mifflin.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="sociomateriality">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge organizational">Organizational Studies</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Orlikowski, 2007</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Sociomateriality</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Technology and social practice are inseparable and co-produced together through everyday work practices</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Technology and social practice are ontologically entangled, not separate layers that interact. Work outcomes emerge through sociomaterial practices where human intentions, organizational norms, and material features are performed and produced together, making them inseparable in analysis.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🔗 <strong>Inseparability:</strong> Technology and social practice cannot be meaningfully separated; they are produced together</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔄 <strong>Performativity:</strong> Reality is produced through ongoing practices, not pre-existing and separate</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📋 <strong>Routines as Unit:</strong> Study emerges through organizational routines where material features and social norms become entangled</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚙️ <strong>Material Details Matter:</strong> Data, interfaces, algorithms, and configuration are integral to understanding practice, not backdrop to human action</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Provides a lens for studying digital work practices, avoiding both technological determinism and pure social constructivism. Particularly valuable for understanding how technology and organizations co-evolve, digital transformation processes, and emerging platform dynamics.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Orlikowski (2007)</mark>, "Sociomaterial practices: Exploring technology at work,"
                                    <em>Organization Studies</em>. Key contribution: technology and social practice are
                                    <span class="construct-badge">inseparable</span> in everyday work, so we should study them as <span class="construct-badge">entangled</span>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Organization studies / science and technology studies (practice theory, materiality
                                    turn).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed foundations, but developed into a core IS lens through IS scholars
                                    (especially <mark>Orlikowski</mark> and colleagues).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Mostly Type II (explanation), but it is also ontological (it changes what we think
                                    the phenomenon is). It is not designed for precise prediction.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Sociomaterial practices</span>; <span class="construct-badge">entanglement/inseparability</span>; <span class="construct-badge">performativity</span>; <span class="construct-badge">materiality</span>;
                                    <span class="construct-badge">routines</span>; <span class="construct-badge">"technology-in-practice"</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Outcomes come from ongoing <span class="construct-badge">practices</span> where human intentions, organizational norms,
                                    and material features are performed together. Technology does not sit outside
                                    practice, and practice is not purely social.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for studying situated work practices and ongoing change. Hard to translate into
                                    simple variable models. Often fits interpretive and process methods more than
                                    cross-sectional surveys.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Sociomaterial</span> lenses continue to show up in top outlets for studying social media
                                    and responsibility in digital contexts, for example, a sociomaterial examination of
                                    social protest cycles and recent work on digital responsibility.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Sociomateriality</span> became influential in IS because it challenged a common habit in our field:
                        treating "technology" as a thing you add into a social setting, and then measuring its "impact".
                        <mark>Orlikowski's 2007 paper</mark> argues that in real organizational life, social and material are not
                        separate layers that interact. They are <span class="construct-badge">entangled in practice</span>. People do not just use
                        technology. They enact <span class="construct-badge">practices</span> that are simultaneously social (norms, meanings, power) and
                        material (devices, software, data, interfaces).</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        For comps, it helps to say explicitly what problem this solves. <span class="construct-badge">Sociomateriality</span> gives you a language to study digital work without either
                        blaming outcomes only on human choice or claiming the artifact determines everything. It also
                        pushes you to pay attention to <span class="construct-badge">routines</span> and to how technology is enacted differently across
                        situations.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The core proposition is inseparability - technology and social practice are produced together as people work
                    </div>
                    
                    <p>If we separate "the social" and "the material" as two
                        independent variables, we miss how work actually happens. <span class="construct-badge">Sociomateriality</span> claims that the unit
                        of analysis should often be the <span class="construct-badge">practice</span> itself, not isolated actors or isolated artifacts. This
                        is why many sociomaterial studies focus on <span class="construct-badge">routines</span>, coordination, and ongoing change rather
                        than on one-time adoption decisions.</p>
                    
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <span class="construct-badge">Sociomateriality</span> is different from "technology affects
                        behavior" theories because it is not mainly a linear causal story. It is a constitutive story.
                        It says that what the technology is, and what the social practice is, are produced together as
                        people work. That is why mechanism language is often about <span class="construct-badge">performativity</span> (how actions produce
                        realities) rather than about X causing Y.
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Boundary conditions matter. <span class="construct-badge">Sociomateriality</span> is strong
                        for explaining how digital and social become intertwined over time, but it is not designed for
                        precise prediction. It can be hard to operationalize because it pushes against clean separation
                        of constructs. If your research design requires clear independent and dependent variables, you
                        need to be explicit about how you translate sociomaterial ideas without breaking the basic
                        ontological point.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, <span class="construct-badge">sociomateriality</span> grew into a broad lens with internal debates. One debate is about how
                        strong the ontological claim should be. Some work treats <span class="construct-badge">sociomateriality</span> as a reminder to
                        include <span class="construct-badge">materiality</span> and <span class="construct-badge">practices</span> (a softer version). Other work treats <span class="construct-badge">inseparability</span> as a
                        strict ontological commitment (a stronger version). That difference matters because it affects
                        what counts as a good explanation and what research methods make sense. <span class="construct-badge">Sociomateriality</span> has
                        been used to study infrastructures, platforms, and social media, where the boundary between
                        "tool" and "social system" is blurry. <mark>Tarafdar and Ray (2021)</mark> is a good example: they use a
                        sociomaterial perspective to study social protest cycles, where content, platform mechanics, and
                        collective action become <span class="construct-badge">entangled</span>. A related 2020-2025 stream is digital responsibility. <mark>Recker
                        et al. (2025)</mark> is not a sociomateriality paper, but it captures the broader top-journal shift
                        toward theorizing responsibility and harms in digital settings. <span class="construct-badge">Sociomateriality</span> is often a good
                        companion lens in this space because responsibility is enacted through <span class="construct-badge">practices</span> and artifacts
                        (logs, interfaces, controls), not only through attitudes.</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Integration with other theories is common but risky. <span class="construct-badge">Sociomateriality</span> pairs naturally with practice theory and with process views
                        of change. It can also be combined with affordance theory, but only if you are clear whether you
                        treat affordances as stable potentials of an artifact or as something that only exists in
                        practice. The exam move is to name that tension instead of ignoring it.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Sociomateriality</span> helps IS researchers avoid shallow "IT impact" stories. It forces you
                        to take the artifact seriously while also taking organizational <span class="construct-badge">practices</span> seriously. It is
                        especially strong for studying ongoing transformation and emergent use, where outcomes are not
                        planned in advance.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can be hard to translate into testable hypotheses because it
                        resists separating constructs. It can also become a label that researchers use without actually
                        doing sociomaterial analysis (for example, they mention "<span class="construct-badge">entanglement</span>" but still run a standard
                        variable model). Conceptual clarity is crucial because different scholars use the term in
                        different ways.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A common misuse is to use <span class="construct-badge">sociomateriality</span> as
                        decoration, while still treating technology as an independent variable and treating the social
                        as context. Another is to claim <span class="construct-badge">inseparability</span> but then only study human narratives and ignore
                        the material details (data, interfaces, algorithms, permissions) that shape <span class="construct-badge">practice</span>.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>Actor-network theory</mark> is a close alternative (it also treats human
                        and nonhuman together). <mark>Structuration theory</mark> and <mark>adaptive structuration theory</mark> are also common,
                        but they have different assumptions about structure and agency. <mark>Affordance theory</mark> is another
                        alternative when you want an action-possibility mechanism rather than a constitutive ontology.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use <span class="construct-badge">sociomateriality</span> when the question is about technology and work <span class="construct-badge">practices</span>
                        becoming <span class="construct-badge">entangled</span> over time, and splitting "tech" from "social" would hide the mechanism.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How do employees and an AI-based decision support tool co-produce
                        new accountability <span class="construct-badge">practices</span>, and how do those <span class="construct-badge">practices</span> reshape what the tool is used for over
                        time?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis</strong> (framed as a proposition, since this lens is often qualitative): "As
                        organizations introduce AI decision tools, accountability will shift from individual explanation
                        to sociomaterial practices of documentation and auditability, and this shift will change both
                        work routines and how the tool is configured." What I would measure (simple): In a qualitative
                        design, I would trace routines and artifacts: how people document decisions, how audit logs are
                        used, what parts of the AI output are treated as authoritative, and how tool configuration
                        changes after incidents. If a quantitative component is needed, I would operationalize specific
                        sociomaterial patterns (for example, frequency of audit log use, number of workflow changes, or
                        changes in documentation practices) and connect them to outcomes like perceived accountability.
                        <strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Orlikowski, W. J. (2007)</mark>. Sociomaterial practices: Exploring technology at
                        work. <em>Organization Studies, 28</em>(9), 1435-1448.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Part A Divider -->
            <div class="part-divider" id="part-a">
                <div>
                    <h2>💻 Part A: Core IS Theories</h2>
                    <p style="margin: 0; opacity: 0.9; font-size: 0.95rem;">Information Systems-native theories and
                        frameworks</p>
                </div>
                <div class="part-count">15 Theories</div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="digital-object-theory-faulkner-runde-2019">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Faulkner & Runde, 2019</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Digital Object Theory (Faulkner & Runde, 2019)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">An ontology for understanding what digital objects are through their material bearers and social positioning</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Digital objects exist through multiple layers: bitstrings are borne by file formats, which are borne by storage systems, and so on. But what a digital object "is" and what it "does" depend fundamentally on its social positioning—the rights, responsibilities, and expectations assigned to it in specific organizational contexts.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🔗 <strong>Layered Bearers:</strong> Digital objects exist through nested material and nonmaterial layers (bitstrings, files, storage, systems)</div>
                        <div class="key-point">👥 <strong>Social Positioning:</strong> Identity and system function emerge from rights, responsibilities, and organizational expectations, not technology alone</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚙️ <strong>System Function:</strong> What an object legitimately does depends on its position in the sociotechnical system</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📊 <strong>Ontological Clarity:</strong> Precise conceptualization separates technical layers from social roles, enabling clear theorizing of IT artifacts</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Provides foundational clarity on what IT artifacts are, responding to critiques of under-theorization. Essential for moving beyond vague "technology" language to precise specification of digital object identity and function in sociotechnical systems.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Faulkner & Runde (2019)</mark>, "Theorizing the Digital Object," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>.
                                    Key contribution: an ontology for <span class="construct-badge">digital objects</span> (material vs
                                    nonmaterial, <span class="construct-badge">bitstrings</span>, <span class="construct-badge">syntactic objects</span>) using bearer
                                    theory, plus the insight that identity and <span class="construct-badge">system functions</span> come from
                                    <span class="construct-badge">social positioning</span>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS with roots in philosophy/ontology (objects and nonmaterial entities).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed conceptually (ontology), but aimed at IS (response to under-theorizing of
                                    the IT artifact).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation of what digital objects are).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Material vs nonmaterial objects</span>, <span class="construct-badge">syntactic objects</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">bitstrings</span>, <span class="construct-badge">bearers</span> (material/nonmaterial) and layers,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">social positions</span> (rights/responsibilities),
                                    <span class="construct-badge">system function</span>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>A <span class="construct-badge">digital object</span> is always borne by something (<span class="construct-badge">material</span> and sometimes <span class="construct-badge">nonmaterial
                                    bearers</span>). But what the object "is" and what it "does" depends on <span class="construct-badge">social positioning</span>
                                    and community expectations.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Great for conceptual clarity, but hard to operationalize and test. Use it as a
                                    foundation for IT artifact theorizing, not a full EP model.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Faulkner and Runde</mark> return to an old IS problem: we talk about "technology" all the time, but we
                        are not always clear what exactly we mean by the <mark>IT artifact</mark>. This is a direct response to
                        <mark>Orlikowski and Iacono's</mark> under-theorizing critique. In BCIS 6670 notes, the professor emphasized
                        one takeaway as the most important: the idea of <span class="construct-badge">social positions</span> and how rights and
                        responsibilities give digital objects identity in a sociotechnical system.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        A digital object becomes what it is through social positioning: identity is not only technical
                    </div>
                    
                    <p>The paper separates <span class="construct-badge">material objects</span> (physical bearers) and <span class="construct-badge">nonmaterial objects</span> (like <span class="construct-badge">bitstrings</span>
                        and <span class="construct-badge">syntactic objects</span>). It uses bearer theory to explain how a <span class="construct-badge">digital object</span> exists through
                        layers (a <span class="construct-badge">bitstring</span> borne by a file format, which is borne by storage hardware, etc.).</p>
                    
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        The key IS insight: <span class="construct-badge">social positioning</span> defines rights and responsibilities expected
                        of an object in that position. That is why the same technical artifact can become "different"
                        objects in different organizational settings.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>The course chain is clear in Week 2 materials: <mark>Orlikowski & Iacono (2001)</mark> argues we
                        under-theorize the IT artifact. <mark>Faulkner & Runde (2019)</mark> responds by giving an ontology for
                        digital objects. <mark>Sarker et al. (2019)</mark> connects the discipline identity back to sociotechnical
                        theorizing. Then <mark>Baird & Maruping (2021)</mark> uses a more agentic view (delegation) for AI-era
                        artifacts.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Very strong logical structure; forces conceptual clarity about what a
                                digital object is; makes <span class="construct-badge">social positioning</span> central (very exam-ready).</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Can become cumbersome and hard to operationalize; easy to get
                                lost in "where the bitstring lives" details.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong>
                                Treating the ontology as a predictive model; ignoring <span class="construct-badge">social positioning</span> and using only
                                the technical layer as "the object."</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Orlikowski &
                            Iacono (2001)</mark> for views of the artifact; affordances for action possibilities;
                            sociomateriality for entanglement-in-practice.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How does the <span class="construct-badge">social positioning</span> of a <span class="construct-badge">digital object</span>
                        shape what users treat as the object's legitimate <span class="construct-badge">system function</span>?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "When a <span class="construct-badge">digital object</span> is positioned with clear rights and
                        responsibilities, users will coordinate around it more consistently than when positioning is
                        ambiguous."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> Evidence of <span class="construct-badge">social positioning</span> (formal role
                        in processes, rights/responsibilities written into policies), plus evidence of how the artifact
                        is enacted in practice (logs, handoffs, governance).
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong>
                        <mark>Faulkner, P., & Runde, J. (2019)</mark>. Theorizing the digital object. <em>MIS Quarterly, 43</em>(4),
                        1279-1302. <em>Grounding in BCIS 6670 materials:</em>
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 2/Notes/Week2_Paper_Summaries.md</code>,
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 2/Assignments/Critique_Faulkner.md</code>, and extracted text files in
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 2/Papers/</code>.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="sociotechnical-axis-of-cohesion-sarker-et-al-2019">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Sarker et al., 2019</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Sociotechnical Axis of Cohesion (Sarker et al., 2019)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">The sociotechnical perspective as the defining axis of cohesion and identity for the IS discipline</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> The IS discipline's distinctiveness rests on theorizing the interaction between social and technical dimensions. A six-type classification reveals that when IS research abandons sociotechnical theorizing, the field risks losing disciplinary identity, fragmenting internally, and failing to address humanistic and ethical outcomes.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🔀 <strong>Sociotechnical Axis:</strong> Discipline identity depends on theorizing the interplay of social and technical, not privileging one over the other</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📊 <strong>Six-Type Classification:</strong> Papers vary from social-dominant to technical-dominant, with interaction types theorizing genuine interdependence</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Distinctiveness Risk:</strong> When IS research becomes purely social or purely technical, it loses disciplinary distinctiveness and becomes vulnerable to fragmentation</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚖️ <strong>Humanistic Outcomes:</strong> Sociotechnical focus ensures attention to both instrumental and humanistic consequences of technology</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> A discipline-level framework that clarifies what makes IS research distinctive. Essential for positioning research projects within the field and understanding how technology and organization truly interact rather than merely coexist.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Sarker et al. (2019)</mark>, "The Sociotechnical Axios of Cohesion for the IS Discipline:
                                    Its Historical Legacy and Its Continued Relevance," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Key
                                    contribution: argues the <span class="construct-badge">sociotechnical perspective</span> is the <span class="construct-badge">axis of cohesion</span> for IS,
                                    and offers a <span class="construct-badge">six-type classification</span> of MISQ/ISR research along a social-technical
                                    continuum.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (discipline identity and sociotechnical tradition).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">IS-native</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type I (analysis/classification) plus Type II (explanation of discipline
                                    fragmentation risks).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Sociotechnical axis of cohesion</span>, <span class="construct-badge">six types</span> (Type I to Type VI), <span class="construct-badge">instrumental vs
                                    humanistic outcomes</span>, <span class="construct-badge">distinctiveness</span> and <span class="construct-badge">ethical failure risks</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When IS stops theorizing <span class="construct-badge">social-technical interaction</span>, the field loses
                                    <span class="construct-badge">distinctiveness</span>, divides internally, and can fail ethically by ignoring <span class="construct-badge">humanistic
                                    outcomes</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>It is a discipline-level framework; not an individual-level causal model. Most
                                    useful as a critique and positioning lens.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Sarker et al.</mark> were worried that IS research was drifting away from its <span class="construct-badge">sociotechnical roots</span>. They
                        reviewed <mark>991 MISQ and ISR papers (2000-2016)</mark> and showed most work is either social-dominant or
                        treats technology in narrow ways. BCIS 6670 Week 2 notes add exam-ready framing from Professor
                        Sidorova, including the <mark>"Transport Test"</mark>: if you can transport the model from an IT context
                        (like IT security) to a non-IT context (like physical security in a school) with no change in
                        constructs or argument, then the paper is primarily social and technology is not really
                        theorized.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The six types classify how papers treat the social and the technical - without a shared sociotechnical axis, IS risks losing distinctiveness
                    </div>
                    
                    <p>The <span class="construct-badge">six types</span> are a classification of how papers treat the social and the technical. One clear
                        use in comps answers is to show where a paper sits and why that matters.</p>
                    
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        If a paper is <span class="construct-badge">Type I</span> social-dominant, it can be valuable, but it should not pretend to be sociotechnical. If a paper
                        is <span class="construct-badge">Type IV (interaction)</span>, it needs an interaction mechanism, not only survey variables.
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        The mechanism is discipline-level: without a shared <span class="construct-badge">sociotechnical axis</span>, IS risks losing
                        distinctiveness, fragmenting into disconnected communities, and failing ethically by ignoring
                        humanistic outcomes.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>Week 2 materials also discuss why <span class="construct-badge">Type I</span> dominates in top journals (practical reasons about data
                        availability and publication incentives). For comps, I can use this to show I understand
                        incentives without excusing shallow theorizing. This framework also connects to IT artifact
                        debates: <mark>Orlikowski & Iacono (2001)</mark> is a critique of missing IT; <mark>Faulkner & Runde (2019)</mark> gives
                        an ontology; delegation work makes agency and authority explicit. The <span class="construct-badge">sociotechnical axis</span> is the
                        "discipline positioning" umbrella over these moves.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Gives a concrete classification of how IS research treats technology;
                                provides language for discipline identity and ethical outcomes.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It is easy to overuse as a policing tool ("everything must be
                                in the middle") instead of a positioning lens.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Treating the <span class="construct-badge">six types</span> as survey categories without analyzing the
                                IT artifact; claiming <span class="construct-badge">Type IV interaction</span> without an interaction mechanism.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> Sociomateriality and affordances are alternative ways
                            to theorize the social-technical relationship, but they answer different questions
                            (entanglement vs action possibilities vs discipline cohesion).</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "Does this IS study theorize <span class="construct-badge">social-technical
                        interaction</span>, or can it be 'transported' to a non-IT context without change?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "The relationship between AI design features and user outcomes is
                        stronger when the design features change work practices (<span class="construct-badge">social-technical interaction</span>) than when
                        technology is treated as background."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong>
                        <ol class="framework-steps">
                            <li>Evidence of technology-in-use (not only perceptions)</li>
                            <li>Interaction mechanisms between social and technical</li>
                            <li><span class="construct-badge">Instrumental</span> and <span class="construct-badge">humanistic outcomes</span> together</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA
                            citation:</strong> <mark>Sarker, S., Chatterjee, S., Xiao, X., & Elbanna, A. (2019)</mark>. The
                        sociotechnical axis of cohesion for the IS discipline: Its historical legacy and its continued
                        relevance. <em>MIS Quarterly, 43</em>(3), 695-719. <em>Grounding in BCIS 6670 materials:</em>
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 2/Notes/Week2_Paper_Summaries.md</code>,
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 2/Papers/sarker_extracted.txt</code>, and
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 2/Assignments/Critique_Sarker.md</code>.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="5-views-of-the-it-artifact-orlikowski-iacono-2001">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Orlikowski & Iacono, 2001</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>5 Views of the IT Artifact (Orlikowski & Iacono, 2001)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">A taxonomy diagnosing how IS research conceptualizes and theorizes the IT artifact, from under-theorization to ensemble perspectives</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> IS research often under-theorizes the IT artifact, treating it as absent, nominal, or a black-box tool. A five-view taxonomy (Nominal, Tool, Computational, Proxy, Ensemble) exposes these patterns and calls for richer theorization where the artifact is embedded in organizational and practice contexts.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🏷️ <strong>Nominal & Tool Views:</strong> IT is either unnamed or treated as a stable black-box, risking under-theorization</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔢 <strong>Computational & Proxy Views:</strong> Focus on technical capabilities or surrogate measures (spending) instead of actual artifact properties</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔀 <strong>Ensemble View:</strong> Richest conceptualization where IT is embedded in users, organizations, and enacted through practices</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚠️ <strong>Discipline Distinctiveness:</strong> When IS research under-theorizes IT, the field loses distinctiveness and explanatory power</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> A diagnostic and critiquing framework for IS research. Essential for literature reviews, positioning papers, and understanding how IT conceptualization affects theoretical strength. Pushes the discipline toward richer artifact theorization.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Orlikowski & Iacono (2001)</mark>, "Desperately Seeking the IT in IT Research: A Call to
                                    Theorizing the IT Artifact," <em>Information Systems Research</em>. Key
                                    contribution: argues IS research often <span class="construct-badge">under-theorizes IT</span> and offers <span class="construct-badge">five views</span>
                                    (<span class="construct-badge">Nominal</span>, <span class="construct-badge">Tool</span>, <span class="construct-badge">Computational</span>, <span class="construct-badge">Proxy</span>, <span class="construct-badge">Ensemble</span>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (self-critique about the discipline).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">IS-native</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type I (analysis/classification). Taxonomy of views rather than a causal model.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Nominal view</span>, <span class="construct-badge">Tool view</span>, <span class="construct-badge">Computational view</span>, <span class="construct-badge">Proxy view</span>, <span class="construct-badge">Ensemble view</span>;
                                    <span class="construct-badge">under-theorization of IT artifact</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When the <span class="construct-badge">IT artifact</span> is treated as "commonplace" and unproblematic, explanations of
                                    IT effects become weak. The taxonomy helps diagnose how papers treat the artifact
                                    and where it disappears.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best used for literature critique and theory-section design. It does not directly
                                    explain behavior outcomes.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Orlikowski and Iacono</mark> reviewed <mark>ISR papers (1990s)</mark> and argued that in many studies the <span class="construct-badge">IT artifact</span>
                        is missing from theorizing or treated in a shallow way. Their discipline-identity point is
                        simple: if "IT" is our subject matter but we do not theorize IT, then IS loses distinctiveness.
                        Affiliation is visible in the PDF: <mark>Wanda J. Orlikowski</mark> was at <mark>MIT</mark> and <mark>C. Suzanne Iacono</mark> was at
                        the <mark>National Science Foundation</mark>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The five views are a clean exam tool for diagnosing how papers treat the IT artifact
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>1️⃣ Nominal</h4>
                            <p>IT is basically a label; the artifact is absent</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>2️⃣ Tool</h4>
                            <p>IT is a stable black-box tool</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>3️⃣ Computational</h4>
                            <p>Focus on computational capabilities</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>4️⃣ Proxy</h4>
                            <p>IT is measured via surrogates (like IT spending)</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>5️⃣ Ensemble</h4>
                            <p>IT embedded in users, organizations, and practices</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        In BCIS 6670 Week 2, the course chain was explicit: <mark>Orlikowski & Iacono (2001)</mark> critique → <mark>Faulkner & Runde (2019)</mark> digital object ontology → <mark>Sarker
                        et al. (2019)</mark> sociotechnical discipline identity → <mark>Baird & Maruping (2021)</mark> agentic artifacts and
                        delegation.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS research, this paper became a reference point for pushing the field away from <span class="construct-badge">nominal/proxy</span>
                        treatments and toward richer artifact conceptualizations (<span class="construct-badge">ensemble views</span>, artifact-in-practice
                        arguments, digital objects, sociomateriality).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Simple and powerful taxonomy; fast way to critique weak IT treatments;
                                gives a clear angle in comps answers.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Descriptive and
                                does not provide causal mechanisms; a comps answer needs to go beyond critique and
                                propose a better artifact theorization.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong>
                                Citing only "IT is under-theorized" while still relying on <span class="construct-badge">proxy measures</span>; claiming an
                                <span class="construct-badge">ensemble view</span> without data on practices.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Digital
                            Object Theory</mark> (ontology), sociomateriality (entanglement), affordances (action
                            possibilities).</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "Which <span class="construct-badge">IT artifact view</span> does my study implicitly
                        adopt, and what does that hide or reveal?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Studies that
                        treat AI as an <span class="construct-badge">ensemble</span> (artifact-in-practice) produce stronger explanations than studies that
                        rely on <span class="construct-badge">proxy measures</span> alone."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> Artifact features, usage
                        practices, and organizational context (for an <span class="construct-badge">ensemble view</span>). If I must use a proxy, I state the
                        limitation and propose a plan for richer theorizing.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong>
                        <mark>Orlikowski, W. J., & Iacono, C. S. (2001)</mark>. Desperately seeking the IT in IT research: A call to
                        theorizing the IT artifact. <em>Information Systems Research, 12</em>(2), 121-134. <em>Grounding
                            in BCIS 6670 materials:</em> <code>BCIS 6670/Week 2/Notes/Week2_Paper_Summaries.md</code>
                        and scanned PDF in <code>BCIS 6670/Week 2/Papers/</code>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="affective-response-model-arm-zhang-2013">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Zhang, 2013</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Affective Response Model (ARM) (Zhang, 2013)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">A framework clarifying affective concepts and their relationships in ICT contexts through taxonomy and nomological network</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Affect research in ICT is hindered by inconsistent concept definitions. ARM provides a structured vocabulary by organizing affective concepts (emotion, mood, feeling) across dimensions and proposing a nomological network showing how these concepts relate. This conceptual clarity improves measurement, hypothesis specification, and comparative understanding across studies.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🏷️ <strong>Affective Taxonomy:</strong> Distinguishes emotion (intense, object-specific), mood (diffuse, ambient), and feeling (subjective sensation) across dimensions</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔗 <strong>Nomological Network:</strong> Proposes explicit relationships among affective concepts showing how they influence each other and system use</div>
                        <div class="key-point">📏 <strong>Measurement Clarity:</strong> Precise concept definitions enable defensible operationalizations that align across studies and prevent construct confusion</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⏱️ <strong>Context-Specific:</strong> Tailored to ICT contexts and direct human-technology experience, not general psychology</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Exemplifies how theory papers can contribute through conceptual clarity rather than causal prediction. Helps IS researchers specify affective concepts precisely in technology contexts, improving measurement and enabling meaningful comparisons across empirical studies.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Zhang (2013)</mark>, "The Affective Response Model: A Theoretical Framework of Affective
                                    Concepts and Their Relationships in the ICT Context," <em><mark>MIS Quarterly</mark></em>. Key
                                    contribution: clarifies <mark>affective concepts in ICT</mark> via a <mark>taxonomy</mark> and proposes a
                                    <mark>nomological network</mark> (propositions) so affect research becomes more consistent.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td><mark>Psychology</mark> (<span class="construct-badge">affect</span>) brought into <mark>IS/HCI</mark> in <mark>ICT contexts</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed concepts (<span class="construct-badge">affect</span>), but theorized specifically for <mark>ICT context</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td><mark>Type IV</mark> (EP) with a strong <mark>Type I</mark> component (<mark>taxonomy</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Affect</span> (umbrella), <span class="construct-badge">emotion</span>/<span class="construct-badge">mood</span>/<span class="construct-badge">feeling</span>, <span class="construct-badge">taxonomy dimensions</span>, <span class="construct-badge">nomological network</span>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>The paper first clarifies concepts (<span class="construct-badge">taxonomy</span>), then proposes relationships among
                                    them (<span class="construct-badge">network</span>), so <mark>measurement</mark> and <mark>interpretation</mark> align across studies.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td><mark>ICT context</mark> and <span class="construct-badge">affective concepts</span> (not a full <mark>cognitive model</mark>). Focus is <mark>direct
                                    experience with ICT</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <mark>Zhang</mark> frames the problem as <mark>inconsistency</mark>: <span class="construct-badge">affect</span> studies in ICT are growing, but concepts and
                        definitions vary, which creates contradictions. Before asking what causes affect, we need <mark>conceptual clarity</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><mark>Zhang</mark> frames the problem as <mark>inconsistency</mark>: <span class="construct-badge">affect</span> studies in ICT are growing, but concepts and
                        definitions vary, which creates contradictions. Before asking "what causes <span class="construct-badge">affect</span>" or "what
                        <span class="construct-badge">affect</span> causes," we need conceptual clarity about <span class="construct-badge">affective concepts</span> and how they relate in ICT.
                        The ARM is built around three research questions: (1) what are the pertinent <span class="construct-badge">affective concepts</span>,
                        (2) how are they similar/different, and (3) how are they related.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        ARM's core contribution is a <mark>structured vocabulary</mark> for <span class="construct-badge">affect</span> in ICT contexts. The <span class="construct-badge">taxonomy</span>
                        organizes <span class="construct-badge">affective concepts</span> across dimensions, and the <span class="construct-badge">nomological network</span> proposes how these
                        concepts relate.
                    </div>

                    <p>ARM's core contribution is a <mark>structured vocabulary</mark> for <span class="construct-badge">affect</span> in ICT contexts. The <span class="construct-badge">taxonomy</span>
                        organizes <span class="construct-badge">affective concepts</span> across dimensions, and the <span class="construct-badge">nomological network</span> proposes how these
                        concepts relate.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        For comps, the value is that you can defend <mark>measurement choices</mark>: "I am
                        measuring <span class="construct-badge">mood</span>, not <span class="construct-badge">emotion</span>" is not cosmetic. It changes <mark>temporal dynamics</mark>, <mark>triggers</mark>, and
                        <mark>interpretation</mark>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In <mark>BCIS 6670</mark>, ARM is treated as a good "<mark>theory paper</mark>" exemplar because it shows what a clean
                        <mark>conceptual contribution</mark> looks like: define constructs carefully, show relationships, and explain
                        why definitions matter for <mark>empirical work</mark>. It also connects to the course's broader theme of
                        "<mark>theory as clarity work</mark>" (not only theory as prediction).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Reduces <mark>concept confusion</mark>; gives a defensible vocabulary and <span class="construct-badge">nomological
                                structure</span>; directly improves <mark>measurement</mark> and <mark>interpretation</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Still requires good <mark>operationalization</mark> in context; <span class="construct-badge">taxonomy</span> can
                                be cited superficially without changing actual measures.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Using "<span class="construct-badge">affect</span>" as a <mark>catch-all label</mark>; mixing <span class="construct-badge">mood</span> and <span class="construct-badge">emotion</span>
                                measures; claiming ARM but not aligning hypotheses with the <span class="construct-badge">network logic</span>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> Related work in <mark>emotion and affect in HCI</mark>, but ARM is
                            specifically <mark>ICT-focused</mark>. If the key story is <mark>cognition and effort</mark> rather than <span class="construct-badge">affect</span>,
                            <mark>cognitive load</mark> lenses may fit better.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How do different <mark>ICT design features</mark> trigger
                        distinct <span class="construct-badge">affective responses</span> (<span class="construct-badge">emotion</span> vs <span class="construct-badge">mood</span>), and how do these responses shape subsequent
                        use?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "In <mark>high-interruption contexts</mark>, ICT features that
                        increase <mark>perceived control</mark> reduce <span class="construct-badge">negative emotion</span> intensity and improve continued use
                        intentions."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> Separate measures for <span class="construct-badge">emotion</span> vs <span class="construct-badge">mood</span>,
                        <mark>timing of experience</mark>, and the <mark>ICT stimulus type</mark> (<mark>object vs behavior stimulus</mark>), aligned with the
                        ARM <span class="construct-badge">taxonomy</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Zhang, P. (2013)</mark>. The affective response
                        model: A theoretical framework of affective concepts and their relationships in the ICT context.
                        <em><mark>MIS Quarterly, 37</mark></em>(1), 247-274.</p>

                    <p><em>Grounding in BCIS 6670 materials:</em>
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Research Papers/Papers/Zhang2013AffectiveResponceTheory_MISQ2013.pdf</code>.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="is-delegation-framework">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Baird & Maruping 2021</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>IS Delegation Framework</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Reframes IS use as ongoing delegation of authority between humans and agentic artifacts.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Delegation to agentic IS artifacts is governed by three interconnected processes: appraisal (assessing capabilities and risks), distribution (allocating authority and accountability), and coordination (managing interactions, overrides, and handoffs). This is a dynamic, adaptive process rather than a static adoption decision.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Three-Part Process:</strong> Appraisal (assess), Distribution (allocate authority), Coordination (manage daily interactions)</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Dynamic Adjustment:</strong> Delegation changes as experience grows, outcomes occur, and task conditions shift—not a one-time choice</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Preference Alignment:</strong> Real delegation requires the artifact optimize human/organizational preferences, not only internal objectives</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Boundary Conditions:</strong> Most salient with agentic artifacts (autonomy, learning, decision agency) and high-stakes tasks with accountability demands</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Shifts IS use theory from "intention to use" to fundamental questions of authority allocation, accountability, and governance in human-AI systems—essential for understanding modern agentic IS artifacts.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Baird and Maruping (2021)</mark>, "The Next Generation of Research on IS Use: A Theoretical
                                    Framework of Delegation to and from Agentic IS Artifacts," <em><mark>MIS Quarterly</mark></em>.
                                    Key contribution: reframes <mark>IS use</mark> as <span class="construct-badge">delegation of authority</span> between humans and
                                    <span class="construct-badge">agentic IS artifacts</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td><mark>IS</mark> (drawing on <mark>delegation</mark>, <mark>authority</mark>, and <mark>human-automation research</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><mark>IS-native</mark> (built for <span class="construct-badge">agentic IS artifacts</span> like <mark>AI</mark> and <mark>robots</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td><mark>Type II</mark> leaning <mark>Type IV</mark>: it explains <span class="construct-badge">delegation dynamics</span> and also supports
                                    prediction of when <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> will increase/decrease.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Appraisal</span> (evaluate capabilities and risk); <span class="construct-badge">distribution</span> (allocate authority);
                                    <span class="construct-badge">coordination</span> (manage interaction and handoffs); <span class="construct-badge">agent archetypes</span> (<mark>reflexive</mark>,
                                    <mark>supervisory</mark>, <mark>anticipatory</mark>, <mark>prescriptive</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People delegate when they believe the agent can <mark>perform well enough</mark> and when the
                                    <mark>cost of coordination</mark> is acceptable. <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> is an ongoing adjustment of <span class="construct-badge">authority</span>
                                    and <span class="construct-badge">accountability</span> between human and system.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Applies to <span class="construct-badge">agentic IS artifacts</span> (<mark>autonomy</mark>, <mark>learning</mark>, and some <mark>decision agency</mark>). Less
                                    useful for traditional <mark>passive tools</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> depends on <mark>task stakes</mark>,
                                    <mark>explainability</mark>, and <span class="construct-badge">accountability</span> needs.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td><mark>Human-AI collaboration</mark> research in <mark>top outlets</mark> keeps expanding, including <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span>
                                    and <mark>identity questions</mark> in <mark>JAIS</mark> and <mark>trust dynamics</mark> in <mark>MISQ</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The IS delegation framework was proposed because "<mark>IS use</mark>" in the AI era is not just clicking
                        buttons. With <span class="construct-badge">agentic artifacts</span>, using the system often means <mark>handing over authority</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p>The IS delegation framework was proposed because "<mark>IS use</mark>" in the <mark>AI era</mark> is not just clicking
                        buttons. With <span class="construct-badge">agentic artifacts</span>, using the system often means <mark>handing over authority</mark>: letting an
                        algorithm decide, letting a robot act, or letting an AI agent recommend a course of action.
                        <mark>Baird and Maruping (2021)</mark> argue that <mark>classic IS use theories</mark> under-theorize this <span class="construct-badge">transfer of
                        authority</span>. Their framework puts <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> at the center and treats <mark>human-system relationships</mark>
                        as something <mark>negotiated</mark> and <mark>adjusted over time</mark>. Even though the paper is IS-native, it responds
                        to long-running ideas from <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> and <span class="construct-badge">authority</span> in organizations and from <mark>human-automation
                        interaction</mark>. The key IS move is to make <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> a theory of "<mark>use</mark>" that explicitly fits
                        <mark>autonomy</mark>, <mark>learning</mark>, and <mark>dynamic behavior</mark> in modern artifacts.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> between humans and <span class="construct-badge">agentic IS artifacts</span> is a process with
                        three connected components: <span class="construct-badge">appraisal</span>, <span class="construct-badge">distribution</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">coordination</span>.
                    </div>

                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Appraisal</h4>
                            <p>How people assess what the artifact can do, how <mark>reliable</mark> it is, and what the <mark>risks</mark> are.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Distribution</h4>
                            <p>How <span class="construct-badge">authority</span> is allocated (<mark>who decides</mark>, <mark>who acts</mark>, and <mark>who is accountable</mark>).</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Coordination</h4>
                            <p>How the relationship is managed day-to-day (<mark>monitoring</mark>, <mark>overrides</mark>, <mark>escalation rules</mark>, and <mark>handoffs</mark>).</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <p>The mechanism is <mark>dynamic</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> is rarely a one-time choice. As people gain <mark>experience</mark>,
                        <span class="construct-badge">appraisal</span> changes. As outcomes occur (good or bad), <span class="construct-badge">distribution</span> shifts (more <mark>autonomy granted
                        or taken back</mark>). As tasks change, <span class="construct-badge">coordination</span> costs change.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> is an <mark>adaptive governance process</mark>, not a <mark>static adoption decision</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> becomes most salient when the artifact is <mark>agentic</mark> and when
                        tasks have <mark>real consequences</mark> (<mark>medical decisions</mark>, <mark>hiring</mark>, <mark>credit</mark>, <mark>security monitoring</mark>). In
                        <mark>low-stakes contexts</mark>, delegation can look like routine use. In <mark>high-stakes contexts</mark>, it becomes a
                        question of <span class="construct-badge">accountability</span> and <mark>control</mark>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>

                    <p>Since <mark>2021</mark>, the broader IS conversation has moved quickly toward <mark>human-AI collaboration</mark>,
                        <span class="construct-badge">accountability</span>, and the <mark>social consequences of AI</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> fits naturally into that evolution
                        because it gives a structured way to ask "<mark>who has authority</mark>" and "<mark>who is responsible</mark>" in
                        sociotechnical systems.</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>BCIS 6670 Week 2 refinement:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> is
                        not just "let the AI decide." It is about <code>preference alignment</code>. The class used a
                        thermostat example: the thermostat might "prefer" keeping things very cold to maximize its
                        longevity, but the human wants comfort (like 72F). If the artifact's objective is not aligned to
                        the delegator's preferences, <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> is not real <span class="construct-badge">authority transfer</span>, it is just <mark>automation
                        that can work against the human</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p>The same notes also summarize <mark>levels of agency</mark> (<mark>simple reflex</mark>,
                        <mark>model-based</mark>, <mark>utility-based</mark>) and highlight that <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> becomes qualitatively different when
                        artifacts become <mark>utility-based</mark> and optimize a <code>utility function</code> that must be
                        aligned.</p>

                    <p><strong>Extensions:</strong></p>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Professional identity:</strong> <mark>Strich et al. (2021)</mark>
                            show how AI can threaten or strengthen professional role identities, which matters because
                            <mark>identity</mark> shapes whether people are willing to delegate and how they interpret AI decisions.</li>

                        <li><strong>Trust and relational dynamics:</strong> <mark>You and Robert (2024)</mark> study <span class="construct-badge">trust</span> in
                            working with robots using <mark>relational demography theory</mark>, and that directly links to <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span>
                            because <span class="construct-badge">trust</span> shapes how much <span class="construct-badge">authority</span> humans are willing to hand over.</li>

                        <li><strong>Integration with other theories:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> can be integrated with <mark>trust theory</mark> (why people accept
                            vulnerability), with <mark>accountability frameworks</mark> (how responsibility is assigned), and with
                            <mark>affordance theory</mark> (what actions are possible given the artifact and context).</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        The exam trap is to treat <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> as just another antecedent model. Its real value is <mark>reframing the dependent
                        variable</mark>: not "<mark>use</mark>", but <span class="construct-badge">authority allocation</span>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> The framework is useful because it fits the reality of <mark>modern AI systems</mark>. It helps IS
                            research move beyond "<mark>intention to use</mark>" and ask more serious questions about <span class="construct-badge">authority</span>,
                            <span class="construct-badge">accountability</span>, and <mark>ongoing adjustment</mark>. It is also <mark>flexible across contexts</mark>, since <span class="construct-badge">appraisal</span>,
                            <span class="construct-badge">distribution</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">coordination</span> show up in many human-AI relationships.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Because it is
                            broad, <mark>measurement is a challenge</mark>. Researchers can label many things as "<span class="construct-badge">appraisal</span>" or
                            "<span class="construct-badge">coordination</span>" without clear operationalization. Another limitation is that <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> can be
                            <mark>multi-actor</mark> (<mark>teams</mark>, <mark>organizations</mark>, <mark>regulators</mark>), so <mark>individual-level surveys</mark> may miss the real
                            governance mechanisms.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> A common misuse is to apply <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span>
                            language to <mark>any automation</mark>, even when the system is not <mark>agentic</mark>. Another is to treat <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span>
                            as <mark>one-way</mark> (human to AI) and ignore delegation from AI to humans (<mark>alerts</mark>, <mark>escalations</mark>,
                            <mark>requests</mark>). A third is to <mark>ignore accountability</mark>: <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> without <mark>responsibility</mark> is not the
                            real phenomenon the framework is trying to capture.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Trust theory</mark>
                            explains willingness to accept vulnerability; <mark>automation bias and reliance theory</mark> explain
                            over/under-reliance; <mark>sociomateriality</mark> explains entanglement of practices. <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> is
                            complementary, but it is not interchangeable with these.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> theory when the question is about humans <mark>handing off tasks or
                        decisions</mark> to AI/IS artifacts, and the outcome is <span class="construct-badge">authority</span>, <mark>reliance</mark>, or <span class="construct-badge">accountability</span> (not
                        just "<mark>use</mark>").
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "In <mark>cybersecurity operations centers</mark>, when do analysts
                        delegate intrusion detection decisions to AI tools, and how do <mark>audit</mark> and <span class="construct-badge">accountability</span>
                        requirements change that <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span>?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Higher <span class="construct-badge">appraisal</span> of AI capability is
                        positively associated with greater <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> of <span class="construct-badge">decision authority</span> to the AI tool, and this
                        relationship is weaker when <span class="construct-badge">accountability</span> demands are high."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Appraisal</span> can be captured with <mark>perceived capability</mark> and <mark>reliability</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Distribution</span> can be
                        captured by who has <mark>final decision rights</mark> (human vs AI) and <mark>override frequency</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Coordination</span> can
                        be captured by <mark>monitoring intensity</mark>, <mark>escalation rules</mark>, and <mark>handoff latency</mark>. For stronger
                        evidence, <mark>logs of overrides and escalations</mark> are ideal.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Baird, A., &
                        Maruping, L. M. (2021)</mark>. The next generation of research on IS use: A theoretical framework of
                        delegation to and from agentic IS artifacts. <em><mark>MIS Quarterly, 45</mark></em>(1), 315-341.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">Extended Notes from BCIS 6670</span>

                    <p>The <mark>Week 2 notes</mark> add practical points that enhance exam readiness.</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>Preference Alignment:</strong> For real <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span>, the artifact must optimize the <mark>preferences of the
                        human/organization</mark>, not only its own internal objective. The class used a <mark>thermostat example</mark>: a
                        thermostat can "keep temperature low," but the human wants comfort (say 72°F). Real <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span>
                        implies we design the <code>utility function</code> to reflect <mark>human/organizational preference</mark>,
                        not the artifact's default.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Levels of Agency</strong> (mentioned in class with a <mark>Russell
                        & Norvig</mark> reference): <code>simple reflex agent</code>, <code>model-based agent</code>, and
                        <code>utility-based agent</code>. The exam-ready point is "<mark>more choice → more internal
                        processing → more agentic</mark>." That helps explain why <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> becomes qualitatively different
                        with <mark>utility-based artifacts</mark> (<span class="construct-badge">agentic AI</span>). (Primary Russell & Norvig source not found in the
                        current workspace.)</p>

                    <p><strong>ChatGPT Example:</strong> We cannot treat <mark>ChatGPT preferences</mark> as
                        only "<mark>user satisfaction</mark>" because design can embed <mark>company constraints</mark> (e.g., <mark>cost</mark> and <mark>profit
                        motives</mark>). This is a clean bridge to <mark>Agency Theory</mark>: <code>preference alignment</code> and <mark>incentives</mark> still
                        matter when the agent is digital.</p>

                    <p><strong>Delegation as Social Positions:</strong> The class
                        also connected <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> to <mark>digital objects</mark> and <mark>social positions</mark>: <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> can be seen as an
                        interaction between two "<mark>social positions</mark>" (human and <span class="construct-badge">agentic IT</span>), where <mark>rights</mark> and
                        <mark>responsibilities travel together</mark>. That helps position <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> as <mark>sociotechnical governance</mark>,
                        not only behavior.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="human-ai-delegation-dynamics-liu-et-al-2025">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Liu et al. 2025</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Human-AI Delegation Dynamics</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Models delegation willingness as latent states that evolve through feedback loops and can polarize over time.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Delegation is a dynamic feedback system where managers observe performance outcomes, update beliefs about AI capability, and shift their latent willingness to delegate. Using a Hidden Markov Model, the paper captures delegation willingness as three sticky states (low/medium/high) that evolve through experience and can polarize, causing teams with identical AI systems to develop divergent delegation trajectories.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Latent States:</strong> Delegation willingness as three sticky states (low/medium/high) observable through delegation behavior and overrides</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Feedback Loop:</strong> Manager appraisals update beliefs → shifts latent willingness → shapes next delegation decisions → creates cycle</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Polarization Effect:</strong> Teams tend to stay in low or high states and can develop divergent trajectories even under identical AI systems</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Measurable Dynamics:</strong> Uses trace data (delegation share, overrides, KPI outcomes) to analyze governance changes as latent state transitions</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Makes delegation explicitly dynamic and measurable using operational data, enabling IS researchers to analyze human-AI relationships as changing sociotechnical systems rather than static adoption intentions.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Liu et al. (2025)</mark>, "Find the Good. Seek the Unity: A Hidden Markov Model of Human-AI
                                    Delegation Dynamics," <em><mark>MIS Quarterly</mark></em> (Research Note). Key contribution:
                                    models <code>delegation willingness</code> as a <mark>latent state</mark> and shows how
                                    willingness can <mark>polarize over time</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td><mark>IS</mark> + <mark>modeling/statistics</mark> (<mark>Hidden Markov Model</mark>) in <mark>human-AI collaboration</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><mark>IS-native lens</mark> (builds on <mark>IS delegation</mark>); borrowed method (<mark>HMM</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td><mark>Type IV</mark> (EP). Explains a <span class="construct-badge">feedback mechanism</span> and models <span class="construct-badge">delegation dynamics</span> over time
                                    (<span class="construct-badge">state transitions</span>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Delegation decision</span> (observable % tasks), <span class="construct-badge">delegation willingness</span> (latent states),
                                    <span class="construct-badge">performance appraisals</span> (Team vs Human, Team vs AI, Team vs Team), <span class="construct-badge">AI capability
                                    assessment</span>, <span class="construct-badge">delegation feedback loop</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Managers do <code>performance appraisal</code>, appraisal updates latent
                                    <code>willingness</code>, <span class="construct-badge">willingness</span> shapes future <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span>, and the cycle
                                    repeats.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td><mark>Retail firm context</mark> where AI is embedded in <mark>ERP replenishment</mark>. Requires <mark>rich logs</mark>,
                                    <mark>overrides</mark>, and <mark>KPI feedback</mark> over time.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The paper starts from a very IS question: if <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> is not a <mark>one-time choice</mark>, but changes
                        week by week, how should we model it?
                    </div>

                    <p>The paper starts from a very IS question: if <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> is not a one-time choice, but changes
                        week by week, how should we model it? <code>Delegation decision</code> is <mark>observable</mark> (the
                        percent of tasks delegated), but <code>delegation willingness</code> is not directly observed
                        and behaves like a <mark>state</mark>. The authors use a <mark>Hidden Markov Model</mark> to infer these <span class="construct-badge">latent states</span>
                        from observable behavior over time. Theoretically, they build on the <mark>IS Delegation Framework</mark> and
                        combine it with <code>instance-based learning theory (IBLT)</code> to argue that decision makers
                        update <span class="construct-badge">delegation strategies</span> through <mark>experience</mark> and <span class="construct-badge">feedback</span>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core exam story:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Delegation</span> in a <code>human-AI dyad</code> is a <span class="construct-badge">feedback system</span>. Managers
                        appraise outcomes, update beliefs about <code>AI capability</code>, and that shifts their latent
                        <code>willingness to delegate</code>. <span class="construct-badge">Willingness</span> then shapes the next round of <span class="construct-badge">delegation
                        decisions</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p>One finding that is easy to use in a comps answer is that <span class="construct-badge">delegation willingness</span> can
                        be captured as <mark>three latent states</mark> (<mark>low/medium/high</mark>) and these states are "<mark>sticky</mark>". People tend
                        to stay in <mark>low or high states</mark> and can <mark>polarize over time</mark>. That gives you a <mark>mechanism-focused</mark> way
                        to talk about why two teams can end up with very different <span class="construct-badge">delegation trajectories</span> even under
                        the same AI.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <span class="construct-badge">Delegation willingness</span> states are <mark>sticky</mark> and can <mark>polarize</mark> over time - teams can end up with very different trajectories under the same AI.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>For IS, the big move is making <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> explicitly <mark>dynamic and measurable</mark>, rather than treating
                        it as a static "<mark>intention</mark>" variable. In <mark>enterprise AI</mark>, we often have <mark>trace data</mark> (<span class="construct-badge">delegation
                        shares</span>, <mark>overrides</mark>, <mark>performance dashboards</mark>), and the paper shows how to use that to theorize
                        <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> as a <mark>changing sociotechnical relationship</mark>. This also connects cleanly back to the <mark>AI
                        Delegation Framework</mark>: <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> is shaped by <span class="construct-badge">appraisal</span> and <span class="construct-badge">feedback loops</span>. The added value is
                        the modeling logic for <span class="construct-badge">latent willingness</span> and <span class="construct-badge">transition probabilities</span>, which is a practical way
                        to analyze <mark>governance changes</mark> over time.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Strong <mark>dynamic view</mark>; clear <span class="construct-badge">feedback mechanism</span>; concrete
                                operationalization of <span class="construct-badge">latent willingness</span> from behavior.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong>
                                Needs <mark>rich operational data</mark> and a setting where <span class="construct-badge">delegation</span> is <mark>logged and appraised</mark>;
                                generalization needs careful <mark>boundary conditions</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Treating <span class="construct-badge">latent states</span> as <mark>stable psychological traits</mark>; using
                                "<mark>dynamic</mark>" language but analyzing only <mark>cross-sectional snapshots</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>IS Delegation Framework</mark> and <mark>ADF</mark> for conceptual
                            grounding; <mark>trust theory</mark> when the core story is <mark>vulnerability and reliance</mark> rather than
                            <span class="construct-badge">authority allocation</span>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How do <span class="construct-badge">appraisal feedback</span> and <span class="construct-badge">performance
                        comparisons</span> shape managers' <span class="construct-badge">delegation willingness</span> to AI over time?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Positive <span class="construct-badge">AI performance appraisals</span> increase the probability of
                        transitioning from a <mark>medium to a high</mark> <span class="construct-badge">delegation willingness</span> state over time."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Delegation share</span> over time, <mark>overrides</mark>, <mark>KPI outcomes</mark>, and <span class="construct-badge">appraisal
                        comparisons</span> (<mark>Team vs AI</mark>, <mark>Team vs Human</mark>) to connect <span class="construct-badge">feedback</span> to <span class="construct-badge">state transitions</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Liu, J., Yue, W. T., Leung, A. C. M., & Zhang, X. (2025)</mark>.
                        Find the good. Seek the unity: A hidden Markov model of human-AI delegation dynamics. <em><mark>MIS
                            Quarterly, 49</mark></em>(3), 1185-1204. https://doi.org/10.25300/MISQ/2024/18232</p>

                    <p><em>Grounding in BCIS 6670 materials:</em> PDF in <code>BCIS 6670/Research Papers/</code> (delegation
                        dynamics paper).</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="human-ai-hybrid-problem-solving-raisch-fomina-2024">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge strategy">Strategy</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Raisch & Fomina 2024</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Human-AI Hybrid Problem-Solving</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Three types of hybrid search configurations and their effects on organizational search scope and depth.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Organizations employ three distinct configurations for hybrid human-AI problem-solving: autonomous search (each operates independently), sequential search (one follows the other), and interactive search (continuous back-and-forth collaboration). Each configuration produces different outcomes in search scope and depth, with interactive search generally yielding broader and deeper exploration.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Three Configurations:</strong> Autonomous (separate paths), Sequential (one then other), Interactive (continuous collaboration)</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Search Mechanics:</strong> Each configuration affects organizational search scope (breadth of solutions) and search depth (thoroughness of exploration)</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Complementarities:</strong> AI excels at rapid breadth; humans at depth, judgment, and context—interaction leverages both strengths</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Design Implications:</strong> Configuration choice depends on problem characteristics, time constraints, and desired balance of novelty vs. quality</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Provides a structured taxonomy of human-AI collaboration modes in organizational contexts, enabling IS researchers to design and analyze hybrid systems that leverage complementary capabilities.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Raisch & Fomina (2023 proof; 2024 in syllabus context)</mark>, "Combining Human and
                                    Artificial Intelligence: Hybrid Problem-Solving in Organizations," <em><mark>Academy of
                                        Management Review</mark></em>. Key contribution: <mark>three types</mark> of
                                    <code>hybrid problem-solving</code> (<code>autonomous search</code>,
                                    <code>sequential search</code>, <code>interactive search</code>) and propositions on
                                    <code>search scope</code> and <code>search depth</code>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td><mark>Organization/strategy</mark> + <mark>behavioral theory of the firm</mark> (<span class="construct-badge">organizational search</span>) with a
                                    <mark>technology-conscious view of AI</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><mark>Borrowed</mark> (management origin), but very usable in IS for <mark>human-AI configurations</mark> and
                                    <span class="construct-badge">search mechanisms</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td><mark>Type IV</mark> (EP) conceptually: propositions about how <mark>configurations</mark> produce <mark>outcomes</mark>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Autonomous search</span>/<span class="construct-badge">sequential search</span>/<span class="construct-badge">interactive search</span>, <span class="construct-badge">problem definition</span>, <span class="construct-badge">solution search</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">selection</span>, <code>search scope</code>, <code>search depth</code>, <mark>AI-enabled
                                    mechanisms</mark> (e.g., <code>latent representations</code>,
                                    <code>interactive experimentation</code>, <code>anticipatory quantification</code>).
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Differences come from how humans and AI <mark>combine</mark> across <span class="construct-badge">problem definition</span>, <span class="construct-badge">search</span>,
                                    and <span class="construct-badge">selection</span>. That coordination changes <mark>novelty</mark> (<code>scope</code>) and how much solutions
                                    build on <mark>existing knowledge</mark> (<code>depth</code>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Focus is <mark>exploratory problem-solving</mark> (not <mark>routine automation</mark>). <mark>Time</mark> and <mark>expertise</mark>
                                    are important boundary conditions.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The historical problem is simple: classic <span class="construct-badge">organizational search theory</span> is mostly <mark>human-centric</mark>.
                        But now AI is involved in problem-solving, and many problems are
                        solved in a "<mark>hybrid</mark>" way, not just by automation.
                    </div>

                    <p>The historical problem is simple: classic <span class="construct-badge">organizational search theory</span> is mostly <mark>human-centric</mark>.
                        But now AI (especially <mark>generative AI</mark>) is involved in <span class="construct-badge">problem-solving</span>, and many problems are
                        solved in a "<mark>hybrid</mark>" way, not just by automation. The authors argue outcomes depend on <mark>how
                        organizations combine humans and AI</mark> (<mark>process matters</mark>). They also bound the scope early: the
                        focus is <mark>exploratory tasks</mark> (<mark>new and less-explored problems</mark>). Without this boundary, the model
                        becomes too generic to be useful.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        The main claim is that "<mark>hybrid</mark>" is not just putting humans and AI next to each other. We need to
                        specify roles across <span class="construct-badge">problem definition</span>, <span class="construct-badge">solution search</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">selection</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p>Based on this, the paper theorizes <mark>three processes</mark>:</p>

                    <div class="four-elements">
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Autonomous Search</h4>
                            <p>AI drives representation and solution search (via <code>latent representations</code> and
                                <code>latent space exploration</code>) and humans play a larger role in <span class="construct-badge">selection</span>. <strong>Expectation:</strong> <mark>Higher scope</mark> (more distant solutions) but <mark>lower depth</mark> (less grounded in existing
                                knowledge).</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Sequential Search</h4>
                            <p>Humans and AI work <mark>one after another</mark>, creating
                                <code>refined representations</code> and enabling <code>privileged search</code>. <strong>Expectation:</strong> <mark>Narrower scope</mark> but <mark>deeper solutions</mark>.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="element-card">
                            <h4>Interactive Search</h4>
                            <p>Humans and AI <mark>iterate</mark> (<code>shifting representations</code>, <code>interactive experimentation</code>)
                                and <span class="construct-badge">selection</span> becomes <code>interactive selection</code> (human heuristics combined with AI
                                quantification). <strong>Expectation:</strong> <mark>Broader scope</mark> than human-only, with <mark>depth similar</mark> to
                                human-only (novelty through recombination).</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>For IS, the value is <mark>process-level language</mark> for saying where "<mark>human-AI complementarity</mark>" actually
                        sits. If we only say "<mark>complementarity</mark>", it stays vague. This paper makes complementarity
                        concrete by locating it in <span class="construct-badge">representation</span>, <span class="construct-badge">search</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">selection</span>.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        This overlaps with the <mark>IS Delegation Framework</mark> but the angle is different. <mark>Delegation</mark> is about transferring <mark>rights and
                        responsibilities</mark> (<span class="construct-badge">authority and accountability</span>). <mark>Hybrid problem-solving</mark> is about producing
                        solutions and organizing <span class="construct-badge">search</span>. In comps answers, this contrast helps you pick the right lens
                        for the question.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Clear <mark>process configurations</mark>; compact outcomes (<code>scope</code> and
                                <code>depth</code>); explicit <mark>AI-enabled mechanisms</mark> that are easy to use in comps
                                answers.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> <mark>Conceptual model</mark>, so operationalization is hard
                                (especially measuring <code>scope/depth</code>). Easy to <mark>over-generalize</mark> beyond <mark>exploratory tasks</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Using the <mark>three types</mark> as a <mark>superficial taxonomy</mark>
                                without process evidence; mixing <mark>routine decision-making</mark> with <mark>exploratory
                                problem-solving</mark>; using "<mark>interactive</mark>" as a buzzword with no <mark>interaction-cycle evidence</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>IS Delegation Framework</mark> for <span class="construct-badge">authority distribution</span>;
                            <mark>sociotechnical lenses</mark> when the core issue is <mark>context</mark>, <mark>identity</mark>, and <mark>social positioning</mark>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How do <span class="construct-badge">autonomous</span>, <span class="construct-badge">sequential</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">interactive</span>
                        human-AI problem-solving processes affect <code>search scope</code> and <code>search depth</code> in <mark>exploratory tasks</mark>?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "<span class="construct-badge">Interactive search</span> increases <code>search scope</code> compared to
                        collective human search, while yielding similar <code>search depth</code> on average."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> <mark>Workflow logs</mark> and <mark>trace data</mark> (who defined the problem, who generated
                        options, who selected). For outcomes, a <mark>novelty/distance metric</mark> (<code>scope</code>) and a
                        <mark>reliance-on-existing-knowledge metric</mark> (<code>depth</code>).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Raisch,
                        S., & Fomina, K. (2023)</mark>. Combining human and artificial intelligence: Hybrid problem-solving in
                        organizations. <em><mark>Academy of Management Review,</mark></em> 1-24.
                        https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2021.0421</p>

                    <p><em>Grounding in BCIS 6670 materials:</em>
                        <code>BCIS 6670/Week 3 & 4/Papers/COMBINING HUMAN AND ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE: HYBRID PROBLEM-SOLVING IN ORGANIZATIONS.pdf</code>
                        and <code>BCIS 6670/StudyGuide/session3.html</code>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Part B Divider -->
            <div class="part-divider" id="part-b">
                <div>
                    <h2>🏢 Part B: Organizational & Strategic Theories</h2>
                    <p style="margin: 0; opacity: 0.9; font-size: 0.95rem;">Theories from organization science,
                        economics, and strategy</p>
                </div>
                <div class="part-count">18 Theories</div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="resource-based-view-rbv">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge strategy">Strategic Management</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Barney, 1991</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Resource-Based View (RBV)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Sustained competitive advantage through valuable, rare, and inimitable resources</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Firms differ in their resources and capabilities. When some resources are hard to copy or buy, they generate sustained performance differences. In IS, IT alone rarely creates advantage — it is the complementary assets and orchestration around IT that matter.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">💎 <strong>VRIN Framework:</strong> Resources must be Valuable, Rare, Inimitable, Non-substitutable</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔒 <strong>Isolating Mechanisms:</strong> Path dependence and causal ambiguity protect advantages</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🔗 <strong>Complementarity:</strong> IT advantage comes from bundling with governance, talent, and routines</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⚠️ <strong>Circularity Risk:</strong> Defining "valuable" only by performance creates tautology</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>Relevance for IS:</strong> Central to IT value and digital strategy research — explains why some firms extract sustained advantage from IT investments while others do not
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Barney (1991)</mark>, "Firm resources and sustained competitive advantage," <em><mark>Journal of
                                        Management</mark></em>. Key contribution: explains <span class="construct-badge">sustained advantage</span> through
                                    <mark>valuable</mark>, <mark>rare</mark>, <mark>inimitable</mark>, and <mark>non-substitutable</mark> resources.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Important precursor</td>
                                <td><mark>Wernerfelt (1984)</mark>, "A resource-based view of the firm," <em><mark>Strategic Management
                                        Journal</mark></em>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Strategic management (with links to economics).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (imported into IS strategy and IT value research).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type IV (explanation and prediction): explains why advantage persists and supports
                                    predictions about which resources can sustain it.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Resources</span>; <span class="construct-badge">capabilities</span>; <span class="construct-badge">VRIN/VRIO</span>; <span class="construct-badge">competitive advantage</span>; <span class="construct-badge">sustained advantage</span>;
                                    <span class="construct-badge">isolating mechanisms</span> (<mark>path dependence</mark>, <mark>causal ambiguity</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Firms differ in their <span class="construct-badge">resources</span> and <span class="construct-badge">capabilities</span>. When some <span class="construct-badge">resources</span> are <mark>hard to
                                    copy or buy</mark>, they can generate <span class="construct-badge">sustained performance differences</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Hard to measure "<mark>value</mark>" and "<mark>inimitability</mark>" without becoming <mark>circular</mark>. <mark>Digital
                                    resources</mark> can be <mark>replicated fast</mark>, so <span class="construct-badge">sustained advantage</span> often comes from
                                    <span class="construct-badge">complementary assets</span> and <mark>orchestration</mark>, not from IT alone.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Recent MISQ work reframes digital resources as strategic assets and pushes for
                                    clearer construct definitions in digital strategy research. In my local reading set,
                                    this is the clearest 2020-2025 top-outlet RBV-adjacent anchor, so I log it as
                                    partial coverage in QA.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        RBV comes from a classic strategy question: why do some firms outperform others in a way that
                        <mark>lasts</mark>? The basic answer is that firms have different <span class="construct-badge">resources</span> and <span class="construct-badge">capabilities</span>, and those differences matter for <span class="construct-badge">performance</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p><mark>Penrose</mark> is an early root. She treats the firm as a <mark>bundle of productive
                        resources and services</mark>. <mark>Wernerfelt (1984)</mark> is the direct precursor that names a "<mark>resource-based view</mark>". <mark>Barney (1991)</mark> is the seminal formalization that most
                        people cite in comps answers because it gives the <span class="construct-badge">VRIN</span> logic in a clear way (<mark>valuable</mark>, <mark>rare</mark>,
                        <mark>inimitable</mark>, <mark>non-substitutable</mark>).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Sustained competitive advantage</span> depends on <span class="construct-badge">resources</span> and
                        <span class="construct-badge">capabilities</span> that competitors cannot easily get or copy.
                    </div>

                    <p>"<span class="construct-badge">Resources</span>" can be <mark>assets</mark>, <mark>processes</mark>,
                        <mark>knowledge</mark>, or <mark>relationships</mark>, but the key point is not the label. The key is whether the resource
                        creates <mark>value</mark>, is <mark>scarce</mark>, and is protected by <span class="construct-badge">isolating mechanisms</span>. The causal
                        mechanism in RBV is usually explained through two ideas: <span class="construct-badge">heterogeneity</span> and <span class="construct-badge">immobility</span>. Firms
                        differ (<span class="construct-badge">heterogeneity</span>), and those differences can persist because some <span class="construct-badge">resources</span> are hard to
                        transfer or imitate (<span class="construct-badge">immobility</span>).</p>

                    <p>In <mark>digital contexts</mark>, the "<mark>hard to imitate</mark>" part is often not
                        the software itself. It is the <span class="construct-badge">complementarity</span> around it, like <mark>data quality routines</mark>,
                        <mark>governance</mark>, <mark>talent</mark>, and the <mark>learning-by-doing</mark> that accumulates over time.</p>

                    <div class="critical-point">
                        RBV can become <mark>circular</mark> if a paper defines a resource as "<mark>valuable</mark>"
                        only because the firm performs well. A good RBV study is careful about <mark>defining the resource before
                        looking at performance</mark>, specifying competitors, and explaining why imitation is hard.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>

                    <p>IS researchers imported RBV mainly to answer <mark>IT value questions</mark>. A simple RBV argument is: IT by
                        itself is <mark>easy to buy</mark>, so IT rarely creates <span class="construct-badge">sustained advantage</span> alone.</p>

                    <p><mark>Mata, Fuerst, and Barney (1995)</mark> is a foundational IS piece because it explicitly applies RBV logic to
                        IT and argues that <mark>managerial IT skills</mark> and <mark>firm-specific complements</mark> are more likely to meet
                        <span class="construct-badge">VRIN</span> conditions than the technology itself. <mark>Wade and Hulland (2004)</mark> provide an IS-focused
                        review and classify IS resources (<mark>outside-in</mark>, <mark>inside-out</mark>, and <mark>spanning</mark>).</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        For comps, Wade and Hulland (2004) is a strong
                        citation because it lets you speak in an IS-native way (<mark>IT assets</mark> vs <mark>IT capabilities</mark> vs
                        <mark>relational resources</mark>) instead of only repeating VRIN.
                    </div>

                    <p><mark>Piccoli et al. (2022)</mark> push for
                        clearer construct definitions around "<span class="construct-badge">digital resources</span>" and "<span class="construct-badge">digital strategic initiatives</span>".</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> RBV is useful because it forces you to stop saying "<mark>IT leads to performance</mark>" in a
                            generic way. It pushes you to specify what the <span class="construct-badge">resource</span> is, why it is <mark>valuable</mark>, why it is <mark>rare</mark>,
                            and why competitors cannot copy it.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> RBV often struggles with <mark>measurement</mark> and <mark>endogeneity</mark>.
                            Firms that perform well may invest more in <span class="construct-badge">resources</span>, so it is hard to know <mark>direction of
                            causality</mark>. Many RBV studies stay at a high level and do not open the
                            <mark>black box</mark> of how <span class="construct-badge">capabilities</span> are built and maintained.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Calling any IT system a "<mark>strategic resource</mark>" without showing <mark>scarcity</mark> or
                            <mark>inimitability</mark>. Claiming <span class="construct-badge">VRIN</span> without evidence (no discussion of
                            competitors or substitutes). Treating the argument as <mark>timeless</mark> and ignoring that
                            <span class="construct-badge">digital resources</span> can <mark>diffuse quickly</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Agency theory</mark> or <mark>transaction cost logic</mark> for governance issues. <mark>Institutional theory</mark> for legitimacy and regulation. <mark>Dynamic capability thinking</mark> for rapid change contexts.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use RBV when the question is about why some firms get <span class="construct-badge">sustained performance</span>
                        benefits from <span class="construct-badge">IT resources</span> and <span class="construct-badge">capabilities</span> while others do not.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "When do <span class="construct-badge">digital strategic initiatives</span> become a <span class="construct-badge">sustained competitive advantage</span>, and what
                        <span class="construct-badge">complementary digital resources</span> make that advantage durable?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Firms with
                        stronger <span class="construct-badge">digital resources</span> (<mark>data governance routines</mark> and <mark>analytics talent</mark>) will have higher
                        <span class="construct-badge">performance</span>, and this effect will be stronger when those <span class="construct-badge">resources</span> are embedded in <mark>firm-specific
                        processes</mark> that are hard for competitors to imitate."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would
                        define <span class="construct-badge">digital resources</span> concretely (<mark>governance maturity</mark>, <mark>data quality routines</mark>,
                        <mark>analytics talent depth</mark>) and measure outcomes using <mark>objective performance</mark> where possible. I would
                        try to use <mark>longitudinal data</mark> because resource building takes time, and I would discuss
                        <mark>endogeneity</mark> explicitly (high performers can buy more resources).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Barney, J. (1991)</mark>.
                        Firm resources and sustained competitive advantage. <em><mark>Journal of Management, 17</mark></em>(1),
                        99-120.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="agency-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge economics">Economics</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Jensen & Meckling 1976</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Agency Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Governance structures reduce agency problems through contracts, monitoring, and incentives under information asymmetry.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> When principals delegate work to agents who have different goals and better information, agency problems arise. Governance structures—monitoring, incentives, and contracts—address hidden action (moral hazard) and hidden information (adverse selection) by making behavior more observable and aligning payoff structures.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Principal-Agent Problem:</strong> Agents may prioritize self-interest over principal's goals; information asymmetry prevents direct observation</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Agency Costs:</strong> Monitoring (reduces moral hazard), incentives (align payoffs), bonding, and residual loss from imperfect alignment</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Governance Mechanisms:</strong> Behavior-based contracts (monitor actions), outcome-based contracts (monitor results) chosen by goal conflict level</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Boundary Conditions:</strong> Strongest when goal conflict, measurability, and economic incentives are salient; weaker when intrinsic motivation or shared identity drives behavior</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains IT governance, outsourcing relationships, and cybersecurity disclosure as outcomes of information asymmetry and monitoring choices—technologies shape what can be monitored and observed.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Jensen and Meckling (1976)</mark>, "Theory of the firm: Managerial behavior, agency costs
                                    and ownership structure," <em><mark>Journal of Financial Economics</mark></em>. Key contribution:
                                    formalizes <span class="construct-badge">principal-agent problems</span> and <span class="construct-badge">agency costs</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Key synthesis</td>
                                <td><mark>Eisenhardt (1989)</mark> clarifies agency theory's assumptions, mechanisms, and when to use
                                    it in organizational research.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Economics/finance and organizational economics.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (widely imported into IS for governance, outsourcing, and security
                                    disclosure).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II and often Type IV: explains incentive and monitoring choices and can
                                    generate predictions about governance outcomes.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Principal</span>, <span class="construct-badge">agent</span>, <span class="construct-badge">information asymmetry</span>, <span class="construct-badge">moral hazard</span>, <span class="construct-badge">adverse selection</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">monitoring</span>, <span class="construct-badge">incentives</span>, <span class="construct-badge">contracts</span>, <span class="construct-badge">agency costs</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When agents have different goals and more information than principals, they may act
                                    in self-interest. Principals respond through contracts, incentives, and monitoring
                                    to align behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Works best when goal conflict, measurability, and contracting are central. Less
                                    fitting when intrinsic motivation, identity, or shared goals drive behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Agency logic appears in recent top-outlet IS work on cyber risk disclosures and
                                    governance choices under information asymmetry. In my local reading set, this is the
                                    clearest 2020-2025 top-outlet anchor, so I log it as partial coverage in QA.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Agency theory starts with a simple idea: when one party (a principal) delegates work to another
                        party (an agent), problems can arise because they may have different goals and the agent usually
                        has better information about what they are doing. Jensen and Meckling (1976) describe the firm
                        as a nexus of contracts and explain agency costs as the costs of monitoring, bonding, and
                        residual loss. Eisenhardt (1989) is a key synthesis because it turns the theory into an
                        exam-ready toolkit. She clarifies the main assumptions (self-interest, information asymmetry),
                        the conditions that make agency problems worse (uncertainty, goal conflict), and the main
                        governance choices (behavior-based vs outcome-based contracts). Affiliation note: I did not
                        verify author affiliations from the original articles in my local workspace, so I am not listing
                        them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Governance structures</span> are chosen to reduce <span class="construct-badge">agency problems</span>. The mechanism is <mark>alignment under</mark> <span class="construct-badge">information
                        asymmetry</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Monitoring</span> reduces <mark>hidden action</mark> (<span class="construct-badge">moral hazard</span>) by making behavior more observable.
                        <span class="construct-badge">Incentives</span> and <span class="construct-badge">contracts</span> shift the payoff structure so the <span class="construct-badge">agent's</span> best choice is closer to the
                        <span class="construct-badge">principal's</span> interest.</p>

                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> Agency theory fits best when <mark>goal conflict</mark> and <mark>contracting</mark> are
                        central. Less fitting when work is driven by <mark>intrinsic motivation</mark>, <mark>shared identity</mark>, or
                        <mark>professional norms</mark>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, agency theory has been widely used in research on IT outsourcing, IT governance, and
                        inter-organizational relationships because those contexts naturally involve delegation and
                        information asymmetry. The IS twist is that digital technologies also change monitoring and
                        measurability. Logs, dashboards, and analytics can reduce information gaps, but they can also
                        create new moral hazard problems (people learn to game metrics). More recently, agency logic
                        appears in cybersecurity disclosure work. Cyber risk is hard for investors to observe directly,
                        which increases information asymmetry. Managers may face incentives to frame disclosures in ways
                        that protect reputation or reduce perceived blame. Cao et al. (2025) is a good recent anchor
                        because it studies cyber risk disclosures and shareholder response, and it creates a clean
                        setting for contrasting incentive logic (agency) with framing logic (prospect theory).
                        Integration with other theories is common in modern IS settings. Agency theory often pairs well
                        with prospect theory when you want to model both the manager's strategic disclosure choices
                        (agency) and the investor's psychological response to framing (prospect). It can also pair with
                        institutional theory when regulation changes disclosure incentives and monitoring.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Agency theory gives a clear mechanism for <span class="construct-badge">governance</span> under <mark>delegation</mark>. It helps you
                            explain why <span class="construct-badge">contracts</span>, <span class="construct-badge">monitoring</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">incentives</span> exist.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> The biggest limitation is
                            <mark>behavioral realism</mark>. The theory often assumes <mark>self-interested agents</mark> and treats motivation as
                            mainly economic. In many IS contexts, <mark>professional values</mark>
                            and <mark>intrinsic motivation</mark> matter.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Treating agency theory as a generic story about
                            "<mark>misaligned incentives</mark>" without specifying the <span class="construct-badge">principal</span>, <span class="construct-badge">agent</span>, <span class="construct-badge">information asymmetry</span>, and the
                            governance instrument. Using agency language at the <mark>individual level</mark> when the
                            real agency relationship is <mark>organizational</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Stewardship theory</mark> when agents are motivated to act in the principal's interest. <mark>Trust
                            theory</mark> when governance happens through relationships. <mark>Institutional theory</mark> when behavior is driven by
                            <mark>legitimacy and regulation</mark>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use agency theory when the question is about <span class="construct-badge">incentives</span>, <span class="construct-badge">monitoring</span>, and
                        <span class="construct-badge">information asymmetry</span> (<mark>outsourcing</mark>, <mark>platform governance</mark>, or <mark>cybersecurity disclosure</mark>).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How do <span class="construct-badge">information asymmetry</span> and <span class="construct-badge">monitoring capability</span> shape a firm's
                        decision to disclose cyber risks proactively versus only after an incident?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Firms with greater <span class="construct-badge">information asymmetry</span> between managers and shareholders will provide cyber
                        risk disclosures that emphasize <mark>mitigation and response</mark> rather than <mark>prevention</mark>."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> Operationalize <span class="construct-badge">information asymmetry</span> using proxies like <mark>analyst
                        forecast dispersion</mark>, <mark>governance indicators</mark>, or <mark>disclosure complexity</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Monitoring capability</span> can
                        be proxied by <mark>audit strength</mark>, <mark>internal control quality</mark>, or <mark>security governance maturity</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Jensen, M. C., & Meckling, W. H. (1976)</mark>.
                        Theory of the firm: Managerial behavior, agency costs and ownership structure. <em><mark>Journal of
                            Financial Economics, 3</mark></em>(4), 305-360.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="institutional-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge sociology">Sociology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">DiMaggio & Powell 1983</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Institutional Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Organizations adopt similar structures and practices for legitimacy through coercive, normative, and mimetic pressures.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Organizations become similar (isomorphic) not only for efficiency but primarily to gain legitimacy. Three institutional pressures drive adoption: coercive (laws, regulations), normative (professional standards), and mimetic (copying peers under uncertainty). Scott's three pillars—regulative, normative, and cognitive—explain how institutions work at field and organizational levels.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Three Pressures:</strong> Coercive (rules/sanctions), Normative (professional standards), Mimetic (copying under uncertainty)</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Institutional Pillars:</strong> Regulative (formal rules), Normative (values/obligations), Cognitive (taken-for-granted beliefs)</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Legitimacy Driver:</strong> Organizations adopt practices to appear legitimate to stakeholders, not only to improve efficiency</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Field-Level Effect:</strong> Strongest at organizational field/industry level; explains convergence and industry-wide adoption patterns</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains IT adoption, compliance patterns, privacy breach notification, and technology regulation as outcomes of institutional pressures for legitimacy rather than pure efficiency optimization.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>DiMaggio and Powell (1983)</mark>, "The iron cage revisited: Institutional isomorphism and
                                    collective rationality in organizational fields," <em>American Sociological
                                        Review</em>. Key contribution: explains why organizations become similar through
                                    <span class="construct-badge">legitimacy</span> pressures.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Key synthesis</td>
                                <td><mark>Scott (1995)</mark>, <em>Institutions and Organizations</em>. Clarifies <mark>regulative,
                                    normative, and cognitive pillars</mark> and how <span class="construct-badge">institutions</span> shape organizations.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Sociology (new institutionalism).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (imported widely into IS for diffusion, compliance, and legitimacy
                                    questions).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains organizational convergence, adoption, and compliance
                                    through institutional pressures and legitimacy.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Institutions</span>; <span class="construct-badge">legitimacy</span>; <span class="construct-badge">organizational field</span>; <span class="construct-badge">isomorphism</span> (<mark>coercive, mimetic,
                                    normative</mark>); <span class="construct-badge">institutional pillars</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Organizations adopt structures and practices to look legitimate, not only to be
                                    efficient. Pressures from regulators, peers, and professional norms drive
                                    similarity.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Works best at field/industry level and under uncertainty or regulation. Less precise
                                    for micro-level cognition unless paired with other theories.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Institutional logic shows up in recent MISQ work on privacy breach notification and
                                    regulation, where laws and norms create coercive pressure and legitimacy incentives.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Institutional theory</mark> (new institutionalism) developed to explain a pattern that efficiency-based
                        theories often miss: organizations in the same field frequently become similar, even when there
                        is no clear efficiency reason to do so. <mark>DiMaggio and Powell (1983)</mark> explain this similarity
                        through <span class="construct-badge">isomorphism</span>. Organizations face <span class="construct-badge">coercive pressures</span> (laws, regulations), <span class="construct-badge">normative
                        pressures</span> (professional standards), and <span class="construct-badge">mimetic pressures</span> (copying peers under uncertainty). The
                        key mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">legitimacy</span>. Organizations need to be seen as appropriate by important
                        audiences. <mark>Scott (1995)</mark> provides a broader synthesis by framing <span class="construct-badge">institutions</span> through three
                        pillars: <mark>regulative</mark> (rules and sanctions), <mark>normative</mark> (values and obligations), and <mark>cognitive</mark>
                        (taken-for-granted beliefs). In comps answers, Scott is useful because it helps you specify what
                        kind of institutional pressure you mean, instead of using the term in a vague way. Affiliation
                        note: I did not verify author affiliations from the original articles/books in my local
                        workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> Many organizational actions are driven by <span class="construct-badge">legitimacy</span>, not only
                        efficiency. Adoption decisions often reflect pressures from regulators, professional norms, and
                        peer imitation.
                    </div>

                    <p>That is why institutional theory is strong for explaining <mark>diffusion</mark> and
                        <mark>convergence</mark> in industries like healthcare, finance, and public sector IT. The causal mechanism
                        is <mark>pressure and meaning</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Coercive pressure</span> changes behavior through formal requirements and
                        sanctions. <span class="construct-badge">Normative pressure</span> works through professional training and shared standards about
                        "good practice". <span class="construct-badge">Mimetic pressure</span> works through copying and benchmarking under uncertainty.
                        Scott's pillars help you explain why these pressures can be both external (laws) and internal
                        (taken-for-granted beliefs). Boundary conditions are built into the level of analysis.
                        Institutional theory is strongest at the <mark>field and organizational level</mark>. If your research
                        question is micro-level cognition (what one individual believes), institutional theory alone may
                        be too coarse unless you connect it to micro mechanisms (sensemaking, identity, professional
                        role).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, institutional theory became a common lens for understanding IT adoption, diffusion, and
                        compliance. It is especially useful when the dependent variable is "why do organizations adopt
                        the same practice" or "why do they comply". <mark>Orlikowski and Barley (2001)</mark> is a useful bridge
                        paper for IS because it argues that technology and <span class="construct-badge">institutions</span> shape each other, and it
                        encourages IS scholars to take institutions seriously rather than treating them as background
                        context. For comps, it is also a clean way to connect institutional thinking to debates about
                        the IT artifact and sociotechnical change. Recent top-outlet IS work uses institutional logic to
                        study privacy and regulation. <mark>Kim et al. (2024)</mark> study privacy breaches and customer notification
                        effects, which is tightly linked to <span class="construct-badge">coercive and normative pressures</span> around disclosure and
                        <span class="construct-badge">legitimacy</span>. <mark>Seidel et al. (2025)</mark> focus on regulating emerging technologies and shows how
                        abstraction and elaboration shape prospective sensemaking, which is an institutional process for
                        building shared expectations and legitimacy.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Integration with institutional logics:</strong> Classic institutional theory emphasizes <mark>convergence</mark>, while institutional logics emphasizes
                        <mark>heterogeneity</mark> and conflict among multiple logics. In comps answers, the clean contrast is:
                        institutional theory explains why organizations become <em>similar</em>; institutional logics explains
                        why they can stay <em>different</em> and how conflicts play out.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Institutional theory is powerful for explaining <mark>organizational similarity</mark> and
                            <mark>compliance</mark>. It gives you a clear way to talk about why firms adopt practices for <span class="construct-badge">legitimacy</span>
                            reasons, especially in regulated environments and under uncertainty.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Institutional
                            explanations can become <mark>vague</mark> if the paper does not specify the institutional pressure and the
                            audience that matters. Another limitation is that the theory can underplay <mark>agency and power</mark>
                            unless you bring those in explicitly. This is why institutional logics and practice theories are
                            often used alongside it.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A common misuse is listing "<span class="construct-badge">coercive,
                            mimetic, normative</span>" pressures as three survey variables without showing what the pressures
                            actually are in the field. Another misuse is treating <span class="construct-badge">institutions</span> as <mark>static</mark>, when many digital
                            domains are changing quickly.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>RBV</mark> and <mark>agency theory</mark> are useful
                            when the main driver is value or incentives rather than legitimacy. <mark>Sociomateriality</mark> and
                            <mark>affordance theory</mark> are useful when the main story is about how technology and practice co-produce
                            change over time.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use institutional theory when the question is about adoption driven by <span class="construct-badge">legitimacy
                        pressures</span> (<span class="construct-badge">coercive, normative, or mimetic</span>) rather than pure efficiency.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "Do stronger privacy breach notification requirements change firm behavior, and
                        through what type of institutional pressure?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Stronger <span class="construct-badge">coercive institutional pressure</span> (stricter notification requirements and enforcement) is associated with
                        greater investment in privacy and security controls over time."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I
                        would operationalize <span class="construct-badge">coercive pressure</span> using variation in <mark>laws</mark>, <mark>enforcement intensity</mark>, and
                        <mark>penalties</mark>. I would measure organizational responses using observable signals like <mark>security
                        hiring</mark>, <mark>governance changes</mark>, or <mark>adoption of privacy management tools</mark>. Outcomes can include breach
                        incidence or customer response metrics. The exam point is to map the design to the mechanism:
                        <span class="construct-badge">coercive pressure</span> should produce <mark>compliance behaviors</mark> and <mark>legitimacy-seeking actions</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>DiMaggio, P. J., & Powell, W. W. (1983)</mark>.
                        The iron cage revisited: Institutional
                        isomorphism and collective rationality in organizational fields. <em>American Sociological
                            Review, 48</em>(2), 147-160.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="complexity-science-complexity-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge">Systems Theory</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Simon 1962, Benbya et al. 2020</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Complexity Science / Complexity Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Many-part systems produce emergent behaviors through feedback loops and interdependence; small changes can cascade into large effects.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Complex adaptive systems have many interacting parts whose collective behavior cannot be predicted by analyzing isolated components. Digital systems—platforms, ecosystems, AI models—exhibit emergence, coevolution, nonlinearity, and feedback effects. Simon's nearly decomposable hierarchies explain why we can study subsystems partly in isolation but must account for emergent interactions.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Emergence & Interdependence:</strong> System-level behavior emerges from many component interactions; behaviors not predictable from parts alone</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Feedback Loops:</strong> Actions in one part change conditions in others, feeding back to create nonlinearity and path dependence</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Adaptive Coevolution:</strong> People, organizations, and technologies adapt and change together, creating dynamic sociotechnical systems</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Boundary Conditions:</strong> Most applicable to genuinely interconnected systems (platforms, AI, ecosystems); less useful for stable, decomposable phenomena</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Essential for understanding digital ecosystems, platform dynamics, cybersecurity vulnerabilities from system integration, and why standard linear causal models fail in interconnected sociotechnical systems.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Simon (1962)</mark>, "The architecture of complexity," <em>Proceedings of the American
                                        Philosophical Society</em>. Key contribution: complex systems are often
                                    <mark>hierarchical and nearly decomposable</mark>, which explains why we can study them in parts
                                    but still face <span class="construct-badge">emergent behavior</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Key IS adaptation</td>
                                <td><mark>Benbya et al. (2020)</mark>, "Complexity and information systems research in the emerging
                                    digital world," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: positions complexity
                                    science as essential for understanding digital systems (<span class="construct-badge">emergence</span>, <span class="construct-badge">coevolution</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">nonlinearity</span>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Systems science, organizational theory, cognitive science.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (brought into IS as a broad theoretical perspective).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Mostly Type II (explanation): explains why linear models fail in complex digital
                                    systems. Often used as an overarching perspective rather than a precise predictive
                                    model.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Complexity</span>, <span class="construct-badge">emergence</span> (weak/strong), <span class="construct-badge">nonlinearity</span>, <span class="construct-badge">feedback loops</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">self-organization</span>, <span class="construct-badge">coevolution</span>, <span class="construct-badge">adaptation</span>, <mark>chaos</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Many interacting parts produce system-level behavior that cannot be understood by
                                    adding up isolated effects. Small changes can trigger large outcomes through
                                    feedback and interdependence.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for complex adaptive systems (platform ecosystems, AI sociotechnical systems,
                                    multi-unit organizations). Less useful when the phenomenon is stable and
                                    decomposable. Prediction is often limited, so explanation and pattern recognition
                                    are emphasized.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Complexity theory is used directly in recent MISQ work on cybersecurity and
                                    organizational complexity, including M&A and multihospital systems.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Complexity thinking</mark> starts from a simple observation: many important systems have many
                        interacting parts, and the system behavior is not just the sum of the parts. <mark>Simon's (1962)</mark>
                        "architecture of complexity" is foundational because it explains why complex systems are often
                        <mark>hierarchical and nearly decomposable</mark>. We can study subsystems in isolation up to a point, but
                        interactions still create <span class="construct-badge">emergent outcomes</span>. In IS, this perspective became more central as
                        digital systems stopped looking like stand-alone applications and started looking like
                        <mark>ecosystems</mark>: platforms, APIs, data flows, and AI models embedded in organizations and society.
                        <mark>Benbya et al. (2020)</mark> argue that complexity science offers the right concepts for the digital
                        world, especially <span class="construct-badge">emergence</span>, <span class="construct-badge">coevolution</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">nonlinearity</span>. Affiliation note: I did not verify
                        author affiliations from the original articles in my local workspace, so I am not listing them
                        here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> Many digital phenomena are <span class="construct-badge">complex adaptive systems</span>. Outcomes <span class="construct-badge">emerge</span>
                        from interactions among many agents and artifacts, and small changes can lead to large effects
                        through <span class="construct-badge">feedback loops</span> and <span class="construct-badge">interdependence</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p>That is why linear "X causes Y" models can miss the
                        main story when the phenomenon is highly interconnected. The causal mechanism is <mark>interaction</mark>.
                        When components are tightly coupled, actions in one part of the system change conditions in
                        other parts. Those changes feed back into future action, which produces <span class="construct-badge">nonlinearity</span> and <mark>path
                        dependence</mark>. This mechanism is not only technical. It is <mark>sociotechnical</mark>: people adapt,
                        organizations change routines, and technologies evolve through updates and learning. Boundary
                        conditions are important. Complexity is most helpful when the system is genuinely interconnected
                        and adaptive. If the phenomenon is stable, decomposable, and governed by simple causal chains,
                        complexity language can become unnecessary. Another key boundary is <mark>prediction</mark>: complexity
                        theories often prioritize explanation, patterns, and process over precise point prediction.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p><mark>Benbya et al. (2020)</mark> is a key IS adaptation because it positions complexity science as a core
                        perspective for IS research and gives the field an agenda for studying <span class="construct-badge">emergence</span>, <span class="construct-badge">coevolution</span>,
                        and <span class="construct-badge">nonlinear dynamics</span> in the digital world. In 2020-2025, complexity shows up strongly in
                        cybersecurity research. <mark>Schneier and Vance (2025)</mark> explicitly argue that <span class="construct-badge">complexity</span> is a
                        fundamental enemy of security, which is a clean bridge between complexity theory and security
                        outcomes. <mark>Liang et al. (2025)</mark> use a complexity perspective to explain why mergers and
                        acquisitions increase data breaches, highlighting how integration creates new <span class="construct-badge">interdependencies</span>
                        and hidden vulnerabilities. <mark>Tanriverdi et al. (2025)</mark> study multihospital systems and show how
                        enterprise-wide data analytics platforms can tame some of that complexity by standardizing,
                        centralizing visibility, and enabling coordination.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Integration with systems theory and chaos theory:</strong> These are part of the same family of ideas. In comps answers, the
                        simplest move is: <mark>systems theory</mark> gives the holistic vocabulary, <mark>complexity</mark> adds emergence and
                        adaptation, and <mark>chaos</mark> adds sensitive dependence and unpredictability in nonlinear dynamics.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Complexity thinking fits modern digital phenomena where platforms, AI, and ecosystems
                            create strong <span class="construct-badge">interdependence</span>. It helps you explain why interventions have <mark>unintended effects</mark>
                            and why small events can <mark>cascade</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Complexity</span> can become a <mark>loose metaphor</mark> if the
                            paper does not specify what is complex (the system, the task, the organization, the ecosystem).
                            It can also be hard to translate into testable hypotheses because <mark>prediction is limited</mark> and many
                            mechanisms operate at once.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A common misuse is using the word
                            "complexity" to mean "complicated" or "hard" without specifying <span class="construct-badge">interactions</span> and <span class="construct-badge">feedback</span>.
                            Another misuse is claiming <span class="construct-badge">emergence</span> without tracing a process that shows how micro interactions
                            produced macro outcomes.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> If your phenomenon is mostly about
                            incentives and governance, <mark>agency theory</mark> may be a cleaner fit. If it is about legitimacy and
                            regulation, <mark>institutional theory</mark> may be stronger. Complexity is most useful when <span class="construct-badge">interdependence</span>
                            and <span class="construct-badge">nonlinear dynamics</span> are central.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use complexity theory when the question is about <span class="construct-badge">interdependencies</span> and <span class="construct-badge">nonlinear
                        effects</span> in digital systems (where a simple "one cause, one effect" story fails).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "How do mergers and acquisitions increase data breaches, and what governance
                        mechanisms reduce that risk?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Greater post-merger <span class="construct-badge">system interdependence</span> is
                        positively associated with breach incidence, and this relationship is weaker for firms with
                        enterprise-wide data analytics platforms."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would operationalize
                        <span class="construct-badge">complexity</span> using <mark>integration diversity</mark> (systems, processes, units), <span class="construct-badge">interdependence</span> indicators,
                        and <mark>governance fragmentation</mark>. Outcomes can be <mark>breach events</mark> over time. Mitigation mechanisms can
                        be platform adoption (enterprise-wide analytics), <mark>standardization</mark>, and <mark>monitoring</mark>. For causal
                        claims, panel designs and quasi-experimental approaches are useful because complexity and
                        security are both endogenous.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Simon, H. A. (1962)</mark>. The architecture of
                        complexity. <em>Proceedings of the American Philosophical Society, 106</em>(6), 467-482.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="human-capital-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge economics">Economics</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Becker 1964</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Human Capital Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Education and training are investments in skills that generate future returns through increased productivity.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Individuals and firms invest in human capital (skills and knowledge) when expected returns exceed costs. Skills raise productivity; general human capital is portable, while firm-specific human capital compounds within organizational routines and contexts. Skills also depreciate as technology changes, requiring ongoing investment.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Investment Logic:</strong> Skills treated as capital; costs (tuition, wages, opportunity time) versus expected productivity returns</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 General vs. Firm-Specific:</strong> General skills portable across employers; firm-specific skills embed in routines and context, creating switching costs</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Productivity Mechanism:</strong> Skills compound over time; skilled people learn faster and create better routines but face depreciation from technology change</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Measurement Challenges:</strong> Hard to observe directly; proxied by education, certifications, job titles; signaling and institutional pressures also drive investment</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains IT talent investment, cybersecurity hiring after breaches, and analytics talent roles in organizational capabilities—observable in job postings and hiring responses.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Becker (1964)</mark>, <em>Human Capital: A Theoretical and Empirical Analysis, with Special
                                        Reference to Education</em>. Key contribution: models education and training as
                                    <mark>investments</mark> that raise <span class="construct-badge">productivity</span> and future returns.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Economics (labor economics).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS for IT skills, digital talent, security workforce).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II and sometimes Type IV: explains talent investment decisions and can predict
                                    hiring/training responses to shocks.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Human capital</span> (skills/knowledge); <span class="construct-badge">investment</span> (education, training); <span class="construct-badge">returns</span>; <mark>general
                                    vs firm-specific skills</mark>; <span class="construct-badge">productivity</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Individuals and firms invest in skills when expected returns exceed costs. Skills
                                    raise productivity and improve outcomes (wages, performance).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Human capital is hard to measure directly, and investments can be driven by
                                    signaling or institutional norms, not only productivity. Skills also depreciate as
                                    technology changes.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Top-outlet IS work uses human capital theory to study post-breach hiring and the
                                    role of analytics talent in firm knowledge outcomes.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Human capital theory</mark> begins with an economic framing: skills and knowledge are a form of capital
                        that people and firms invest in because those investments generate future returns. <mark>Becker (1964)</mark>
                        formalizes this argument and makes a key distinction between <span class="construct-badge">general human capital</span> (skills you
                        can take anywhere) and <span class="construct-badge">firm-specific human capital</span> (skills that are most valuable inside one
                        firm). That distinction is very exam-useful in IS topics like analytics and cybersecurity
                        because much of the value depends on <mark>context and routines</mark>, not only on "having smart people".
                        Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliations from the original book in my local
                        workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Investment and return</span>. Individuals invest in education and training when
                        expected returns exceed costs (tuition, time, effort). Firms invest in training and hiring when
                        the expected <span class="construct-badge">productivity</span> gains exceed costs (wages, training time, turnover risk).
                    </div>

                    <p>The
                        mechanism is <mark>productivity and accumulation</mark>. Skills raise the ability to produce output (or to
                        produce output more efficiently). Over time, skills can compound because skilled people learn
                        faster and can create better routines. In digital settings, the mechanism also includes
                        <mark>depreciation</mark>: technical skills can become obsolete when technology changes. Boundary conditions
                        include measurement and alternative mechanisms. <span class="construct-badge">Human capital</span> is hard to observe directly, so
                        researchers often use proxies (<mark>education, job titles, certifications, postings</mark>). Also, not all
                        investment is productivity-driven. <mark>Signaling</mark> and <mark>institutional pressures</mark> can drive education and
                        hiring, so a good study separates productivity logic from reputation logic.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS research, human capital theory is often used when the key resource is <mark>digital talent</mark>. A
                        common move is to treat <mark>analytics talent</mark>, <mark>cybersecurity talent</mark>, or <mark>digital leadership skills</mark> as
                        investments that shape organizational outcomes. <mark>Castillo et al. (2021)</mark> is a strong IS example
                        that focuses on business analytics talent and links it to firm knowledge <span class="construct-badge">exploration</span> and
                        <span class="construct-badge">exploitation</span>, which is exactly a human capital mechanism (talent enables what the firm can learn
                        and do). <mark>Bana et al. (2025)</mark> is a clean recent cybersecurity example. It studies <span class="construct-badge">human capital
                        acquisition</span> after breaches, which frames breaches as shocks that change the perceived returns to
                        security talent and trigger hiring responses.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Integration with RBV:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Human capital</span> can be an RBV-relevant resource when it is <mark>scarce</mark> and embedded in <mark>firm-specific
                        routines</mark>, but human capital theory helps you explain <em>why</em> the firm invests in that talent in the
                        first place (expected returns).
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Human capital theory provides a clear economic mechanism for <span class="construct-badge">talent investment</span>. It is
                            especially useful in IS because digital capabilities often depend on specialized skills, and
                            hiring/training decisions are observable in data (<mark>job postings, resumes, internal training
                            records</mark>).</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> The biggest limitation is that "<span class="construct-badge">human capital</span>" can become a <mark>vague label</mark>.
                            Without careful measurement, it is easy to confuse skills with headcount. Another limitation is
                            that the theory can ignore <mark>social and institutional factors</mark>, like professional norms, labor
                            market constraints, and equity issues.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A common misuse is treating
                            <mark>job titles as direct measures of skill</mark>. Another misuse is assuming hiring always reflects
                            rational investment, when hiring can also be <mark>symbolic</mark> or driven by regulatory pressure.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>RBV</mark> is a strong alternative when the outcome is sustained
                            advantage rather than investment choice. <mark>Institutional theory</mark> is useful when hiring is driven by
                            legitimacy and compliance. <mark>Social capital theory</mark> is useful when the key resource is
                            relationships and access, not only skill.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use human capital theory when the question is about investing in skills (<mark>training,
                        hiring, retention</mark>) and how that <span class="construct-badge">investment</span> affects digital performance or security outcomes.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "After a data breach, do firms invest more in cybersecurity talent,
                        and how does that investment shape future breach risk?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Firms experience an
                        increase in cybersecurity-related hiring after a breach, and the increase is larger when the
                        breach has greater public visibility."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would measure <span class="construct-badge">human
                        capital investment</span> through <mark>job posting data</mark> (cybersecurity roles, analytics roles, PR roles) and
                        capture breach characteristics and timing. Outcomes can include future breach incidence or proxy
                        measures of security posture. For stronger causal inference, I would use <mark>panel methods</mark> and
                        compare breached firms to <mark>matched controls</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Becker, G. S. (1964)</mark>.
                        <em>Human capital: A theoretical and empirical analysis, with special reference to
                            education</em>. Chicago, IL: University of Chicago Press.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="modularity-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge strategy">Strategy</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Baldwin & Clark 2000</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Modularity Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Modular architecture with clear interfaces enables independent innovation and reduces coordination costs.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Systems decomposed into modules with stable interfaces enable faster innovation and change. Modules can be redesigned independently while maintaining overall system function. Interfaces become rules that enable and constrain innovation simultaneously, creating option value through recombination but also power asymmetries in control.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Architecture & Interfaces:</strong> Clear interfaces between modules enable independent change; modules loosely coupled, interfaces stabilized</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Coordination Costs:</strong> Modularity lowers coordination requirements; allows parallel work and faster innovation cycles</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Recombination & Option Value:</strong> Modular designs create building blocks for combination; support strategic flexibility and ecosystem innovation</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Boundary Conditions:</strong> Fails under tight coupling (safety-critical, real-time systems); interface control creates power asymmetries</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains digital platforms, API ecosystems, digital resource recombination, and why interface stability shapes complementor innovation in platform governance.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Modularity has roots in design and organization research. A common modern anchor is
                                    <mark>Baldwin and Clark (2000)</mark>, <em>Design rules</em> (<span class="construct-badge">modularity</span> as an architecture that
                                    enables <mark>recombination and innovation</mark>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Organization theory / design / strategy.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed, but widely used in IS strategy and digital platform research.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II/IV: modularity explains how architecture shapes innovation and coordination
                                    (Type II) and can support predictions about flexibility and performance under change
                                    (Type IV).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Modules</span>, <span class="construct-badge">interfaces</span>, <span class="construct-badge">decomposition</span>, <span class="construct-badge">recombination</span>, <span class="construct-badge">platform architecture</span>, <span class="construct-badge">boundary
                                    resources</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When parts are loosely coupled and connected through stable interfaces, people can
                                    change one part without breaking everything. That lowers coordination costs and
                                    increases speed of innovation.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Modularity helps when tasks can be partitioned and interfaces can be stabilized. It
                                    can fail when strong interdependencies require tight integration, or when interface
                                    control becomes a power struggle.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Piccoli et al. (2022) connect digital resources to recombination in MISQ, which
                                    aligns with modularity as a design logic for strategy. GenAI platform governance
                                    work on boundary resources also reflects modular interface dynamics.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Modularity</mark> was proposed to explain why some complex products and systems innovate faster than
                        others. The core idea is architectural: if you can <span class="construct-badge">decompose</span> a system into <span class="construct-badge">modules</span> with clear
                        <span class="construct-badge">interfaces</span>, you can redesign modules independently and still keep the overall system
                        functioning. <mark>Baldwin and Clark's</mark> framing is influential because it connects <span class="construct-badge">modularity</span> to
                        strategic options: modular designs create <mark>option value</mark> because they support <span class="construct-badge">recombination</span>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> System architecture shapes what kinds of change are easy or hard.
                        <span class="construct-badge">Modularity</span> creates flexibility by lowering <mark>coordination requirements</mark> across components.
                    </div>

                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Interfaces</span> become the "rules of the game": they enable innovation, but they also constrain it.
                        In IS, the mechanism often shows up in digital resources and platforms. <mark>APIs</mark>, <mark>data standards</mark>,
                        and <span class="construct-badge">boundary resources</span> act like modular interfaces. When these are <mark>stable</mark>, ecosystems can
                        innovate quickly. When platforms change them unpredictably, complementors face risk and
                        uncertainty. Boundary conditions matter in exam answers. If a system has <mark>tight coupling</mark>
                        (safety-critical, real-time interdependence), modularity is harder. Also, modularity is not
                        neutral. Control of <span class="construct-badge">interfaces</span> can create <mark>power asymmetries</mark> between platform owners and
                        complementors.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS research uses <span class="construct-badge">modularity</span> to explain digital innovation, platform ecosystems, and digital
                        strategy. A typical move is to link modular architecture to <span class="construct-badge">recombination</span> and then to business
                        value. <mark>Piccoli et al. (2022)</mark> discuss digital resources in a way that supports this logic:
                        resources become building blocks for strategic initiatives. In GenAI platform governance,
                        <span class="construct-badge">boundary resources</span> shape who can build what and how fast. <mark>Mayer et al. (2025)</mark> show governance
                        shifts as GenAI changes the platform boundary-resource landscape, which is a modern
                        modularity-adjacent story even when modularity is not the headline word.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Modularity</span> is practical and mechanism-focused. It gives you clear design levers
                            (<span class="construct-badge">interfaces</span>, <span class="construct-badge">decomposition</span>) and helps explain why digital ecosystems can <mark>scale innovation</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Modularity can be overused as a <mark>buzzword</mark>. Not every system is meaningfully modular,
                            and many architectures are <mark>hybrid</mark>. Another weakness is that modularity can hide the <mark>politics of
                            interfaces and standards</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Treating <mark>APIs</mark> as automatically modular
                            and beneficial, without analyzing <span class="construct-badge">interface stability</span>, governance, and dependency. Another
                            misuse is assuming modularity always improves performance, even when <mark>integration and reliability</mark>
                            are the real bottlenecks.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>RBV</mark> for resource advantage, <mark>complexity
                            science</mark> for nonlinear interdependence, and <mark>sociomateriality</mark> when you want to explain innovation
                            as practice-level entanglement rather than architecture.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use modularity when the exam question is about <span class="construct-badge">platform architecture</span>, <span class="construct-badge">boundary
                        resources</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">recombination</span> driven innovation.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "How does API instability affect complementor innovation in a GenAI platform ecosystem?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Greater <span class="construct-badge">interface stability</span> is positively associated with complementor innovation output,
                        mediated by lower <mark>coordination costs</mark>."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Interface stability</span>
                        (frequency and magnitude of API changes), complementor innovation (feature releases, new apps),
                        and <mark>coordination cost</mark> proxies (developer time, issue reports, rework). I would also measure
                        <mark>governance changes</mark> because they often co-move with interface decisions.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong>
                        <mark>Baldwin, C. Y., & Clark, K. B. (2000)</mark>. <em>Design rules: The power of modularity</em>. MIT
                        Press.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="matching-theory-similarity-and-fit">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge economics">Economics</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Gale & Shapley 1962</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Matching Theory (Similarity and Fit)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Similarity reduces friction and coordination costs; dissimilarity increases integration risk and vulnerability.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Outcomes depend on alignment between entities, not only standalone qualities. When systems, cultures, or practices don't match well, coordination becomes harder and risk increases. Dissimilarity creates translation work and can expose security gaps through inconsistent policies and heterogeneous infrastructure.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Matching & Coordination:</strong> Similarity reduces friction; mismatched systems/incentives/routines require more translation and integration work</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Integration Risk:</strong> Dissimilarity increases complexity through heterogeneous infrastructure and inconsistent policies; higher vulnerability exposure</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Fit Logic:</strong> Outcomes determined by alignment between entities; selection (similar firms choose each other) and reverse causality are confounds</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Boundary Conditions:</strong> Most useful for M&A, partnerships, vendor selection; less useful when power or institutions dominate regardless of fit</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains post-merger breach risk, partner selection outcomes, and why organizational dissimilarity creates cybersecurity vulnerabilities through integration complexity.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>"Matching" has multiple traditions. In economics, a classic foundation is <mark>Gale and
                                    Shapley (1962)</mark> on <mark>stable matching</mark>. In IS, recent work uses matching logic more
                                    broadly as <span class="construct-badge">similarity/fit</span> as a mechanism in inter-firm outcomes.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Economics (matching markets), organizational theory (fit/similarity).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II/IV: matching explains why similarity affects coordination and outcomes, and
                                    supports prediction of higher risk or higher success under certain mismatch
                                    conditions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Similarity/dissimilarity</span>, <span class="construct-badge">fit/misfit</span>, <span class="construct-badge">coordination costs</span>, <span class="construct-badge">integration risk</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When entities do not match well (different systems, cultures, practices),
                                    coordination becomes harder and risk increases. When they match, integration is
                                    smoother.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Most useful when fit is central (M&A integration, partner selection, vendor-client
                                    matches). Less useful when power or institutions dominate regardless of fit.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Liang et al. (2025) apply a matching-style logic to M&A and breach risk, showing how
                                    dissimilarity contributes to complexity and vulnerability.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>The strict formal version of <mark>matching</mark> comes from economics, where the goal is to explain <mark>stable
                        matches</mark> between two sides (like applicants and schools). For IS comps answers, a practical use
                        is the broader matching intuition: outcomes depend on <span class="construct-badge">alignment</span> between entities, not only on
                        their standalone qualities.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Similarity</span> can reduce friction while <span class="construct-badge">dissimilarity</span> can increase it.
                        The mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">coordination</span>: mismatched systems, incentives, or routines require more
                        translation work.
                    </div>

                    <p>In digital contexts, mismatches can create <mark>security gaps</mark> (inconsistent
                        policies, heterogeneous infrastructures) and <mark>integration failures</mark>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, matching logic often appears in <mark>partner selection</mark>, <mark>outsourcing fit</mark>, and <mark>M&A integration</mark>. A
                        strong recent example is <mark>Liang et al. (2025)</mark>, who link organizational <span class="construct-badge">dissimilarity</span> to breach
                        risk through complexity.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Key exam move:</strong> Show the chain: <span class="construct-badge">dissimilarity</span> → <span class="construct-badge">integration
                        complexity</span> → vulnerability exposure.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Matching theory gives you a clean mechanism for why context matters without making the
                            model vague. It is also easy to translate into measurable constructs (<mark>distance metrics,
                            similarity indices</mark>).</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Similarity</span> is not always good. Too much similarity can reduce
                            <mark>learning and innovation</mark>. Also, <span class="construct-badge">fit</span> can be <mark>socially constructed</mark>: actors can perceive mismatch
                            even when the technical mismatch is small.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Treating any
                            correlation between similarity and outcomes as causal, without considering <mark>selection</mark> (similar
                            firms choose each other) and <mark>reverse causality</mark>. Another misuse is using simplistic similarity
                            metrics that miss the dimensions that actually matter.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong>
                            <mark>Institutional theory</mark> for legitimacy pressures, <mark>RBV</mark> for resource complementarity, and <mark>complexity
                            science</mark> when mismatch produces nonlinear risk rather than linear coordination costs.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use matching theory when the exam question is about <span class="construct-badge">fit</span>, <mark>alignment</mark>, and
                        <span class="construct-badge">integration risk</span> (especially M&A and partnerships).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "How does cultural and system dissimilarity in M&A affect post-merger cybersecurity incidents?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Greater <span class="construct-badge">dissimilarity</span> between merging firms is positively associated with
                        post-merger breach incidence, mediated by <span class="construct-badge">integration complexity</span>."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Dissimilarity</span> measures (<mark>industry, IT stack diversity, geographic spread</mark>), <span class="construct-badge">integration
                        complexity</span> proxies (systems count, process heterogeneity), and breach outcomes from incident
                        databases. A strong design is to compare incidents <mark>before vs after the deal</mark> with controls.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Gale, D., & Shapley, L. S. (1962)</mark>. College admissions and the stability of
                        marriage. <em>The American Mathematical Monthly, 69</em>(1), 9-15.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="distributed-tuning-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Mayer et al. 2025</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Distributed Tuning Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Platform ecosystems adapt governance through many small decisions distributed across complementors and platforms.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> As boundary resources (like GenAI) emerge and change, platform ecosystems don't change governance through single decisions. Instead, many complementors and platform organizations make small tuning adjustments to what they build, what they expose, and what they control. These distributed choices aggregate into emergent governance shifts that adapt the ecosystem.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Distributed Decision Making:</strong> Governance emerges from many small choices by complementors and platforms, not centralized control</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Boundary Resource Adaptation:</strong> As resources change (e.g., GenAI capabilities), complementors tune what they build and how they use interfaces</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Emergent Governance:</strong> Aggregate of distributed choices creates ecosystem-level governance patterns without explicit coordination</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Platform Ecosystem Dynamics:</strong> Applies to platform evolution, ecosystem health, and innovation patterns; requires longitudinal observation</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains how digital platform ecosystems adapt governance patterns through distributed choices rather than top-down control, essential for understanding emerging technology governance.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>The idea is emerging in platform governance research. <mark>Mayer et al. (2025)</mark> propose a
                                    <mark>governance shift</mark> story around GenAI as a <span class="construct-badge">boundary resource</span> in platform ecosystems.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS / platform ecosystems (organization + digital governance).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native (developed in IS platform governance context).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains governance dynamics (resistance and accommodation)
                                    rather than aiming for a stable predictive model.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Resistance</span>, <span class="construct-badge">accommodation</span>, <span class="construct-badge">boundary resources</span>, <span class="construct-badge">governance shift</span>, <span class="construct-badge">ecosystem dynamics</span>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Platforms and ecosystem actors tune governance through cycles: actors resist or push
                                    back, the platform adapts, and a new temporary balance emerges.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Fits best when the ecosystem is dynamic and the platform can actually adjust rules
                                    and resources. Less useful for one-shot adoption contexts.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Mayer et al. (2025) show governance dynamics around GenAI boundary resources.
                                    Complementor ecosystem studies in the same JMIS GenAI platform stream reinforce the
                                    ecosystem mechanism.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Distributed tuning theory</mark> responds to a modern platform question: <span class="construct-badge">governance</span> is not set once. It
                        is <mark>continuously adjusted</mark> as technology and actor capabilities change. <mark>GenAI</mark> is a strong trigger
                        because it changes what complementors can build and what users expect, which pressures existing
                        governance arrangements.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Governance</span> evolves through <mark>distributed interaction</mark>, not only
                        top-down decisions. <span class="construct-badge">Resistance</span> is not noise—it is a mechanism that signals misfit between
                        governance rules and ecosystem needs.
                    </div>

                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Accommodation</span> is the platform response that maintains
                        ecosystem health. This is exam-friendly because it gives you a process mechanism: <span class="construct-badge">resistance</span> →
                        <span class="construct-badge">accommodation</span> → new equilibrium, repeated over time. It also naturally connects to <mark>power</mark>: not
                        everyone can resist equally.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, platform governance research already talks about <span class="construct-badge">boundary resources</span> and control.
                        Distributed tuning adds a <mark>dynamic mechanism</mark> that emphasizes <mark>cycles</mark> rather than static governance
                        choices. It also fits with <mark>complexity science</mark>: small governance tweaks can have large ecosystem
                        effects when <mark>interdependencies</mark> are high.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> It is realistic about platform governance. It explains why <mark>stable governance is hard</mark>
                            in fast-moving digital environments, and it gives you a clear <mark>temporal story</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can
                            be hard to <mark>operationalize</mark> as a testable model because the cycle can look different across
                            ecosystems. It also risks becoming <mark>descriptive</mark> if you do not identify clear events and
                            mechanisms.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Labeling any platform change as tuning without
                            evidence of <span class="construct-badge">resistance</span> and <span class="construct-badge">accommodation</span>, or ignoring <mark>asymmetry</mark> (some actors have more voice and
                            leverage).</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>Institutional theory</mark> for legitimacy and rules, <mark>RBV</mark> for
                            resource advantage, and <mark>sociomateriality</mark> for practice-level entanglement in ecosystems.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use distributed tuning when the exam question is about <span class="construct-badge">platform governance</span>
                        changing over time through <span class="construct-badge">ecosystem pushback</span> and adaptation.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "How do GenAI platform governance rules evolve as complementors and users push back against
                        restrictions?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Higher levels of complementor <span class="construct-badge">resistance</span> are associated with
                        greater platform <span class="construct-badge">accommodation</span> in governance policies over time."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong>
                        <span class="construct-badge">Resistance</span> events (<mark>public complaints, developer forum protests, policy circumvention</mark>),
                        <span class="construct-badge">accommodation</span> events (<mark>API changes, rule changes, new boundary resources</mark>), and <span class="construct-badge">ecosystem</span> outcomes
                        (complementor activity, user adoption). A <mark>process design</mark> with event sequences fits well.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Mayer, A.-S., Kostis, A., Strich, F., & Holmström, J. (2025)</mark>. Shifting dynamics:
                        How generative AI as a boundary resource reshapes digital platform governance. <em>Journal of
                            Management Information Systems, 42</em>(2), 400-430.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Part C Divider -->
            <div class="part-divider" id="part-c">
                <div>
                    <h2>🧠 Part C: Behavioral & Psychological Theories</h2>
                    <p style="margin: 0; opacity: 0.9; font-size: 0.95rem;">Theories of human cognition, motivation, and
                        decision-making</p>
                </div>
                <div class="part-count">22 Theories</div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="prospect-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Kahneman & Tversky 1979</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Prospect Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">People evaluate outcomes relative to reference points; loss aversion and probability weighting create systematic deviations from expected utility.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> People are reference-dependent decision makers who feel losses more acutely than equally-sized gains. They underweight high probabilities, overweight low probabilities, and evaluate outcomes as changes from a reference point (usually status quo) rather than final wealth levels. Framing the same objective outcome as loss vs. gain systematically changes preferences.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Reference Dependence:</strong> Outcomes evaluated relative to reference point, not absolute wealth; same outcome feels different as gain or loss</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Loss Aversion:</strong> Losses feel more painful than equal-sized gains feel good (asymmetry in value function); motivates risk-seeking under losses</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Probability Weighting:</strong> Overweight small probabilities, underweight moderate/high probabilities; nonlinear probability transformation</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Framing Effects:</strong> How outcomes are framed (loss vs. gain, probability presentation) systematically changes choices without changing objective risk</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains cybersecurity disclosure framing, risk investment decisions under uncertainty, and how managers and users interpret security threats and privacy trade-offs.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Kahneman and Tversky (1979)</mark>, "Prospect theory: An analysis of decision under risk,"
                                    <em>Econometrica</em>. Key contribution: people evaluate outcomes relative to a
                                    <span class="construct-badge">reference point</span>, show <span class="construct-badge">loss aversion</span>, and weight probabilities nonlinearly.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Major extension</td>
                                <td><mark>Tversky and Kahneman (1992)</mark>, <mark>cumulative prospect theory</mark> (improves <span class="construct-badge">probability
                                    weighting</span> and handles more choice patterns).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Psychology/behavioral economics.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS to explain risk decisions, privacy, security investment, and
                                    disclosure responses).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II and often Type IV: explains systematic deviations from expected utility and
                                    can predict direction of choices under framing.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Reference point</span>, <span class="construct-badge">loss aversion</span>, <span class="construct-badge">value function</span> (diminishing sensitivity),
                                    <span class="construct-badge">probability weighting</span>, <span class="construct-badge">framing</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People are more sensitive to losses than to equal-sized gains, so framing an outcome
                                    as a loss vs a gain changes preferences. People also overweight small probabilities
                                    and underweight moderate/high probabilities.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for decisions under risk/uncertainty with meaningful framing. Less useful for
                                    routine habitual behavior. Also sensitive to how reference points are defined.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Prospect theory appears in recent top-outlet IS work on cyber risk disclosures. In
                                    my local source set, this is the clearest 2020-2025 top-outlet example, so I log
                                    this as a partial coverage area.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Prospect theory</mark> was developed because <mark>expected utility theory</mark> could not explain many real
                        decision patterns. <mark>Kahneman and Tversky (1979)</mark> show that people do not evaluate outcomes as
                        final wealth levels. They evaluate changes relative to a <span class="construct-badge">reference point</span> (often the status quo).
                        That is why the same objective outcome can feel like a <mark>gain</mark> to one person and a <mark>loss</mark> to another
                        person. The other big idea is <span class="construct-badge">loss aversion</span>: losses usually feel more painful than equal-sized
                        gains feel good. For comps, the Nobel point is worth mentioning briefly. <mark>Kahneman</mark> received the
                        Nobel Prize in economics for this line of work (Tversky had passed away and Nobel prizes are not
                        awarded posthumously). The origin discipline is psychology, but the impact is behavioral
                        economics and then many applied fields, including IS. <mark>Tversky and Kahneman (1992)</mark> extend the
                        theory into <mark>cumulative prospect theory</mark>, which refines <span class="construct-badge">probability weighting</span> and handles a wider
                        range of choice patterns. Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliations from the
                        original articles in my local workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main propositions:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Reference dependence</span>, <span class="construct-badge">loss aversion</span>, and nonlinear <span class="construct-badge">probability
                        weighting</span>. People care about changes from a reference point, not only final states. They react
                        more strongly to losses than to gains.
                    </div>

                    <p>They also do not treat probabilities linearly: small
                        probabilities can be overweighted, while moderate and high probabilities can be underweighted,
                        depending on the case. The mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">framing</span>. If the same choice is presented as avoiding a
                        loss versus achieving a gain, preferences can shift. This is why prospect theory is so useful
                        for digital decisions under uncertainty: the same privacy setting, security control, or
                        disclosure message can be perceived very differently depending on what the person treats as the
                        baseline and whether they see the situation as a <mark>loss context</mark>. Boundary conditions matter. You
                        have to be clear about the <span class="construct-badge">reference point</span>. In many studies, the hardest part is not running the
                        regression, it is defining what counts as "<mark>baseline expectations</mark>" for the decision maker.
                        Prospect theory is also strongest for <mark>one-shot or salient decisions</mark> under risk. In routine
                        repeated behavior, habits and learning can dominate, and framing effects can weaken.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, prospect theory is most useful when the dependent variable is a decision under uncertainty
                        with meaningful <span class="construct-badge">framing</span>. Classic examples include <mark>security investment decisions</mark>, <mark>privacy
                        disclosure choices</mark>, and <mark>reactions to risk information</mark>. The theory helps you explain why people
                        do not behave like expected utility would predict, especially when they feel the situation is a
                        <mark>loss context</mark> (for example, after a breach). <mark>Cao et al. (2025)</mark> is a nice recent top-outlet
                        example because it studies cyber risk disclosures and shareholder response and shows how
                        <mark>preventive versus mitigative framing</mark> can matter.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Bridge to agency theory:</strong> Managers choose disclosure framing strategically (<mark>agency</mark>), and investors respond
                        through <span class="construct-badge">loss aversion</span> and <span class="construct-badge">framing</span> (prospect). Integration with other theories is common and
                        often necessary. Prospect theory explains the psychology of response to risk messages, but it
                        does not explain why certain messages are produced in the first place. <mark>Agency theory</mark> and
                        <mark>institutional theory</mark> can explain those production incentives (governance, regulation,
                        legitimacy), while <mark>trust theory</mark> can explain why the same risk information is accepted or
                        rejected as credible.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Prospect theory gives a strong, mechanism-based explanation for <span class="construct-badge">framing</span> effects and
                            <span class="construct-badge">loss</span> sensitivity. It is widely accepted and gives you directional predictions that are often
                            exam-friendly ("loss-framed contexts change risk preferences").</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> The theory can be
                            hard to apply cleanly without clear <span class="construct-badge">reference points</span> and clear framing manipulations. Another
                            limitation is that many real IS settings mix risk, trust, social influence, and institutional
                            constraints, so prospect theory alone can be <mark>incomplete</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A common
                            misuse is using the term "<span class="construct-badge">loss aversion</span>" as a general synonym for "people dislike bad outcomes"
                            without specifying reference points. Another is claiming a prospect theory mechanism without
                            actually measuring <span class="construct-badge">framing</span> or <span class="construct-badge">probability</span> perceptions.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>Expected
                            utility theory</mark> is the main competing baseline in economics. <mark>Bounded rationality</mark> and <mark>sensemaking</mark>
                            perspectives can be stronger when the main issue is interpretation rather than preference.
                            <mark>Protection motivation</mark> logic can be stronger when the mechanism is threat appraisal and coping
                            appraisal rather than gain-loss framing.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use prospect theory when the question is about risky decisions and <span class="construct-badge">framing</span> (<mark>gain
                        vs loss</mark>) shaping choices like disclosure, security investment, or response to incidents.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "After a breach, do investors react differently when cyber risk disclosures
                        emphasize prevention versus mitigation, and why?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "In a post-breach <mark>loss context</mark>, disclosures that emphasize <mark>prevention</mark> will be associated with less negative shareholder
                        response than disclosures that emphasize <mark>mitigation and response</mark>."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would code disclosure text for <mark>preventive versus mitigative emphasis</mark>, define the
                        breach event window, and measure market reaction using an <mark>event study</mark> approach. To connect to
                        mechanism, I would also measure baseline expectations (<span class="construct-badge">reference points</span>) using prior
                        disclosures, analyst expectations, or industry norms.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Kahneman, D., & Tversky, A. (1979)</mark>. Prospect theory: An analysis of decision under risk. <em>Econometrica,
                            47</em>(2), 263-291.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="trust-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge behavioral">Behavioral</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Mayer, Davis & Schoorman 1995</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Trust Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Trust is willingness to be vulnerable based on perceived ability, benevolence, and integrity of the trustee.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Trust enables risky action under uncertainty. When people perceive trustees as competent (ability), well-intentioned (benevolence), and principled (integrity), they accept vulnerability through disclosure, reliance, and cooperation. Distinct from trustworthiness (beliefs about characteristics), trust is the willingness to accept vulnerability conditional on risk perception and context safeguards.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Trustworthiness Drivers:</strong> Ability (competence), Benevolence (good intentions), Integrity (principles/honesty)—three distinct dimensions shape perceived trustworthiness</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Vulnerability Mechanism:</strong> Trust enables disclosure, reliance, cooperation when outcomes cannot be fully controlled; shaped by perceived risk and uncertainty</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Context Dependence:</strong> Safeguards, accountability, and norms shape perceived risk and determine whether trust is sufficient for vulnerable actions</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Target-Specific:</strong> Trust in humans, organizations, technologies, and AI systems differs; researchers must specify trustee type and vulnerability context</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Central to understanding privacy disclosure, technology adoption under uncertainty, human-AI collaboration, and how users make decisions about vulnerable information sharing in digital systems.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Mayer, Davis, and Schoorman (1995)</mark>, "An integrative model of organizational trust,"
                                    <em>Academy of Management Review</em>. Key contribution: <span class="construct-badge">trust</span> as <mark>willingness to be
                                    vulnerable</mark>, driven by perceived <span class="construct-badge">ability</span>, <span class="construct-badge">benevolence</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">integrity</span>.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Key IS trust measures</td>
                                <td><mark>McKnight, Choudhury, and Kacmar (2002)</mark> develop and validate trust measures for
                                    e-commerce contexts in <em>Information Systems Research</em>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Organizational behavior / social psychology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (adapted heavily in IS for e-commerce, privacy, human-AI interaction).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II and often Type IV: explains how trust forms and predicts behavior under
                                    uncertainty and vulnerability.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Trust</span> (willingness to be vulnerable); <span class="construct-badge">trustworthiness</span> (<span class="construct-badge">ability</span>/competence,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">benevolence</span>, <span class="construct-badge">integrity</span>); <span class="construct-badge">propensity to trust</span>; <span class="construct-badge">perceived risk</span>/uncertainty; <mark>trusting
                                    intentions and behaviors</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When people perceive a trustee as competent, well-intentioned, and principled, they
                                    accept vulnerability and engage in risky exchange (sharing info, relying on
                                    systems).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Trust matters when there is vulnerability and uncertainty. It differs across targets
                                    (human, organization, technology, AI) and is shaped by context, norms, and
                                    accountability.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Trust remains central in top IS work on private information disclosure and
                                    human-robot collaboration.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Trust theory</mark> starts from <mark>vulnerability</mark>. <mark>Mayer, Davis, and Schoorman (1995)</mark> define <span class="construct-badge">trust</span> as the
                        <mark>willingness to be vulnerable</mark> to another party (the trustee) based on the expectation that the
                        trustee will act in a way that matters to you. Their key move is separating <span class="construct-badge">trust</span> (the
                        willingness) from <span class="construct-badge">trustworthiness</span> (beliefs about <span class="construct-badge">ability</span>, <span class="construct-badge">benevolence</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">integrity</span>). That
                        separation is very useful in IS because systems and firms can signal <span class="construct-badge">trustworthiness</span>, but
                        trusting behavior still depends on context and risk. In IS, trust became central with <mark>e-commerce</mark>
                        and online services. Users often must share personal information and rely on systems they cannot
                        fully monitor. <mark>McKnight et al. (2002)</mark> are important because they translate trust into measurable
                        IS constructs and provide validated scales that became widely reused (<mark>trusting beliefs, trusting
                        intentions, and institution-based trust</mark>). Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliations
                        from the original articles in my local workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Trust</span> enables risky action under uncertainty. When people believe a
                        trustee has the <span class="construct-badge">ability</span> to do the task, has <span class="construct-badge">benevolent</span> intentions, and has <span class="construct-badge">integrity</span>, they are
                        more willing to accept <mark>vulnerability</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p>That vulnerability can show up as <mark>disclosure</mark> (sharing
                        personal data), <mark>reliance</mark> (following recommendations), or <mark>cooperation</mark> (collaborating with a
                        system or a partner). The mechanism is a <mark>belief-to-action pathway</mark>. Perceived <span class="construct-badge">trustworthiness</span>
                        shapes <span class="construct-badge">trust</span> (willingness to be vulnerable). Trust then increases <mark>risk-taking</mark> in the
                        relationship when the situation involves uncertainty and potential harm. Trust is also shaped by
                        the context: <mark>safeguards</mark>, <mark>accountability</mark>, and <mark>norms</mark> can raise or lower perceived risk and change
                        how much trust is needed. Boundary conditions are tied to risk and target. Trust only matters
                        when there is something to lose and you cannot fully control the outcome. Trust also differs by
                        <mark>target</mark>. Trust in a human coworker, trust in a firm, and trust in an AI system are related but
                        not identical, so good IS work is explicit about the trustee.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS research expanded <span class="construct-badge">trust</span> beyond e-commerce into <mark>privacy, platforms, and now human-AI
                        collaboration</mark>. As systems became more agentic and less transparent, trust shifted from being a
                        "nice to have" variable to being a core mechanism for <mark>acceptance and reliance</mark>. <mark>Zalmanson et al.
                        (2022)</mark> is a good recent MISQ anchor in the privacy space. It studies how social cues shape trust
                        and then shape private information disclosure, which is a clean trust mechanism: cues influence
                        perceived <span class="construct-badge">trustworthiness</span>, trust affects <mark>willingness to be vulnerable</mark>, and vulnerability shows
                        up as disclosure. <mark>You and Robert (2024)</mark> is a good recent anchor in the human-robot space. It
                        connects trust to relational demography and preferences for working with robots versus humans,
                        showing that trust is not only about system accuracy. It is also about <mark>social categorization</mark> and
                        perceived fit.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Integration with other theories:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Trust</span> often pairs with <mark>TAM and UTAUT</mark>
                        in adoption models, but the exam move is to show they explain different things: TAM explains
                        <mark>usefulness and effort</mark>, trust explains <mark>vulnerability under uncertainty</mark>. Trust also pairs
                        naturally with <mark>delegation</mark> because delegation is basically a decision about how much authority
                        you give to a system, which is impossible without some level of trust.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Trust</span> theory is powerful because it captures a real mechanism that shows up in many IS
                            settings: people must rely on systems they cannot fully observe, and trust is what enables that
                            reliance. It also gives a useful construct structure (<span class="construct-badge">ability</span>, <span class="construct-badge">benevolence</span>, <span class="construct-badge">integrity</span>) that
                            helps measurement and theorizing.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Trust can become a <mark>vague umbrella</mark> if researchers
                            do not specify the target and the risk. Measurement is also hard because trust and risk
                            perceptions can be <mark>endogenous</mark> and change together over time.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A
                            common misuse is treating trust as a <mark>single item or a single dimension</mark>, which loses the theory.
                            Another is treating trust as a general attitude without connecting it to <mark>vulnerability</mark> and
                            <mark>uncertainty</mark>. A third is mixing <mark>trust in the technology</mark> with <mark>trust in the provider</mark> and not
                            separating them.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> In some settings, <mark>perceived risk</mark> and <mark>privacy
                            calculus</mark> models are more direct. In others, <mark>institutional safeguards and regulation</mark> can
                            substitute for trust. For human-AI contexts, <mark>reliance and delegation frameworks</mark> can be more
                            precise about authority allocation than generic trust alone.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use trust theory when the question is about relying on a system or party under
                        <mark>uncertainty and vulnerability</mark> (privacy, e-commerce, AI advice).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "How do social cues on a platform shape user trust and private information disclosure?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Stronger social cues increase <span class="construct-badge">trust</span> in the platform, and higher trust increases
                        users' private information disclosure."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would operationalize
                        <mark>social cues</mark> using visible signals (verification badges, friend activity, community norms
                        messages) and measure <span class="construct-badge">trust</span> using validated scales (<span class="construct-badge">ability</span>, <span class="construct-badge">benevolence</span>, <span class="construct-badge">integrity</span>). <mark>Disclosure</mark>
                        can be measured through behavioral logs (what users share, privacy settings) instead of only
                        surveys.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Mayer, R. C., Davis, J. H., & Schoorman, F. D. (1995)</mark>. An
                        integrative model of organizational trust. <em>Academy of Management Review, 20</em>(3),
                        709-734.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="social-comparison-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Festinger 1954</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Social Comparison Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">People evaluate abilities and opinions by comparing themselves with similar others, especially under uncertainty.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> When standards are ambiguous, people look to similar others to judge how they are doing. Upward comparisons (to those performing better) can motivate or discourage depending on perceived attainability. Downward comparisons protect self-esteem but reduce motivation. Digital platforms make social information constantly visible, intensifying comparison effects at scale.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Self-Evaluation Through Comparison:</strong> People infer "where I stand" through observing similar others; comparison shapes self-concept and emotions</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Upward vs. Downward Comparison:</strong> Upward (to others doing better) can motivate or discourage; downward (to others doing worse) protects self-esteem but reduces effort</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Emotional Effects:</strong> Comparisons trigger pride, envy, anxiety depending on similarity and perceived attainability of the comparison target</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Digital Amplification:</strong> Platforms make metrics, rankings, and interactions visible at scale, increasing comparison frequency and emotional impact</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains online community dynamics, social media effects on emotional well-being, leaderboard impacts on engagement, and unintended emotional consequences of visible metrics in digital platforms.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Festinger (1954)</mark>, "A theory of social comparison processes," <em>Human
                                        Relations</em>. Key contribution: people evaluate opinions and abilities by
                                    comparing themselves with others, especially under <mark>uncertainty</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Social psychology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS for social media, online communities, and disclosure/engagement
                                    dynamics).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how comparison processes shape emotions,
                                    self-evaluations, and behaviors.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Comparison target</span>, <span class="construct-badge">upward vs downward comparison</span>, <span class="construct-badge">similarity</span>, <span class="construct-badge">self-evaluation</span>,
                                    <span class="construct-badge">self-enhancement</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When people are unsure, they look to similar others to judge how they are doing.
                                    Upward comparisons can motivate or discourage; downward comparisons can protect
                                    self-esteem.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Strongest when standards are ambiguous and when social information is visible
                                    (social media). Effects depend on similarity, closeness, and whether comparison
                                    feels attainable.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Explicit social comparison mechanisms appear in MISQ work on online health
                                    communities and unintended emotional effects. Additional top-outlet uses are less
                                    common in the local reading set, so this is logged as a partial coverage area.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Social comparison theory</mark> starts from <mark>uncertainty</mark>. <mark>Festinger (1954)</mark> argues that when people cannot
                        evaluate their opinions or abilities objectively, they compare themselves to others. <span class="construct-badge">Similar
                        others</span> are especially important because the comparison feels more informative. This creates a
                        social mechanism for <span class="construct-badge">self-evaluation</span> and also pressure toward <mark>uniformity</mark> in groups. Affiliation
                        note: I did not verify author affiliations from the original article in my local workspace, so I
                        am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> Exposure to others' performance, opinions, and outcomes shapes how
                        people feel and what they do, especially when standards are unclear. Comparisons can be <span class="construct-badge">upward</span>
                        (to someone doing better) or <span class="construct-badge">downward</span> (to someone doing worse).
                    </div>

                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Upward comparison</span> can motivate
                        improvement, but it can also create <mark>discouragement and negative emotions</mark> if the gap feels too
                        large. <span class="construct-badge">Downward comparison</span> can protect <mark>self-esteem</mark>, but it can also reduce motivation. The
                        mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">self-evaluation</span> through social information. People infer "where I stand" by looking
                        at others. That inference then shapes emotions (<mark>pride, envy, anxiety</mark>), self-concept, and
                        behavior (effort, withdrawal, disclosure, engagement). In digital environments, platforms make
                        social information <mark>visible at scale</mark>, which makes comparison more frequent and sometimes harder
                        to avoid. Boundary conditions include <span class="construct-badge">similarity</span> and <mark>attainability</mark>. Comparisons are usually
                        strongest when the other person feels similar and when the comparison feels relevant. They are
                        also shaped by whether the upward target feels <mark>attainable</mark>. If the target feels impossible,
                        upward comparison is more likely to harm than help.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Social comparison</span> became more important in IS as digital platforms made comparison constant.
                        <mark>Likes, follower counts, leaderboards</mark>, and visible support interactions create a steady stream of
                        "where do I stand?" signals. This is why social comparison is a strong lens for <mark>social media,
                        online learning platforms, health communities</mark>, and workplace social tools. In the 2020-2025
                        reading set, <mark>Zhou et al. (2023)</mark> is a useful recent MISQ anchor because it studies <mark>unintended
                        emotional effects</mark> in online health communities. Even if the focal lens in a specific paper is
                        not always labeled as "social comparison," the phenomenon fits the theory: observing others'
                        interactions and outcomes can shape <span class="construct-badge">self-evaluation</span> and emotions. I treat this as partial
                        coverage and log it in QA.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Connection to emotional contagion:</strong> Comparison explains <mark>interpretation</mark> ("what does this mean for me?"), while contagion explains
                        <mark>spread</mark> ("how do emotions move through the network?"). In many online settings, both mechanisms
                        operate together.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Social comparison</span> theory gives a clean micro mechanism for why social information
                            changes emotions and behavior. It is simple, intuitive, and fits modern platforms where <mark>metrics
                            and visibility</mark> are built into the design.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Effects are <mark>heterogeneous</mark>. The same
                            comparison can motivate one person and discourage another. That means good IS work needs
                            moderators like <span class="construct-badge">similarity</span>, <mark>self-esteem</mark>, and the design of the social information itself.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A common misuse is treating any social influence effect as social
                            comparison. Comparison is specifically about <span class="construct-badge">self-evaluation</span> relative to others. Another misuse
                            is ignoring the <mark>direction of comparison</mark> (<span class="construct-badge">upward vs downward</span>) and the perceived <mark>attainability</mark> of
                            the target.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>Social identity theory</mark> is often stronger when the
                            mechanism is group belonging rather than self-evaluation. <mark>Emotional contagion theory</mark> is stronger
                            when the main mechanism is affect spread. <mark>Goal systems theory</mark> and <mark>self-regulation theories</mark> can
                            be stronger when the main mechanism is cue-driven motivation rather than comparison.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use social comparison when the question is about users looking at others online
                        and how that affects <mark>emotions, behavior, or engagement</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "How do leaderboards in an online learning platform affect engagement and well-being for high-performing
                        versus low-performing students?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Greater exposure to <span class="construct-badge">upward comparisons</span> on
                        a leaderboard increases engagement for users who see the target as <mark>attainable</mark>, but decreases
                        well-being for users who see the gap as <mark>unattainable</mark>."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would
                        measure exposure to leaderboard information (<mark>views, rank position, rank changes</mark>) and outcomes
                        like study time, course completion, and self-reported well-being. I would also measure perceived
                        <span class="construct-badge">similarity</span> and <mark>attainability</mark> to capture the mechanism. If possible, I would run a <mark>field
                        experiment</mark> by varying leaderboard visibility.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Festinger, L. (1954)</mark>. A
                        theory of social comparison processes. <em>Human Relations, 7</em>(2), 117-140.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="ego-depletion-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Baumeister et al. 1998</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Ego Depletion Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Sustained self-control effort depletes mental resources, reducing capacity for later self-control and increasing policy violations.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Self-control functions as a limited resource. After sustained effort (resisting temptation, maintaining focus, following strict rules), people become temporarily depleted and more likely to take shortcuts or violate rules. This creates within-person temporal patterns: the same person complies better early and worse later depending on prior effort demands. Motivation, habits, and context can override depletion.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Limited Resource Model:</strong> Self-control capacity is finite; sustained effort depletes reserves for later self-control tasks</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Temporal Dynamics:</strong> Within-person fluctuation: same person more compliant early, less later; depends on daily effort demands and workload</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Policy Violation Pathway:</strong> Depletion increases likelihood of taking the easy/risky path when full compliance requires sustained effort</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Boundary Conditions:</strong> Replication debated in psychology; motivation, habits, and incentives can override effects; hard to distinguish from workload/stress</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains temporal patterns of security policy violations, when behavioral cybersecurity controls break down during high-effort periods, and why end-of-day violations increase.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Baumeister et al. (1998)</mark>, "Ego depletion: Is the active self a limited resource?",
                                    <em>Journal of Personality and Social Psychology</em>. Key contribution:
                                    <span class="construct-badge">self-control</span> draws on a <span class="construct-badge">limited resource</span> that can be <span class="construct-badge">depleted</span>, leading to later
                                    lapses.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Psychology (self-regulation).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS for security behavior and compliance over time).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains why self-control failures increase after sustained
                                    effort.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Self-control</span>, <span class="construct-badge">limited resource</span>, <span class="construct-badge">depletion</span>, <span class="construct-badge">fatigue</span>, <mark>subsequent self-regulation
                                    performance</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>After people spend mental effort controlling impulses, they have less capacity left
                                    for later self-control tasks, so they are more likely to take shortcuts or violate
                                    rules.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Evidence has been debated in psychology (replication and effect size). Motivation,
                                    habits, and context can reduce or override depletion effects.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Ego depletion logic is used in MISQ behavioral cybersecurity work to explain
                                    temporal patterns of policy violations.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><mark>Ego depletion theory</mark> comes from self-regulation research. <mark>Baumeister et al. (1998)</mark> propose that
                        <span class="construct-badge">self-control</span> works like a <span class="construct-badge">limited resource</span>. When people use self-control heavily (<mark>resisting
                        temptation, focusing attention, following strict rules</mark>), they become temporarily <span class="construct-badge">depleted</span>, which
                        makes later self-control tasks harder. In everyday terms, after a long stretch of effort, people
                        are more likely to take <mark>shortcuts</mark>. For comps, it is important to mention the <mark>controversy</mark>. Later
                        work in psychology raised <mark>replication and effect-size concerns</mark>, so the exam-safe move is to
                        treat ego depletion as a <mark>debated mechanism</mark> and to be explicit about how you would test it in
                        your specific context. Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliations from the original
                        article in my local workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> Sustained <span class="construct-badge">self-control</span> effort reduces the capacity for later
                        self-control, increasing the likelihood of lapses. The theory predicts <mark>within-person fluctuation</mark>
                        over time: the same person can be more compliant early and less compliant later, depending on
                        recent self-control demands.
                    </div>

                    <p>The mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">resource depletion</span> (or, in later interpretations,
                        shifts in motivation and attention after effort). For IS research, the important point is not
                        the metaphor of "willpower fuel." The important point is the <mark>temporal pattern</mark>: cognitive effort
                        and <span class="construct-badge">fatigue</span> change the probability of taking the easy path, especially when the easy path is a
                        <mark>policy violation</mark> or a <mark>risky click</mark>. Boundary conditions are strong. <mark>Motivation, habits, and
                        incentives</mark> can override depletion effects. Also, not every performance drop is ego depletion.
                        <mark>Workload, stress, and time pressure</mark> can produce similar patterns. This is why a good study
                        measures competing explanations and uses designs that capture <mark>within-person change</mark>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Ego depletion</span> shows up in IS most naturally in <mark>behavioral cybersecurity</mark> research. Security
                        compliance often requires repeated <span class="construct-badge">self-control</span>: <mark>resisting convenience, following procedures,
                        and staying alert</mark>. In real work life, that effort can vary by day, workload, and situational
                        pressure, which makes depletion logic attractive. In the 2020-2025 reading set, <mark>Cram et al.
                        (2024)</mark> is a useful recent MISQ anchor for the general point that behavioral cybersecurity should
                        be studied with attention to <mark>time and within-person fluctuation</mark>. I treat the ego depletion link
                        as partial coverage because the paper is broader than one mechanism, and I log that in QA.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Pairing with neutralization theory:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Depletion</span> can explain "why people are more
                        likely to slip," while <mark>neutralization</mark> can explain "how people justify the slip to themselves."
                        Together, they give a more complete story for policy violations.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Ego depletion</span> provides a simple explanation for why compliance can fail over time even
                            when attitudes are stable. It pushes IS researchers to model <mark>temporal dynamics</mark> instead of
                            treating security behavior as a stable trait.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> The <mark>replication debate</mark> means you
                            should be careful not to treat ego depletion as settled fact. Another weakness is that <span class="construct-badge">depletion</span>
                            can be hard to distinguish from <mark>workload and stress</mark> without good measurement and design.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A common misuse is using <mark>cross-sectional surveys</mark> to test a <mark>within-person
                            temporal mechanism</mark>. Another is assuming that any late-day violation is depletion without
                            measuring effort, <span class="construct-badge">fatigue</span>, and alternative explanations.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>Stress
                            and workload models</mark> can explain similar patterns. <mark>Habit theory</mark> can be stronger for repeated
                            behaviors. <mark>Neutralization theory</mark> can be stronger when the key mechanism is moral justification
                            rather than reduced capacity.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use ego depletion when the question is about <span class="construct-badge">self-control</span> limits, <span class="construct-badge">fatigue</span>, and why
                        security or privacy behaviors break down over time.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "Do employees become more likely to violate security policy after periods of sustained cognitive effort, and
                        when does that pattern show up during the workweek?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Higher prior <span class="construct-badge">self-control</span> demands during the day are associated with a higher likelihood of security policy
                        violations later in the day."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would use <mark>experience sampling</mark> to
                        measure <span class="construct-badge">self-control</span> demands and <span class="construct-badge">fatigue</span> multiple times a day, and link those measures to
                        security behavior (self-reports plus, ideally, log indicators like <mark>risky clicks or policy
                        exceptions</mark>). I would also measure <mark>workload and stress</mark> to rule out alternative explanations.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Baumeister, R. F., Bratslavsky, E., Muraven, M., & Tice, D. M. (1998)</mark>. Ego
                        depletion: Is the active self a limited resource? <em>Journal of Personality and Social
                            Psychology, 74</em>(5), 1252-1265.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="goal-systems-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Kruglanski et al. 2002</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Goal Systems Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Goals and means form cognitive networks; environmental cues activate goals that guide behavior through means selection.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Goals and means are cognitively interconnected; a single cue can activate multiple goals simultaneously or suppress conflicting ones. When goals conflict, commitment to one goal increases and commitment to others decreases. Means (behaviors, strategies) can be substituted if they serve the same goal, creating equifinality where different actions achieve the same outcome.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Goal-Means Networks:</strong> Goals and means linked cognitively; cue activation spreads through network to activate related goals and suppress conflicting ones</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Equifinality & Substitutability:</strong> Multiple means can serve same goal; if one means is blocked, people substitute others to achieve goal</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Goal Commitment Shifts:</strong> When goals conflict, commitment to focal goal increases and commitment to other goals decreases (spreading activation)</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Contextual Activation:</strong> Environmental cues activate goals outside conscious awareness; affects what people perceive, value, and attempt</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains how interface design, notifications, and contextual cues activate security/privacy goals and shape behavior; shows why blocking one means redirects to alternatives.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Kruglanski et al. (2002)</mark>, "The theory of goal systems," <em>Psychological
                                        Review</em>. Key contribution: <span class="construct-badge">goals</span> and <span class="construct-badge">means</span> form a cognitive network; cues
                                    activate goals, which guide behavior through means selection.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Psychology (motivation and self-regulation).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS for disclosure and digital behavior shaped by cues).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how cues activate goals and how goal-means
                                    structures drive behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Goals</span>, <span class="construct-badge">means</span>, <span class="construct-badge">goal activation</span>, <span class="construct-badge">goal shielding</span>, <span class="construct-badge">equifinality</span> (many means to same
                                    goal), <span class="construct-badge">multifinality</span> (one means serves many goals).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>The environment triggers certain goals. Once a goal is active, people choose
                                    behaviors (means) that help reach that goal, and they may ignore competing goals.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Strongest when goals are situationally activated and when behavior is flexible. Less
                                    fitting for rigid constraints or habits. Multiple goals can compete, so context
                                    matters.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Goal systems logic appears in MISQ work on private information disclosure, where
                                    social cues activate social goals that increase disclosure.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Goal systems theory was developed to explain motivated behavior as a structured cognitive system,
                        not as isolated goals. Kruglanski et al. (2002) argue that goals and means are connected in a
                        network. This network explains equifinality (many means can serve the same goal) and
                        multifinality (one means can serve many goals). It also explains why cues matter: environmental
                        cues can activate goals, which then guide what behaviors feel attractive or "right" in the
                        moment. Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliations from the original article in my
                        local workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> Behavior depends on which <span class="construct-badge">goals</span> are active and which <span class="construct-badge">means</span> are
                        linked to those goals in a person's goal system. Once a goal is activated, people tend to select
                        means that serve it and shield it from competing goals.
                    </div>

                    <p>This creates predictable patterns:
                        people ignore some information, focus on some cues, and choose behaviors that fit the active
                        goal. The mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">activation</span> and <mark>linkage</mark>. Cues activate a goal. The activated goal
                        increases the accessibility of linked <span class="construct-badge">means</span>. Those means then guide action. Because means can be
                        connected to multiple goals, the same digital behavior (for example, sharing a post) can serve
                        different goals (<mark>belonging, self-presentation, helping others</mark>). This is a useful exam move
                        because it helps explain why one variable like "privacy concern" is not enough. Boundary
                        conditions include <mark>competition among goals</mark> and structural constraints. If the environment leaves
                        little choice (strict rules, strong constraints), goal-means networks matter less. Also,
                        multiple goals can be active at once, which can create <mark>tradeoffs and inconsistent behavior</mark>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>Goal systems theory is not as commonly used as a headline IS theory, but it fits many digital
                        behavior settings where cues activate goals. Privacy disclosure, social media engagement, and
                        online support behaviors often depend on which goal is activated (social connection, impression
                        management, reciprocity). In the local reading set, Zalmanson et al. (2022) is a strong recent
                        MISQ anchor for cues and private information disclosure. I treat the goal systems connection as
                        partial coverage because the paper's main framing is trust and social cues, not goal systems
                        explicitly, but the cue-to-goal logic is directly relevant. Goal systems also integrates well
                        with trust theory and social comparison. Trust shapes whether disclosure feels safe, while goal
                        activation shapes whether disclosure feels worthwhile in the moment.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Goal systems</span> theory gives a clear mechanism for <mark>cue-driven behavior</mark>. It helps you move
                            beyond "people do X" toward "which <span class="construct-badge">goal</span> was active and why did this behavior feel like a good
                            <span class="construct-badge">means</span>?" That is especially useful for digital environments built around cues and prompts.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> The network can be hard to <mark>measure directly</mark>. Many studies use proxies for
                            <span class="construct-badge">goal activation</span>, which can weaken validity. Also, because multiple goals can be active, the
                            theory can become <mark>complex</mark> quickly if you try to model the full system.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A common misuse is treating goals as <mark>stable traits</mark> instead of <mark>situationally activated
                            states</mark>. Another is assuming a single goal explains behavior when multiple goals are likely
                            operating (privacy, belonging, status, helping).</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>Theory of planned
                            behavior</mark> is often used for deliberate intention. <mark>Habit theory</mark> is useful for repeated routines.
                            <mark>Social comparison</mark> and <mark>emotional contagion</mark> are useful when the mechanism is social information
                            and emotion rather than goal activation.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use goal systems when the question is about <mark>competing goals</mark> (convenience vs
                        security, social connection vs privacy) and how cues shift which goal wins.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "How do privacy interface cues activate social goals that increase private information
                        disclosure on a platform?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Social cues that activate <span class="construct-badge">belonging goals</span>
                        increase disclosure intentions, and this effect is weaker when perceived risk is high."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would manipulate or measure <mark>cues</mark> (friend activity prompts, community
                        messages) and measure <span class="construct-badge">goal activation</span> with short state measures (belonging, impression
                        management). Disclosure can be measured through behavioral logs. I would include <mark>trust</mark> and
                        <mark>perceived risk</mark> to capture why some users resist disclosure even when goals are activated.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Kruglanski, A. W., Shah, J. Y., Fishbach, A., Friedman, R., Chun, W. Y., &
                        Sleeth-Keppler, D. (2002)</mark>. A theory of goal systems. <em>Psychological Review, 109</em>(2),
                        331-352.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="professional-role-identity-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge organizational">Organizational</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Ashforth 2001</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Professional Role Identity Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Professional roles become part of self-concept; identity threats trigger emotional responses and identity work to restore coherence.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Over time, professional roles become central to self-concept ("I am a doctor," "I am an analyst"). When technology or change threatens expertise boundaries, decision authority, or what counts as "good work," people experience identity threat and engage in identity work—resistance, reinterpretation, distancing, or learning. Experienced professionals and novices respond differently to identical threats.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Role-Based Identity:</strong> Professional roles become part of self-concept through narratives, social validation, and boundary work; stronger in high-status professions</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Identity Threat Mechanism:</strong> Technology threatens expertise, authority, status; triggers emotional responses and identity work (resistance, reinterpretation, learning)</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Experience-Dependent Responses:</strong> Experienced professionals experience threat; novices experience enablement—same tool, different identity implications</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Identity Work Outcomes:</strong> Can result in resistance, role expansion, learning, or distancing; depends on availability of alternative valued identities</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains AI adoption resistance among experts, why professional norms shape technology acceptance, and how identity threat affects delegation willingness and trust.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Ashforth (2001)</mark>, <em>Role transitions in organizational life: An identity-based
                                        perspective</em>. Key contribution: explains how roles become <span class="construct-badge">identities</span> and how
                                    people manage identity across <mark>transitions and threats</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Organizational behavior / social psychology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS for technology-induced role change and human-AI collaboration).
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how identity shapes meaning, motivation, resistance,
                                    and adaptation to change.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Role identity</span>, <span class="construct-badge">self-concept</span>, <span class="construct-badge">identity salience</span>, <span class="construct-badge">identity threat</span>, <span class="construct-badge">identity work</span>, <span class="construct-badge">role
                                    transitions</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When a role is central to who someone is, changes that threaten the role trigger
                                    emotional responses and identity work. People resist, redefine, or adapt to protect
                                    a valued identity.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Strongest in professional contexts with clear role norms and status (law, medicine,
                                    finance, academia). Less relevant when roles are weak or temporary. Identity
                                    dynamics also depend on experience level and status.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Professional role identity is used in IS work on AI and work, showing how AI
                                    threatens experienced professionals while empowering novices.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Professional role identity theory comes from identity research in organizational behavior. The
                        basic idea is that roles are not just job descriptions. Over time, roles become part of a
                        person's self-concept ("I am a doctor", "I am a professor", "I am a cybersecurity analyst").
                        Ashforth (2001) focuses on role transitions and shows that identity is managed through
                        narratives, social validation, and boundary work. When a valued role is threatened, people
                        respond emotionally and engage in identity work to restore a coherent sense of self. Affiliation
                        note: I did not verify author affiliations from the original book in my local workspace, so I am
                        not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Identity</span> shapes meaning and motivation at work. When a professional
                        role is central to who someone is, changes that threaten that role trigger emotional reactions
                        and behavioral responses.
                    </div>

                    <p>People can resist change, redefine the role, or adapt in ways that
                        protect status and self-worth. The mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">identity threat</span> and <span class="construct-badge">identity work</span>. A threat can
                        come from technology that changes <mark>expertise boundaries</mark>, shifts <mark>decision authority</mark>, or changes
                        what counts as "good work." People then engage in <span class="construct-badge">identity work</span> to maintain a positive and
                        coherent identity. That work can include <mark>resistance, reinterpretation, distancing, or learning</mark>.
                        Boundary conditions include role strength and status. The theory is strongest in professional
                        contexts with clear norms and status hierarchies (<mark>medicine, law, finance, academia</mark>). It is less
                        central in temporary roles or low-identity jobs. It also matters who the technology affects.
                        <mark>Novices and veterans</mark> can experience the same tool differently because identity and status
                        differ.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>This theory became very relevant in IS as <mark>AI and automation</mark> started to reshape professional work.
                        In many cases, the main issue is not usefulness. It is "what happens to my expertise and status
                        when a system can do part of my job?" That is an <span class="construct-badge">identity</span> mechanism. <mark>Strich et al. (2021)</mark> is a
                        strong recent IS anchor in the human-AI collaboration space. It shows how AI can be experienced
                        as an <span class="construct-badge">identity threat</span> for <mark>experienced professionals</mark> while being experienced as an enabler for
                        <mark>novices</mark>, which is a clean exam-ready story.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Integration with other theories:</strong> Professional <span class="construct-badge">role identity</span> pairs naturally with <mark>delegation</mark> because delegation is about authority
                        allocation, and authority is tied to professional status. It also pairs with <mark>trust</mark> because when
                        identity is threatened, people may distrust the system and resist relying on it even if it is
                        accurate.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Role identity</span> theory adds depth to IS adoption and change research because it explains
                            resistance and adaptation as <mark>meaning-based</mark>, not only as cost-benefit decisions. It fits AI
                            contexts especially well because AI often shifts what counts as <mark>expertise</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Identity
                            dynamics are hard to measure with simple surveys. The theory often fits best with <mark>qualitative
                            and process methods</mark>, which can be seen as a limitation if the field expects predictive models.
                            Another limitation is that identity explanations can become <mark>too broad</mark> if the paper does not
                            specify what the valued identity is and what exactly threatens it.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong>
                            A common misuse is treating identity as just another individual difference variable without
                            tracing <span class="construct-badge">identity threat</span> and <span class="construct-badge">identity work</span>. Another misuse is assuming identity threat always
                            produces <mark>resistance</mark>. Sometimes it produces <mark>learning and role expansion</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>TAM and UTAUT</mark> explain beliefs and intentions, but they often miss identity threat.
                            <mark>Institutional theory</mark> can explain role change when professional norms shift at the field level.
                            <mark>Sociomateriality</mark> can explain how identity is enacted in practice with artifacts and routines.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use professional <span class="construct-badge">role identity</span> when the question is about professional norms and
                        identity shaping adoption, resistance, or delegation, especially in <mark>expert work</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "How does introducing an AI assistant change professional role identity for
                        experienced versus novice employees, and how does that shape willingness to delegate work to the
                        AI tool?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Experienced professionals experience greater <span class="construct-badge">role identity threat</span>
                        from AI assistants, which reduces their willingness to delegate decision authority, while
                        novices experience lower threat and higher willingness to delegate."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I would measure <span class="construct-badge">role identity threat</span> using validated identity threat items adapted to
                        the role (<mark>threat to expertise, threat to status</mark>). Delegation can be measured by <mark>override
                        behavior</mark> and <mark>reliance on AI recommendations</mark>. I would also capture <mark>career stage</mark> (novice vs
                        veteran) and include <mark>trust</mark> as a mediator or boundary condition.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Ashforth, B. E. (2001)</mark>. <em>Role transitions in organizational life: An identity-based perspective</em>.
                        Mahwah, NJ: Lawrence Erlbaum.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="media-richness-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge strategy">Strategy</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Daft & Lengel 1986</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Media Richness Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Media effectiveness depends on richness (feedback, cues, personalization) matching task complexity and equivocality.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Different communication media have different "richness"—capacity to convey multiple information cues (tone, immediacy, personal focus) simultaneously. Effective communication matches media richness to task needs: complex, equivocal tasks require rich media (face-to-face); routine tasks work with lean media (email). Mismatch creates misunderstanding and inefficiency. Organizations vary in media choice due to norms, structure, and user experience.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Media Richness Dimensions:</strong> Feedback speed, paralinguistic cues, personal focus, language variety—face-to-face richest, text leanest</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Fit Model:</strong> Effectiveness determined by match between media richness and task equivocality; mismatch causes problems</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Equivocality Concept:</strong> Complex, ambiguous tasks need rich media; routine, clear tasks work with lean media</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Organizational Variation:</strong> Media choice influenced by norms, experience, organizational structure, and access to communication technology</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains communication effectiveness in remote work, security incident reporting, and when organizations choose email vs. meetings for sensitive information.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Daft and Lengel (1986)</mark>, "Organizational information requirements, media richness and
                                    structural design," <em><mark>Management Science</mark></em>. Key contribution: <mark>communication
                                    performance</mark> depends on matching <span class="construct-badge">media richness</span> to <span class="construct-badge">task equivocality</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td><mark>Organization theory</mark> / <mark>communication</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td><mark>Borrowed</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td><mark>Type II</mark> (explanation): explains how <span class="construct-badge">media characteristics</span> shape <mark>understanding</mark> under
                                    <span class="construct-badge">uncertainty</span> and <span class="construct-badge">equivocality</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Media richness</span>, <span class="construct-badge">equivocality</span>, <span class="construct-badge">uncertainty</span>, <span class="construct-badge">feedback speed</span>, <span class="construct-badge">multiple cues</span>, <span class="construct-badge">language
                                    variety</span>, <span class="construct-badge">personal focus</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td><mark>Richer media</mark> reduce <span class="construct-badge">ambiguity</span> because they allow <mark>fast feedback</mark> and <mark>more cues</mark>. <mark>Lean
                                    media</mark> work for <mark>routine information exchange</mark>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>The theory was developed <mark>before modern digital media</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Richness</span> can be <mark>socially
                                    constructed</mark> and influenced by <mark>norms</mark> and <mark>experience</mark>. Also, people do not always
                                    choose the "<mark>right</mark>" media because <mark>power</mark> and <mark>convenience</mark> matter.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Media richness</span> is still cited in <mark>digital communication research</mark>, but in my local
                                    course reading set I did not verify a clean <mark>2020-2025 MISQ/ISR/JMIS/JAIS</mark> paper that
                                    uses it as the <mark>primary lens</mark>. (Logged as a limitation in QA if you want strict
                                    top-outlet examples.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <span class="construct-badge">Media richness theory</span> started from an organizational problem: managers face <mark>ambiguous situations</mark>
                        where a message can be interpreted in multiple ways.
                    </div>

                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Media richness theory</span> started from an organizational problem: managers face <mark>ambiguous situations</mark>
                        where a message can be interpreted in multiple ways. <mark>Daft and Lengel</mark> argue that <span class="construct-badge">uncertainty</span> and
                        <span class="construct-badge">equivocality</span> create different communication needs. When a task is <mark>equivocal</mark>, you need <mark>rich media</mark>
                        that supports <mark>sensemaking</mark>, not just <mark>information transfer</mark>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> the "<mark>fit</mark>" logic: <mark>match media to task</mark>. <mark>Rich media</mark> (<mark>face-to-face</mark>,
                        <mark>interactive channels</mark>) help when meaning is unclear. <mark>Lean media</mark> (<mark>reports</mark>, <mark>simple messages</mark>) are
                        efficient for <mark>routine tasks</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p>The mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">feedback</span> and <span class="construct-badge">cues</span>. <mark>Rich media</mark> allow quick
                        back-and-forth and more context, which reduces <mark>misunderstanding</mark>.</p>

                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> Digital channels can be both <mark>rich and lean</mark> depending on how they are used. A
                        video meeting can still feel "<mark>lean</mark>" if people keep cameras off and do not interact. Also,
                        "<span class="construct-badge">richness</span>" is not only technical. It depends on <mark>shared norms</mark>, <mark>trust</mark>, and <mark>experience</mark> with the
                        medium.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>

                    <p>In IS, <span class="construct-badge">media richness</span> often gets paired with <mark>social presence</mark> and related communication theories.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        A common exam move is to show the difference: <span class="construct-badge">media richness</span> focuses on <mark>information processing</mark>
                        and <span class="construct-badge">ambiguity reduction</span>, while <mark>social presence</mark> focuses on the <mark>feeling of human connection</mark>. Both
                        can matter in online contexts, but they are not the same mechanism.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> It gives a clear, intuitive mechanism for <mark>communication choices</mark>. It is useful when you
                            need to explain why some digital communication fails even when information is technically
                            available.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can be too <mark>deterministic</mark>. People do not always choose media based on
                            task requirements. <mark>Cost</mark>, <mark>politics</mark>, <mark>privacy</mark>, and <mark>habit</mark> matter. Also, the digital world created
                            <mark>media hybrids</mark> that do not fit a simple richness ranking.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Treating
                            <span class="construct-badge">richness</span> as a <mark>fixed attribute</mark> of a technology (email is always lean, video is always rich)
                            instead of considering how people <mark>actually use the channel</mark>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives/competitors:</strong> <mark>Social
                            presence theory</mark>, <mark>sociomateriality</mark> for practice-level communication, and <mark>institutional theory</mark>
                            when channel choices are shaped by <mark>norms</mark> and <mark>legitimacy</mark>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        Use <span class="construct-badge">media richness</span> when the exam question is about <mark>communication breakdowns</mark>,
                        <span class="construct-badge">ambiguity</span>, and why <mark>channel choice</mark> matters (<mark>remote work</mark>, <mark>AI mediated communication</mark>).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "In <mark>distributed teams</mark>, when does moving from <mark>chat to video</mark> reduce
                        misunderstanding and improve coordination?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "For <span class="construct-badge">high-equivocality tasks</span>,
                        using <mark>richer media</mark> (video with interactive feedback) is associated with higher <span class="construct-badge">shared
                        understanding</span> than using <mark>lean media</mark> (text chat)."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Task
                        equivocality</span>, <span class="construct-badge">communication medium</span> used, <span class="construct-badge">shared understanding</span> (agreement on goals/roles), and
                        <mark>coordination outcomes</mark> (<mark>rework</mark>, <mark>delays</mark>). I would also measure <mark>norms</mark> (<mark>camera use</mark>, <mark>response
                        expectations</mark>) because they shape effective <span class="construct-badge">richness</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Daft, R. L., &
                        Lengel, R. H. (1986)</mark>. Organizational information requirements, media richness and structural
                        design. <em><mark>Management Science, 32</mark></em>(5), 554-571.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="social-presence-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Short, Williams & Christie 1976</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Social Presence Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Media create varying degrees of social presence; higher presence increases connection, engagement, and trust but also pressure and exposure.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Different communication channels convey different levels of social presence—the sense of "real person" interaction, warmth, and immediacy. Face-to-face creates highest presence; text creates lowest. Higher presence increases engagement, persuasion, and trust because interactions feel more human, but can also increase pressure and reduce privacy. Social presence depends on media design but also on norms, identity, and context.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Social Presence Concept:</strong> Degree to which medium conveys warmth, intimacy cues, and sense of real-person interaction; varies by channel</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Engagement & Persuasion Pathway:</strong> Higher presence → perceived connection → increased engagement, trust, and persuasiveness in communication</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Privacy & Pressure Trade-off:</strong> Higher presence increases exposure feeling; users feel more watched and less able to hide or edit responses</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Context-Dependent:</strong> Norms, user experience, and interaction design influence experienced presence independent of technical features</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains engagement in social media, e-commerce interactions, and remote collaboration; shows why firm engagement strategies affect customer responses and community participation.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td><mark>Short, Williams, and Christie (1976)</mark>, <em>The social psychology of
                                        telecommunications</em>. Key contribution: media differ in the degree to which
                                    they convey <span class="construct-badge">social presence</span> (a sense of "real person" interaction).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Social psychology / communication.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how communication media shape feelings of
                                    connection, warmth, and immediacy, which then shape interaction outcomes.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td><span class="construct-badge">Social presence</span>, <span class="construct-badge">interpersonal connection</span>, <span class="construct-badge">immediacy</span>, <span class="construct-badge">intimacy cues</span>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When a medium creates stronger social presence, people feel more connected and
                                    engaged, which changes persuasion, trust, and interaction quality.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Social presence is not only technical. Norms, identity, and context shape it. High
                                    presence can also have downsides (pressure, privacy concerns).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>In MISQ social media research, social presence logic helps explain engagement and
                                    consumer responses (for example, firm engagement strategies that manage interaction
                                    intensity). In my course reading list, Ren et al. (2023) is a strong anchor in this
                                    area.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Social presence theory was proposed to explain why telecommunication channels feel different.
                        Some channels feel personal and warm, others feel distant. The key idea is that media can create
                        different degrees of social presence, and that this affects how people interact and what kinds
                        of tasks the medium supports.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> Higher <span class="construct-badge">social presence</span> changes interaction quality. It can increase
                        engagement, persuasion, and trust because interactions feel more human.
                    </div>

                    <p>But it can also increase
                        <mark>pressure</mark> or reduce <mark>privacy</mark> because the other person feels more "present." In IS, the mechanism
                        often matters for <mark>social media, e-commerce, and remote collaboration</mark>. If the platform increases
                        <span class="construct-badge">social presence</span> (comments, replies, live interactions), users may feel more engaged, but they
                        may also feel more <mark>exposed</mark>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS research often combines <span class="construct-badge">social presence</span> with <mark>trust</mark> and <mark>persuasion</mark> theories. A clean
                        integration is: <span class="construct-badge">social presence</span> increases perceived <mark>warmth</mark> and <span class="construct-badge">interpersonal connection</span>, which
                        can increase trust and engagement. <mark>Ren et al. (2023)</mark> connect firm social media engagement to
                        sales outcomes, which fits a social presence story: firm actions shape the quality of
                        interaction and user response.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> It is a simple mechanism that fits many digital contexts. It helps you explain why the
                            same message can land differently depending on the channel and the interaction design.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can be hard to separate <span class="construct-badge">social presence</span> from other related constructs like
                            <mark>richness or enjoyment</mark>. Also, the theory can become <mark>too broad</mark> if it explains everything as
                            "presence."</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Treating social presence as a <mark>feature list</mark> rather than
                            a user experience, and ignoring negative effects (<mark>privacy, social pressure, fatigue</mark>).</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <mark>Media richness</mark> for ambiguity processing, <mark>emotional contagion</mark> for
                            emotion spread, and <mark>sociomateriality</mark> for how communication practices and artifacts co-produce
                            outcomes.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use social presence when the exam question is about online engagement, relational
                        signals, and why "human feeling" matters in digital interaction.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "How do firm replies and community interactions on social media change customer engagement and
                        purchase behavior?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Higher perceived <span class="construct-badge">social presence</span> on a firm's social
                        media page is positively associated with customer engagement, which is positively associated
                        with sales performance."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Social presence</span> perceptions (survey) or
                        proxies (<mark>reply rates, conversational depth</mark>), engagement outcomes (<mark>likes, comments, time</mark>), and
                        performance outcomes (sales). I would also control for <mark>content quality and audience size</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> <mark>Short, J., Williams, E., & Christie, B. (1976)</mark>. <em>The social psychology
                            of telecommunications</em>. London: Wiley.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="agenda-setting-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge">Communication</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">McCombs & Shaw 1972</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Agenda-Setting Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Media attention and prominence shape what issues people think are important; not what to think, but what to think about.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Through exposure patterns, prominence, and repetition, information environments shape issue salience and what people perceive as important. Platforms and algorithms now act as primary agenda-setters. Second-level agenda-setting shapes which attributes or frames become salient. Digital platforms enable personalized agendas and strategic manipulation (bots, fake engagement) that artificially inflate apparent importance.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Attention Shaping:</strong> Prominence and repetition increase perceived importance; salience formation drives what people care about</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Attribute Framing:</strong> Second-level agenda-setting shapes which attributes and frames of an issue become salient</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Platform Amplification:</strong> Algorithms, bots, and coordinated fake engagement can artificially inflate salience and redirect attention</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Personalization in Digital Environments:</strong> Feeds are community-specific and audience-dependent; agendas can be strategically engineered</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains how platform design, algorithmic curation, and coordinated manipulation shape public attention; central to understanding disinformation, bot engagement, and viral dynamics.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>McCombs and Shaw (1972), "The agenda-setting function of mass media," <em>Public
                                        Opinion Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: media attention influences what issues
                                    the public thinks are important (salience).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Communication / political science.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how attention and salience are shaped by information
                                    environments.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Salience, agenda, issue attention, attribute emphasis (second-level agenda setting).
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Repeated exposure and prominence increase perceived importance. People focus on what
                                    the information environment keeps highlighting.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Works best when audiences rely on an information environment for issue cues. In
                                    fragmented media, effects can vary by community and algorithmic feeds.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>In MISQ social media and disinformation research, agenda-setting logic helps explain
                                    attention dynamics. Lee et al. (2024) study how bot-assisted engagement spills over
                                    into public attention, which is a clear agenda-setting style mechanism.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Agenda-setting started from a simple idea: mass media may not tell people <mark>what to think</mark>, but it
                        strongly influences <mark>what people think about</mark>. By allocating attention and prominence, media shape
                        issue <span class="construct-badge">salience</span>. This is now very relevant for IS because platforms and algorithms have become
                        attention infrastructures. In digital environments, the "agenda setters" include <mark>algorithms</mark>,
                        <mark>influencers</mark>, and coordinated manipulation like <mark>bots</mark>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that attention is shaped by <span class="construct-badge">exposure patterns</span>. The mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">salience
                        formation</span>: <mark>prominence</mark> and <mark>repetition</mark> increase perceived importance. A second-level idea is that
                        media also shape which <span class="construct-badge">attributes</span> or <span class="construct-badge">frames</span> become salient.</p>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>IS exam move:</strong> Connect agenda-setting to <mark>platform design</mark> and <mark>manipulation</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Bots</span> and <span class="construct-badge">fake engagement</span> can artificially
                        inflate apparent salience, which changes what users attend to.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>Digital platforms changed agenda-setting because attention is now <mark>personalized</mark> and <mark>interactive</mark>.
                        The "<span class="construct-badge">agenda</span>" can be community-specific and can be <mark>strategically engineered</mark>.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Strong IS example:</strong> <mark>Lee et al. (2024)</mark> studies <span class="construct-badge">bot-assisted fake engagement</span> and its <span class="construct-badge">spillover</span> into
                        public attention. That is exactly an agenda-setting type claim, but in a platform setting.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Agenda-setting gives a clear mechanism for <span class="construct-badge">attention dynamics</span>. It helps explain why
                        information environments can shift public focus even without changing beliefs directly.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Causal identification can be hard because attention and coverage can influence each
                        other (<mark>endogeneity</mark>). Another limitation is <mark>heterogeneity</mark>: different users see different feeds.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Treating correlation between online mentions and attention as
                        causal without a design, and ignoring <span class="construct-badge">algorithmic curation</span>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> Social
                        influence theories for persuasion, institutional theory for legitimacy, and information
                        processing theories for how attention leads to cognition and decisions.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use agenda-setting when the exam question is about <span class="construct-badge">attention</span>, <span class="construct-badge">salience</span>, and how
                        platforms or bots shape what people focus on.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "Do bot-assisted likes
                        and shares increase public attention to disinformation topics, and does that attention spill
                        over to related issues?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Higher levels of <span class="construct-badge">bot-assisted fake engagement</span> are
                        positively associated with subsequent public attention to the targeted topic."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Bot-assisted engagement</span> (detected bots and fake interactions), <span class="construct-badge">public
                        attention</span> (search volume, posting volume, news coverage), and <span class="construct-badge">spillover</span> to related topics. A
                        good design is <mark>time series with shocks</mark> or <mark>quasi-experiments</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> McCombs, M.
                        E., & Shaw, D. L. (1972). The agenda-setting function of mass media. <em>Public Opinion
                            Quarterly, 36</em>(2), 176-187.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="consumer-decision-process-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge">Marketing</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Engel-Blackwell-Miniard</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Consumer Decision Process Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">People move through decision stages from need recognition to post-purchase evaluation; different information matters at each stage.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Consumer decisions move through stages: need recognition, search, evaluation, purchase, post-purchase evaluation. High involvement decisions trigger deeper information processing; low involvement relies on cues and heuristics. Platform design, firm engagement, and information availability shape what consumers see during each stage, affecting search, evaluation, and purchase behavior.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Decision Stages:</strong> Need recognition → search → evaluation → purchase → post-purchase; staged process with different information needs</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Involvement-Dependent Processing:</strong> High involvement → deep information processing; Low involvement → cue-based heuristics and peripheral route</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Information Availability:</strong> Reviews, comments, influencer engagement, and firm responses shape information available during evaluation stage</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Platform Design Effects:</strong> E-commerce and social commerce platforms shape what information consumers access, potentially disrupting natural search/evaluation</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains how platform design, firm engagement, and e-commerce features affect consumer purchase journeys; shows why review systems, engagement metrics, and influencer presence shape sales outcomes.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Consumer decision process models in marketing (often associated with the
                                    Engel-Blackwell-Miniard tradition) describe stages from need recognition to
                                    post-purchase evaluation.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Marketing / consumer behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how information, involvement, and evaluation
                                    processes shape purchase and engagement decisions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Decision stages (need recognition, search, evaluation, purchase, post-purchase),
                                    involvement, information processing, persuasion cues.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People move through decision stages, and different information matters at different
                                    stages. High involvement decisions trigger deeper processing, while low involvement
                                    decisions can be driven by cues.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Real decisions are not always staged and rational. People can be impulsive, social,
                                    and bounded. The theory fits better when decisions are deliberate and comparable
                                    across consumers.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>MISQ social media commerce papers use decision-process logic to connect engagement
                                    strategies to consumer behavior. In my course reading list, Ren et al. (2023) is a
                                    strong anchor for firm social media engagement and sales performance.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Consumer decision process models were built to explain how people decide what to buy. The basic
                        intuition is <mark>staged</mark>: people recognize a <span class="construct-badge">need</span>, <span class="construct-badge">search</span> for information, <span class="construct-badge">evaluate</span> options, decide,
                        and then <span class="construct-badge">evaluate the outcome</span> afterward. This is not a perfect description of every purchase,
                        but it is useful for structuring how information and persuasion work across time.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that decisions depend on <span class="construct-badge">information flow</span> and <span class="construct-badge">involvement</span>. When
                        involvement is <mark>high</mark>, people process information more deeply and care about diagnostics. When
                        involvement is <mark>low</mark>, people rely more on <span class="construct-badge">cues</span> and <span class="construct-badge">heuristics</span>.</p>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>IS mechanism:</strong> Platform design and firm engagement change what <span class="construct-badge">information</span> and <span class="construct-badge">cues</span>
                        consumers see, which can shift how they <mark>search</mark>, <mark>evaluate</mark>, and <mark>decide</mark>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS researchers use this theory to study <mark>e-commerce journeys</mark> and <mark>social commerce</mark>. A clean exam
                        move is to connect it to platform features: <span class="construct-badge">reviews</span>, <span class="construct-badge">comments</span>, <span class="construct-badge">influencer disclosure</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">firm
                        responses</span> are all inputs into decision stages.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Strong IS example:</strong> <mark>Ren et al. (2023)</mark> show how managing social media
                        engagement connects to sales performance, which fits a consumer decision logic: engagement
                        affects <span class="construct-badge">information availability</span> and <span class="construct-badge">trust cues</span>, which then shape behavior.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> It is practical and easy to explain. It helps you structure an exam answer about how
                        digital channels shape purchase behavior.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can oversimplify. People do not always
                        move through stages in order. Social influence and platform algorithms can also disrupt the
                        "search and evaluate" story.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Treating <span class="construct-badge">engagement metrics</span> as the
                        same thing as decision outcomes, and ignoring <mark>endogeneity</mark> (firms engage more when customers are
                        already interested).</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> Social presence and trust for relational
                        mechanisms, prospect theory for risk framing, and information processing theory for attention
                        limits.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use consumer decision process theory when the exam question is about how digital
                        engagement strategies shape consumer behavior over a <mark>journey</mark>, not only one click.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "When should a firm respond to comments on social media to increase
                        conversion and sales?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "<span class="construct-badge">Firm responses</span> to user comments increase sales
                        performance by improving consumers' <span class="construct-badge">evaluation</span> of the firm and reducing <span class="construct-badge">uncertainty</span>."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> Comment volume and sentiment, <span class="construct-badge">firm response timing</span> and content, consumer
                        actions (clicks, conversion), and sales outcomes. A stronger design would use <mark>instrumental
                        variables</mark> or <mark>experiments</mark> (randomized response strategies).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Engel, J. F.,
                        Blackwell, R. D., & Miniard, P. W. (1995). <em>Consumer behavior</em> (8th ed.). Dryden Press.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="appraisal-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Lazarus 1991</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Appraisal Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Emotions arise from cognitive appraisals of events in relation to goals and coping capacity; same event produces different emotions depending on interpretation.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Emotions are not automatic reactions; they depend on appraisal—how people interpret events in relation to personal goals and coping ability. Same event creates anxiety if appraised as threatening and coping feels low; creates anger if appraised as unfair and caused by others. Digital environments (social media, health communities) trigger emotional responses when users appraise exposure to others as threatening to self-evaluation or goal-relevant.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Appraisal-Emotion Linkage:</strong> Emotion type determined by appraisal content (threat, unfairness) and coping potential, not objective situation</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Goal Relevance & Congruence:</strong> Events appraised as relevant to personal goals and incongruent with those goals trigger stronger emotional reactions</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Coping Potential:</strong> Events appraised as threatening with low coping potential trigger anxiety; same events with high coping potential trigger challenge emotions</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🎯 Digital Amplification:</strong> Online visibility of others' outcomes, support, success creates appraisals of self-evaluation threat and goal incongruence</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains unintended emotional effects in online communities, social media, and digital platforms where users observe others and appraise their own standing and goal progress.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Lazarus (1991), <em>Emotion and adaptation</em>. Key contribution: emotions arise
                                    from cognitive appraisals of situations in relation to goals and coping resources.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Psychology (emotion and stress).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains why specific emotions arise and how they drive
                                    behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Appraisal, goal relevance, goal congruence, coping potential, emotion categories.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People feel emotions based on how they interpret (appraise) an event: is it good/bad
                                    for my goals, and can I cope with it? Different appraisals lead to different
                                    emotions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Strong for emotion episodes and stress contexts. Harder to use when emotions are
                                    weak, habitual, or socially performed rather than internally experienced.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>In MISQ health community research, appraisal logic helps explain how online exposure
                                    leads to unintended emotions and behavior. Zhou et al. (2023) is a strong example in
                                    this space.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Appraisal theory was developed to explain why the same event can produce different emotions
                        across people. <mark>Lazarus</mark> argues that emotions are not only automatic reactions. They depend on
                        <span class="construct-badge">appraisal</span>: how the person interprets the event in relation to <span class="construct-badge">goals</span> and <span class="construct-badge">coping capacity</span>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">appraisal</span> → <span class="construct-badge">emotion</span> → <span class="construct-badge">action</span>. If a situation is appraised as
                        <mark>threatening</mark> and coping feels low, <span class="construct-badge">anxiety</span> may arise. If it is appraised as unfair and caused by
                        others, <span class="construct-badge">anger</span> may arise. These emotions then shape behavior.
                    </div>

                    <p>In IS, appraisal theory is useful
                        when you want to explain emotional reactions in digital environments, especially social and
                        comparative contexts (social media, health communities).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS researchers apply appraisal theory to understand digital <span class="construct-badge">emotion dynamics</span> (<span class="construct-badge">stress</span>, <span class="construct-badge">envy</span>,
                        <span class="construct-badge">shame</span>, <span class="construct-badge">pride</span>). A clean recent case is <mark>online health communities</mark>: people may feel negative
                        emotions not only from their own situation but from what they <mark>observe about others</mark>.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Strong IS example:</strong> <mark>Zhou et al. (2023)</mark> show unintended emotional effects in such communities, which fits appraisal and social
                        comparison logic.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> It gives a mechanism for emotions that is more precise than just saying "people feel
                        bad." It helps you link <mark>platform design</mark> (what people see) to emotional outcomes.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Appraisal</span> can be hard to measure in real time, and retrospective self-reports can be biased.
                        Emotions are also socially shaped, so purely cognitive appraisal can miss norms and identity.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Treating emotions as generic positive/negative outcomes without
                        specifying the <span class="construct-badge">appraisal process</span>, and ignoring <mark>timing</mark> (emotion episodes change quickly).</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> Emotional contagion for spread, social comparison for
                        self-evaluation, and ego depletion for resource limits when you want to explain lapses rather
                        than feelings.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use appraisal theory when the exam question is about <span class="construct-badge">emotions</span> triggered by digital
                        exposure and how those emotions lead to behavior (disclosure, quitting, engagement).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How does seeing others receive support in an online health forum shape
                        observers' emotions and participation?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Exposure to others' support is
                        associated with increased <span class="construct-badge">negative emotion</span> among observers when it is appraised as a <span class="construct-badge">threat to
                        self-evaluation</span>, which reduces posting behavior."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Exposure</span> (what
                        content people see), <span class="construct-badge">appraisal indicators</span> (self-evaluation threat), <span class="construct-badge">emotions</span> (specific emotions
                        like envy, sadness), and behavior (posting, quitting). A strong design uses <mark>experience sampling</mark>
                        or <mark>platform trace data</mark> paired with short surveys.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Lazarus, R. S. (1991).
                        <em>Emotion and adaptation</em>. Oxford University Press.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="information-processing-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Wright et al., 2023</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Information Processing Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How cognitive capacity limits and context affect deception detection and security behavior.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> People have limited cognitive capacity. Context shapes what cues are noticed and how deeply they are processed, which affects deception detection. Phishing succeeds when attackers exploit attention limits and context pressures.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Bounded Rationality:</strong> People cannot process all information and rely on cues and heuristics under constraints</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Context Effects:</strong> Workload, social pressure, and trust reduce careful processing of diagnostic cues</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Multilevel View:</strong> Individual processing is shaped by organizational and network context</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Application:</strong> Explains phishing susceptibility through cognitive mechanisms rather than blame</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Provides a clear mechanism for why security violations occur even with awareness training by focusing on cognitive capacity and contextual constraints.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Information processing is a broad tradition in cognitive science and organizational
                                    behavior. In IS security, Wright et al. (2023) use a multilevel information
                                    processing perspective to explain deception detection and phishing susceptibility in
                                    context.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Cognitive psychology / cognitive science / organizational behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II/IV: explains cognitive limits and processing mechanisms (Type II) and can
                                    support prediction of deception detection outcomes under different contexts (Type
                                    IV).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Limited attention, cognitive capacity, cues, processing depth, deception detection.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People have limited capacity. Context shapes what cues are noticed and how deeply
                                    they are processed, which affects whether deception is detected.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Strong when cognition and attention are central. Less useful when the outcome is
                                    driven mainly by incentives, culture, or structural opportunity.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Wright et al. (2023) in MISQ is a direct top-outlet example connecting information
                                    processing to phishing susceptibility.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Information processing perspectives start from <mark>bounded rationality</mark>: people cannot process all
                        information, so they rely on <span class="construct-badge">cues</span> and <span class="construct-badge">heuristics</span> under constraints. In security, this matters
                        because phishing succeeds when attackers exploit <span class="construct-badge">attention limits</span> and <span class="construct-badge">context pressures</span>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Deception detection</span> depends on <span class="construct-badge">processing</span>. People detect deception
                        when they notice <mark>diagnostic cues</mark> and have enough <span class="construct-badge">capacity</span> and <span class="construct-badge">motivation</span> to process them.
                    </div>

                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Context</span> changes both attention and capacity. For example, <mark>workload</mark>, <mark>social pressure</mark>, or <mark>trust</mark>
                        can reduce careful processing.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Multilevel perspective:</strong> <mark>Wright et al. (2023)</mark> make the perspective explicitly <mark>multilevel</mark>: individual <span class="construct-badge">processing</span> is shaped
                        by <span class="construct-badge">organizational</span> and <span class="construct-badge">network context</span>. This is useful for IS because phishing does not happen in
                        a vacuum. <mark>Work routines</mark>, <mark>email volume</mark>, and <mark>social connections</mark> shape exposure and processing.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> It provides a clear mechanism for why people fall for deception even when they "know
                        better." It shifts the story from <mark>blame</mark> to <span class="construct-badge">context</span> and <span class="construct-badge">cognition</span>.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can underplay
                        deliberate risk taking and incentives. Also, cognitive processing is hard to measure without
                        intrusive methods.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Treating awareness training as sufficient
                        without considering context, and using generic self-report measures of "attention" that do not
                        match the real task.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> PMT for threat appraisal and coping, routine
                        activity/opportunity for situational exposure, and neutralization for rationalization after
                        violations.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use information processing when the exam question is about why people do not
                        detect deception and how <span class="construct-badge">context</span> changes <span class="construct-badge">cognitive capacity</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "How do
                        workload and social network position affect employees' phishing susceptibility?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Higher <span class="construct-badge">workload</span> is positively associated with <span class="construct-badge">phishing susceptibility</span> because it
                        reduces available cognitive capacity for deception detection."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong>
                        <span class="construct-badge">Workload</span> (email volume, task load), <span class="construct-badge">network position</span> (centrality), <span class="construct-badge">phishing outcomes</span> (simulation
                        clicks, real incidents), and <span class="construct-badge">attention proxies</span> (response time, email reading patterns). A
                        <mark>multilevel design</mark> fits well.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Wright, R. T., Johnson, S. L., & Kitchens, B.
                        (2023). Phishing susceptibility in context: A multilevel information processing perspective on
                        deception detection. <em>MIS Quarterly, 47</em>(2).</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="contextual-theory-context-shapes-cognition-and-behavior">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge organizational">Organizational</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Wright et al., 2023</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Contextual Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How social and organizational context shapes cognitive processing and behavior across situations.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Context changes what people notice and how they interpret cues. That changes behavior even when the person's traits do not change. Workload, network exposure, and routines shape cognition and action differently across contexts.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Context Shapes Cognition:</strong> Workload, routines, and social networks affect what employees notice and prioritize</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Multilevel Effects:</strong> Context operates at individual, team, and organizational levels simultaneously</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Specificity Required:</strong> Context works best when operationalized clearly and linked to cognitive mechanisms</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Behavior Variation:</strong> Same person behaves differently under different contextual pressures</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains security behavior variation across teams and time periods by focusing on context rather than individual blame, supporting situational interventions.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>In my course materials, "contextual theory" is used as a label for the idea that
                                    social and organizational context shapes cognitive processing and behavior. A
                                    concrete IS formalization is Wright et al. (2023) on phishing susceptibility in
                                    context.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Organization science / psychology (context effects).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed logic, but applied in IS security research.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains why the same individual can behave differently under
                                    different contexts.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Context (workload, routines, social network), cognition, attention, behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Context changes what people notice and how they interpret cues. That changes
                                    behavior even when the person's traits do not change.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Context is broad. If not specified, it becomes vague. The theory works best when
                                    context is operationalized clearly and linked to a specific cognitive mechanism.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Wright et al. (2023) is a direct top-outlet example: it connects work context and
                                    network context to phishing outcomes through an information processing mechanism.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>The simple idea is that people do not make decisions <mark>in a vacuum</mark>. In IS, <span class="construct-badge">context</span> is often the
                        missing piece. Two employees can have the same training, but different <span class="construct-badge">workload</span>, different
                        <span class="construct-badge">network exposure</span>, and different <span class="construct-badge">routines</span>. Those differences shape what they see and how they
                        react.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Context</span> shapes <span class="construct-badge">cognition</span>, and cognition shapes <span class="construct-badge">behavior</span>. This is not
                        only "environment matters" as a vague statement. The mechanism is specific: context affects
                        <span class="construct-badge">attention</span>, <span class="construct-badge">processing depth</span>, and <span class="construct-badge">cue interpretation</span>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Strong IS example:</strong> <mark>Wright et al. (2023)</mark> operationalizes <span class="construct-badge">context</span> at <mark>multiple levels</mark>
                        and links it to <span class="construct-badge">deception detection</span>. The exam move is to argue that context is not just a
                        control variable. It is <mark>part of the causal story</mark>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Contextual theory prevents <mark>individual-blame</mark> explanations and supports richer
                        interventions (changing workflow, reducing exposure, redesigning systems).</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can be
                        too broad. If you include too many context variables without a clear mechanism, you get noise
                        and weak theory.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Saying "context matters" and then only adding
                        context as a moderator without explaining why, or using context as a <mark>post-hoc explanation</mark> for
                        unexpected results.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> Institutional theory for macro context,
                        routine activity for exposure and opportunity, and PMT for threat appraisal.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use contextual theory when the exam question is about why <span class="construct-badge">behavior changes across
                        situations</span> (phishing, compliance, adoption across departments).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "Why
                        do some teams become consistently more vulnerable to phishing during peak workload periods?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Teams with higher <span class="construct-badge">workload</span> and higher <span class="construct-badge">external exposure</span> have higher
                        <span class="construct-badge">phishing susceptibility</span>, mediated by reduced <span class="construct-badge">attention to deception cues</span>."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Workload</span>, <span class="construct-badge">exposure</span> (external emails), <span class="construct-badge">team routines</span> (meeting load), and phishing
                        outcomes. A good design includes <mark>time variation</mark> (within-person or within-team) to show context
                        shifts.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Wright, R. T., Johnson, S. L., & Kitchens, B. (2023). Phishing
                        susceptibility in context: A multilevel information processing perspective on deception
                        detection. <em>MIS Quarterly, 47</em>(2).</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="negative-affectivity-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Watson & Clark, 1984</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Negative Affectivity Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Stable personality tendency to experience and report negative emotions, relevant to survey method bias.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Some people carry a stable negative affective style that shapes how they perceive and report. This trait creates interpretive bias and can inflate relationships among self-report measures if not controlled.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Trait Stability:</strong> Negative affectivity is a stable personality characteristic across contexts</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Interpretive Bias:</strong> High negative affectivity individuals interpret situations more negatively</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Common Method Bias:</strong> Artificial correlations can inflate when all measures are self-reported</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Methodological Control:</strong> Use objective measures or include it as a control variable to separate trait from actual experience</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Critical for validity of self-reported security perceptions; helps distinguish actual behavior changes from survey response bias in IT use and security compliance studies.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Watson and Clark (1984) and related work define negative affectivity as a stable
                                    tendency to experience negative emotions and view situations negatively. This
                                    concept is often used in methods discussions about common method bias in
                                    self-reports.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Personality psychology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type I/II: it classifies a trait (Type I analysis) and explains stable differences
                                    in affective experience (Type II). In IS, it is often used as a methods control
                                    rather than a main theory.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Trait negative affectivity, negative mood, pessimistic appraisal tendencies.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Some people are more likely to interpret events negatively. This shapes their survey
                                    responses and reported experiences across many measures.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Most relevant for self-reported perceptions (satisfaction, stress, trust). Less
                                    relevant when outcomes are objective behaviors or trace data.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Negative affectivity is mainly a measurement and survey-quality concern rather than
                                    a main IS theory lens. It appears indirectly in discussions of common method bias
                                    and survey design. (Not a common "theory" citation in top IS empirical papers.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Negative affectivity</span> was developed to capture stable <mark>personality differences</mark>. For IS comps, the
                        reason it matters is <mark>methodological</mark>: if respondents have a general tendency to rate everything
                        negatively, you can get <mark>artificial correlations</mark> across self-reported constructs. This is why
                        negative affectivity is discussed alongside <span class="construct-badge">common method bias</span>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core claim:</strong> <mark>Stability</mark> - some people carry a <span class="construct-badge">negative affective style</span> that shapes how they
                        perceive and report. The mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">interpretive bias</span> plus <span class="construct-badge">mood</span>. This can <mark>inflate
                        relationships</mark> among self-report measures if you do not design studies carefully.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>IS usage:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Negative affectivity</span> is most often used as a <mark>control variable</mark> or as a warning about survey
                        design. The exam move is to connect it to <span class="construct-badge">validity</span>: if your key variables are all self-reported
                        perceptions in the same survey, negative affectivity is one plausible <mark>alternative explanation</mark>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> It helps explain why self-report data can be misleading. It gives you a concrete
                        alternative explanation that is not "bad respondents."</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> It can be <mark>over-controlled</mark>. If
                        negative affectivity is part of the real phenomenon (for example, stress leading to security
                        mistakes), controlling it away can remove real variance.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Using it
                        as a checkbox control without thinking about whether it is confounding or part of the mechanism.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Common method bias</span> frameworks (method variance), and research
                        designs that use multiple sources (trace data + surveys) to reduce self-report bias.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use negative affectivity in exam answers when you need to discuss <span class="construct-badge">survey validity
                        threats</span> and <span class="construct-badge">alternative explanations</span> (common method bias).
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "Do
                        employees who report high technostress also report lower compliance, or is the relationship
                        partly driven by negative affectivity?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "<span class="construct-badge">Negative affectivity</span> is positively
                        associated with reported <span class="construct-badge">technostress</span> and negatively associated with reported <span class="construct-badge">satisfaction</span>,
                        inflating their correlation."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> Include a <span class="construct-badge">negative affectivity
                        scale</span>, <mark>separate measurement waves</mark>, and use <mark>objective outcomes</mark> when possible (policy compliance
                        logs). Then test whether relationships hold after controlling for trait affect.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Watson, D., & Clark, L. A. (1984). Negative affectivity: The disposition to experience
                        aversive emotional states. <em>Psychological Bulletin</em>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="polygenic-score-theory-biological-foundations-of-it-use">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Behavioral Genetics</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Polygenic Score Theory (Biological Foundations of IT Use)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Biological and genetic foundations of individual differences in IT adoption and security behaviors.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Some variation in technology use and security behavior may have genetic components. Polygenic scores aggregate genetic predispositions relevant to IT use traits like openness and conscientiousness.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Genetic Contribution:</strong> Technology adoption traits have partial genetic basis</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Polygenic Aggregation:</strong> Multiple genetic variants combine to predict behavioral predispositions</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Nature-Nurture Interaction:</strong> Genetic tendencies interact with environment and training</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Implication:</strong> Some security-related traits (conscientiousness, risk awareness) have biological foundations</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Provides boundary conditions for training and intervention effectiveness; explains why awareness programs may not fully override biologically-based risk tolerance or openness traits.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Brown and Sias (2023), "The fault in our stars: Molecular genetics and information
                                    technology use," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: introduces polygenic
                                    scores as a way to connect genetic predispositions to IT use outcomes.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Genetics / behavioral genetics.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed methods and theory, applied in IS.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type IV (explanation and prediction): predicts IT use from biological
                                    predispositions and explains part of variance through stable individual differences.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Polygenic score (PGS), genetic predispositions (education, neuroticism), IT use over
                                    the life course.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Genetic variants shape traits and capabilities that influence learning and behavior,
                                    which then influence technology use across the life span.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>High ethical sensitivity (privacy, discrimination). Also, biology is not destiny:
                                    environment and context still matter, and effect sizes are usually small.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Brown and Sias (2023) in MISQ is the key top-outlet proof-of-life example in my
                                    local set. This is a newer stream, so the top-outlet footprint is still limited.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p><span class="construct-badge">Polygenic score</span> approaches come from genetics, where researchers aggregate many <mark>small genetic
                        effects</mark> into a score that predicts an outcome or trait. <mark>Brown and Sias (2023)</mark> bring this logic
                        into IS by asking whether <span class="construct-badge">biological predispositions</span> relate to long-run IT use.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> NOT <mark>determinism</mark>. <span class="construct-badge">Stable predispositions</span> can be one input into
                        technology use patterns, alongside <span class="construct-badge">environment</span> and <span class="construct-badge">opportunity</span>.
                    </div>

                    <p>The mechanism is <mark>indirect</mark>: <span class="construct-badge">genes</span>
                        influence <span class="construct-badge">traits</span> (like education-related propensity or neuroticism), traits influence <span class="construct-badge">learning</span>
                        and <span class="construct-badge">comfort with technology</span>, and that influences use.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Emerging IS direction:</strong> The big exam value is not "genetics explains everything." It is
                        <mark>methodological</mark> and <mark>theoretical</mark>: it pushes IS to consider deeper sources of <span class="construct-badge">heterogeneity</span> and to
                        separate <span class="construct-badge">stable predispositions</span> from <span class="construct-badge">situational drivers</span>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> It introduces a new source of variance that IS often ignores. It can help explain
                        persistent individual differences in use even after controlling for demographics.</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> <mark>Ethical risk is high</mark>. There are also risks of <span class="construct-badge">population stratification</span>, weak generalizability
                        across ancestries, and <mark>misinterpretation as destiny</mark>. Another weakness is that the link to IS
                        theory can be thin if the paper does not connect biology to real mechanisms and contexts.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> Over-claiming causality, ignoring ethics and governance, and treating
                        genetic predictors as substitute for context and social factors.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong>
                        Traditional behavioral theories (TAM, UTAUT, role identity) explain <mark>proximal beliefs</mark> and
                        meanings. Contextual and institutional theories explain environment and constraints. A strong
                        exam answer can position genetics as <mark>distal antecedents</mark>, not replacements.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use polygenic score theory when the exam question invites a discussion of <span class="construct-badge">deep
                        heterogeneity</span>, <span class="construct-badge">long-run adoption</span>, or novel data sources (genetics) and their <mark>ethical
                        implications</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "Do genetic predispositions related to education
                        predict later-life IT use, and does training moderate that relationship?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong>
                        "Higher <span class="construct-badge">polygenic scores</span> associated with educational attainment are positively associated with
                        IT use in adulthood."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> <span class="construct-badge">IT use measures</span> (device use, online
                        behaviors), <span class="construct-badge">polygenic scores</span> from genetic data, <span class="construct-badge">education and training exposures</span>, and strong
                        privacy governance. Designs should be careful about <mark>sample composition</mark> and <mark>ethical consent</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Brown, S. A., & Sias, R. W. (2023). The fault in our stars: Molecular
                        genetics and information technology use. <em>MIS Quarterly, 47</em>(2).</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Part D Divider -->
            <div class="part-divider" id="part-d">
                <div>
                    <h2>🔒 Part D: Criminological & Security Theories</h2>
                    <p style="margin: 0; opacity: 0.9; font-size: 0.95rem;">Theories of cybersecurity, crime, and
                        deviant behavior</p>
                </div>
                <div class="part-count">15 Theories</div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="routine-activity-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge security">Criminology</span>
                        <span class="theory-badge">Cohen & Felson, 1979</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Routine Activity Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Crime and security incidents happen when opportunity structures align — not just when people are "bad"</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Security incidents occur when three elements converge: a motivated offender, a suitable target, and the absence of a capable guardian. Change any one element and incident rates drop — it is a theory of situational opportunity, not psychology.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point">🎯 <strong>Suitable Target:</strong> Exposed data, weak access controls, valuable assets</div>
                        <div class="key-point">👤 <strong>Motivated Offender:</strong> Presence of someone with capability and intent</div>
                        <div class="key-point">🛡️ <strong>Capable Guardian:</strong> Monitoring, authentication, supervision that blocks convergence</div>
                        <div class="key-point">⏱️ <strong>Convergence:</strong> All three must align in time and space for an incident</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>Relevance for IS:</strong> Core framework for IS security and cybercrime research — maps directly to access controls, monitoring systems, and organizational change contexts that create or remove opportunities
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Cohen and Felson (1979), "Social change and crime rate trends: A routine activity
                                    approach," <em>American Sociological Review</em>. Key contribution: crime occurs
                                    when motivated offenders, suitable targets, and lack of capable guardians converge
                                    in time and space.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Criminology/sociology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS security and cybercrime research).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains when harmful events occur based on opportunity
                                    structures.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Motivated offender, suitable target, capable guardian, convergence (time/space),
                                    routine activities.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Security incidents happen when opportunity structures line up. Reduce any one
                                    element (offender, target, weak guardianship) and incidents drop.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Focuses on opportunity, not offender psychology. Best for explaining patterns of
                                    incidents and situational risk, not deep motivations.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Routine activity logic appears in IS security work on opportunity contexts. In my
                                    local reading set, the clearest top-outlet anchors are Wang et al. (2019) on
                                    unauthorized access attempts and Liang et al. (2025) on M&A-related breach risk, so
                                    I log this as partial 2020-2025 coverage.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Routine activity theory was developed to explain crime patterns without assuming crime is only
                        about <mark>offender motivation</mark>. <mark>Cohen and Felson (1979)</mark> argue that crime happens when <mark>three elements</mark>
                        converge in time and space: <span class="construct-badge">motivated offenders</span>, <span class="construct-badge">suitable targets</span>, and absence of <span class="construct-badge">capable
                        guardians</span>. The theory was originally used to explain social change and crime rate trends, but
                        the mechanism is general: changes in <span class="construct-badge">routine activities</span> change <span class="construct-badge">opportunity structures</span>.
                        Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliations from the original article in my local
                        workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>

                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Opportunity</span>. Even if <span class="construct-badge">motivation</span> stays constant, incidents rise when
                        targets become more <mark>suitable</mark> and <span class="construct-badge">guardianship</span> becomes <mark>weaker</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p>In cyber settings, this maps
                        cleanly to <mark>access rights</mark>, <mark>exposed data</mark>, <mark>weak monitoring</mark>, and <mark>limited deterrence</mark>. The causal
                        mechanism is <span class="construct-badge">convergence</span>. Security incidents happen when an offender has access to a target at a
                        moment when guardianship is weak. <span class="construct-badge">Guardianship</span> can be <mark>technical</mark> (authentication, monitoring) and
                        <mark>social</mark> (supervision, norms).</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Key exam move:</strong> Show that routine activity is not a theory of
                        "bad people." It is a theory of <mark>situational risk</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> Routine
                        activity theory does not explain deep motivations or moral reasoning. It is best for explaining
                        incident patterns and the effect of controls. If your research question is "why would an
                        employee want to do this," you usually need a complementary theory like <mark>neutralization</mark>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS security researchers use routine activity logic because digital systems <mark>create and remove
                        opportunities</mark>. The unit of analysis can be <span class="construct-badge">log events</span> (access attempts), <span class="construct-badge">organizational changes</span>
                        (role transitions), or structural changes that alter guardianship.</p>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Strong IS anchors:</strong> <mark>Wang et al. (2019)</mark> studies unauthorized access attempts over time and frames the
                        behavior through <span class="construct-badge">opportunity contexts</span>. <mark>Liang et al. (2025)</mark> shows how mergers and acquisitions create integration complexity, which often produces
                        temporary <span class="construct-badge">weak guardianship</span> and <span class="construct-badge">exposed targets</span>. Even if the paper is framed as complexity,
                        routine activity logic helps you explain the <mark>situational opportunity mechanism</mark> during
                        organizational change.
                    </div>

                    <p>Routine activity also integrates well with <mark>deterrence perspectives</mark> and
                        with <mark>neutralization theory</mark>. Routine activity explains the <span class="construct-badge">situational opportunity</span>, while
                        neutralization explains how people <mark>justify misuse</mark> once the opportunity exists.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>

                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Routine activity theory is <mark>simple</mark> and <mark>actionable</mark>. It gives you a clear way to design
                        controls: reduce <span class="construct-badge">target suitability</span>, increase <span class="construct-badge">guardianship</span>, or reduce <span class="construct-badge">offender capability</span>. It
                        also fits well with security log data because many constructs can be operationalized directly
                        (access, monitoring, exposure).</li>

                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> The theory can look too <mark>mechanical</mark> if you ignore
                        motivation and morality. Many violations are not only opportunity, they are also <mark>justification</mark>
                        and <mark>stress</mark>. Another limitation is that defining "capable guardianship" can be tricky in digital
                        systems where monitoring exists but is ignored.</li>

                        <li><strong>Common misapplications in IS:</strong> A common misuse is
                        treating any security control as guardianship without specifying how it actually changes
                        opportunity. Another is using routine activity to explain intentional fraud without considering
                        motivation and rationalization.</li>

                        <li><strong>Alternatives and competitors:</strong> Neutralization theory is a strong
                        alternative when the mechanism is moral justification. Agency theory is useful for governance
                        and incentives. Institutional theory is useful when policy and regulation shape security
                        behavior at the field level.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>

                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use routine activity when the question is about <span class="construct-badge">exposure</span> and <span class="construct-badge">opportunity</span> in cyber
                        incidents (targets, offenders, guardianship) rather than attitudes.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "Does expanding employee access to systems increase unauthorized access attempts, even when
                        motivation does not change?"</p>

                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Increases in <span class="construct-badge">system access privileges</span> are
                        associated with increases in <span class="construct-badge">unauthorized access attempts</span>."</p>

                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure (simple):</strong> I
                        would use <mark>access control logs</mark> to measure privilege changes and unauthorized access attempts over
                        time. I would also capture <span class="construct-badge">guardianship measures</span> (monitoring alerts, audit frequency) and
                        <span class="construct-badge">organizational changes</span> (role transitions, restructuring) to isolate <span class="construct-badge">opportunity contexts</span>. A
                        simple exam point is that this design directly matches the theory: <mark>opportunity structures change
                        first, incidents follow</mark>.
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Cohen, L. E., & Felson, M. (1979). Social change
                        and crime rate trends: A routine activity approach. <em>American Sociological Review,
                            44</em>(4), 588-608.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="neutralization-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge criminology">Criminology</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Neutralization Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How individuals rationalize rule-breaking and policy violations before and after committing them.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Before violating rules, people use neutralization techniques to manage cognitive dissonance: denying responsibility, condemning condemners, appealing to higher loyalty, or denying injury. After violation, these rationalizations persist.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Cognitive Dissonance:</strong> Neutralization resolves conflict between beliefs and behavior</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Technique Varieties:</strong> Denial of responsibility, injury, victim, condemner condemnation, higher loyalties</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Pre- and Post-Violation:</strong> Both prevents and justifies violations after they occur</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Application:</strong> Explains persistent insecurity despite knowledge of rules and policies</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Essential for understanding why policy compliance fails; shows that rule-breakers use moral reasoning to justify violations, requiring cultural and structural interventions beyond rules alone.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Sykes and Matza (1957), "Techniques of neutralization: A theory of delinquency,"
                                    <em>American Sociological Review</em>. Key contribution: people justify deviance
                                    through neutralization techniques that reduce guilt.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Criminology/sociology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS for security policy violations and insider misuse).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains why people violate rules even when they know the
                                    rules, by focusing on moral rationalizations.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Techniques of neutralization: denial of responsibility, denial of injury, denial of
                                    victim, condemnation of condemners, appeal to higher loyalties.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People protect their self-image by reframing rule-breaking as acceptable ("everyone
                                    does it", "no one is harmed", "I had no choice"). These rationalizations weaken
                                    internal controls and enable deviance.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Works best for violations by "normal" people who still care about norms. Less
                                    relevant for offenders who fully reject the norm system.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Neutralization is used in MISQ behavioral cybersecurity work (often combined with
                                    ego depletion) to explain security policy violations over time.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Neutralization theory was developed to explain why deviance can happen <mark>without a full rejection
                        of social norms</mark>. <mark>Sykes and Matza (1957)</mark> argue that many offenders still <mark>accept conventional
                        values</mark>, but they temporarily <span class="construct-badge">neutralize</span> those values through <span class="construct-badge">justifications</span>. This is why
                        neutralization is useful for <mark>insider security behavior</mark>. Many employees who violate policy still
                        see themselves as <mark>good people</mark>. Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliations from the
                        original article in my local workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> People use <span class="construct-badge">neutralization techniques</span> to reduce <span class="construct-badge">guilt</span> and protect
                        <span class="construct-badge">self-image</span>, which makes rule-breaking psychologically easier.
                    </div>
                    <p>The classic techniques: <span class="construct-badge">denial of responsibility</span> ("I had no choice"), <span class="construct-badge">denial of injury</span> ("no harm done"), <span class="construct-badge">denial of
                        victim</span> ("they deserve it"), <span class="construct-badge">condemnation of condemners</span> ("security is unreasonable"), and <span class="construct-badge">appeal
                        to higher loyalties</span> ("I did it for the team"). The mechanism is <mark>moral disengagement</mark> through talk
                        and reasoning. Neutralizations weaken <span class="construct-badge">internal controls</span>. In IS settings, this
                        often shows up as <mark>productivity justifications</mark> ("I needed to get the work done") or <mark>fairness
                        justifications</mark> ("this policy is unrealistic").</p>
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> Neutralization is
                        strongest for "ordinary" offenders who still care about norms. Less relevant for actors who fully reject the norm system.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>Neutralization became a core IS security lens because it matches the reality of policy
                        violations. Many violations are done by employees who feel <mark>time
                        pressure</mark>, <mark>convenience needs</mark>, or <mark>loyalty to work goals</mark>.</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Classic IS anchor:</strong> <mark>Siponen and Vance (2010)</mark> in MISQ show how neutralization helps explain employee security policy
                        violations and why awareness alone does not solve the problem. In the 2020-2025 reading set, <mark>Cram et al. (2024)</mark> is a useful anchor for
                        within-person and time-sensitive designs.
                    </div>
                    <p>Integration with <mark>ego
                        depletion</mark> is common: depletion can explain <mark>when</mark> people slip, and neutralization can explain <mark>how they justify</mark> the slip.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Neutralization gives a realistic mechanism for <mark>insider violations</mark>. Explains
                        why good people do bad security actions, and suggests interventions beyond training.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Measuring neutralization is not always easy. Neutralization can be <mark>post-hoc rationalization</mark> after the violation, creating
                        causal ambiguity if study design is not careful.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Treating neutralization as a <mark>personality trait</mark> (it's more situational). Using neutralization language without measuring actual techniques.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Deterrence for punishment, Ego depletion for temporal lapses, Routine activity for opportunity. Neutralization is most
                        useful for <mark>moral-justification mechanisms</mark>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use neutralization when the question is about how people <span class="construct-badge">justify rule breaking</span>
                        (policy violations, piracy, misuse) to protect their <span class="construct-badge">self-image</span>.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong>
                        "When employees bypass security controls for productivity, what neutralization techniques do
                        they use, and which techniques predict repeated violations?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Employees who
                        endorse stronger <span class="construct-badge">neutralization beliefs</span> (especially <span class="construct-badge">appeal to higher loyalties</span>) will report
                        higher rates of security policy violations."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> Neutralization using survey items mapping to classic techniques, combined with
                        behavioral outcomes (self-reported violations and log-based indicators). A strong design is <mark>time-separated</mark> (measure neutralization first,
                        then observe behavior) to reduce post-hoc rationalization problems.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Sykes,
                        G. M., & Matza, D. (1957). Techniques of neutralization: A theory of delinquency. <em>American
                            Sociological Review, 22</em>(6), 664-670.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="environmental-criminology-opportunity-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge criminology">Criminology</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Brantingham & Brantingham</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Environmental Criminology / Opportunity Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How physical and temporal environments create opportunities for security breaches and violations.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Crime (including insider threats and data theft) requires three elements: motivated offender, suitable target, and absence of guardianship. Opportunity theory focuses on how environment enables violation.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Routine Activity:</strong> Environmental patterns create predictable opportunities and guard gaps</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Three Elements:</strong> Motivated offender + suitable target + lack of guardianship = violation opportunity</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Situational Design:</strong> Redesigning workflows and systems reduces opportunity for violation</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Security:</strong> Access controls, monitoring, and system design reduce opportunity regardless of offender motivation</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Practical framework for designing secure systems; shifts focus from policing intent to reducing structural opportunity for violations through architecture and workflow design.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Brantingham and Brantingham (1981), <em>Environmental Criminology</em>. Key
                                    contribution: crime patterns are shaped by environmental and situational opportunity
                                    structures, including place and routine movement.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Criminology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS to study insider threat and unauthorized access as
                                    opportunity-driven).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains misconduct through opportunity contexts, not only
                                    motives.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Opportunity, situational context, environmental conditions, access, guardianship,
                                    target exposure.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Access and situational opportunity create temptation and lower the cost of
                                    misconduct, increasing the chance of incidents even when motivation is constant.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Strongest for situational explanations and incident patterns. Does not fully explain
                                    offender motivation or moral reasoning without combining with other theories.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Opportunity logic appears in MISQ work showing that system access itself increases
                                    unauthorized access attempts, highlighting opportunity beyond motivation.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Environmental criminology developed as a way to explain crime patterns through <mark>place</mark> and
                        <span class="construct-badge">opportunity</span>. <mark>Brantingham and Brantingham (1981)</mark> argue that crime is not randomly distributed. It
                        clusters where opportunities exist. The key idea is that <span class="construct-badge">motivation</span> may be relatively stable,
                        but <span class="construct-badge">opportunity</span> varies across environments, and that variation drives incident patterns. In IS
                        security, this maps well to <mark>insider threats</mark>. An employee may have similar motivation across
                        days, but if they gain <mark>access to sensitive systems</mark> or if <span class="construct-badge">monitoring</span> weakens, the opportunity to
                        offend increases. This is why opportunity-focused theories are attractive in <mark>log-based security
                        research</mark>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Opportunity</span> is a key driver of misconduct, sometimes even more than
                        <span class="construct-badge">motivation</span>. If the environment makes misconduct easy and low-risk, incidents rise.
                    </div>
                    <p>In IS terms, opportunity is created by <mark>access rights</mark>, <mark>weak authentication</mark>, <mark>poor monitoring</mark>, and
                        <mark>transitions</mark> (role changes, mergers). The mechanism is not "people are bad" but that
                        systems can unintentionally create <mark>low-cost paths to misuse</mark>.</p>
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> Strongest for explaining incident patterns and situational risk, but
                        not why a specific person violates norms. For that, need neutralization or deterrence theory.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, environmental criminology and opportunity logic are often used with <mark>routine
                        activity theory</mark>. Routine activity provides three-element structure (offender, target,
                        guardian), while opportunity theory emphasizes that <span class="construct-badge">access</span> and <span class="construct-badge">situational conditions</span> drive
                        attempts even when motivation is constant.</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Strong IS example:</strong> <mark>Wang et al. (2019)</mark> provide empirical
                        evidence using longitudinal data: having <span class="construct-badge">system access</span> itself increases attempts, suggesting opportunity
                        creates temptation. This links theory to <mark>behavioral trace data</mark>, not only surveys.
                    </div>
                    <p>Integration with <mark>complexity theory</mark>: As organizations become more complex,
                        opportunity contexts multiply. Complexity can weaken <span class="construct-badge">guardianship</span> and increase <span class="construct-badge">accidental
                        exposure</span>.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Practical and measurable. Fits log data and guides interventions. Avoids blaming only "bad actors" by showing how <mark>systems create risk</mark>.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Can underplay <span class="construct-badge">agency</span> and <span class="construct-badge">moral reasoning</span>. Can be used deterministically ("if access exists, crime happens"), which oversimplifies.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Using opportunity language without measuring it (access, monitoring, exposure). Ignoring interaction with <mark>motivation</mark> and <mark>rationalization</mark>.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Deterrence for sanctions, Neutralization for moral justification, PMT for threat appraisal. Opportunity best for <mark>situational access</mark> questions.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use note:</strong> Use opportunity theory when the question is about how <span class="construct-badge">environment</span> and <span class="construct-badge">system
                        design</span> create opportunities for misuse, and how changing the situation reduces incidents.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "Does expanding employee access to systems increase unauthorized
                        access attempts, even when employee motivation does not change?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "Increases
                        in <span class="construct-badge">system access privileges</span> are associated with increases in <span class="construct-badge">unauthorized access attempts</span>."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> Access control logs to measure privilege changes and
                        unauthorized access attempts over time. Capture <span class="construct-badge">guardianship measures</span> (monitoring,
                        alerts) and <span class="construct-badge">organizational changes</span> (role transitions, restructuring) to isolate opportunity
                        contexts.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Brantingham, P. J., & Brantingham, P. L. (1981).
                        <em>Environmental criminology</em>. Beverly Hills, CA: Sage.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="protection-motivation-theory-pmt">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Rogers, 1975</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Protection Motivation Theory (PMT)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How threat and efficacy beliefs drive protective behavior and security compliance.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Protection motivation arises from threat appraisal (severity + vulnerability) and coping appraisal (response efficacy + self-efficacy). High threat plus high efficacy beliefs promote protective behavior.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Threat Appraisal:</strong> Severity and vulnerability of threat influence motivation to protect</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Efficacy Appraisal:</strong> Belief that response works and that you can do it both matter equally</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Fear Without Efficacy:</strong> High threat + low efficacy = denial and avoidance, not protection</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Application:</strong> Explains why fear-based security training often fails without capability building</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Fundamental for designing effective security training; reveals why threat-only messaging backfires unless paired with capability-building and accessible protective responses.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Rogers (1975), "A protection motivation theory of fear appeals and attitude change,"
                                    <em>The Journal of Psychology</em>. Key contribution: explains protective behavior
                                    as the result of threat appraisal and coping appraisal.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Psychology (health behavior and fear appeals).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (widely used in IS security and privacy behavior research).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II/IV: PMT explains why people take protective actions and supports prediction
                                    of protection intentions when constructs are measured well.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Threat appraisal (severity, vulnerability, rewards), coping appraisal (response
                                    efficacy, self-efficacy, response costs), protection motivation, protective
                                    behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People protect themselves when they feel the threat is real and serious, and when
                                    they believe the protective action works, they can do it, and the cost is not too
                                    high.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Works best for deliberate protective choices. Less suitable for habitual behavior,
                                    fatigue-driven lapses, or contexts where behavior is constrained by organizational
                                    power and workflow.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>In recent IS security work, PMT-family logic often shows up through fear-appeal and
                                    message-effectiveness studies and through extensions like the Extended Parallel
                                    Process Model (EPPM). Chen et al. (2021) in ISR is a clear example using EPPM in the
                                    security policy compliance context.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>PMT was created to explain why fear appeals sometimes work and sometimes backfire. <mark>Rogers</mark> argues
                        that protective behavior is not driven by fear alone. It depends on two appraisals. <span class="construct-badge">Threat
                        appraisal</span> answers: "How bad is this, and how likely is it to happen to me?" <span class="construct-badge">Coping appraisal</span>
                        answers: "Does the recommended action work, can I do it, and what will it cost me?" <span class="construct-badge">Protection
                        motivation</span> is the intention that comes from these appraisals.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Core proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">threat appraisal</span> + <span class="construct-badge">coping appraisal</span> → <span class="construct-badge">protective action</span>. In IS security,
                        this maps to behaviors like enabling MFA, updating software, using strong passwords.
                    </div>
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> PMT is not a full theory of organizational security behavior.
                        People can intend to protect but fail due to <mark>time pressure</mark>, <mark>depletion</mark>, conflicting
                        incentives, or policy misfit. PMT often needs organizational context theories.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS work extends PMT: adapting to <mark>workplace constraints</mark> and using <mark>fear-appeal message frameworks</mark>.
                        <span class="construct-badge">EPPM</span> (Extended Parallel Process Model) distinguishes <span class="construct-badge">danger control</span> (protective action) from <span class="construct-badge">fear
                        control</span> (defensive avoidance).</p>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>IS example:</strong> <mark>Chen et al. (2021)</mark> use EPPM to explain inconsistent compliance.
                        <strong>Exam move:</strong> Keep mechanisms distinct - PMT is <mark>appraisal-based</mark>, deterrence is <mark>incentive-based</mark>, neutralization is
                        <mark>moral-justification-based</mark>.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Mechanism-focused, easy to operationalize. Produces clear hypotheses. Flexible - can plug in different threats and actions.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Can over-assume <mark>rational appraisal</mark>. Many studies measure <span class="construct-badge">intention</span>, not behavior, then claim protection.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Using PMT as checklist without specifying threat/action, collapsing <span class="construct-badge">self-efficacy</span> and <span class="construct-badge">response efficacy</span>, ignoring organizational constraints.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives:</strong> TTAT (IS-specific), routine activity for exposure, ego depletion for temporal lapses.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use:</strong> Use PMT when question is about why people take (or don't take) <span class="construct-badge">protective
                        actions</span>, especially when <span class="construct-badge">threat perceptions</span> and <span class="construct-badge">coping beliefs</span> are central.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "What drives employees to enable MFA, and when do time costs
                        override perceived risk?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "<span class="construct-badge">Self-efficacy</span> and <span class="construct-badge">response efficacy</span> are
                        positively associated with MFA adoption intentions, while <span class="construct-badge">response cost</span> is negatively
                        associated."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">Threat severity</span> and <span class="construct-badge">vulnerability</span> perceptions, <span class="construct-badge">response efficacy</span> and <span class="construct-badge">self-efficacy</span> for MFA, <span class="construct-badge">response costs</span> (time,
                        friction), plus actual enabling behavior from system logs.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Rogers, R. W.
                        (1975). A protection motivation theory of fear appeals and attitude change. <em>The Journal of
                            Psychology, 91</em>(1), 93-114.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="technology-threat-avoidance-theory-ttat">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Liang & Xue, 2009</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Technology Threat Avoidance Theory (TTAT)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How individuals manage threats to personal data and privacy through technology use decisions.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> When individuals perceive threats (data breaches, surveillance), they decide to use protective technologies. Decision depends on threat level, efficacy of protection, and costs of adoption.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Threat Perception:</strong> Privacy violations and data theft trigger threat avoidance motivation</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Efficacy Judgment:</strong> Protective technology effectiveness and usability affect adoption decisions</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Cost-Benefit Analysis:</strong> Privacy protection tool adoption depends on tradeoffs with convenience</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Relevance:</strong> Explains adoption patterns for VPNs, password managers, encryption, and privacy tools</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Directly applicable to technology adoption for security; shows that privacy protection requires both threat salience and usable, effective technical solutions.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Liang and Xue (2009), "Avoidance of information technology threats: A theoretical
                                    perspective," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: introduces TTAT as an
                                    IS-grounded model of threat avoidance (threat appraisal + safeguard appraisal ->
                                    avoidance motivation -> avoidance behavior). Liang and Xue (2010) provides an early
                                    empirical test in personal computer usage.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (built by adapting PMT-style appraisal logic to IT threat avoidance).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native (with psychology roots).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type IV (explanation and prediction): specifies appraisals that explain and predict
                                    avoidance motivation and avoidance behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Perceived threat (severity, susceptibility), safeguard effectiveness, safeguard
                                    cost, self-efficacy, avoidance motivation, avoidance behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People avoid IT threats when they feel threatened and believe the safeguards work,
                                    are affordable, and doable. Motivation mediates the move from appraisal to behavior.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for user-facing threat avoidance (malware, phishing defenses, safe computing).
                                    Less suited for organizational governance decisions where incentives and power
                                    dominate.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>TTAT is a core behavioral security lens, but in my local reading set I did not
                                    verify multiple 2020-2025 top-outlet papers that use TTAT as the main framing.
                                    (Logged as a limitation in QA. I can add verified 2020-2025 examples with a targeted
                                    search if needed.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>TTAT was created because security behavior in personal computing is not only about "compliance."
                        It is about <span class="construct-badge">avoidance</span>: avoiding risky sites, avoiding unsafe behavior, and using safeguards.
                        <mark>Liang and Xue</mark> propose TTAT as a theory of threat avoidance in personal
                        computer usage. The theory adapts <span class="construct-badge">threat</span> and <span class="construct-badge">coping appraisals</span> into an IS model with clear
                        IT-specific constructs (<span class="construct-badge">safeguard effectiveness</span> and <span class="construct-badge">cost</span>) and a clear motivational mediator
                        (<span class="construct-badge">avoidance motivation</span>).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <div class="key-insight">
                        <strong>Main proposition:</strong> <span class="construct-badge">threat appraisal</span> and <span class="construct-badge">safeguard appraisal</span> jointly drive <span class="construct-badge">avoidance
                        motivation</span>, which then drives <span class="construct-badge">avoidance behavior</span>. Mechanism: <mark>appraisal → motivation → behavior</mark>.
                    </div>
                    <div class="critical-point">
                        <strong>Boundary conditions:</strong> TTAT fits best at <mark>individual level</mark> and for behaviors under user's control. If behavior is constrained by
                        organization policy, time pressure, or workflow, need additional theories.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Positioning TTAT vs PMT:</strong> PMT is a general psychology theory of protection, while TTAT is an <mark>IS-native theory</mark>
                        tailored to technology threats and safeguards.
                    </div>
                    <p>TTAT integrates with <mark>contextual
                        and temporal perspectives</mark>. Even if <span class="construct-badge">threat appraisal</span> is high, <span class="construct-badge">fatigue</span> and <span class="construct-badge">workload</span>
                        can reduce <span class="construct-badge">self-efficacy</span> and increase perceived <span class="construct-badge">cost</span> of safeguards. This is where TTAT can
                        be combined with ego depletion or contextual information processing.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <ul class="theory-list">
                        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Specific to IT threats with clear constructs matching real security interventions. Easy to use for hypothesis testing and designing interventions.</li>
                        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Can be too <mark>individualistic</mark>. Many studies rely on <span class="construct-badge">self-reported intentions</span> rather than observed behavior.</li>
                        <li><strong>Common misapplications:</strong> Treating <span class="construct-badge">avoidance motivation</span> as same as compliance, ignoring actual safeguard constraints, not specifying threat/safeguard clearly.</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternatives:</strong> PMT for broader protection, routine activity for exposure, neutralization for rationalization.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Exam use:</strong> Use TTAT when question is about user <span class="construct-badge">threat avoidance</span> (phishing, malware)
                        and mechanism is about <span class="construct-badge">threat</span> and <span class="construct-badge">safeguard appraisals</span>.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Example research question:</strong> "What
                        drives employees to avoid risky links and use secure browsing tools during high workload
                        periods?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Example hypothesis:</strong> "<span class="construct-badge">Safeguard effectiveness</span> and <span class="construct-badge">self-efficacy</span> are positively
                        associated with <span class="construct-badge">threat avoidance motivation</span>, which is positively associated with <span class="construct-badge">threat
                        avoidance behavior</span>."</p>
                    <div class="mechanism-highlight">
                        <strong>What I would measure:</strong> Perceived <span class="construct-badge">threat severity/susceptibility</span>,
                        perceived <span class="construct-badge">safeguard effectiveness</span> and <span class="construct-badge">cost</span>, <span class="construct-badge">self-efficacy</span>, then behavior from simulations or
                        logs (click-through rates, safe browsing tool usage). Measure <span class="construct-badge">workload</span> to capture
                        boundary conditions.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Seminal APA citation:</strong> Liang, H., & Xue, Y. (2009). Avoidance of information
                        technology threats: A theoretical perspective. <em>MIS Quarterly, 33</em>(1), 71-90.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="institutional-logics">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge organizational">Organizational</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Thornton & Ocasio, 2008</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Institutional Logics</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How competing institutional belief systems shape organizational security practices and compliance.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Organizations contain multiple institutional logics: market logic (efficiency, profit), bureaucratic logic (rules, stability), professional logic (expertise, reputation). These compete and shape IT security decisions.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Competing Logics:</strong> Organizations navigate multiple legitimate but conflicting institutional pressures</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Logic Influence:</strong> Which logic dominates shapes whether security is cost, compliance, or expertise-driven</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Practice Heterogeneity:</strong> Security practices vary across organizations based on dominant institutional logic</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Application:</strong> Explains why similar companies differ in security investment and governance</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains organizational variation in security investment and culture; shows that security effectiveness depends on institutional alignment, not just best practices.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Thornton, Ocasio, and Lounsbury (2012), <em>The Institutional Logics Perspective: A
                                        New Approach to Culture, Structure, and Process</em>. Key contribution:
                                    organizations are shaped by multiple competing logics (market, professional, state,
                                    community, etc).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Sociology and organizational theory (institutionalism).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS to explain value conflicts, power shifts, and heterogeneity in
                                    digital change).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains variation and conflict through competing cultural
                                    logics rather than assuming one institutional environment.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Institutional logics, organizing principles, legitimacy, fields, hybridity, logic
                                    conflict and accommodation.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Different logics define what is legitimate and valuable. Technology can reinforce
                                    one logic, weaken another, or create hybrids, which changes practices and power.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for settings with multiple stakeholder groups and value conflicts (healthcare,
                                    platforms, public sector). Needs careful empirical grounding (you must show the
                                    logics, not just name them).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>MISQ work uses institutional logics to explain how IT affordances shape societal
                                    change and shift power between logics.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Institutional logics grew out of institutional theory, but it focuses more on heterogeneity and
                        conflict. Classic institutional theory often emphasizes isomorphism and convergence.
                        Institutional logics asks: convergence toward what? It argues that society contains multiple
                        logics, each with its own values, norms, and "ways of organizing" (for example, market logic
                        values efficiency and profit, professional logic values expertise and standards, state logic
                        values rules and public interest). Thornton, Ocasio, and Lounsbury (2012) provide the core
                        synthesis of this perspective. Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliations from the
                        original book in my local workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that organizational action is shaped by multiple, sometimes competing
                        logics. Outcomes depend on which logic dominates, how logics conflict, and how actors build
                        hybrids. This is why institutional logics is often used when you want to explain variation and
                        power struggles, not only convergence. The mechanism is meaning and legitimacy. Logics define
                        what counts as legitimate and valuable. When technology is introduced, it can reinforce one
                        logic, weaken another, or enable hybrid practices. That then changes routines, roles, and power
                        because different groups gain or lose legitimacy under different logics. Boundary conditions
                        include empirical grounding. A common reviewer critique is "you named a logic but did not show
                        it." Good institutional logics work must show how the logics are present in discourse,
                        practices, and governance, not only claim they exist.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, institutional logics is often used to study digital transformation in settings with strong
                        value conflict, like healthcare, public sector, platforms, and societal change. It is also
                        frequently combined with technology affordance thinking to show how IT matters in shifting
                        practices and power. Faik et al. (2020) is a strong MISQ example because it uses an
                        affordance-based institutional logics perspective to explain how IT matters in societal change.
                        This is a clean comps example: affordances explain "how IT enables action," and institutional
                        logics explain "why certain actions become legitimate and powerful." Integration with
                        institutional theory is common. In comps answers, the clean contrast is: institutional theory
                        explains convergence through isomorphic pressures; institutional logics explains heterogeneity
                        through competing logics and hybridization.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Institutional logics is useful because it explains conflict and variation. It helps
                        you talk about digital change as a political and cultural shift, not only a technical
                        implementation. It is also a strong lens for studying power and legitimacy in platform and
                        public sector settings. Weaknesses: The theory can become vague if logics are not clearly
                        specified and measured. It also requires rich data and careful interpretation, which can be
                        challenging in purely survey-based studies. Common misapplications in IS: A common misuse is
                        treating logics as just another set of independent variables. Logics are organizing principles,
                        not simple perceptions. Another misuse is mixing institutional logics and institutional theory
                        without clarifying whether you are explaining convergence or conflict. Alternatives and
                        competitors: Stakeholder theory and sensemaking can explain value conflict at different levels.
                        Institutional theory is stronger when the main pattern is convergence and diffusion.
                        Sociomateriality is stronger when the main focus is on practices and entanglement rather than
                        competing organizing principles.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use institutional logics when the question is about conflicts between value
                        systems (professional vs market vs state) shaping digital change in the same field. Example
                        research question: "In healthcare digitalization, how do market logic and professional logic
                        shape whether AI decision support is used as an efficiency tool or as a quality-of-care tool?"
                        Example hypothesis (more like an exam proposition): "When market logic dominates, AI tools will
                        be justified and designed around efficiency and cost, while when professional logic dominates,
                        AI tools will be justified and designed around expertise, standards, and quality of care." What
                        I would measure (simple): In an empirical study, I would operationalize logics through discourse
                        and governance signals (policy language, KPI focus, training standards, leadership messaging)
                        and connect them to design choices and use patterns. A mixed-method design works well here
                        because logics are cultural and institutional, not only individual beliefs. Seminal APA
                        citation: Thornton, P. H., Ocasio, W., & Lounsbury, M. (2012). <em>The institutional logics
                            perspective: A new approach to culture, structure, and process</em>. Oxford, UK: Oxford
                        University Press.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="relational-demography-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge organizational">Organizational</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Pfeffer, 1985</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Relational Demography Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How demographic similarity between individuals shapes trust, information sharing, and collaboration.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> People are more likely to trust, communicate with, and collaborate with others similar to them in demographic attributes (age, gender, race, background). This affects information security and insider threat dynamics.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Demographic Similarity:</strong> Individuals favor and trust demographically similar others</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Trust and Disclosure:</strong> Higher demographic similarity increases information sharing and reduces skepticism</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Insider Threat Dynamics:</strong> Similar-demographic colleagues may have lower suspicion thresholds</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Security:</strong> Affects social engineering success and insider threat vulnerability</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains why social engineering exploits demographic trust; important for understanding how homogeneous teams may increase insider threat risk through demographic-based trust.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Tsui and O'Reilly (1989), relational demography in superior-subordinate dyads. Key
                                    contribution: similarity/dissimilarity between people shapes interaction quality and
                                    outcomes.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Organizational behavior / social psychology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS for trust, teams, and human-robot collaboration).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how demographic similarity affects trust,
                                    communication, and collaboration.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Relational demography (similarity/dissimilarity), ascribed vs achieved attributes,
                                    social categorization, trust, interaction quality.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People tend to trust and coordinate more easily with similar others, partly due to
                                    shared expectations and social categorization. Dissimilarity can create distance and
                                    reduce trust, depending on context.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Effects depend on salience of attributes, diversity climate, task interdependence,
                                    and whether the "other" is human or technology (robots change attribution).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Relational demography is applied in recent MISQ work to explain trust and preference
                                    in working with robots versus humans.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Relational demography theory begins with a simple observation: similarity and difference between
                        people shape how they relate to each other. Tsui and O'Reilly (1989) develop relational
                        demography in superior-subordinate dyads and show that demographic similarity and dissimilarity
                        can influence interaction quality and outcomes. The deeper idea is social categorization: people
                        use visible cues to categorize others, which shapes trust, communication, and perceived fit.
                        Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliations from the original article in my local
                        workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that similarity tends to reduce friction. When people perceive
                        similarity, they often expect shared norms and easier coordination, which can increase trust and
                        cooperation. Dissimilarity can create distance and misinterpretation, which can reduce trust,
                        especially when tasks require close coordination. The mechanism is categorization and
                        expectation. Similarity influences how quickly people form positive expectations and how they
                        interpret ambiguous behavior. In modern IS settings, this mechanism becomes interesting when the
                        "other" is not a human. Robots and AI systems can trigger categorization processes too, but the
                        cues and attributions can be different. Boundary conditions include salience and climate.
                        Similarity effects are stronger when the attribute is salient and when the environment makes
                        difference meaningful (for example, low inclusion climate). In diverse and inclusive contexts,
                        dissimilarity can be less harmful or even beneficial.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, relational demography is increasingly relevant for human-AI and human-robot collaboration
                        because digital coworkers create new similarity questions. People may feel similarity or
                        distance based on personality cues, communication style, voice, or appearance, not only on human
                        demographics. You and Robert (2024) is a strong recent MISQ anchor because it directly applies
                        relational demography theory to preference for robotic over human coworkers. It shows how trust
                        and willingness to work together can depend on perceived similarity, and it provides a clean
                        exam story for why social categorization matters in technology-mediated work. Integration with
                        trust theory is natural. Relational demography can explain why trust forms more easily with some
                        targets than others, while trust theory explains how that trust translates into vulnerability
                        and reliance.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Relational demography gives a simple social mechanism for collaboration and trust. It
                        is especially useful in IS now because digital coworkers make similarity cues designable, which
                        creates interesting research questions about how design shapes coordination. Weaknesses:
                        Similarity is not always good. Homophily can reduce learning and diversity of ideas, and
                        similarity effects can reflect bias. Another limitation is that demographic attributes may be
                        less meaningful in virtual work unless they are made salient. Common misapplications in IS: A
                        common misuse is treating similarity as a control variable instead of a mechanism. Another is
                        using broad demographic categories without measuring whether those categories are actually
                        salient in the interaction. Alternatives and competitors: Social identity theory can be stronger
                        when group belonging is the main mechanism. Trust theory can be stronger when similarity is not
                        the main driver and competence signals dominate. Institutional perspectives can be stronger when
                        collaboration norms are shaped by professional standards rather than dyad similarity.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use relational demography when the question is about similarity and difference
                        between people shaping trust, collaboration, or preferences (including human vs robot
                        coworkers). Example research question: "Do people prefer to work with robots that communicate in
                        a similar style to them, and does that similarity increase trust and reliance?" Example
                        hypothesis: "Greater perceived similarity between a worker and a robot coworker is positively
                        associated with trust in the robot and willingness to collaborate." What I would measure
                        (simple): I would measure perceived similarity (communication style, values, personality cues)
                        and trust using validated scales. Behavioral outcomes can include willingness to accept robot
                        recommendations, delegation decisions, and performance in team tasks. A strong design is an
                        experiment where the robot's communication style is manipulated. Seminal APA citation: Tsui, A.
                        S., & O'Reilly, C. A. (1989). Beyond simple demographic effects: The importance of relational
                        demography in superior-subordinate dyads. <em>Academy of Management Journal, 32</em>(2),
                        402-423.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="emotional-contagion-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Hatfield et al., 1992</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Emotional Contagion Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How emotions spread through groups and affect collective behavior, risk perception, and security response.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Emotions spread automatically through observation and mimicry. Fear of breaches, distrust of management, or urgency of security incidents spread through teams and affect collective compliance behavior.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Emotional Spread:</strong> Emotions transmit through groups via observation and unconscious mimicry</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Collective Effects:</strong> Group-level emotions influence coordination, risk perception, and cohesion</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Context Amplification:</strong> Crises amplify emotional contagion and can override individual judgment</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Application:</strong> Security incidents create fear cascades; culture of paranoia reduces effectiveness</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains how security breaches create organizational panic and compliance spikes; shows that managing emotions collectively improves sustained compliance more than repeated incidents.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Hatfield, Cacioppo, and Rapson (1994), <em>Emotional Contagion</em>. Key
                                    contribution: emotions can spread between people through automatic mimicry and
                                    social feedback.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Social psychology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS to explain emotional dynamics on social media and online
                                    communities).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how emotions propagate through social interaction
                                    and shared attention.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Emotional contagion, mimicry, synchrony, feedback, shared affect, exposure to
                                    emotional signals.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People unconsciously mimic others' expressions and emotional signals, and that
                                    mimicry feeds back into their own feelings. In digital settings, text, emojis, and
                                    visible reactions can play a similar role.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Stronger with repeated exposure, strong ties, and high attention. Online, contagion
                                    depends on visibility and interpretability of signals (tone, emojis, reactions).
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Emotional contagion mechanisms appear in MISQ work on unintended emotional effects
                                    in online health communities and shared emotional reactions to breach events on
                                    social media.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Emotional contagion theory is about how emotions spread. Hatfield, Cacioppo, and Rapson (1994)
                        argue that people can "catch" emotions through automatic mimicry and social feedback. In
                        face-to-face settings, this happens through expressions, posture, tone, and synchrony. In
                        digital settings, the signals change (text tone, emojis, reactions), but the basic logic is
                        similar: repeated exposure to emotional signals can shift your affect. Affiliation note: I did
                        not verify author affiliations from the original book in my local workspace, so I am not listing
                        them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that emotions can transmit through interaction. People subconsciously
                        mimic emotional expressions and that mimicry feeds back into their own feelings. In online
                        contexts, mimicry can be less direct, but social feedback and shared attention can still create
                        emotional waves. The mechanism in digital settings is exposure plus interpretation. Exposure to
                        emotional content raises the accessibility of that emotion, and social signals (likes, comments,
                        supportive replies) make the emotion socially reinforced. This is why contagious effects are
                        often strongest in high-attention events with repeated exposure. Boundary conditions include
                        visibility and tie strength. Contagion is stronger when the emotional signal is clear, when
                        exposure is repeated, and when relationships are strong. Online, contagion also depends on
                        whether the platform makes emotional signals visible and interpretable.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS research uses emotional contagion to explain emotional dynamics on social media and in online
                        communities. The advantage in IS is that many emotional signals are observable in digital traces
                        (text sentiment, reaction patterns), which makes it possible to study contagion at scale. Zhou
                        et al. (2023) is a useful recent MISQ anchor because it studies unintended emotional effects in
                        online health communities. Bachura et al. (2022) is another strong anchor in a very different
                        context: a data breach event and shared emotional reactions on Twitter. Together, these show how
                        emotional contagion can matter in both support communities and crisis events. Emotional
                        contagion also integrates naturally with social comparison. Contagion explains spread, while
                        comparison explains self-evaluation and why a person might interpret an emotional wave as
                        threatening or motivating.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Emotional contagion gives a clear mechanism for why emotions move through networks and
                        why platform design matters for collective mood. It fits modern IS contexts where emotion is
                        visible and amplified through algorithms and engagement features. Weaknesses: In online
                        settings, it can be hard to separate contagion from homophily (similar people connect) and from
                        common exposure (everyone sees the same news). This creates identification challenges. Common
                        misapplications in IS: A common misuse is calling any correlated emotion "contagion" without
                        testing a diffusion mechanism. Another is ignoring platform algorithms, which can create
                        apparent contagion by co-exposure. Alternatives and competitors: Social comparison theory is a
                        strong alternative when the mechanism is self-evaluation. Appraisal theories are useful when the
                        key mechanism is interpretation of events. Sociomateriality can be useful when the main focus is
                        on practices and platform mechanics rather than emotional transmission alone.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use emotional contagion when the question is about emotions spreading through
                        digital networks and shaping collective reactions or engagement. Example research question:
                        "After a public data breach, how do negative emotions spread on social media, and what platform
                        features amplify or dampen that spread?" Example hypothesis: "Higher exposure to
                        negative-emotion posts is associated with higher likelihood of posting negative-emotion content,
                        consistent with contagion dynamics." What I would measure (simple): I would use social media
                        data to measure exposure (feed position, network neighbor posts) and emotional expression
                        (sentiment and emotion classifiers). I would include time and network structure and try to
                        separate contagion from homophily using designs like time-lagged exposure models or natural
                        experiments. Seminal APA citation: Hatfield, E., Cacioppo, J. T., & Rapson, R. L. (1994).
                        <em>Emotional contagion</em>. Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="structuration-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge organizational">Organizational</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Giddens, 1984</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Structuration Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How structures (rules, systems) and human action mutually constitute each other in organizational systems.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Structures do not simply constrain action; people construct and reconstruct structures through action. IT security policies are both constraining and enabling, and their meaning changes through practice.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Duality of Structure:</strong> Structures enable and constrain action simultaneously</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Recursive Relationship:</strong> Structures shape actions, but actions reproduce or transform structures</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Situated Interpretation:</strong> Rules and systems are interpreted and reinterpreted through use</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Implementation:</strong> Security policies succeed only when embedded in organizational practice</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains why IS implementations sometimes fail despite good design; shows that security success requires ongoing co-production of rules and practices, not one-time deployment.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Giddens (1984), <em>The constitution of society</em>. Key contribution: structure
                                    and agency are a duality, not opposites. Structures shape action, but action
                                    reproduces and changes structures.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Key IS adaptations</td>
                                <td>DeSanctis and Poole (1994) develop Adaptive Structuration Theory (AST) for group
                                    technologies; Orlikowski (1992) applies structuration ideas to technology in
                                    organizations.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Sociology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how social structures and human action recursively
                                    shape each other over time.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Structure, agency, duality of structure, rules and resources, enactment,
                                    routinization, institutionalization.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People act using rules and resources (structures). By acting, they reinforce or
                                    change those structures. Technology is part of the resources and routines through
                                    which this happens.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for process and practice questions about how technology and organization
                                    co-evolve. Harder for short cross-sectional prediction questions because the
                                    mechanism is recursive and time-based.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Structuration is often present as a foundational logic inside practice-based IS
                                    theorizing (including sociomateriality and technology-in-practice work), but it is
                                    less common today as an explicit headline theory in top outlets. (Logged as partial
                                    coverage for strict 2020-2025 main-lens examples.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Structuration theory started from a classic social science tension: are people shaped by social
                        structure, or do people shape structure? Giddens argues the two are inseparable. Structures are
                        the rules and resources that make action possible, but they also constrain it. At the same time,
                        structures only exist because people keep enacting them in practice.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The central proposition is recursion: structure -> action -> structure. In organizations, this
                        means routines, norms, and authority structures are not fixed objects. They are continuously
                        produced through everyday work. In IS, the exam move is to show how technology enters this loop.
                        Technology is not only a tool that "impacts" structure. It is part of the resources and routines
                        that people draw on. When people adopt or adapt technology, they can reproduce existing
                        structures (reinforcing control) or transform them (shifting coordination and power). Boundary
                        conditions are important. Structuration is strongest when you can trace sequences of enactment
                        over time (process data). It is weaker for one-shot surveys where you only observe static
                        perceptions.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>DeSanctis and Poole (1994) adapt structuration to group decision support and other advanced
                        information technologies. Their key move is to translate abstract ideas (rules/resources) into
                        technology features and "spirit" (the intended values embedded in the technology). Users
                        appropriate structures in use, sometimes faithfully, sometimes ironically. Orlikowski (1992)
                        uses structuration ideas to argue that technology is both shaped by human action and shapes
                        action. This work is also part of the path that later leads to sociomateriality debates.
                        Integration with sociomateriality is common. A clean way to frame it is: structuration gives you
                        the structure-agency recursion, while sociomateriality pushes further to treat social and
                        material as inseparable in practice.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Structuration gives a strong process mechanism. It helps you avoid naive determinism
                        ("technology causes change") and naive voluntarism ("people choose whatever"). It supports
                        nuanced exam answers about digital transformation. Weaknesses: It can be too abstract. Without
                        careful operationalization, structuration talk can become vague. It also makes prediction
                        difficult because the mechanism is recursive and path-dependent. Common misapplications in IS:
                        Using structuration language as decoration without tracing enactment, or treating structures as
                        static variables in a regression model while claiming structuration. Alternatives and
                        competitors: Sociomateriality for stronger entanglement claims, institutional theory for
                        field-level pressures, and affordance theory for goal-oriented action possibilities.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use structuration when the exam question is about how technology and organization
                        shape each other over time (routines, power, transformation). Example research question: "How
                        does introducing AI decision support reshape decision authority and routines in a professional
                        service firm over time?" Example hypothesis: Structuration is often tested with process claims
                        rather than classic hypotheses. A good exam claim is: "AI decision support will initially be
                        appropriated to reinforce existing authority structures, but over time it can shift routines and
                        redistribute decision rights as practices stabilize." What I would measure (simple):
                        Longitudinal qualitative data (interviews, observation), traces of technology use (override
                        behavior, workflow changes), and documented rule changes (policies, roles). The key is to show
                        enactment and reproduction or change of structures. Seminal APA citation: Giddens, A. (1984).
                        <em>The constitution of society</em>. Berkeley, CA: University of California Press. # Part F.
                        Meta and philosophical frameworks
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="gregors-five-theory-types">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge meta">Meta-Framework</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Gregor, 2006</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Gregor's Five Theory Types</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Taxonomy for evaluating and categorizing different types of IS and social theories.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Gregor distinguishes five theory types: I (description), II (explanation), III (prediction), IV (explanation and prediction), V (design/technology). Knowing a theory's type clarifies what it claims and how to test it.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Type I Description:</strong> Defines and categorizes phenomena without explaining causes</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Type II Explanation:</strong> Explains why phenomena occur without predicting outcomes</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Type IV Prediction:</strong> Explains and predicts outcomes under different conditions</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Meta-Value:</strong> Clarifies what each theory can and cannot answer in research design</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Essential framework for interpreting IS theories; prevents misapplication of descriptive theories to predictive questions and vice versa.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Gregor (2006), "The nature of theory in Information Systems," <em>MIS
                                        Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: a widely used typology of theory types in IS
                                    (Type I to Type V).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (meta-theory about what "theory" means in IS).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>This is a typology, not a theory of a phenomenon. It is best treated as a
                                    meta-theoretical framework for positioning contributions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Type I (analysis), Type II (explanation), Type III (prediction), Type IV
                                    (explanation and prediction), Type V (design and action).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>The "type" depends on the goal of knowledge: describing, explaining, predicting, or
                                    designing. Different research designs and contributions fit different types.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Useful for positioning and evaluating theory contributions in IS. Not a substitute
                                    for a substantive theory of a specific phenomenon.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Still widely cited in top journals when authors position contributions or discuss
                                    what counts as theorizing in IS.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Gregor (2006) wrote this paper because IS scholars often use the word "theory" in inconsistent
                        ways. Some papers call a framework a theory. Some call a list of variables a theory. Some call a
                        design method a theory. That creates confusion in comps answers and in journal reviewing because
                        people argue about "theory" without agreeing on what they mean. Gregor's contribution is a
                        typology that makes the differences explicit. It is also an IS-native move. Gregor is not
                        importing a typology from sociology or psychology. She is writing directly for the IS community
                        and trying to strengthen how we build and evaluate knowledge in the field. Affiliation note: I
                        did not verify author affiliation details from the original MISQ PDF in my local workspace, so I
                        am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>Gregor's core idea is that "theory" is not one thing. The type depends on the goal of the
                        knowledge. Type I (analysis) focuses on describing and classifying. Type II (explanation)
                        focuses on why something happens. Type III (prediction) focuses on what will happen without
                        necessarily explaining why. Type IV combines explanation and prediction. Type V (design and
                        action) focuses on how to build and evaluate an artifact or method that solves a problem. BCIS
                        6670's session 3 StudyGuide adds a very exam-useful detail from Gregor (2006) Table 3: theory
                        has components, and different types include different components. The StudyGuide lists seven
                        components: (1) means of representation, (2) primary constructs, (3) statements of relationship,
                        (4) scope, (5) causal explanations, (6) testable propositions, and (7) prescriptive statements.
                        The key point is that Type I is mainly 1-4, Type II adds 5, Type III adds 6 (often without 5),
                        Type IV includes 1-6, and Type V can include all 7. This is a clean way to defend why a paper is
                        "not predictive" but still theoretical, and it helps you see what is missing when a paper claims
                        a type but does not deliver its components. The same StudyGuide also makes the variance vs
                        process distinction explicit. Variance theories ask how much variance in Y is explained by X and
                        are often tested cross-sectionally. Process theories ask about sequences and unfolding, and they
                        usually need longitudinal evidence. A common comps trap is calling something "process" while
                        testing only variance. This connects directly to Markus and Robey (1988) and is a strong
                        reviewer-like critique move. The mechanism here is not causal in the usual sense because this is
                        a meta framework. The mechanism is about evaluation logic. Different types imply different
                        standards. For example, a Type V contribution should be evaluated by usefulness and rigor of
                        design and evaluation, not by the same criteria as a Type IV variance model. Boundary conditions
                        are important. Gregor's typology helps you position contributions, but it does not replace
                        substantive theory. Calling something "Type IV" does not make it explanatory by itself. You
                        still need constructs, mechanisms, and boundaries.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>Gregor's typology has become a standard reference in IS writing. You see it in conceptual papers,
                        editorials, and design science work where authors want to justify that design knowledge can be
                        theory (Type V). It also shows up when authors position why their paper is not trying to predict
                        but is trying to explain (Type II). In the 2020s, it remains relevant as IS scholars debate what
                        next-generation theorizing should look like. Burton-Jones et al. (2021) call for stronger
                        theorizing and for moving beyond narrow templates, and Gregor's language helps because it
                        reminds us that strong work can take different forms. Gregor also pairs naturally with Whetten
                        (1989). Gregor helps you state what kind of theory you are offering. Whetten helps you check
                        whether your theory is complete (what, how, why, boundaries), regardless of type. In comps
                        answers, using both sounds practical and reviewer-aware, not robotic.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: The typology is simple and very useful. It helps you avoid vague statements like "this
                        paper contributes to theory" and instead say what kind of theory and what standards apply. It
                        also helps you explain why design science and conceptual work are legitimate forms of theorizing
                        in IS. Weaknesses: Because it is widely used, it can become a ritual citation. Some papers label
                        a type but do not actually deliver what that type requires (for example, claiming Type IV but
                        providing no mechanism). Another limitation is that real papers can mix types, so the
                        classification can be debated. Common misapplications in IS: A common misuse is treating the
                        typology as a box-checking exercise. Another is using "Type V" to label any practical guideline,
                        even when there is no design artifact and no evaluation. Alternatives and competitors: Whetten's
                        framework is the closest complement because it focuses on completeness. Other "what theory is"
                        pieces exist in organization studies, but Gregor is the clearest IS-native typology in common
                        use.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use Gregor when the exam question is about positioning your contribution
                        (analysis, explanation, prediction, design, or action) and you need clear language for what your
                        theory does. Example research question: "What type of theory contribution is this paper making,
                        and what should we evaluate it on?" Example hypothesis (Type IV example): "Perceived trust is
                        positively associated with private information disclosure." The point is not the specific
                        hypothesis. The point is that if you claim Type IV, you need both a why story (mechanism) and a
                        testable prediction. What I would measure (simple): If I am positioning a paper, I would
                        identify the constructs and relationships (Whetten's what/how), the mechanism (why), and the
                        boundaries (who/where/when). Then I would say whether the paper is mainly describing (Type I),
                        explaining (Type II), predicting (Type III), explaining and predicting (Type IV), or designing
                        an artifact (Type V). Seminal APA citation: Gregor, S. (2006). The nature of theory in
                        Information Systems. <em>MIS Quarterly, 30</em>(3), 611-642.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="whettens-theory-building-elements">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge meta">Meta-Framework</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Whetten, 1989</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Whetten's Theory Building Elements</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Components necessary for strong theory: what, how, why, and boundary conditions.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Strong theories specify WHAT variables matter, HOW they relate (mechanisms), WHY they relate (underlying logic), and WHERE the theory applies (boundary conditions). Weak theories omit one or more elements.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 WHAT Variables:</strong> Clear specification of constructs and their definitions</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 HOW Mechanisms:</strong> Explicit description of relationships and pathways</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 WHY Logic:</strong> Theoretical reasoning that makes the theory comprehensible and defensible</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Boundary Conditions:</strong> Specification of when theory applies and when it fails</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Practical framework for evaluating and building IS theories; guides what to include in theory development for exam and research questions.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Whetten (1989), "What constitutes a theoretical contribution?," <em>Academy of
                                        Management Review</em>. Key contribution: a complete theory answers What
                                    (constructs), How (relationships), Why (logic), and Who/Where/When (boundaries).
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Management/organization research (theory building guidance).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used widely in IS to evaluate theory sections and contributions).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta-theoretical guidance, not a substantive theory type. It is best treated as a
                                    completeness checklist for any theory.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>What, How, Why, Who/Where/When; theoretical contribution; boundary conditions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Whetten's point is that a diagram is not a theory unless it includes the "why" logic
                                    and clear boundaries.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Applies to building and evaluating theory in most social science fields, including
                                    IS. Not a causal theory of a specific phenomenon.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Recent IS editorials and reflection papers still use Whetten-style logic when
                                    discussing what counts as a strong theoretical contribution.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Whetten (1989) wrote this piece to answer a question reviewers and editors always ask: what
                        counts as a real theoretical contribution? His answer is simple but strict. A theory is more
                        than a list of variables or a diagram. A complete theory should answer four things: What (the
                        key constructs), How (the relationships among them), Why (the logic and mechanism), and
                        Who/Where/When (the boundaries). This paper is not IS-native, but it has become part of IS
                        culture because it matches what top journals expect in theory sections. If your dissertation or
                        comps answer is missing the "why" or the boundaries, Whetten gives you a clear way to diagnose
                        the problem. Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliation details from the original AMR
                        PDF in my local workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The core proposition is completeness. Constructs without relationships are not theory.
                        Relationships without logic are not theory. Logic without boundaries is not convincing theory.
                        Whetten is basically saying: you need a coherent package that tells a reader what matters, how
                        it connects, why it should be true, and where it should or should not hold. The mechanism here
                        is rhetorical and scientific at the same time. A strong "why" story helps readers believe the
                        model is not a coincidence. Boundaries help readers understand what the model is not claiming,
                        which makes the claims more falsifiable and easier to test. Boundary conditions are especially
                        exam-friendly. When you add "who/where/when," you show you can think like a reviewer. You are
                        not only trying to win significance. You are showing conceptual discipline. BCIS 6670's session
                        3 StudyGuide also lists Whetten's 7 key reviewer questions. These are easy to use in a comps
                        answer because they sound like actual editor/reviewer logic, not textbook talk: "What's new?",
                        "So what?", "Why so?", "Well done?", "Done well?", "Why now?", and "Who cares?". If I can answer
                        these cleanly in 1 or 2 sentences each, my theory story is usually in good shape. The same
                        StudyGuide also distinguishes incremental versus radical contributions. Incremental
                        contributions extend or refine existing theory. Radical contributions challenge foundational
                        assumptions. This is a useful link to Sun et al. (2025) because it helps you argue that novelty
                        is not only "new constructs," it can be a deeper reframing of assumptions.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, Whetten is used as a writing and reviewing tool. You often see it in how authors justify
                        the completeness of a theoretical argument, and you see it indirectly in reviewer comments
                        ("what is the mechanism?" "what is the boundary condition?"). Gopal et al. (2024) is a recent
                        top-outlet editorial reflection in <em>Information Systems Research</em> that echoes the same
                        message: strong empirical papers need clear theoretical logic, not only interesting data. That
                        is basically Whetten's point in modern form. Whetten also complements Gregor (2006). Gregor
                        helps you state the type of theory you are aiming for. Whetten helps you make it complete for
                        that type. That combination is a strong comps move because it sounds like you understand both
                        theory and how theory is judged in our field.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Whetten is practical. It gives you a clean checklist to improve theory writing and to
                        diagnose weak theory sections. It also pushes you to include boundaries, which is often what
                        separates a strong comps answer from a generic summary. Weaknesses: If used too mechanically, it
                        can push people toward variance models and away from process theorizing. For example, a process
                        paper may not fit cleanly into "X causes Y" even though it still has a strong why story and
                        boundaries. Common misapplications in IS: A common misuse is writing a long "what" section (many
                        constructs) and a long "how" section (many arrows) but a weak "why" section. Another is ignoring
                        boundaries because the author wants the model to feel universal. Alternatives and competitors:
                        Gregor's typology is complementary, not a competitor. Process theorizing guidance is an
                        alternative when the phenomenon is unfolding and dynamic, but even then, Whetten's "why" and
                        boundaries are still useful.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use Whetten when you need to critique or build a theory and show you can cover
                        what, how, why, and boundary conditions clearly. Example research question: "Is my theory
                        section complete in terms of what, how, why, and boundaries?" Example hypothesis:
                        "Explainability of an AI system increases user trust, which increases willingness to rely on the
                        system." The key point is that a good answer would also explain why (mechanism) and where it
                        holds (boundary conditions). What I would measure (simple): I would define the constructs
                        clearly (what), specify the relationships (how), explain the causal logic (why), and state the
                        boundaries (who/where/when). For example, I might argue the effect is stronger in high-stakes
                        decisions and weaker when use is mandatory. Seminal APA citation: Whetten, D. A. (1989). What
                        constitutes a theoretical contribution? <em>Academy of Management Review, 14</em>(4), 490-495.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="correspondence-theory-process-view">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Popper, 1963</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Correspondence Theory (Process View)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Theory as representation of underlying processes; truth as correspondence between claims and reality.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Theories are statements about how processes work. A theory is true if its claims correspond to actual underlying mechanisms. This view emphasizes identifying real causal processes, not just predictive accuracy.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Representation View:</strong> Theories represent actual underlying processes and mechanisms</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Causality Focus:</strong> Emphasis on discovering true causal processes, not patterns</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Mechanism Specificity:</strong> Good theories identify specific mechanisms, not just associations</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Application:</strong> Drives search for deep mechanisms in security behavior, not surface correlations</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Philosophical framework justifying mechanism-focused IS theories; explains why understanding "how" and "why" matters more than just predicting "what."
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Ingold (2015), process-oriented view of "correspondence" and lines/flows. Key
                                    contribution: shifts focus from static entities to ongoing processes and relations.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Key IS adaptation</td>
                                <td>Mousavi Baygi, Introna, and Hultin (2021), "Everything Flows: Studying Continuous
                                    Socio-Technological Transformation in a Fluid and Dynamic Digital World," <em>MIS
                                        Quarterly</em>.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Anthropology / philosophy of practice (process thinking).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed foundations, applied in IS for continuous transformation.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation) with strong ontological flavor (process ontology).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Process, flow, becoming, correspondence, kairos (timing), attentionality,
                                    undergoing.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Digital transformation is not a sequence of discrete projects. It is continuous
                                    becoming. Researchers should study rhythms, timing, attention, and lived experience
                                    of change as it unfolds.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for continuous, fluid phenomena where "before/after" is misleading. Hard to
                                    convert into cross-sectional hypotheses. Often requires process methods and rich
                                    data.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>MISQ process research explicitly uses this lens to study continuous
                                    sociotechnological transformation.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Correspondence here is not the correspondence theory of truth. It is a process view that comes
                        from anthropology and practice-oriented philosophy. Ingold (2015) argues that we should not
                        treat the world as made of fixed objects with stable properties. We should treat it as made of
                        lines, relations, and ongoing movement. In that view, life is not "being," it is "becoming."
                        This matters for IS because many digital phenomena are not stable. Platforms update
                        continuously, practices evolve, and transformation is ongoing. A process view gives you language
                        to study that without forcing everything into before-and-after snapshots. Affiliation note: I
                        did not verify author affiliation details from the original book in my local workspace, so I am
                        not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that reality is processual. Instead of focusing on static entities, you
                        focus on flow, timing, and relational becoming. This is why key constructs in this lens include
                        kairos (meaningful timing), attentionality (what people attend to), and undergoing (how people
                        experience change as it happens). The mechanism is not "X causes Y" in a simple way. It is about
                        how patterns emerge through ongoing action. Change happens through rhythms, interruptions, and
                        re-alignments. In IS terms, transformation is continuous sociotechnological movement, not a
                        sequence of discrete projects. Boundary conditions are practical. This lens fits continuous,
                        fluid phenomena, but it is hard to translate into cross-sectional hypotheses. It often requires
                        process methods, longitudinal data, and sensitivity to timing and context.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>IS scholars have long studied processes (implementation, change management,
                        technology-in-practice). What is newer in Mousavi Baygi et al. (2021) is the explicit push to
                        treat the digital world as fluid and to adjust our theorizing and methods accordingly. Their
                        argument is that stage models and discrete event logic often miss what transformation looks like
                        in a digital era where change never stops. This lens also integrates naturally with
                        sociomateriality and complexity. Sociomateriality emphasizes entangled practices. Correspondence
                        emphasizes flow and becoming. Complexity emphasizes emergence and coevolution. In comps answers,
                        a good move is to show how these align but also how they differ. For example, sociomateriality
                        is a strong claim about inseparability, while correspondence is a strong claim about process and
                        flow.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: The process view is useful because it matches many modern digital settings. It helps
                        you avoid forcing continuous transformation into artificial stages. It also fits interpretive
                        and qualitative work well because it centers lived experience and timing. Weaknesses: It can be
                        hard to make testable predictions, and some reviewers expect variance models. The language can
                        also feel abstract if the paper does not connect concepts like kairos and attentionality to real
                        data and observable patterns. Common misapplications in IS: A common misuse is using process
                        words ("fluid", "flow") but still studying the phenomenon with a simple before/after design that
                        ignores timing and unfolding. Another misuse is treating process as a slogan instead of an
                        analytic commitment. Alternatives and competitors: Stage models and life-cycle models are
                        alternatives when the phenomenon does have clear phases. Sociomateriality is a related
                        alternative when the main focus is entanglement rather than flow. Complexity theory is a related
                        alternative when the main focus is interdependence and emergence.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use correspondence (process view) when the question is about ongoing becoming and
                        change, and you want to explain digital transformation as a lived process, not a fixed before
                        and after. Example research question: "How does a digital transformation unfold as a continuous
                        process of sociotechnological change rather than as a sequence of projects?" Example hypothesis
                        (better as a proposition here): "Digital transformation in platform organizations unfolds
                        through ongoing reconfiguration and re-attunement, where small events and timing (kairos) shape
                        major shifts in routines." What I would measure (simple): I would use longitudinal data
                        (interviews, observations, digital trace data) and build a process narrative that tracks
                        rhythms, turning points, and reconfigurations. I would look for how attention shifts, how
                        practices change, and how technology features and governance evolve together. Seminal APA
                        citation: Ingold, T. (2015). <em>The life of lines</em>. London, UK: Routledge.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="care-theory-of-dignity">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge behavioral">Behavioral</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Margalit, 1996</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>CARE Theory of Dignity</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Dignity and respect shape compliance, cooperation, and organizational justice perceptions.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> People comply more with rules and authority when they feel respected and trusted. Surveillance, monitoring, and distrust reduce dignity and trigger resistance and violation rather than compliance.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Dignity Perception:</strong> Individuals seek and respond to treatment showing respect and trust</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Compliance Drivers:</strong> High dignity increases voluntary compliance over coercion</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Surveillance Backfire:</strong> Excessive monitoring signals distrust and reduces dignity perception</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Culture:</strong> Security implemented with dignity support builds culture; punitive approach triggers circumvention</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains why punitive security approaches reduce effectiveness; shows that sustainable compliance requires treating employees as trusted professionals, not potential threats.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Leidner and Tona (2021), "The CARE Theory of Dignity Amid Personal Data
                                    Digitalization," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: explains how
                                    digitalization creates dignity claims and affronts, triggering responses to restore
                                    equilibrium.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS-native theory with roots in moral philosophy and dignity scholarship.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II leaning Type IV: explains dignity dynamics and supports predictions about
                                    when responses (regulation, protest, redesign) will emerge.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Claims, Affronts, Response, Equilibrium (CARE); dignity types: behavioral,
                                    meritocratic, inherent.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Personal data digitalization can enhance dignity (claims) and violate dignity
                                    (affronts). When affronts outweigh claims, dignity disequilibrium triggers responses
                                    aimed at restoring equilibrium.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for contexts involving personal data, surveillance, profiling, and AI systems
                                    that affect autonomy, recognition, and human worth. Not designed as a narrow
                                    behavioral intention model.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>CARE is part of a broader top-journal movement toward digital responsibility and
                                    ethical IS theorizing.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>CARE theory was developed because many older IS theories do not cover dignity well. As personal
                        data digitalization expands, people experience both claims (new abilities, recognition,
                        convenience) and affronts (surveillance, loss of autonomy, unfair profiling). Leidner and Tona
                        (2021) argue that IS research needs a mechanism-based theory that explains these dignity
                        dynamics, not only adoption and use. CARE provides that structure through four elements: Claims,
                        Affronts, Response, and Equilibrium. This is also an IS-native contribution. The theory is
                        motivated by moral philosophy and dignity scholarship, but it is written for IS phenomena like
                        datafication, profiling, and AI systems that reshape autonomy and recognition. Affiliation note:
                        I did not verify author affiliation details from the original MISQ PDF in my local workspace, so
                        I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that digitalization creates a dignity balance. Claims are
                        dignity-enhancing aspects of digitalization. Affronts are dignity-violating aspects. When
                        affronts outweigh claims, a dignity disequilibrium occurs and triggers responses aimed at
                        restoring equilibrium. Responses can include individual behaviors (withdrawal, resistance) and
                        collective actions (regulation, activism, redesign). The mechanism is moral and social at the
                        same time. People experience dignity threats as more than inconvenience. They experience them as
                        violations of worth, autonomy, and recognition. That is why responses can be strong and can
                        escalate beyond individual choice into institutional change. Boundary conditions matter. CARE
                        fits best when the phenomenon involves personal data, surveillance, profiling, or algorithmic
                        decision making that affects autonomy and status. It is not designed as a narrow adoption model,
                        and it should not be used as a simple "ethics variable" without tracing claims, affronts, and
                        responses.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>CARE is still new, so the evolution is mostly about how it connects to broader streams. One
                        stream is responsible and ethical AI. Another stream is digital responsibility. Recker et al.
                        (2025) discuss digital responsibility perspectives and future directions, which reflects the
                        broader top-journal movement: IS research is increasingly expected to theorize not only value
                        creation, but also harms and responsibility. CARE is a strong kernel theory in that movement
                        when dignity is the focal harm. Integration with other theories is also exam-friendly.
                        Institutional theory helps you study how responses become formalized as regulation and
                        legitimacy shifts. Sociomateriality helps you study how dignity is enacted in everyday practices
                        with artifacts (logs, interfaces, controls). Delegation helps when the dignity issue comes from
                        authority being shifted to an AI system without accountability.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: CARE addresses an important gap in IS theorizing. It gives you a mechanism to talk
                        about dignity, not only as a value statement but as a dynamic process that produces observable
                        responses. It is also very relevant for comps because ethical and societal impact questions are
                        now common. Weaknesses: Measurement and design are hard. Dignity is deep and multi-dimensional,
                        so simple survey proxies can feel shallow. Another limitation is that the theory can be applied
                        too broadly. Not every negative reaction to technology is a dignity affront. Common
                        misapplications in IS: A common misuse is treating CARE as an "ethics section" and not using it
                        as the main mechanism. Another is labeling something as an affront without specifying which
                        dignity type is threatened (behavioral, meritocratic, inherent) and without showing how
                        responses attempt to restore equilibrium. Alternatives and competitors: Trust theory is useful
                        when the mechanism is vulnerability and reliance rather than dignity. Institutional theory is
                        useful when the main pattern is regulation and legitimacy. Sociomateriality is useful when the
                        main focus is practice-level enactment. CARE is most useful when dignity is the central concept,
                        not an add-on.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use CARE when the question is about how datafication affects dignity, respect, and
                        moral harm, and you need an IS-native lens beyond a basic privacy calculus. Example research
                        question: "When workplaces introduce AI monitoring and profiling tools, how do employees
                        experience dignity claims and affronts, and what responses follow?" Example hypothesis (or
                        proposition): "Greater perceived dignity affronts from AI monitoring are associated with
                        stronger resistance responses (complaints, avoidance, demands for transparency) aimed at
                        restoring dignity equilibrium." What I would measure (simple): I would measure claims and
                        affronts using validated dignity-related items adapted to data practices (autonomy, recognition,
                        fairness), and I would measure responses through a mix of survey and behavior (opt-out rates,
                        grievance reports, policy changes). A strong design would also trace escalation from individual
                        response to institutional response (policy and regulation). Seminal APA citation: Leidner, D.
                        E., & Tona, O. (2021). The CARE Theory of Dignity Amid Personal Data Digitalization. <em>MIS
                            Quarterly, 45</em>(1), 343-370.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="kerlinger-and-lees-theory-of-theory-definition-of-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge meta">Meta-Framework</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Kerlinger & Lee, 2000</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Kerlinger and Lee's Theory of Theory (Definition of Theory)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Definition and standards for what constitutes a scientific theory.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> A scientific theory is a set of related propositions with logical consistency, predictive power, and testability. It distinguishes true theories from ad-hoc explanations, hunches, and frameworks.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Propositional Set:</strong> Theory must be a connected set of claims, not isolated observations</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Logical Consistency:</strong> Propositions must relate logically without internal contradiction</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Testability Requirement:</strong> Theory must generate empirical predictions that can be falsified</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Scientific Standards:</strong> Separates theory from opinion, intuition, and purely descriptive frameworks</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Standards framework ensuring IS theories meet scientific rigor; prevents confusion between true theories and informal explanatory frameworks.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Kerlinger and Lee (2000), <em>Foundations of behavioral research</em>. Key
                                    contribution: a widely cited definition of theory as an interrelated set of
                                    constructs and propositions that explains and predicts phenomena.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Social science methodology / research methods.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta (definition, not a theory of a phenomenon). It is used to clarify what counts
                                    as theory.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Constructs, definitions, propositions, relationships, explanation, prediction.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>A theory is not just a list of variables. It is a connected explanation: what
                                    concepts matter and how they relate.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Useful for evaluating theory quality, not for directly explaining an IS outcome.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>This definition is mostly used in doctoral training and in theory-building debates
                                    rather than as a citation lens inside empirical IS papers. (It is a comps tool, not
                                    a dependent-variable theory.)</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Kerlinger and Lee's contribution is definitional. They provide language that helps you
                        distinguish theory from description. In comps, this definition is useful because it gives you a
                        clean way to critique weak papers: if there are no propositions and no causal story, it may be
                        conceptual labeling, not theory.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main claim is about structure. A theory needs constructs (what), definitions (what the
                        constructs mean), and propositions (how/why). The mechanism is not a causal mechanism of the
                        world. It is a standard for building explanations. Boundary conditions: This definition is
                        helpful, but it is not the only one. Some IS theorizing is process-based and not easily reduced
                        to static propositions. So in exam answers, you can use Kerlinger and Lee to push for clarity
                        without forcing every theory into a variance model.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, this kind of definition supports debates about contribution. It connects naturally to
                        Whetten (what/why/who/where/when) and Gregor's types. Together, they help you position what kind
                        of "theory work" a paper is doing.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: It is simple and powerful. It helps you evaluate whether a paper actually has a
                        theoretical argument or only variables and results. Weaknesses: It can bias you toward variance
                        theorizing and away from process and interpretive theorizing if used rigidly. Common
                        misapplications in IS: Using the definition as a "gatekeeping" tool to dismiss process theories
                        or design theories that do not look like hypothesis models. Alternatives and competitors: Gregor
                        (2006) for theory types and Whetten (1989) for theory-building elements.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use Kerlinger and Lee when the exam question is "what is theory?" or when you need
                        to critique a paper for weak theorizing. Example research question: "What makes an IS paper's
                        theory contribution strong enough for a top journal?" Example hypothesis (or proposition):
                        "Papers that specify constructs and causal mechanisms clearly will be evaluated as stronger
                        contributions than papers that only report significant relationships." What I would measure
                        (simple): I would operationalize theory quality using coding of construct clarity, presence of
                        mechanisms, and boundary conditions, then link that to reviewer outcomes or citation impact.
                        Seminal APA citation: Kerlinger, F. N., & Lee, H. B. (2000). <em>Foundations of behavioral
                            research</em> (4th ed.). Harcourt College Publishers.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="computational-theory-development-ctd">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Grover et al., 2019</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Computational Theory Development (CTD)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Using computational methods and simulation to develop and test theories in complex organizational systems.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Computational models allow theorists to specify complex mechanisms precisely and simulate outcomes. Agent-based models and simulations reveal emergent properties not visible in traditional analysis.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Mechanistic Specification:</strong> Forces explicit specification of mechanisms and parameters</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Emergent Properties:</strong> Simulation reveals system-level outcomes from individual-level rules</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Sensitivity Analysis:</strong> Computational models enable testing how outcomes vary with parameters</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Theory Development:</strong> Identifies mechanisms and boundary conditions more efficiently than empirical cycles</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Modern approach to IS theory development; enables testing complex security and adoption dynamics through simulation before expensive empirical studies.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Berente, Seidel, and Safadi (2019), "Data-driven computationally intensive theory
                                    development," <em>Information Systems Research</em>. Key contribution: a structured
                                    approach for building theory from big, unstructured, digital trace data.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS + computational social science.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native approach (borrows computational methods, but theorizing goals are IS).
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta/theory-building method: it is not a theory of one phenomenon, but a method to
                                    generate Type II/IV theories.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Computational sampling, synchronic analysis, lexical framing, diachronic analysis,
                                    theory iteration.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>You use computation to surface patterns in large data, then you interpret and frame
                                    those patterns into mechanisms, and then you iterate over time to refine theory.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Works best when digital trace data captures meaningful behavior and language. Risks
                                    include spurious patterns, weak construct validity, and overfitting without theory.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Computational theorizing continues to grow in IS, especially in social media,
                                    security analytics, and AI contexts. CTD is a key anchor because it links
                                    computation to theory (not only prediction).</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>CTD is motivated by a real IS tension: we have more data than ever (logs, text, platforms), but
                        data alone does not equal theory. Berente et al. argue that we should not only use big data for
                        prediction. We should use it to build explanations. Their contribution is to outline steps that
                        keep theorizing disciplined when computation is involved.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>CTD is not a causal theory of one phenomenon. Its core proposition is methodological: theory can
                        be built through a disciplined loop that combines computational pattern finding with human
                        interpretation and framing. The mechanism is the loop itself: computational discovery helps you
                        see patterns you would miss, and theorizing helps you avoid meaningless correlations. Boundary
                        conditions matter. If you only optimize predictive accuracy, you can miss mechanisms. If you
                        only interpret without rigorous computation, you can miss scale and structure. CTD argues you
                        need both.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, CTD fits well with platform and social media studies where the data is large and
                        language-rich. It also fits security analytics (attack narratives, dark web text) and AI work
                        where trace data reveals use patterns and breakdowns. CTD also connects to classic grounded
                        theory logic in a modern way. It keeps the "constant comparison" spirit, but it adds
                        computational support to handle scale.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: CTD is a strong answer when the exam question is about "how do we build theory from
                        big data?" It gives a clear workflow and it keeps theory, not only prediction, at the center.
                        Weaknesses: Construct validity is a major risk. Just because an algorithm clusters text does not
                        mean the clusters map to real constructs. Another risk is confirmation bias: researchers may
                        frame patterns to fit what they already believe. Common misapplications in IS: Treating
                        computational outputs as theory, and skipping the step of articulating mechanisms and boundary
                        conditions. Alternatives and competitors: Grounded theory (manual qualitative theorizing),
                        deductive theorizing with large datasets (econometrics), and design science when the goal is
                        building artifacts rather than explaining.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use CTD when the exam question involves theory building from digital trace data
                        (social media, logs, AI usage) and you need a credible "how" story. Example research question:
                        "How do professionals change their work routines when GenAI tools enter the workflow, based on
                        large-scale trace data?" Example hypothesis (or proposition): "Trace data will reveal distinct
                        routinization patterns that can be framed as different appropriation mechanisms (reinforcement
                        vs transformation) over time." What I would measure (simple): System logs of tool usage over
                        time, text artifacts (prompts, outputs), and contextual metadata (role, task type). Then use CTD
                        steps to build a mechanism-based model from observed patterns. Seminal APA citation: Berente,
                        N., Seidel, S., & Safadi, H. (2019). Data-driven computationally intensive theory development.
                        <em>Information Systems Research, 30</em>(1), 50-64.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="construct-obsolescence-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge meta">Meta-Framework</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Benbasat & Zmud, 1999</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Construct Obsolescence Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Framework for identifying when constructs become outdated as technology and practice evolve.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Constructs and measures used in older theories may become obsolete as technology changes. IT acceptance theories developed for desktop IT may not apply to mobile, cloud, or social technologies.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Technology Evolution:</strong> Rapid IT change can render theory constructs outdated quickly</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Context Dependency:</strong> Constructs valid for one era may lose relevance in new contexts</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Continuous Updating:</strong> Theories require updating as technology capabilities and use contexts change</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Critique:</strong> Critical lens for examining when theories need modernization</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Important caution for exam; reminds that older theories may have limited applicability to contemporary technologies like cloud, mobile, and AI-based security.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Compeau, Correia, and Thatcher (2022), "When constructs become obsolete," <em>MIS
                                        Quarterly</em>. Key contribution: argues that IS constructs can become outdated
                                    as technology and context evolve, and proposes a systematic updating approach.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (measurement and theorizing).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta/theory-building: it is a theory about construct validity over time, guiding how
                                    to keep explanation/prediction theories meaningful.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Construct obsolescence, construct domain, updating cycle (review, revise, validate).
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When technology changes, what a construct refers to can drift. If we keep using old
                                    measures, we measure the wrong thing and our theories become misleading.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Most relevant for fast-changing digital contexts (AI, platforms). Less urgent for
                                    stable phenomena.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Compeau et al. (2022) is itself a top-outlet proof-of-life and a clear response to
                                    the problem of outdated constructs in modern IS research.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>The construct obsolescence argument starts from an uncomfortable reality: IS studies often reuse
                        classic constructs and scales for decades, even when technologies and practices change. Compeau
                        et al. argue that this can quietly damage theory because the construct meaning drifts while the
                        scale stays fixed. Their contribution is to define the problem and propose a process for
                        updating constructs responsibly.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The core proposition is that construct validity is time-sensitive in IS. Technology changes can
                        change the construct domain. If the domain changes, the old measure may no longer represent the
                        construct. The mechanism is domain drift. That drift creates measurement error and can flip
                        relationships. Boundary conditions: Not every construct becomes obsolete. Some human traits and
                        broad organizational concepts are more stable. The key is to diagnose obsolescence rather than
                        assume it.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>This theory is already IS-specific. The extension work is how it will be used: researchers can
                        apply it to update constructs like "computer self-efficacy" into "IT self-efficacy" or to update
                        "use" constructs in a world of AI delegation and automation. It also connects to Gregor and
                        Whetten: if a theory's constructs are obsolete, the whole explanation chain weakens, no matter
                        how good the statistical model looks.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: It directly addresses a major reviewer concern in modern IS: relevance and validity in
                        fast-changing contexts. It gives a method to defend updated constructs instead of doing ad hoc
                        scale edits. Weaknesses: Updating constructs can harm comparability with prior research. Also,
                        the process requires careful work and can be resource intensive. Common misapplications in IS:
                        Treating "new tech" as automatic obsolescence, or making superficial wording updates without
                        re-validating the construct domain. Alternatives and competitors: Classic construct validation
                        frameworks and careful boundary condition specification. Construct obsolescence is an
                        IS-specific reminder, not a replacement for validity work.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use construct obsolescence when the exam question is about measurement validity
                        over time, or when you need to justify updating a classic scale for a new technology context.
                        Example research question: "Is 'perceived usefulness' still the same construct when the IT
                        artifact is a GenAI agent that acts autonomously?" Example hypothesis (or proposition): "As IT
                        becomes more agentic, classic usefulness items will capture only part of the construct domain,
                        and updated items about responsibility and control will improve validity." What I would measure
                        (simple): Content validity via expert panels, exploratory and confirmatory factor analysis with
                        new items, and tests of measurement invariance across tech contexts. Seminal APA citation:
                        Compeau, D., Correia, J., & Thatcher, J. B. (2022). When constructs become obsolete: A
                        systematic approach to evaluating and updating constructs for information systems research.
                        <em>MIS Quarterly, 46</em>(2), 679-711.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="consistency-motif-theory-common-method-bias">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge psychology">Psychology</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Heider, 1958</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Consistency Motif Theory (Common Method Bias)</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Tendency to maintain consistency between beliefs, attitudes, and behaviors; relevance to common method bias.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> People strive for cognitive consistency. If asked about security attitudes, they provide consistent responses. If behaviors contradict stated attitudes, they adjust either behavior or attitude reports to reduce dissonance.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Consistency Seeking:</strong> People maintain alignment between beliefs, attitudes, and reported behavior</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Response Consistency:</strong> Respondents provide correlated responses to maintain consistency in surveys</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Common Method Bias:</strong> Inflated correlations among self-report measures due to consistency seeking</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Measurement Implication:</strong> Mix objective and subjective measures to avoid consistency artifacts</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains significant portion of common method bias; shows why self-reported security attitudes and behaviors appear more correlated than actual behavior would suggest.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Podsakoff, MacKenzie, Lee, and Podsakoff (2003) discuss the "consistency motif" as a
                                    key source of common method variance in self-report surveys. Key contribution:
                                    explains why respondents try to appear consistent across answers, inflating
                                    correlations.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Organizational behavior / methods (survey research).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS methods discussions).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Meta (measurement validity issue, not a phenomenon theory).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Consistency motif, common method variance, item context effects, response styles.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>When people answer a survey, they may try to keep their answers consistent, even if
                                    reality is more mixed. This creates artificial correlations across constructs
                                    measured in the same survey.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Most relevant when key variables are self-reported in a single survey at one time.
                                    Less relevant when outcomes are trace data or when multiple sources are used.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Like negative affectivity, this is mainly a validity concern rather than a core IS
                                    theory lens. It remains relevant because IS still uses many surveys, but it is
                                    rarely a "main theory" citation in top journals.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>The consistency motif was introduced to explain a common survey pattern: correlations can be
                        inflated because of how the data was collected, not because constructs are truly related.
                        Respondents may want to look rational and consistent. They may also infer "what the researcher
                        wants" and answer accordingly.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The core proposition is methodological: measurement method can create shared variance. The
                        mechanism is response consistency. If a respondent says "I like this system" early, they may
                        answer later items in a way that matches that stance, including items about usefulness,
                        satisfaction, and intention.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, this becomes a comps and reviewer point. When a study uses one survey to measure all
                        predictors and outcomes, you should discuss common method bias threats and what the authors did
                        to reduce them (time separation, multiple sources, marker variables).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: It gives a clear alternative explanation for survey findings. It improves the quality
                        of theory testing by forcing better designs. Weaknesses: It can be over-invoked. Some
                        researchers treat it as a universal critique even when designs reduce the risk. Common
                        misapplications in IS: Using Harman's single-factor test as the only remedy, or claiming "no
                        CMB" without serious evidence. Alternatives and competitors: Better research design is the best
                        alternative: use trace data, experiments, multiple respondents, or time-lagged measurement.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use consistency motif when the exam question is about survey validity, common
                        method bias, and how to defend or critique causal claims from self-reports. Example research
                        question: "Are reported relationships between perceived usefulness and satisfaction partly
                        driven by survey response consistency?" Example hypothesis (method concern): "Single-survey
                        designs will show stronger correlations between perceptual constructs than multi-source designs,
                        consistent with consistency motif effects." What I would measure (simple): Compare effect sizes
                        across designs (single-source vs multi-source), use time separation, and incorporate objective
                        measures (usage logs) to validate. Seminal APA citation: Podsakoff, P. M., MacKenzie, S. B.,
                        Lee, J.-Y., & Podsakoff, N. P. (2003). Common method biases in behavioral research: A critical
                        review of the literature and recommended remedies. <em>Journal of Applied Psychology,
                            88</em>(5), 879-903. # Part G. Systems and design theories</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="systems-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge organizational">Organizational</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">von Bertalanffy, 1968</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Systems Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Framework for understanding complex systems with interdependent components, feedback loops, and emergent properties.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Systems have boundaries, inputs, processes, outputs, and feedback. Security systems involve technical controls, human practices, and organizational structures in continuous interaction and adaptation.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 System Interdependence:</strong> Security success depends on alignment across technical, human, and organizational levels</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Feedback Loops:</strong> Incidents create feedback that should reshape policies, training, and systems</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Emergent Properties:</strong> System-level security emerges from component interactions, not component effectiveness alone</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Holistic View:</strong> Security requires managing whole system, not optimizing individual components</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Essential framework for understanding organizational security as complex system; explains why technical fixes alone fail without complementary human and organizational changes.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>von Bertalanffy (1968), <em>General System Theory: Foundations, Development,
                                        Applications</em>. Key contribution: systems have properties that arise from
                                    interactions among parts; open systems exchange energy/information with
                                    environments.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Systems science / biology (general systems theory), later used in management and
                                    engineering.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used broadly across IS and complexity thinking).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains whole-system properties and interdependence; often
                                    used as an overarching perspective.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>System, boundary, environment, inputs/outputs, feedback, interdependence, open
                                    systems, equifinality.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>The whole is not reducible to isolated parts. Feedback and interdependence create
                                    system-level outcomes, so interventions must consider the full system.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for phenomena where interactions matter (sociotechnical systems, platforms, AI
                                    ecosystems). Less useful when the phenomenon is decomposable and linear.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Systems thinking appears in recent IS work treating generative AI as a
                                    sociotechnical system with system-level properties and societal impacts.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>General systems theory was proposed as a way to find common principles across different domains
                        (biology, engineering, organizations). von Bertalanffy (1968) argues that many phenomena are
                        better understood as open systems. Systems exchange energy, information, and resources with
                        environments, and system behavior depends on feedback and interdependence. The big idea is that
                        reductionism often fails because studying parts in isolation misses system-level properties. IS
                        is a natural home for systems thinking because information systems are sociotechnical. They
                        combine technical components, human behavior, organizational routines, and institutional
                        environments. Systems theory provides language to talk about that whole without pretending the
                        technical and the social can be separated cleanly. Affiliation note: I did not verify author
                        affiliation details from the original book in my local workspace, so I am not listing them here
                        (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that system outcomes emerge from interactions and feedback among parts.
                        That means interventions can have unintended effects because changing one part changes the
                        conditions for other parts. Concepts like boundaries, environment, inputs/outputs, and feedback
                        help you define what system you are talking about and what counts as inside versus outside. The
                        mechanism is interdependence. When components are connected, actions in one component influence
                        others. Feedback loops can amplify change (positive feedback) or stabilize it (negative
                        feedback). Equifinality is also important: different initial conditions can lead to similar
                        outcomes, which is a useful way to explain why the same digital tool can lead to different paths
                        in different organizations but still converge to similar performance levels. Boundary conditions
                        are basically about specificity. Systems theory is broad and can become vague if you do not
                        specify the system boundaries, key feedback loops, and the level of analysis. It is strongest
                        when you can point to concrete interdependence, not when you use "system" as a synonym for
                        "everything."</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, systems thinking appears in many areas: enterprise systems, platform ecosystems, digital
                        resilience, and now AI. It often sits behind concepts like "sociotechnical systems" and
                        "ecosystems," even when authors do not cite Bertalanffy directly. Storey et al. (2025) is a good
                        recent anchor because it frames generative AI as an evolving technology with broad societal
                        impact and research opportunities. That is a systems move: it treats the phenomenon as connected
                        to many parts (work, ethics, governance, society) rather than as one tool feature. Benbya et al.
                        (2020) also reinforces this systems view by emphasizing interdependence and emergence in the
                        digital world. Integration with complexity and chaos theory is common. In comps answers, you can
                        say: systems theory gives the holistic view and boundary language; complexity adds emergence and
                        adaptation; chaos adds sensitive dependence and long-run unpredictability.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Systems theory is useful because it fits the reality of IS. Most IS outcomes are not
                        caused by one variable. They come from interactions among technology, people, routines, and
                        environment. Systems thinking helps you design better interventions by anticipating feedback and
                        unintended consequences. Weaknesses: The biggest weakness is vagueness. If you do not specify
                        boundaries and mechanisms, systems thinking can become a slogan. Another limitation is that it
                        often does not give precise predictions, so it needs to be paired with more specific mechanisms
                        for hypothesis testing. Common misapplications in IS: A common misuse is saying "this is a
                        system" and then still running a simple linear model without addressing interdependence. Another
                        is using systems language without identifying feedback loops or system boundaries. Alternatives
                        and competitors: When you need precise behavioral prediction, acceptance and trust models can be
                        more direct. When you need explanation of legitimacy and regulation, institutional theory can be
                        more direct. Systems thinking is best when interaction and feedback are central.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use systems theory when the question is about a whole sociotechnical system with
                        feedback loops and unintended consequences, not isolated variables. Example research question:
                        "When organizations adopt generative AI assistants, what system-level feedback loops create
                        unintended consequences for work quality and accountability?" Example hypothesis: "Greater
                        reliance on AI-generated output increases short-term productivity but also increases the need
                        for new accountability routines (monitoring, auditing), which changes work practices over time."
                        What I would measure (simple): I would measure reliance through usage logs, measure productivity
                        through output metrics, and measure accountability routines through audit log usage and policy
                        changes. I would look for feedback patterns (incidents leading to new controls leading to new
                        workarounds) rather than only one-time effects. Seminal APA citation: von Bertalanffy, L.
                        (1968). <em>General system theory: Foundations, development, applications</em>. New York, NY:
                        George Braziller.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="theory-of-hierarchical-systems">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge organizational">Organizational</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Simon, 1962</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Theory of Hierarchical Systems</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How hierarchical decomposition enables management of complex systems while preserving emergent behavior.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Complex systems are often hierarchical and nearly decomposable, which explains why we can study subsystems but still get emergent behavior. Hierarchy lets you manage complexity by breaking systems into parts, but interdependencies create system-level outcomes.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Hierarchical Structure:</strong> Complex systems benefit from hierarchical organization and decomposition</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Near Decomposability:</strong> Subsystems can be studied somewhat independently but retain interdependencies</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Complexity Management:</strong> Hierarchy enables coordination and predictability in complex systems</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Architecture:</strong> Explains how IT systems are designed with layers while maintaining security and functionality</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Essential for understanding IT system complexity management and why security must operate across multiple hierarchical levels of IT architecture.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Simon (1962), "The architecture of complexity," <em>Proceedings of the American
                                        Philosophical Society</em>. Key contribution: complex systems are often
                                    hierarchical and nearly decomposable, which explains why we can study subsystems but
                                    still get emergent behavior.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Systems science / organizational theory / cognitive science.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains why hierarchy and decomposition shape complexity,
                                    coordination, and predictability.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Hierarchy, subsystems, near decomposability, interdependence, emergent behavior.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Hierarchy lets you manage complexity by breaking systems into parts, but
                                    interdependencies across parts still create system-level outcomes.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Works best when systems are at least partly decomposable. Less helpful when coupling
                                    is extreme and decomposition fails (highly entangled systems).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>In MISQ design science research, Tuunanen et al. (2024) use a "design echelons" idea
                                    to handle complexity in DSR planning and knowledge contributions, which is a
                                    hierarchical-systems logic applied to IS research practice.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Simon wrote about complexity because many systems are too complicated to understand as a whole.
                        His key insight is that hierarchical systems are common in nature and organizations. Hierarchies
                        allow near decomposability: subsystems can be studied somewhat independently, even though
                        interactions still matter.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that hierarchy is a structural solution to complexity. It reduces
                        coordination demands within a level, but cross-level interactions still create emergence. The
                        mechanism is decomposition plus constrained interaction. In IS, this matters because
                        organizations and digital systems are layered (infrastructure, applications, processes, teams,
                        ecosystems). A hierarchical lens helps you explain why local optimization can still produce
                        global failures and why governance often needs multi-level coordination.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS research practice, Tuunanen et al. (2024) show a strong application: design echelons help
                        plan and communicate DSR contributions under complexity. This is a nice exam example because it
                        uses a hierarchical logic to solve an IS research problem, not only an organizational one. This
                        theory also connects to holons and information ecology. Holons are nested whole/part units, and
                        information ecology studies ecosystem integration mechanisms. These are different labels for
                        related multi-level thinking.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: It gives a simple structure for thinking about complex systems: levels, subsystems,
                        and cross-level interactions. It helps in both theorizing and design (how to structure
                        interventions). Weaknesses: It can tempt you to assume systems are neatly decomposable when they
                        are not. Many digital systems are deeply interconnected, and decomposition can hide critical
                        dependencies. Common misapplications in IS: Treating hierarchy as only an org chart issue,
                        ignoring technical interdependencies, and assuming that decomposing a system automatically
                        reduces risk. Alternatives and competitors: Complexity science for adaptation and coevolution,
                        sociomateriality for entanglement in practice, and modularity theory for interface-based
                        decomposition.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use hierarchical systems when the exam question is about managing complexity
                        across levels (enterprise systems, DSR complexity, multi-unit cybersecurity). Example research
                        question: "How can IS design teams structure their work to manage complexity in building and
                        scaling a digital platform?" Example hypothesis (or proposition): "Using a hierarchical design
                        approach (echelons) improves coordination and reduces rework by clarifying which decisions
                        belong at which level." What I would measure (simple): Rework rates, coordination load
                        (meetings, dependencies), and clarity of design decisions across levels. For DSR, I would also
                        code the clarity of communicated design knowledge contributions. Seminal APA citation: Simon, H.
                        A. (1962). The architecture of complexity. <em>Proceedings of the American Philosophical
                            Society, 106</em>(6), 467-482.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="chaos-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Lorenz, 1963</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Chaos Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Deterministic nonlinear systems exhibit sensitive dependence on initial conditions and unpredictability.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Small differences in initial conditions can lead to large differences in outcomes over time. This makes long-term prediction difficult even when the system rules are known. Applies to nonlinear systems with feedback.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Sensitive Dependence:</strong> Tiny initial condition differences produce vastly different outcomes</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Nonlinearity Effects:</strong> Nonlinear systems cannot be predicted by linear extrapolation</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Deterministic Chaos:</strong> Unpredictability does not mean randomness; system follows rules but outcomes are unpredictable</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Implication:</strong> Explains inherent unpredictability in large IT systems and cyber attacks despite deterministic rules</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Justifies focus on resilience and adaptation rather than perfect prediction in IT security and complex digital systems.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Lorenz (1963), "Deterministic nonperiodic flow," <em>Journal of the Atmospheric
                                        Sciences</em>. Key contribution: shows how deterministic nonlinear systems can
                                    produce unpredictable behavior (sensitive dependence on initial conditions).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Mathematics/physics (nonlinear dynamics), meteorology.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS as part of complexity science to explain unpredictability in
                                    digital systems).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains why prediction is hard even with deterministic rules
                                    when systems are nonlinear and sensitive.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Nonlinearity, sensitive dependence on initial conditions, attractors,
                                    unpredictability, deterministic chaos.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Small differences in starting conditions can lead to large differences in outcomes
                                    over time. This makes long-term prediction difficult even when the system rules are
                                    known.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Applies to nonlinear dynamical systems with feedback. It is not a synonym for
                                    randomness. Also, "chaos" should not be used as a casual metaphor without specifying
                                    dynamics.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Chaos concepts show up in MISQ complexity work as part of explaining
                                    unpredictability in the digital world and in cybersecurity complexity discussions.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Chaos theory grew from attempts to model complex physical systems. Lorenz (1963) found that
                        simple deterministic equations could produce irregular, non-repeating patterns, and that tiny
                        differences in initial conditions led to very different trajectories. This is the classic
                        "butterfly effect" idea: small inputs can cascade into large outcomes through nonlinear
                        dynamics. In IS, chaos theory is rarely used alone. It usually appears as part of complexity
                        science, reminding researchers that even with strong models, prediction can be limited when
                        feedback loops and interdependence create sensitive dynamics.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The core proposition is sensitive dependence. In a chaotic system, you can know the governing
                        rules, but you cannot predict the long-run state because small errors in initial conditions grow
                        quickly. The mechanism is nonlinear feedback. The system can look random, but it is
                        deterministic, which is a subtle but important exam nuance. Boundary conditions: Not all complex
                        systems are chaotic. Chaos is a specific type of behavior. Also, chaos does not mean "anything
                        can happen". Chaotic systems can have structure, like attractors, but they still resist precise
                        long-term prediction.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, chaos theory mainly appears in the context of complexity science. Benbya et al. (2020)
                        include chaos as one of the key concepts for understanding the emerging digital world, where
                        platforms, ecosystems, and AI systems can produce unexpected outcomes through interaction and
                        feedback. Cybersecurity is another area where chaos-like dynamics are plausible: small
                        configuration changes can create large vulnerabilities, and the attack-defense interaction can
                        create nonlinear escalation patterns. Schneier and Vance (2025) highlight how complexity becomes
                        the enemy of security, which connects to the idea that predictability declines as systems become
                        more interconnected and dynamic.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Chaos theory gives a clear reason why prediction can fail even when systems are
                        deterministic. It supports a more realistic view of digital systems where small events can have
                        big effects. Weaknesses: In IS, chaos is often misused as a metaphor for "messy". Without
                        specifying dynamics, "chaos" adds little. Also, chaos theory by itself does not tell you what to
                        do; it needs to be connected to governance and design decisions. Common misapplications in IS:
                        The most common misuse is labeling a phenomenon as chaotic without showing nonlinearity,
                        feedback, or sensitivity. Another is treating chaos as randomness, which misses the core
                        theoretical point. Alternatives and competitors: Complexity science offers a broader toolkit for
                        emergence and coevolution. Systems theory offers a holistic view without requiring chaotic
                        dynamics. Contingency theories offer more practical fit-based explanations when the main issue
                        is alignment rather than unpredictability.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use chaos theory when the question is about nonlinear dynamics where small changes
                        can trigger big outcomes and prediction is limited, especially in digital risk and crises.
                        Example research question: "Do small configuration changes in enterprise systems create
                        disproportionate changes in security incident risk over time?" Example hypothesis: "Small
                        increases in system interdependence lead to nonlinear increases in incident risk, consistent
                        with sensitive dependence and feedback dynamics." What I would measure (simple): I would track
                        configuration changes, dependency graphs, and incident logs over time. I would look for
                        nonlinear relationships and feedback (incidents leading to patches leading to new
                        vulnerabilities). The exam point is to show you would not just say "chaos", you would test for
                        nonlinear dynamics. Seminal APA citation: Lorenz, E. N. (1963). Deterministic nonperiodic flow.
                        <em>Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 20</em>(2), 130-141.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="theory-of-digital-objects">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge is-native">IS-Native</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Kallinikos et al., 2013</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Theory of Digital Objects</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Digital objects have distinctive properties: malleability, agency, and dependencies that shape their use and control.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Digital objects are malleable (easy to copy, modify, distribute), exhibit agency through algorithms, and create dependencies across systems. These properties change how information is valued, controlled, and secured.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Malleability:</strong> Digital objects can be endlessly copied, modified, and distributed without degradation</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Algorithmic Agency:</strong> Digital objects embed logic that acts autonomously through systems</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Systemic Dependencies:</strong> Digital objects create tight coupling and dependencies across systems</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Security Challenge:</strong> Malleability enables rapid spread of malware and unauthorized access</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains unique security challenges of digital systems compared to physical systems; justifies why traditional security approaches inadequate for data protection.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>In my course reading set, Jussupow, Benbasat, and Heinzl (2024) provide a modern
                                    MISQ anchor for thinking about the nature of digital artifacts (and why people react
                                    differently to algorithms depending on how the digital object is experienced).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS / digital artifact theory (informed by organization and technology studies).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native direction (built for digital artifacts).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains why perceptions and behavior differ depending on how
                                    a digital object is encountered and interpreted.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Digital object, algorithmic core, interface/embodiment, interpretability, perceived
                                    agency.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>People do not respond to "the algorithm" in the abstract. They respond to the
                                    digital object as it is presented and experienced (outputs, explanations, UI cues).
                                    That changes trust, aversion, and reliance.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for human-AI and algorithmic decision contexts. Less relevant when the IT
                                    artifact is simple and fully transparent.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Jussupow et al. (2024) is itself a top-outlet proof-of-life anchor, and it connects
                                    directly to current IS debates about algorithm aversion, appreciation, and
                                    explainability.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>"Digital object" thinking grows from a basic IS problem: we often talk about IT artifacts as if
                        they are stable, simple objects. But many modern artifacts are layered and opaque. An AI system
                        can be a model, a service, a UI, and a set of governance choices at the same time. This makes
                        user reactions harder to explain with older "tool" assumptions.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The core proposition is that the nature of the digital object matters for perception and
                        behavior. If the object looks like a black box, people may distrust it or resist relying on it
                        even when it performs well. If the object provides interpretable cues and fits existing
                        routines, people may appreciate and rely on it more. The mechanism is interpretation and
                        perceived agency. People ask, "Is this thing acting on its own?" and "Can I understand or
                        control it?" Those perceptions shape reliance and delegation decisions.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>This area connects strongly to explainable AI work and to delegation. Asatiani et al. (2020)
                        discuss challenges of explaining black-box AI, which is part of the same puzzle: digital objects
                        can be hard to interpret and justify. Delegation theory then asks what happens when we shift
                        authority to such objects.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: This lens is very current. It helps you explain why AI adoption is not only usefulness
                        and ease, but also interpretability, accountability, and perceived agency. Weaknesses: The
                        concept can become fuzzy if you do not specify which layer of the digital object is driving the
                        effect (model, UI, explanation, governance). It also overlaps with sociomateriality and
                        affordances, so you need clear boundaries. Common misapplications in IS: Using "digital object"
                        language without linking it to measurable perceptions (control, transparency) or observable
                        behaviors (reliance, overrides). Alternatives and competitors: Trust theory for vulnerability
                        and reliance, sociomateriality for practice entanglement, and affordance theory for action
                        possibilities.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use digital objects when the exam question is about how the nature of AI artifacts
                        (black box vs interpretable object) shapes trust, reliance, and resistance. Example research
                        question: "How does providing explanations change reliance on algorithmic recommendations in
                        high-stakes decisions?" Example hypothesis: "Greater perceived interpretability of an AI
                        decision-support object is positively associated with reliance, mediated by reduced algorithm
                        aversion." What I would measure (simple): Interpretability perceptions, trust, reliance
                        (override rates), and task outcomes. I would also measure whether explanations are actually
                        used, not only provided. Seminal APA citation: Jussupow, E., Benbasat, I., & Heinzl, A. (2024).
                        An integrative perspective on algorithm aversion and appreciation in decision-making. <em>MIS
                            Quarterly, 48</em>(4), 1575-1590.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="information-ecology-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge organizational">Organizational</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Davenport & Prusak, 1997</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Information Ecology Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Information systems are ecological systems with interdependent species, habitats, and evolutionary dynamics.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Information ecology treats information systems as ecosystems where different stakeholder groups (species) interact, compete, and co-evolve. Health of ecology depends on diversity, mutual adaptation, and balance.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Ecosystem Metaphor:</strong> Organizations have information species (departments, groups) that interact and compete</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Interdependence:</strong> Groups depend on each other and must adapt to coexist productively</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Evolutionary Dynamics:</strong> Information practices evolve through interaction, not top-down design alone</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IS Culture:</strong> Security success requires ecological balance; overly centralized control reduces resilience</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains why imposing security policies top-down often fails; shows that sustainable security requires attention to organizational information culture and stakeholder interactions.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Wang (2021), "Connecting the parts with the whole: Toward an information ecology
                                    theory of digital innovation ecosystems," <em>MIS Quarterly</em>. Key contribution:
                                    explains ecosystem integration through information mechanisms (programming, sensing,
                                    tracing).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>IS (ecosystems), with systems and ecology inspirations.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>IS-native.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains how information mechanisms enable coordination and
                                    integration across ecosystem actors.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Information ecology, programming, sensing, tracing, ecosystem integration,
                                    holons/part-whole relations.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Digital tech enables integration by programming coordination rules, sensing states
                                    and changes, and tracing actions for accountability. These information flows connect
                                    parts to the whole.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best for ecosystem settings where information is a central coordination resource.
                                    Less useful when integration is blocked mainly by politics or regulation rather than
                                    information.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Wang (2021) is the key top-outlet proof-of-life anchor in my local set, and it
                                    connects directly to ongoing digital ecosystem research.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Information ecology theory was proposed because digital innovation ecosystems need integration,
                        but integration is not only about contracts and strategy. It is also about information. Wang
                        argues that digital technologies change what can be known and coordinated across actors, and
                        that these information capabilities are central to ecosystem functioning.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that information mechanisms drive ecosystem integration. Programming
                        creates coordination rules and routinized linkages. Sensing creates awareness and
                        responsiveness. Tracing creates accountability and enables governance. The mechanism is
                        coordination through information. When actors can see shared states and trace actions,
                        coordination becomes more feasible and trust can be supported through accountability.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>This theory sits next to holon thinking. Holons capture part-whole nesting. Information ecology
                        adds the specific IS mechanism: information flows and traceability that connect levels. It also
                        pairs naturally with platform governance. Boundary resources can enable programming, sensing,
                        and tracing, but governance rules can also restrict them.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: It is IS-native and mechanism-driven. It gives you vocabulary for ecosystem
                        coordination that is more concrete than generic "ecosystem" talk. Weaknesses: It can underplay
                        power conflicts. Information can integrate, but actors may still resist sharing. Also,
                        programming and tracing can create surveillance concerns, so the theory connects to dignity and
                        responsibility questions. Common misapplications in IS: Treating "information availability" as
                        sufficient without specifying which mechanism (programming, sensing, tracing) is doing the work.
                        Alternatives and competitors: Systems theory for holistic framing, institutional logics for
                        competing value systems, and sociomateriality for practice-level enactment of ecosystem
                        coordination.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use information ecology when the exam question is about digital ecosystem
                        integration and the role of information flows, traceability, and coordination mechanisms.
                        Example research question: "How do traceability and sensing capabilities in a platform ecosystem
                        affect coordination and accountability across partners?" Example hypothesis: "Greater tracing
                        capability is positively associated with ecosystem accountability and negatively associated with
                        opportunistic behavior." What I would measure (simple): Platform traceability features (audit
                        logs, provenance), sensing features (dashboards, alerts), coordination outcomes (issue
                        resolution time), and accountability outcomes (dispute rates, compliance events). Seminal APA
                        citation: Wang, P. (2021). Connecting the parts with the whole: Toward an information ecology
                        theory of digital innovation ecosystems. <em>MIS Quarterly, 45</em>(1), 397-422.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="holon-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge philosophy">Philosophy</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Koestler, 1967</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Holon Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Systems consist of holons: entities that are simultaneously parts of larger wholes and wholes in themselves.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> A holon is a unit that is both independent (a whole) and dependent (a part of a larger system). Organizations, teams, and individuals are all holons. This duality affects how information security must be designed and enforced.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Dual Nature:</strong> Each level (individual, team, organization) functions as both autonomous unit and part of larger system</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Autonomy Tensions:</strong> Conflict between individual autonomy and organizational control shapes compliance</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Hierarchic Integration:</strong> Multiple levels must maintain autonomy while coordinating toward common goals</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ Security Design:</strong> Effective security balances individual autonomy with organizational control</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains why security policies that eliminate individual autonomy create resistance and failure; shows that sustainable security requires respecting both individual and organizational needs.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Koestler (1967), <em>The Ghost in the Machine</em>. Key contribution: introduces the
                                    "holon" as something that is simultaneously a whole and a part of a larger system
                                    (nested hierarchy).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Philosophy of systems / cybernetics / organizational thought.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS to think about ecosystems, modularity, and hierarchical
                                    systems).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II (explanation): explains coordination and emergence in nested systems by
                                    focusing on part-whole duality.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Holon, holarchy, Janus face (autonomy and dependence), nested systems, integration
                                    vs independence.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Each unit has its own goals and autonomy, but it is also constrained by the larger
                                    system it belongs to. System outcomes depend on how holons coordinate across levels.
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Best when the phenomenon is genuinely multi-level and nested (ecosystems, platforms,
                                    complex organizations). Less useful for flat, independent settings.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Holon logic appears in MISQ theorizing about digital innovation ecosystems and
                                    information ecology mechanisms.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Koestler introduced the idea of a holon to explain complex systems that are neither purely
                        hierarchical machines nor purely flat networks. A holon is something that is simultaneously a
                        whole (it has its own identity and autonomy) and a part of a larger whole (it depends on
                        higher-level structures). Koestler uses the "Janus face" idea: the holon looks inward as a whole
                        and outward as a part. This idea is useful in IS because digital ecosystems are full of nested
                        units. A complementor is a "whole" business with its own goals, but it is also a "part" of a
                        platform ecosystem with governance, standards, and dependencies. Affiliation note: I did not
                        verify author affiliation details from the original book in my local workspace, so I am not
                        listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is part-whole duality. Many coordination problems come from managing the
                        tension between autonomy and integration across levels. If holons are too autonomous, the system
                        fragments. If holons are too tightly controlled, local adaptation and innovation decline. The
                        mechanism is nested coordination. Interactions across levels create system outcomes, and
                        constraints can travel downward while innovations can travel upward. In platforms, for example,
                        governance rules constrain complementors, but complementor innovation can reshape what the
                        platform becomes. Boundary conditions matter. Holon thinking is most useful when the phenomenon
                        is genuinely multi-level and nested. If the setting is flat and independent, holon language adds
                        little. It is also easy to misuse as a metaphor if you do not specify what the holons are and
                        what the levels are.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, holon logic usually appears inside broader ecosystem and systems theorizing. Researchers
                        use it to reason about modularity, governance, and the part-whole tension in digital ecosystems
                        and enterprise architectures. Wang (2021) is a useful top-outlet anchor because it explicitly
                        focuses on "connecting the parts with the whole" in digital innovation ecosystems through an
                        information ecology theory. I treat this as holon-adjacent rather than a pure holon-theory
                        paper, so I log it as partial coverage in QA. Holon thinking also integrates naturally with
                        systems theory and complexity science. Systems theory gives the boundary language. Complexity
                        adds emergence and adaptation. Holon theory highlights the nested structure and
                        autonomy-integration tension.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Holon theory is useful when you need a clear way to talk about nested systems. It
                        helps you explain why governance is hard in ecosystems and why one-size-fits-all control can
                        backfire. Weaknesses: The theory is abstract and can become vague. Without a clear mapping to
                        levels, roles, and governance mechanisms, holon language can sound like poetic systems talk.
                        Common misapplications in IS: A common misuse is using holons as a fancy synonym for "modules"
                        without the autonomy part. Another is using it as a metaphor for complexity without specifying
                        the nested structure. Alternatives and competitors: Systems theory and complexity science are
                        close alternatives. Institutional theory and institutional logics can be stronger when the main
                        focus is legitimacy, power, and value conflict rather than nesting.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use holon theory when the question is about nested part-whole structures
                        (platforms, ecosystems) and how local autonomy and central control must be balanced. Example
                        research question: "In a generative AI platform ecosystem, how do complementors balance autonomy
                        with platform governance, and how does that tension shape innovation outcomes?" Example
                        hypothesis: "Stronger platform standardization increases ecosystem integration but reduces
                        complementor autonomy, which shifts innovation from radical to incremental forms." What I would
                        measure (simple): I would measure governance changes (API rules, review policies, data access
                        restrictions), complementor autonomy (ability to choose models, pricing, and data), and
                        innovation outcomes (new feature releases, diversity of apps, churn). A mixed-method design
                        works well because governance is both formal (rules) and enacted (practice). Seminal APA
                        citation: Koestler, A. (1967). <em>The ghost in the machine</em>. London, UK: Hutchinson.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="ostroms-collective-action-theory">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                    <span class="theory-badge economics">Economics</span>
                    <span class="theory-badge">Ostrom, 1990</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Ostrom's Collective Action Theory</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">How groups manage shared resources without tragedy; institutional design enables cooperation.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-preview">
                    <p><strong>Core Concept:</strong> Groups can sustain cooperation on shared resources when they establish clear rules, monitor behavior, enforce sanctions, and have voice in governance. This applies to shared IT infrastructure and data resources.</p>
                    <div class="theory-key-points">
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔑 Resource Governance:</strong> Shared resources require institutional rules and monitoring to prevent overuse</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>📊 Enforcement Mechanisms:</strong> Sanctions and transparency deter free-riding and enforce compliance</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>🔄 Participatory Design:</strong> When stakeholders help design rules, compliance and effectiveness increase</div>
                        <div class="key-point"><strong>⚡ IT Application:</strong> Shared data and infrastructure security requires clear rules, transparency, and enforcement</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="theory-relevance">
                    <strong>IS Relevance:</strong> Explains how to design sustainable security for shared organizational resources; shows that participation in rule creation improves compliance and effectiveness.
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Reference</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Field</th>
                                <th>Notes</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Seminal work</td>
                                <td>Ostrom (1990), <em>Governing the Commons: The Evolution of Institutions for
                                        Collective Action</em>. Key contribution: shows how communities can self-govern
                                    common-pool resources through design principles, countering simple "tragedy of the
                                    commons" predictions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Discipline of origin</td>
                                <td>Political science / institutional economics.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>IS-native or borrowed?</td>
                                <td>Borrowed (used in IS for digital commons, platforms, and societal grand challenges).
                                </td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gregor (2006) type</td>
                                <td>Type II and sometimes Type V when reframed as design principles for governance.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Core constructs</td>
                                <td>Collective action, common-pool resources, self-governance, monitoring, graduated
                                    sanctions, conflict resolution, nested enterprises, design principles.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Mechanism (plain)</td>
                                <td>Cooperation can be sustained when governance rules fit local conditions, monitoring
                                    is credible, sanctions are graduated, and participants have voice. These
                                    institutions reduce free-riding and build trust.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boundary conditions</td>
                                <td>Works best when communities can participate in rule-making and monitoring. Scaling
                                    to global contexts is difficult, which is why nested governance and design tensions
                                    matter.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2020-2025 IS "proof of life"</td>
                                <td>Ostrom-inspired ideas are used in <em>Information Systems Research</em> to theorize
                                    digital approaches to societal grand challenges through global-local design
                                    tensions.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📚 Foundational Origins</span>
                    <p>Ostrom's work challenged a common assumption: shared resources inevitably lead to overuse unless
                        a central authority controls them or they are privatized. In <em>Governing the Commons</em>
                        (1990), she shows that many communities successfully manage common-pool resources through
                        self-governance. She identifies design principles for robust governance, like clear boundaries,
                        collective choice arrangements, monitoring, graduated sanctions, and accessible conflict
                        resolution. For comps, the Nobel point matters. Ostrom received the Nobel Prize in economics for
                        this work. The deeper exam value is that her theory is optimistic but not naive. It is not
                        "people cooperate." It is "people can cooperate when institutions are designed well."
                        Affiliation note: I did not verify author affiliation details from the original book in my local
                        workspace, so I am not listing them here (logged in QA).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">💎 Theoretical Core</span>
                    <p>The main proposition is that collective action problems can be solved through institutions that
                        align incentives, enable monitoring, and support participation. Ostrom's design principles
                        describe what robust governance looks like: users participate in rule making, boundaries are
                        clear, monitoring exists, sanctions are graduated, and governance is nested when the system is
                        large. The causal mechanism is institutional. Rules change behavior by changing expectations and
                        by reducing free-riding. Monitoring makes behavior visible. Sanctions make defection costly.
                        Participation increases legitimacy, which increases compliance. In many cases, the mechanism is
                        not "more punishment," it is better fit: rules that match local conditions and that users see as
                        fair. Boundary conditions are crucial. Collective action is easier when communities are stable
                        and can monitor. It is harder when the resource is global, when users are anonymous, or when
                        power is highly unequal. That is why scaling to digital settings often raises new tensions
                        around identity, monitoring, and governance legitimacy.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔗 Evolution and Extensions (IS focus)</span>
                    <p>In IS, Ostrom is used to study digital commons and digital governance problems where coordination
                        is difficult and free-riding is possible. Examples include open-source communities, platform
                        governance, and digital approaches to societal grand challenges. Nambisan and George (2024) is a
                        strong recent IS anchor that theorizes digital approaches to societal grand challenges through
                        global-local design tensions. This connects well to Ostrom because it highlights the need for
                        nested governance and the difficulty of scaling institutions from local to global contexts.
                        Integration with institutional theory is common. Institutional theory explains field-level
                        pressures and legitimacy. Ostrom explains micro-to-meso governance design principles that can
                        sustain participation and monitoring. Together, they give a strong exam story: pressures shape
                        what is expected, and design principles shape what actually works.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Critical Analysis
                        (Exam-ready)</span>
                    <p>Strengths: Ostrom gives a practical and evidence-based alternative to the "tragedy of the
                        commons" story. The design principles are easy to remember and very exam-friendly because they
                        translate into clear governance variables (participation, monitoring, sanctions). Weaknesses:
                        Generalizing across contexts is hard. Digital commons can involve anonymous users, fast
                        membership change, and power asymmetry, which can weaken the original assumptions. Another
                        limitation is that design principles can be treated as a checklist without showing which
                        principle actually matters in the case. Common misapplications in IS: A common misuse is listing
                        the design principles without measuring them or showing evidence. Another is treating the
                        principles as universal rules rather than context-dependent guidance. Alternatives and
                        competitors: Agency theory is useful when governance is mainly about incentives and contracts.
                        Institutional theory is useful when governance is shaped by regulation and legitimacy. Trust
                        theory is useful when participation depends on perceived vulnerability and benevolence.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label"
                        style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dc3545 0%, #fd7e14 100%);">⚠️ Practical Application
                        for Exam</span>
                    <p>Exam use note: Use Ostrom when the question is about governance and participation in shared
                        digital resources (open source, data commons, community moderation) and how rules shape
                        cooperation. Example research question: "What governance design principles make online
                        communities resilient and sustainable over time?" Example hypothesis: "Online communities with
                        clearer boundaries, stronger monitoring, and accessible conflict resolution will have higher
                        long-term participation and lower rule violations." What I would measure (simple): I would
                        operationalize boundaries (membership rules), monitoring (moderation activity, automated
                        detection), sanctions (warning and ban policies), and conflict resolution (appeal processes).
                        Outcomes can include participation retention and rule violation rates. A strong design is
                        longitudinal because governance effects accumulate over time. Seminal APA citation: Ostrom, E.
                        (1990). <em>Governing the commons: The evolution of institutions for collective action</em>.
                        Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press. # Cross-theory contrasts (exam vignettes)</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="contrast-1-agency-theory-vs-prospect-theory-in-cybersecurity-disclosures">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge meta">Comparative Analysis</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Contrast 1: Agency Theory vs Prospect Theory in cybersecurity disclosures</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Two complementary lenses for understanding how managers frame cyber risk to stakeholders under different incentives and psychological contexts.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Comparison</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Dimension</th>
                                <th>Agency Theory</th>
                                <th>Prospect Theory</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>Core Focus</td><td>Manager incentives and information asymmetry between managers (agents) and shareholders (principals)</td><td>Investor psychology and reference-dependent decision-making under risk</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Key Mechanism</td><td>Alignment of payoff structures through monitoring, contracts, and incentives</td><td>Framing of outcomes relative to reference points; loss aversion and probability weighting</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Unit of Analysis</td><td>Governance relationship and disclosure choice (strategic framing of information)</td><td>Individual/investor interpretation of disclosure and market response</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Assumptions</td><td>Self-interested managers optimize disclosure to manage reputation and regulatory risk</td><td>Investors are reference-dependent; losses feel more painful than equal-sized gains</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>IS Application</td><td>Explains why firms disclose cyber incidents strategically, withhold certain details, or emphasize mitigative measures over prevention</td><td>Explains why disclosure framing (preventive vs. mitigative) changes investor reactions and stock price impact</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔑 Key Differences</span>
                    <p><strong>Locus of explanation:</strong> Agency theory looks at the <span class="construct-badge">supply side</span>—why managers produce certain disclosures. Prospect theory looks at the <span class="construct-badge">demand side</span>—how investors interpret and react to those disclosures. Agency theory is about <mark>strategic choice</mark> under <span class="construct-badge">information asymmetry</span>; prospect theory is about <mark>psychological response</mark> to how information is framed.</p>
                    <p><strong>Time horizon and incentives:</strong> Agency theory emphasizes <mark>long-term reputation and regulatory costs</mark>. Managers may disclose proactively if monitoring is strong or if disclosure costs are lower than the risk of uncontrolled disclosure. Prospect theory emphasizes <mark>immediate framing effects</mark>. The same cyber incident framed as "prevention in progress" (gain frame) versus "mitigation of past damage" (loss frame) can trigger opposite investor responses regardless of underlying risk.</p>
                    <p><strong>Role of information asymmetry:</strong> Agency theory places <span class="construct-badge">information asymmetry</span> at the center—managers know more and use that advantage strategically. Prospect theory assumes information is disclosed but interpreted through psychological biases—even with full information, framing determines choice.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🤝 Where They Overlap</span>
                    <p>Both theories recognize that cyber risk disclosures are <mark>not neutral acts</mark>. Managers are strategic, and investors are not purely rational. Both predict that <mark>framing and context matter</mark> for disclosure reception. Both apply well to cybersecurity because cyber events are high-uncertainty, salient, and carry both reputational and regulatory consequences. The integration point is clear: managers strategically choose disclosure framing (agency), and investors respond through loss aversion and probability weighting (prospect). In a cyber incident, managers face pressure to disclose (regulation, monitoring), but they also control how the incident is framed (preventive efforts, mitigation readiness, industry context). Investors then respond to that framing, which feeds back into managers' disclosure incentives for future incidents.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🎯 When to Use Which</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Use Agency Theory when:</strong> The research question is about <mark>governance incentives</mark>, <mark>monitoring</mark>, or <mark>disclosure timing</mark>. For example: "Do firms with stronger institutional ownership disclose cyber incidents faster?" or "How does audit quality shape cyber risk reporting?" Agency theory explains why certain governance structures lead to different disclosure choices.
                    </div>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Use Prospect Theory when:</strong> The research question is about <mark>investor reaction</mark> or <mark>framing effects</mark>. For example: "Do investors respond differently to cyber disclosures that emphasize prevention versus incident response?" or "How does breach timing (fiscal quarter, post-earnings) change stock price impact?" Prospect theory explains the psychological mechanism behind differential responses to the same cyber event.
                    </div>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Use both together when:</strong> The full story is about <mark>disclosure production and reception</mark>. For example: "How do governance structures shape whether managers frame disclosures in preventive versus mitigative terms, and how do those framing choices affect investor reactions and future disclosure incentives?" This is the richest answer and shows sophisticated integration.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="contrast-2-institutional-theory-vs-institutional-logics">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge meta">Comparative Analysis</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Contrast 2: Institutional Theory vs Institutional Logics</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Macro-level isomorphic pressures (why organizations converge) versus micro-level competing meaning systems (why organizations differ in how they respond).</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Comparison</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Dimension</th>
                                <th>Institutional Theory</th>
                                <th>Institutional Logics</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>Core Focus</td><td>How field-level pressures (coercive, normative, mimetic) push organizations toward similar structures and practices</td><td>How multiple competing belief systems (market, professional, state, community logics) shape heterogeneous organizational responses to the same pressures</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Key Mechanism</td><td>Isomorphism through legitimacy-seeking: organizations adopt practices to appear legitimate to stakeholders</td><td>Logic dominance: which logic is salient shapes whether an organization treats a policy as cost (market logic), compliance (state logic), or expertise (professional logic)</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Unit of Analysis</td><td>Organizational field (industry/sector) convergence; adoption diffusion patterns</td><td>Intra-organizational conflict and hybrid practices; power shifts between stakeholder groups with different logics</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Assumptions</td><td>Organizations in the same field will converge because legitimacy pressures are similar</td><td>Organizations in the same field may diverge because different groups pull toward different logics; power determines which logic wins</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>IS Application</td><td>Explains why similar firms adopt similar security frameworks (NIST, ISO) and why security practices diffuse across industries</td><td>Explains why two banks with the same compliance mandate invest differently in security: one as cost-minimization (market logic) vs. expertise-driven (professional logic)</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔑 Key Differences</span>
                    <p><strong>Explanatory scope:</strong> Institutional theory excels at explaining <mark>convergence and similarity</mark>. Why do most firms in healthcare, finance, or tech adopt similar governance structures? Institutional theory says: legitimacy pressures in the field push toward isomorphism. Institutional logics focuses on <mark>variation and conflict</mark>. Why do two firms adopt the same framework but implement it differently? Institutional logics says: competing logics within each firm shape implementation differently, depending on which groups have power.</p>
                    <p><strong>Ontology of institutions:</strong> Institutional theory treats institutions as <mark>external pressures</mark> on organizations. The field is "out there," and organizations respond. Institutional logics treats institutions as <mark>internalized meaning systems</mark> held by actors inside organizations. Different stakeholders (IT leaders, CFOs, auditors) carry different logics, and outcomes reflect which logic dominates internally.</p>
                    <p><strong>Homogeneity vs. heterogeneity:</strong> Institutional theory predicts <mark>homogeneity within fields</mark>: similar organizations converge on similar practices. Institutional logics predicts <mark>heterogeneity even in similar organizations</mark> when different logics compete. A state agency and a private firm may face the same regulatory pressure (institutional theory says they'll converge), but if the agency emphasizes state/public-interest logic and the firm emphasizes market logic, they'll diverge in actual practice.</p>
                    <p><strong>Change mechanism:</strong> In institutional theory, change happens through <mark>field-level shifts</mark> (new regulation, new norms). In institutional logics, change happens through <mark>power shifts</mark> between logics within organizations. Technology can tip the balance toward one logic over another.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🤝 Where They Overlap</span>
                    <p>Both theories recognize that <mark>legitimacy and social acceptance matter</mark>, not just efficiency. Both emphasize that organizations are embedded in broader social environments, not islands. Both apply well to security and compliance contexts where external regulation meets internal organizational dynamics. The integration is natural: institutional theory explains field-level isomorphic pressures (why security frameworks converge across firms), and institutional logics explains how different firms interpret and prioritize those pressures differently based on internal logic competition. For example, GDPR creates a coercive institutional pressure (everyone must comply), but which logic organizations prioritize—market logic (compliance as cost to minimize), professional logic (compliance as data governance excellence), or state logic (compliance as citizen protection)—determines investment level, governance structure, and actual practice intensity.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🎯 When to Use Which</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Use Institutional Theory when:</strong> The question is about <mark>field-level convergence</mark> or <mark>adoption diffusion</mark>. For example: "Why do cybersecurity frameworks like NIST diffuse across industries?" or "How do regulatory changes shape compliance adoption rates?" Institutional theory explains isomorphism and legitimacy-driven diffusion at the field level.
                    </div>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Use Institutional Logics when:</strong> The question is about <mark>intra-organizational variation</mark>, <mark>conflict resolution</mark>, or <mark>practice heterogeneity</mark>. For example: "Why do two firms with identical compliance mandates invest differently in security?" or "How do competing logics between IT and Finance shape security budgeting?" Institutional logics explains variation driven by which internal stakeholder logic dominates.
                    </div>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Use both together when:</strong> The full story involves <mark>field-level pressures creating convergence at the formal level, but internal logic conflicts creating divergence at the implementation level</mark>. For example: "How do regulatory pressures (institutional theory) create convergence in security policies, but internal logic conflicts between market and professional logics (institutional logics) produce divergent implementation and effectiveness?" This shows understanding of nested dynamics.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="paper-card theory-preview-card" id="contrast-3-technology-affordances-vs-sociomateriality">
                <div class="theory-header">
                    <div class="theory-meta-badges">
                        <span class="theory-badge meta">Comparative Analysis</span>
                    </div>
                    <h2>Contrast 3: Technology Affordances vs Sociomateriality</h2>
                    <p class="theory-tagline">Action possibilities that exist independent of practice (affordances) versus technology and practice co-produced together as ontologically inseparable (sociomateriality).</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">📊 Quick Comparison</span>
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Dimension</th>
                                <th>Technology Affordances</th>
                                <th>Sociomateriality</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>Core Focus</td><td>Action possibilities that a technology makes available to goal-oriented users given their capabilities and context</td><td>How technology and social practice are ontologically entangled and co-produced through ongoing work routines</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Key Mechanism</td><td>Relational property between artifact, user goals, and context; actualization occurs when users perceive and enact affordances</td><td>Performativity: outcomes emerge through practices where material features, norms, and intentions are inseparably produced together</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Unit of Analysis</td><td>Specific action possibilities (e.g., anonymity affordance, persistence affordance); actualization by user groups over time</td><td>Situated practices and organizational routines; material and social features as a single analytical unit</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Technology Status</td><td>Technology has properties/potentials that exist independent of whether they are used; affordances can be latent (not actualized)</td><td>Technology is only ever known through practice; "what the technology is" is produced simultaneously with "what the practice is"</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>IS Application</td><td>Explains why a feature (e.g., encryption) enables some users (privacy-conscious) but constrains others (compliance auditors); heterogeneous use of same technology</td><td>Explains how security tools reshape organizational routines; audit practices don't just implement the tool, they enact what the tool becomes in use</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🔑 Key Differences</span>
                    <p><strong>Ontological commitment:</strong> Technology affordances assume that technology has <mark>properties independent of practice</mark>. A password manager affords certain actions (generating complex passwords, auto-filling, securely storing) whether or not a user actualizes them. The affordance exists as a potential. Sociomateriality claims that <mark>technology and practice are ontologically inseparable</mark>. "What the password manager is" is not separate from "how it is used in organizational routines." The technology is enacted through practice; it does not pre-exist practice.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causality and determinism:</strong> Affordance theory avoids technological determinism by saying technology <mark>enables, constrains, and affords possibilities</mark>—but users actualize or ignore those possibilities based on goals and context. This is still somewhat directional: technology has properties that enable/constrain. Sociomateriality avoids determinism more radically by claiming <mark>no directionality</mark>—social and material are mutually constituting in real time. Neither determines the other; they are produced together.</p>
                    <p><strong>Latency and actualization:</strong> Affordances can exist but not be actualized. A security tool might afford transparency (through audit logs), but if no one reads the logs, the transparency affordance remains latent. Sociomateriality does not separate potential from actual; it focuses on what emerges through practice. The question is not "what affordances exist" but "what practices and routines are performed, and what realities do those performances bring into being?"</p>
                    <p><strong>Measurement and methods:</strong> Affordance research often uses comparative designs: how do different user groups actualize the same affordances differently? Or longitudinal: how does actualization change over time? Sociomaterial research uses deep observation of practices: ethnography, process tracing, or document analysis to show how material and social features are entangled in specific routines.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🤝 Where They Overlap</span>
                    <p>Both theories reject <mark>technological determinism</mark> (technology automatically causes outcomes). Both take <mark>the artifact seriously</mark> without reducing outcomes to user choice or social factors alone. Both emphasize <mark>heterogeneous implementation</mark>—the same technology can produce different outcomes in different contexts. Both apply well to understanding digital transformation in organizations because they explain why a security tool, platform, or system does not have one single effect; it depends on what users can do (affordances) and how practices evolve (sociomateriality). The tension between them is real and worth acknowledging: affordance theory allows that technology has properties independent of practice; sociomateriality denies that separation. Some scholars argue they can be combined by treating affordances as <mark>stable potentials</mark> and sociomateriality as <mark>practice-specific enactments of those potentials</mark>, but others argue that's a compromise that violates sociomateriality's core ontological claim.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-section">
                    <span class="analysis-label">🎯 When to Use Which</span>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Use Affordances when:</strong> The research question is about <mark>action possibilities</mark> and <mark>heterogeneous actualization</mark> across user groups. For example: "How do platform ephemerality affordances change user disclosure behavior?" or "What affordances do security dashboards provide to different stakeholders (auditors, IT teams, executives) and how do they perceive and use them differently?" Affordance theory is designed to explain why the same feature enables some and constrains others.
                    </div>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Use Sociomateriality when:</strong> The research question is about <mark>how practices and technology co-evolve</mark> or <mark>how organizational routines are reshaped through technology</mark>. For example: "How do employees and an AI audit tool co-produce new audit practices, and how do those practices reshape what the tool is used for over time?" or "How do security incident response routines become entangled with log analysis tools?" Sociomateriality is designed to show how the boundary between "tool" and "practice" is blurry and fluid.
                    </div>
                    <div class="exam-tip">
                        <strong>Use both together (carefully) when:</strong> You want to explain both <mark>what possibilities the technology creates</mark> (affordances) and <mark>how those possibilities are enacted through situated practices</mark> (sociomateriality). For example: "A security monitoring tool affords real-time threat detection (affordance), but whether that affordance is actualized depends on organizational routines of alert triage and response, which co-evolve with how the tool is configured and used (sociomateriality)." If you combine them, be explicit about whether you treat affordances as independent potentials (slight risk of slipping back toward determinism) or as always-already enacted in practice (pure sociomaterial stance).
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

